<BODY>
<PB REF="00000045.tif" N="[1]">
<HEAD>THE PRICKE OF CONSCIENCE.</HEAD>
<DIV1 TYPE="prologue">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e myght of &thorn;e Fader almyghty,</L>
<L>&THORN;e witte of &thorn;e Son alwytty,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e gudnes of &thorn;e Haligast,</L>
<L N="4">A Godde and Lorde of myght mast,</L>
<L>Be wyth us and us help and spede,</L>
<L>Now and ever, in al our nede;</L>
<L>And specialy at this bygynnyng,</L>
<L N="8">And bryng us alle til gude endyng. Amen.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Before ar any thyng was wroght,</L>
<L>And ar any bygynnyng was of oght,</L>
<L>And befor al tymes, als we sal trow,</L>
<L N="12">&THORN;e sam God ay was &thorn;at es now,</L>
<L>&THORN;at woned ever in his godhede,</L>
<L>And in thre persons and anhede.</L>
<L>For God wald ay with &thorn;e Fader and &thorn;e Son</L>
<L N="16">And wyth &thorn;e Haligast in anhede won,</L>
<L>Als God in a substance and beyng</L>
<L>With-outen any bygynnyng;</L>
<L>Bygynnyng of hym, myght never nan be,</L>
<L N="20">He was ay God in trinit&eacute;,</L>
<L>&THORN;at was ay als wys and ful of wytte,</L>
<L>And als myghty als he es yhitte,</L>
<L>W[h]as<NOTE PLACE="foot">whose.</NOTE> myght and wytte of him-selve was tan,</L>
<L N="24">For never na God was bot he alan.</L>
<L>&THORN;e sam God sythyn was &thorn;e bygynnyng,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e first maker of alle thyng;
<PB REF="00000046.tif" N="2"></L>
<L>And als he is bygynnyng of alle,</L>
<L N="28">Wyth-outen bygynnyng swa we him call,</L>
<L>Ende of al wyth-outen ende,</L>
<L>&THORN;us es in haly bokes contende;</L>
<L>For als he was ay God in trinit&eacute;</L>
<L N="32">Swa he es, and ay God sal be;</L>
<L>And als he first bygan alle thing,</L>
<L>Swa sal he, at &thorn;e last, mak endyng</L>
<L>Of alle &thorn;ing bot of heven and helle,</L>
<L N="36">And of man, and fende, and aungelle,</L>
<L>&THORN;at aftir &thorn;is lyfe sal lyf ay,</L>
<L>And na qwik creature bot &thorn;ai,</L>
<L>Als men may se in &thorn;is boke contende,</L>
<L N="40">&THORN;at wille it se or here to &thorn;e ende.</L>
<L>And God that mad man sal ay be &thorn;an,</L>
<L>Als he is now, God and man.</L>
<L>Alle thyng thurgh his myght made he,</L>
<L N="44">For with-outen hym myght nathing be.</L>
<L>Alle thyng &thorn;at he bygan and wroght</L>
<L>Was byfor &thorn;e bygynnyng noght.</L>
<L>Alle thing he ordaynd aftir is wille</L>
<L N="48">In sere kyndes, for certayn skylle;</L>
<L>Whar-for &thorn;e creatours &thorn;at er dom,</L>
<L>And na witt ne skille has, er bughsom</L>
<L>To lof hym, als &thorn;e boke beres wytnesse,</L>
<L N="52">On &thorn;air maner als &thorn;air kynd esse.</L>
<L>For ilk a thyng &thorn;at God has wroght,</L>
<L>&THORN;at folowes &thorn;e kynd and passes it noght,</L>
<L>Loves his maker and hym worshepes,</L>
<L N="56">In &thorn;at at he &thorn;e kynd right kepes;</L>
<L>Sen &thorn;e creatures &thorn;at skill has nane,</L>
<L>Hym loves in &thorn;e kynde &thorn;at &thorn;ai haf tane;</L>
<L>&THORN;an aght man &thorn;at has skille and mynde</L>
<L N="60">Hys creatur worshepe in his kynde,</L>
<L>And noght to be of wers condicion</L>
<L>&THORN;an &thorn;e creatours with-outen reson.</L>
<L>Mans kynd es to folow Goddes wille</L>
<L N="64">And alle hys comandmentes to fulfille;
<PB REF="00000047.tif" N="3"></L>
<L>For of alle &thorn;at God made, mare and les,</L>
<L>Man mast principal creature es,</L>
<L>And alle &thorn;at he made was for man done,</L>
<L N="68">Als yhe sal here aftirward sone.</L>
<L>God to mans kynd had grete lufe</L>
<L>When he ordaynd, for mans byhufe,</L>
<L>Heven and herth and &thorn;e werld brade,</L>
<L N="72">And al other thyng, and man last made</L>
<L>Til hys lyknes and semely stature;</L>
<L>And made hym mast digne creature</L>
<L>Of al other creaturs of kynde;</L>
<L N="76">And gaf hym wytte, skille and mynde,</L>
<L>For to knaw gude and ille;</L>
<L>And &thorn;are-with he gaf hym a fre wille</L>
<L>For to chese, and for to halde</L>
<L N="80">Gude or ille, wethir he walde;</L>
<L>And alswa he ordaynd man to dwelle</L>
<L>And to lyf in erthe, in flesshe and felle,</L>
<L>To knaw his werkes and him worshepe,</L>
<L N="84">And his comandmentes to kepe;</L>
<L>And if he be til God bousom,</L>
<L>Til endeles blis at &thorn;e last to com;</L>
<L>And, if he fraward be, to wende</L>
<L N="88">Til pyne of helle, &thorn;at has nan ende.</L>
<L>Ilk man &thorn;at here lyves, mare and lesse,</L>
<L>God made til his awen lyknesse;</L>
<L>Til wham he has gyven witte and skille</L>
<L N="92">For to knaw bothe gude and ille,</L>
<L>And fre wille to chese, als he vouches save,</L>
<L>Gude or ille whether he wil have;</L>
<L>Bot he &thorn;at his wille til God wil sette,</L>
<L N="96">Grete mede &thorn;arfor mon he gette;</L>
<L>And he &thorn;at til ille settes his wille</L>
<L>Grete payne sal have for &thorn;at ille;</L>
<L>Whar-for &thorn;at man may be halden wode,</L>
<L N="100">&THORN;at cheses &thorn;e ille and leves &thorn;e gude.</L>
<L>Sen God made man of maste dignit&eacute;</L>
<L>Of alle creatures, and mast fre,
<PB REF="00000048.tif" N="4"></L>
<L>And made him til his awen liknes,</L>
<L N="104">In fair stature, als befor sayde es,</L>
<L>And maste has gyven him, and yhit gyves</L>
<L>&THORN;an til any other creature &thorn;at lyves,</L>
<L>And has hight him yit &thorn;ar to</L>
<L N="108">&THORN;e blise of heven, if he uele do;</L>
<L>And yhit when he had done mys,</L>
<L>And thurgh syn was prived of blys,</L>
<L>God tok mans kynd for his sake</L>
<L N="112">And for his love &thorn;e dede wald take,</L>
<L>And with his blode boght him agayne</L>
<L>Til &thorn;at blisse fra endeles payne;</L>
<L>&THORN;us grete lufe God til man kydde,</L>
<L N="116">And many benyfices he him dydde;</L>
<L>Whar-for ilk man, bathe lered and lewed,</L>
<L>Suld thynk on &thorn;at love &thorn;at he man shewed,</L>
<L>And alle &thorn;ier<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;ir (Harl. MS. 4196).</NOTE> benefice hald in mynde,</L>
<L N="120">&THORN;at he &thorn;us dyd til mans kynde,</L>
<L>And love hym and thank him als he can,</L>
<L>And elles es he an unkynd man,</L>
<L>And serve him, bathe day and nyght,</L>
<L N="124">And &thorn;at he has gyven him, use it ryght</L>
<L>And his wittes despende in his service,</L>
<L>Elles es he a fole and noght wise;</L>
<L>And knaw kyndly what God es</L>
<L N="128">And what man self es &thorn;at es les;</L>
<L>How wake man es in saul and body,</L>
<L>And how stalworth God es, and how myghty;</L>
<L>How man God greves &thorn;at dose noght wele,</L>
<L N="132">And what man es worthi &thorn;ar-for to fele,</L>
<L>How mercyful and gracyouse God es,</L>
<L>And how ful he es of gudenes;</L>
<L>How rightwes God es and how sothefast,</L>
<L N="136">And what he has done and sal do at &thorn;e last,</L>
<L>And ilk day dos to man-kynde;</L>
<L>&THORN;is suld ilk man knaw and haf in mynde.
<PB REF="00000049.tif" N="5"></L>
<L>For &thorn;e right way &thorn;at lyggus til blys,</L>
<L N="140">And &thorn;at ledys a man theder, es &thorn;ys;</L>
<L>&THORN;e way of mekenes principaly,</L>
<L>And of drede, and luf of God almyghty,</L>
<L>&THORN;at may be cald &thorn;e way of wysdom;</L>
<L N="144">In-tyl whilk way na man may com</L>
<L>Wyth-outen knawyng of God here,</L>
<L>And of his myght, and his werkes sere,</L>
<L>Bot here he may til &thorn;at knawyng wynne.</L>
<L N="148">Hym byhoves knaw him-self with-inne,</L>
<L>Elles may he haf na knawing to come</L>
<L>In-til &thorn;e forsayde way of wysdome.</L>
<L>Bot som men has wytte to understand,</L>
<L N="152">And yhit &thorn;ai er ful unkunand,</L>
<L>And of som thyng has na knawing</L>
<L>&THORN;at myght styrre &thorn;am to gude lyfyng;</L>
<L>Swylk men had nede to lere ilk day</L>
<L N="156">Of other men, &thorn;at can mare &thorn;an &thorn;ay;</L>
<L>To knaw &thorn;at, myght &thorn;am stir and lede</L>
<L>Til mekenes, and til lufe, and drede;</L>
<L>&THORN;e whilk es way, als befor sayde es,</L>
<L N="160">Til &thorn;e blis of heven &thorn;at es endeles.</L>
<L>In grete perille of saul es &thorn;at man</L>
<L>&THORN;at has witt and mynde and na gude can,</L>
<L>And wil noght lere for to knaw</L>
<L N="164">&THORN;e werkes of God and gode law,</L>
<L>Ne what hym-self es &thorn;at es lest;</L>
<L>Bot lyves als an unskylwys best,</L>
<L>&THORN;at nother has skil, witt, ne mynde;</L>
<L N="168">&THORN;at man lyfes agayn his kynde.</L>
<L>For a man excuses noght his unkunnyng,</L>
<L>&THORN;at his wittes uses noght in leryng,</L>
<L>Namly, of &thorn;at at hym fel to knaw</L>
<L N="172">&THORN;at myght meke his hert and make it law,</L>
<L>Bot he &thorn;at can noght, suld haf wille</L>
<L>To lere to knaw bathe gude and ille;</L>
<L>And he &thorn;at can oght, suld lere mare</L>
<L N="176">To knaw alle &thorn;at hym nedeful ware;
<PB REF="00000050.tif" N="6"></L>
<L>For an unkunnand man, thurgh leryng,</L>
<L>May be broght til undirstandyng</L>
<L>Of many thynges, to knaw and se</L>
<L N="180">&THORN;at has bene, and es, and yhit sal be,</L>
<L>&THORN;at til mekenes myght stir his wille,</L>
<L>And til lufe, and drede, and to fle alle ille.</L>
<L>Many has lykyng trofels to here,</L>
<L N="184">And vanit&eacute;s wille blethly lere,</L>
<L>And er bysy in wille and thoght</L>
<L>To lere &thorn;at &thorn;e saul helpes noght;</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;at ne[de]ful war to kun and knaw,</L>
<L N="188">To listen and lere &thorn;ai er ful slaw;</L>
<L>For-&thorn;i &thorn;ai can noght knaw ne se</L>
<L>&THORN;e peryls &thorn;at &thorn;ai suld drede and fle,</L>
<L>And whilk way &thorn;ai suld chese and take,</L>
<L N="192">And whilk way &thorn;ai suld lef and forsake.</L>
<L>Bot na wonder es, yf &thorn;ai ga wrang</L>
<L>For in myrknes of unknawyng &thorn;ai gang,</L>
<L>With-outen lyght of understandyng</L>
<L N="196">Of &thorn;at, &thorn;at falles til ryght knawyng.</L>
<L>&THORN;ar-for ilk cristen man and weman</L>
<L>&THORN;at has witte and mynd, and skille can,</L>
<L>&THORN;at knaws noght &thorn;e ryght way to chese,</L>
<L N="200">Ne &thorn;e perils &thorn;at ilk wise man flese,</L>
<L>Suld be bughsom ay, and bysy</L>
<L>To here and lere of &thorn;am, namely,</L>
<L>&THORN;at understands and knawes by skille,</L>
<L N="204">Wilk es gude way and wilk es ille.</L>
<L>He &thorn;at right ordir of lyfyng wil luke</L>
<L>Suld bygyn &thorn;us, als says &thorn;e boke;</L>
<L>To knaw first what hym-self es,</L>
<L N="208">Swa may he tyttest come to mekenes,</L>
<L>&THORN;at es grund of al vertus to last,</L>
<L>On whilk al vertus may be sette fast;</L>
<L>For he &thorn;at knawes wele, and can se</L>
<L N="212">What him-self was, and es, and sal be,</L>
<L>A wyser man may he be talde,</L>
<L>Wether he be yhung man or alde,
<PB REF="00000051.tif" N="7"></L>
<L>&THORN;an he &thorn;at can alle other thyng,</L>
<L N="216">And of him-self has na knawyng.</L>
<L>For he may noght right God knaw ne fele,</L>
<L>Bot he can first him-self wele:</L>
<L>&THORN;ar-for a man suld first lere</L>
<L N="220">To knaw him-self propely here;</L>
<L>For if he hym-self knew kyndely,</L>
<L>He suld haf knawyng of God almyghty,</L>
<L>And of his endyng thynk suld he</L>
<L N="224">And of &thorn;e day &thorn;at last sal be.</L>
<L>He suld knaw what &thorn;is worlde es,</L>
<L>&THORN;at es ful of pompe and lythernes,</L>
<L>And lere to knaw and thynk wyth-alle</L>
<L N="228">What sal after &thorn;is lyf falle.</L>
<L>For, knawyng of all &thorn;is shuld hym lede</L>
<L>And mynd with-alle, til mekenes and drede,</L>
<L>And swa may he com to gude lyvyng,</L>
<L N="232">And atte &thorn;e last til a gode endyng;</L>
<L>And when he sal out of &thorn;is world wende,</L>
<L>Be broght til &thorn;e lyfe, &thorn;at has na ende.</L>
<L>&THORN;e bygynnyng of alle &thorn;is proces</L>
<L N="236">Ryght knawyng of a man self es.</L>
<L>Bot som men has mykel lettyng,</L>
<L>&THORN;at lettes &thorn;am to haf right knawyng</L>
<L>Of &thorn;am-selfe, &thorn;at &thorn;ai first suld knaw,</L>
<L N="240">&THORN;at &thorn;am til mekenes first suld draw.</L>
<L>And of &thorn;at, four thynges I find</L>
<L>&THORN;at mase a mans wytt ofte blynd,</L>
<L>And knawyng of hym-self lettes,</L>
<L N="244">Thurgh wilk four, he hym-self forgettes.</L>
<L>Of &thorn;is Saynt Bernard witnes bers</L>
<L>And er &thorn;a four wryten in &thorn;is vers.</L>
<L><I>Forma, favor populi, fervor juvenilis, opesque</I></L>
<L N="248"><I>Surripuere tibi noscere quid sit homo.</I></L>
<L>&THORN;at es "favor of &thorn;e folk and fayrnes,</L>
<L>And fervor of thoght<NOTE PLACE="foot">yhouthe.</NOTE> and riches,
<PB REF="00000052.tif" N="8"></L>
<L>Reves a man sight, skylle and mynde,</L>
<L N="252">To knaw hym-self, what he es of kynde."</L>
<L>&THORN;us &thorn;er four lettes his insight</L>
<L>&THORN;at he knaws noght him-selfe right,</L>
<L>And mas his hert ful hawtayne</L>
<L N="256">And ful fraward til his soverayne.</L>
<L>&THORN;ir four norisches ofte pompe and pride,</L>
<L>And other vices &thorn;at men can noght hyde.</L>
<L>For in him, in wham ane of &thorn;er four es,</L>
<L N="260">Es selden sen any mekenes;</L>
<L>Alswa &thorn;ai lette a man &thorn;at he noght sese</L>
<L>&THORN;e perils of &thorn;e werld, ne vanitese,</L>
<L>Ne of &thorn;e tyme of &thorn;e dede &thorn;at es to come;</L>
<L N="264">Thynkes noght ne of &thorn;e day of dom,</L>
<L>Ne he can noght undirstand ne se</L>
<L>&THORN;e paynes, &thorn;at after &thorn;is lyfe sal be</L>
<L>To synful men &thorn;at here lofes foly,</L>
<L N="268">Ne &thorn;e blise &thorn;at gude men er worthy;</L>
<L>Bot in his delytis settes his hert fast,</L>
<L>And fares als &thorn;is lyfe suld ay last,</L>
<L>And gyffes him noght bot to vanit&eacute;,</L>
<L N="272">And to al &thorn;at lykyng to hym myght be.</L>
<L>Swylk men er noght led with skylle,</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;ai folow, ay, &thorn;air awen wille</L>
<L>And of noght elles thynkes, ne tas hede.</L>
<L N="276">What wonder es yf &thorn;ai haf na drede;</L>
<L>For what &thorn;ai suld drede, &thorn;ai knaw noght,</L>
<L>&THORN;arfor &thorn;ai can haf na drede in thoght,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;at &thorn;at myght &thorn;am to drede bryng,</L>
<L N="280">And &thorn;at es thurgh defaut of knawyng.</L>
<L>Yhit som men wille noght understande</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;at mught mak &thorn;am dredande,</L>
<L>For &thorn;ai wald noght here, bot &thorn;at &thorn;am pays,</L>
<L N="284">&THORN;arfor &thorn;e prophet in psauter says:</L>
<L><I>Noluit intelligere</I></L>
<L><I>ut bene ageret.</I></L>
<L>He says "he has no wille to fele,</L>
<L N="288">Ne to understand for to do wele".
<PB REF="00000053.tif" N="9"></L>
<L>&THORN;is wordes by &thorn;am may be sayd here,</L>
<L>&THORN;at wil noght understand ne lere</L>
<L>To drede God and to do his wille,</L>
<L N="292">Bot folowes &thorn;air likyng and lyves ille.</L>
<L>Som understandes als &thorn;ai here telle,</L>
<L>Bot na drede in &thorn;air hertes may dwelle,</L>
<L>And thurgh defaut of trouthe &thorn;at may be;</L>
<L N="296">For &thorn;ai trow nathyng bot &thorn;at &thorn;ai se,</L>
<L>But groches when &thorn;ai dredful thyng here;</L>
<L>&THORN;arfor &thorn;e prophet says on &thorn;is manere:</L>
<L><I>Non crediderunt</I></L>
<L N="300"><I>et murmuraverunt.</I></L>
<L>&THORN;e prophet sayd "&thorn;ai trowed noght,</L>
<L>And groched" and was angred, in thoght;</L>
<L>&THORN;us er many &thorn;at trowes na thyng</L>
<L N="304">&THORN;at men &thorn;am says ogayn &thorn;air likyng,</L>
<L>Bot groches gretly and waxes fraward,</L>
<L>When men says oght, &thorn;at &thorn;am thynk hard.</L>
<L>Som can se in buk swilk thyng and rede,</L>
<L N="308">Bot lightnes of hert reves &thorn;am drede,</L>
<L>Swa &thorn;at it may noght with &thorn;am dwelle</L>
<L>And &thorn;arfor says God &thorn;us in &thorn;e gospelle:</L>
<L><I>Quia ad tempus credunt, et in tempore</I></L>
<L N="312"><I>temptacionis recedunt.</I></L>
<L>"Til a tyme", he says, "some trowes a thyng</L>
<L>And passes &thorn;ar-fra in &thorn;e tyme of fandyng."</L>
<L>Alswa &thorn;os says &thorn;e prophet David,</L>
<L N="316">In a psalme &thorn;at cordes &thorn;ar-wyth:</L>
<L><I>Et crediderunt in verbis eius. et lau|</I></L>
<L><I>daverunt laudem eius, cito, fecerunt</I></L>
<L><I>et obliti sunt opera eius.</I></L>
<L N="320">He says, "in his wordes, trowed &thorn;ai</L>
<L>And loved his lovyng als &thorn;ai couth say,</L>
<L>But tyte &thorn;ai had don, and forgat</L>
<L>His werkes, and thoght na mar of &thorn;at;"</L>
<L N="324">Swilk men er ay swa unstedfast,</L>
<L>&THORN;at na drede may with &thorn;am last,
<PB REF="00000054.tif" N="10"></L>
<L>For &thorn;ai er swa wilde, when &thorn;ai haf quert,</L>
<L>&THORN;at na drede &thorn;ai can hald in hert;</L>
<L N="328">Bot wha-swa can noght drede may lere,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;is tretice wil rede or here;</L>
<L>Yf &thorn;ai rede or here, til &thorn;e hende,</L>
<L>&THORN;e maters &thorn;at er &thorn;ar-in contende,</L>
<L N="332">And undirstand &thorn;am al and trow,</L>
<L>Parchaunce &thorn;air hertes &thorn;an sal bow,</L>
<L>Thurgh drede &thorn;at &thorn;ai sal consayve &thorn;ar by,</L>
<L>To wirk gude werkes and fle foli.</L>
<L N="336">&THORN;arfor &thorn;is buke es on Ynglese drawen,</L>
<L>Of sere maters, &thorn;at er unknawen</L>
<L>Til laude men &thorn;at er unkunnand,</L>
<L>&THORN;at can na latyn understand,</L>
<L N="340">To make &thorn;am &thorn;am-self first knaw</L>
<L>And fra syn and vanytese &thorn;am draw,</L>
<L>And for to stir &thorn;am til right drede,</L>
<L>When &thorn;ai &thorn;is tretisce here or rede,</L>
<L N="344">&THORN;at sal prikke &thorn;air conscience with-yn,</L>
<L>And of &thorn;at drede may a lofe bygyn</L>
<L>Thurgh comfort of ioyes of heven sere,</L>
<L>&THORN;at men may aftirwar[d] rede and here.</L>
<L N="348">&THORN;is buk, als it-self bers wittenes,</L>
<L>In seven partes divised es.</L>
<L>&THORN;e first party, to knaw and hafe in mynde,</L>
<L>Es of &thorn;e wrechednes of mans kynde.</L>
<L>&THORN;e secunde es of &thorn;e condicions sere</L>
<L N="353">And of &thorn;e unstabelnes of &thorn;is werld here.</L>
<L>&THORN;e thred parte es in &thorn;is buke to rede</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e dede and whi it es to drede.</L>
<L>&THORN;e ferthe part es of purgatory,</L>
<L N="357">Whar saules er clensed of alle foly.</L>
<L>&THORN;e fift es of &thorn;e day of dome,</L>
<L>And of taknes &thorn;at befor sal come.</L>
<L>&THORN;e sext es of &thorn;e payns of helle</L>
<L N="361">&THORN;ar &thorn;e dampned sal ever-mare dwelle.</L>
<L>&THORN;e sevend es of &thorn;e ioys of heven.</L>
<L>&THORN;er er &thorn;e partes of &thorn;is buk seven,
<PB REF="00000055.tif" N="11"></L>
<L N="364">And of ilka parte fynd men may</L>
<L>Sere maters in &thorn;is buk to say.</L>
<L>Ga we now til &thorn;at parte &thorn;at first es,</L>
<L>&THORN;at spekes of mans wrechednes;</L>
<L N="368">For alle &thorn;at byfor es wryten to luk,</L>
<L>Es bot als an entr&eacute; of &thorn;is buk.</L>
</LG>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 N="1" TYPE="book">
<HEAD>Here bygynnes &thorn;e first part &thorn;at es of mans wrechednes.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="372">First whan God made al thyng of noght,</L>
<L>Of the foulest matere man he wroght</L>
<L>&THORN;at was of erthe; for twa skyls to halde;</L>
<L>&THORN;e tane es forthy &thorn;at God walde</L>
<L N="376">Of foul matere, mak man in despite<NOTE PLACE="foot"><P>MS. Addit. 11305 reads:</P><LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"Of so foule matere man make, as in despite</L>
<L>Of the foule fende, him therwith to edwyte."</L>
</LG></NOTE></L>
<L>Of Lucifer &thorn;at fel als tyte</L>
<L>Til helle, als he had synned thurgh pride,</L>
<L>And of alle &thorn;at with him fel &thorn;at tyde;</L>
<L N="380">For &thorn;ai suld have &thorn;an &thorn;e mare shenshepe,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e mare sorow when &thorn;ai tuk kepe,</L>
<L>&THORN;at men of swa foul matere suld duelle</L>
<L>In &thorn;at place fra whilk &thorn;ai felle.</L>
<L N="384">&THORN;e tother skille es &thorn;is to se;</L>
<L>For man suld here &thorn;e meker be</L>
<L>Ay, when he sese and thynkes in thoght,</L>
<L>Of how foul mater he is wroght;</L>
<L N="388">For God, thurgh his gudnes and his myght,</L>
<L>Wald, &thorn;at sen &thorn;at place in heven bright</L>
<L>Was made voyde thurgh &thorn;e syn of pride,</L>
<L>It war filled ogayne on ilka syde</L>
<L N="392">Thurgh &thorn;e vertu of mekenes,</L>
<L>&THORN;at even contrary til pryde es;</L>
<L>&THORN;an may na man &thorn;ider come</L>
<L>Bot he &thorn;at meke es, and boghsome;</L>
<L N="396">&THORN;at proves &thorn;e gospelle &thorn;at says us,</L>
<L>How God sayd til his disciples &thorn;us:
<PB REF="00000056.tif" N="12"></L>
<L><I>Nisi efficiamini sicut parvulus, non intrabitis</I></L>
<L><I>in regnum celorum.</I></L>
<L N="400">"Bot yhe", he sayde, "be als a childe,</L>
<L>&THORN;at es to say, bathe meke and mylde,</L>
<L>Yhe sal noght entre, be na way</L>
<L>Hevenryke &thorn;at sal last ay."</L>
<L N="404">&THORN;an byhoves a man ay here seke,</L>
<L>&THORN;at may tittest make him meke;</L>
<L>Bot nathyng here may meke him mare</L>
<L>&THORN;an to thynk in hert, als I sayde are,</L>
<L N="408">How he was made of a foul matere,</L>
<L>And es noght elles, bot herthe here.</L>
<L>For-&thorn;i says a clerk, als I now say,</L>
<L>'What es man bot herth and clay,</L>
<L N="412">And poudre &thorn;at with &thorn;e wynd brekes?'</L>
<L>And &thorn;arfor Iob &thorn;us to God spekes:</L>
<L><I>Memento, queso, quod sicut lutum feceris</I></L>
<L><I>me, et in pulverem reduces me.</I></L>
<L N="416">He says, "thynk, Laverd, &thorn;at als &thorn;ow made me</L>
<L>Foul erthe and clay here to be,</L>
<L>Right swa &thorn;ou sal turne me agayne</L>
<L>Til erthe and poudre"; &thorn;is es certayn.</L>
<L N="420">&THORN;an says our Laverd God almyghty</L>
<L>Agayne til man, &thorn;us shortly:</L>
<L><I>Memento, homo, quod cinis es,</I></L>
<L><I>et in cinerem reverteris.</I></L>
<L N="424">"Thynk man", he says, "askes er-tow now,</L>
<L>And in to askes agayn turn sal-tow."</L>
<L>&THORN;an es a man noght elles to say</L>
<L>Bot askes and pouder, erthe and clay;</L>
<L N="428">Of &thorn;is suld ilk man here haf mynde</L>
<L>And knawe &thorn;e wrechednes of mans kynde,</L>
<L>&THORN;at may be sene, als I shewe can,</L>
<L>In al &thorn;e partys of &thorn;e lyfe of man.</L>
<L N="432">Alle mans lyfe casten may be,</L>
<L>Principaly, in &thorn;is partes thre,</L>
<L>&THORN;at er &thorn;ir to our understandyng;</L>
<L>Bygynnyng, midward, and endyng.
<PB REF="00000057.tif" N="13"></L>
<L N="436">&THORN;er &thorn;re partes er &thorn;re spaces talde</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e lyf of ilk man, yhung and alde.</L>
<L>Bygynnyng of mans lyf, &thorn;at first es,</L>
<L>Contenes mykel wrechednes;</L>
<L N="440">&THORN;arfor I wille, ar [I] forthir pas,</L>
<L>Shew yhou what a man first was;</L>
<L>Some tyme was when a man was noght,</L>
<L>Befor &thorn;at he was geten and forth-broght.</L>
<L N="444">He was geten aftir, als es knawen,</L>
<L>Of vile sede of man with syn sawen;</L>
<L>He was consayved synfully</L>
<L>With-in his awen moder body,</L>
<L N="448">Whar his herber with-in was dight,</L>
<L>Als David says in &thorn;e psauter right:</L>
<L><I>Ecce in iniquitatibus conceptus sum, et in</I></L>
<L><I>peccatis concepit me mater mea.</I></L>
<L N="452">"Lo", he says, "als man-kynd es</L>
<L>I am consayved in wykkednes,</L>
<L>And my moder has consayved me</L>
<L>In syn and in cayteft&eacute;."</L>
<L N="456">&THORN;ar duellid man in a myrk dungeon,</L>
<L>And in a foul sted of corupcion,</L>
<L>Whar he had na other fode</L>
<L>Bot wlatsom glet, and loper blode,<NOTE PLACE="foot">'Bot lothsom glette and filthede of blode.' MS. Addit. 11305.</NOTE></L>
<L N="460">And stynk and filthe, als I sayde ar,</L>
<L>With &thorn;er he was first norisshed &thorn;ar.</L>
<L>Aftir-warde, when he out came</L>
<L>From &thorn;at dungeon, his moder wame,</L>
<L N="464">And was born til &thorn;is werldys light,</L>
<L>He ne had nouther strenthe ne myght,</L>
<L>Nouther to ga ne yhit to stand,</L>
<L>Ne to crepe with fote, ne with hand.</L>
<L N="468">&THORN;an has a man les myght &thorn;an a beste</L>
<L>When he es born, and es sene leste:</L>
<L>For a best when it es born, may ga</L>
<L>Als tite aftir, and ryn to and fra;
<PB REF="00000058.tif" N="14"></L>
<L N="472">Bot a man has na myght &thorn;ar-to,</L>
<L>When he es born, swa to do;</L>
<L>For &thorn;an may he noght stande ne crepe</L>
<L>Bot ligge and sprawel, and cry and wepe.</L>
<L N="476">For unnethes es a child born fully</L>
<L>&THORN;at it ne bygynnes to goule and cry;</L>
<L>And by &thorn;at cry men knaw &thorn;an</L>
<L>Whether it be man or weman,</L>
<L N="480">For when it es born it cryes swa:<NOTE PLACE="foot">MSS. Addit 22283, 11305 read 'wa'.</NOTE></L>
<L>If it be man it says "a. a",</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e first letter es of &thorn;e nam</L>
<L>Of our forme-fader Adam.</L>
<L N="484">And if &thorn;e child a woman be,</L>
<L>When it es born it says "e. e."</L>
<L>E. es &thorn;e first letter and &thorn;e hede</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e name of Eve &thorn;at bygan our dede.</L>
<L N="488">&THORN;arfor a clerk made on &thorn;is manere</L>
<L>&THORN;is vers of metre &thorn;at es wreten here:</L>
<L><I>Dicentes E. vel A. quot-quot nascuntur ab Eva.</I></L>
<L>"Alle &thorn;as", he says, "&thorn;at comes of Eve,</L>
<L N="492">&THORN;at es al men &thorn;at here byhoves leve,</L>
<L>When &thorn;ai er born what-swa &thorn;ai be,</L>
<L>&THORN;ai say outher a. a, or e. e."</L>
<L>&THORN;us es here &thorn;e bygynnyng</L>
<L N="496">Of our lyfe sorow and gretyng,</L>
<L>Til whilk our wrechednes stirres us;</L>
<L>And &thorn;arfor Innocent says &thorn;us:</L>
<L><I>Omnes nascimur eiulantes,</I></L>
<L N="500"><I>ut nature nostre miseriam</I></L>
<L><I>exprimamus.</I></L>
<L>He says, "al er we born gretand,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>He saith: "we ben ybore everichone</L>
<L>Making sorwe and reuly mone." MS. Addit 11305</L>
</LG></NOTE></L>
<L>And makand a sorowful sembland,</L>
<L N="504">For to shew &thorn;e grete wrechednes</L>
<L>Of our kynd &thorn;at in us es."
<PB REF="00000059.tif" N="15"></L>
<L>&THORN;us when &thorn;e tyme come of our birthe,</L>
<L>Al made sorow and na mirthe;</L>
<L N="508">Naked we come hider, and bare</L>
<L>And pure, swa sal we hethen fare;</L>
<L>Of &thorn;is twa tymes we suld thynk &thorn;an,</L>
<L>For &thorn;us says Iob, &thorn;e rightwes man:</L>
<L N="512"><I>Nudus egressus sum de utero matris</I></L>
<L><I>mee, et nudus revertar illuc.</I></L>
<L>"Naked", he says, "first I cam</L>
<L>Hyder, out of my moder wam,</L>
<L N="516">And naked I sal turne away."</L>
<L>Swa sal we al at our last day.</L>
<L>&THORN;us a man es, at &thorn;e first comyng,</L>
<L>Naked, and bringes with him nathyng;</L>
<L N="520">Bot a rym<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. Lansd. 348 reads 'slow'. MS. Addit 22283 reads 'slouh'. MS. Ad|dit 11305 reads 'reme'.</NOTE> &thorn;at es ful wlatsome,</L>
<L>Es his garment when he forth sal com,</L>
<L>&THORN;at es noght bot a blody skyn</L>
<L>&THORN;at he byfor was lapped in,</L>
<L N="524">Whils he in his moder wam lay,</L>
<L>&THORN;e whilk es a foul thyng to say,</L>
<L>And fouler to here, als says &thorn;e buke,</L>
<L>And aldir-foules<NOTE PLACE="foot">aldir foulest (MS. Harl. 4196.)</NOTE> on to loke;</L>
<L N="528">&THORN;us es a man, als we may se,</L>
<L>In wrechednes borne and cayteft&eacute;,</L>
<L>And for to life here a fon dayse,</L>
<L>&THORN;ar-for Iob &thorn;us openly sayse;</L>
<L N="532"><I>Homo, natus de muliere, brevi vivens</I></L>
<L><I>tempore, repletur multis miseriis.</I></L>
<L>He says, "Man &thorn;at born es of woman<NOTE PLACE="foot"><LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>He saith: "after that a man is bor of a woman</L>
<L>He lyveth but short tyme, and sone bicometh wan." MS. Addit 11305.</L>
</LG></NOTE></L>
<L>Lyfand short time to<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>to</I> is superfluous?</NOTE> ful-fild es &thorn;an</L>
<L N="536">Of many maners of wrechednes."</L>
<L>&THORN;us says Iob, and swa it es,
<PB REF="00000060.tif" N="16"></L>
<L>Alswa man es borne til noght elles</L>
<L>Bot to travayle, als Iob yhit telles:</L>
<L N="540"><I>Homo nascitur ad laborem,</I></L>
<L><I>sicut avis ad volatum.</I></L>
<L>He says, "man es born to travaile right</L>
<L>Als a foul es to &thorn;e flight."</L>
<L N="544">For littel rest in &thorn;is lyf es,</L>
<L>Bot gret travayle and bysynes;</L>
<L>Yhit a man es, when he es born,</L>
<L>&THORN;e fendes son, and fra God es lorn</L>
<L N="548">Ay, til he thurgh grace may com</L>
<L>Til baptem and til cristendom;</L>
<L>&THORN;us may a man his bygynnyng se</L>
<L>Ful of wrechednes and of caytift&eacute;.</L>
<L N="552">&THORN;e tother part of &thorn;e lyf, men calles</L>
<L>&THORN;e mydward, aftir &thorn;at it falles,</L>
<L>&THORN;e wilk reches fra &thorn;e bygynnyng</L>
<L>Of mans lyfe un-til &thorn;e endyng.</L>
<L N="556">&THORN;e bygynnyng of man, als I talde,</L>
<L>Es vile and wreched to behalde;</L>
<L>Bot how foule es man aftir-warde</L>
<L>Tels &thorn;us, openly, saynt Bernarde:</L>
<L N="560"><I>Homo nihil aliud est, quam sperma</I></L>
<L><I>fetidum, saccus stercorum et esca vermium.</I></L>
<L>Saynt Bernard says als &thorn;e buke telles,</L>
<L N="564">&THORN;at "man here es nathyng elles</L>
<L>Bot a foule slyme, wlatsome til men,</L>
<L>And a sekful of stynkand fen,</L>
<L>And wormes fode" &thorn;at &thorn;ai wald have,</L>
<L N="568">When he es dede and layde in grave.</L>
<L>Bot som men and women fayre semes</L>
<L>To &thorn;e syght with-outen, als men demes,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at shewes noght elles bot a skyn;</L>
<L>Bot wha-swa moght se &thorn;am with-in,</L>
<L N="572">Fouler carion moght never be</L>
<L>&THORN;an he suld &thorn;an of &thorn;am se.</L>
<L>&THORN;arfor he &thorn;at had als sharp syght,</L>
<L>And cler eghen and als bright
<PB REF="00000061.tif" N="17"></L>
<L N="576">Als has a best &thorn;at men Lynx calles,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'As hath a beste that men lynx calles,</L>
<L>That may se thurgh <I>nyne stoon walles</I>. MS. Addit 11305.</L>
</LG></NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at may se thurgh thik stane walles,</L>
<L>Littel lykyng suld a man haf &thorn;an</L>
<L>For to behald a faire woman,</L>
<L N="580">For &thorn;an mught he se, with-outen doute,</L>
<L>Als wele with-in als with-oute,</L>
<L>And if he with-in saw hir right,</L>
<L>Sho war ful wlatsom til his sight;</L>
<L N="584">&THORN;us foul with-in ilk man es,</L>
<L>Als &thorn;e buk says and bers witnes.</L>
<L>&THORN;an may we se on &thorn;is manere,</L>
<L>How foul &thorn;e kynd of man es here;</L>
<L N="588">Whar-for I hald a man noght witty</L>
<L>&THORN;at here es over-prowde and ioly,</L>
<L>When he may ilk day here and se</L>
<L>What he es, and was, and sal be.</L>
<L N="592">Bot proud man of &thorn;is tas na hede</L>
<L>For hym wantes skille, &thorn;at hym suld lede,</L>
<L>When he es yhung and luffes laykyng,</L>
<L>Or has ese, and welth, and his lykyng;</L>
<L N="596">Or if he be at grete worshepe,</L>
<L>What hym-self es &thorn;an, he tas na kepe;</L>
<L>Whar-for him-self &thorn;an knawes he leste</L>
<L>And fares als an unresonabel beste,</L>
<L N="600">&THORN;at his awen wille folowes, and noght elles,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ar-for &thorn;e prophet in &thorn;e psauter telles:</L>
<L><I>Homo, cum in honore esset, non intellexit, comparatus</I></L>
<L><I>estiumentis insipientibus, et similis factus est illis.</I></L>
<L N="604">"Man when he is til worshepe broght</L>
<L>Right understandyng has he noght:</L>
<L>He may be likend and he es lyke &thorn;an</L>
<L>Til bestes, &thorn;at na skylle ne witte can;"</L>
<L N="608">&THORN;arfor ilk man &thorn;at has witte and mynde,</L>
<L>Suld thynk of &thorn;e wrechednes of his kynde,</L>
<L>&THORN;at es foul, and vile, and wlatsom;</L>
<L>For he may se fra his body com,
<PB REF="00000062.tif" N="18"></L>
<L N="612">Bathe fra aboven and fra bynethe,</L>
<L>Alkyn filthe with stynkand brethe;</L>
<L>For mar filthe es nane, hard ne nesshe,</L>
<L>&THORN;an es &thorn;at comes fra a mans flesshe;</L>
<L N="616">And &thorn;at may a man bathe se and fele,</L>
<L>&THORN;at wil byhald him-self wele,</L>
<L>How foul he es to mans syght,</L>
<L>And &thorn;arfor says Saynt Bernard right:</L>
<L N="620"><I>Si diligenter consideres quid per os,</I></L>
<L><I>quid per nares, ceterosque meatus</I></L>
<L><I>corporis egreditur, vilius sterquilinium</I></L>
<L><I>nunquam vidisti.</I></L>
<L N="624">"If &thorn;ow wille", he says, "ententyfly se,</L>
<L>And by-hald what comes fra &thorn;e</L>
<L>What thurgh mouthe, what thurgh nese, commonly,</L>
<L><NOTE PLACE="foot">'And other issues of the body: A fouler dongehull sawe thou never none.' MS. Addit 11305:</NOTE>And thurgh other overtes of his<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;e (MS. Harl. 4196).</NOTE> body,</L>
<L N="628">A fouler myddyng saw &thorn;ow never nane,"</L>
<L>&THORN;an a man es, with flesche and bane.</L>
<L>Al &thorn;e tyme &thorn;at a man here lyves,</L>
<L>His kynd na other fruyt gyfes,</L>
<L N="632">Whether he lyf lang or short while,</L>
<L>Bot thyng that es wlatsome and vile,</L>
<L>Als filth and stynk and nathynge elles,</L>
<L>Als Innocent &thorn;us in a boke telles:</L>
<L N="636"><I>Herbas et arbores, inquit, investiga: Ille de se</I></L>
<L><I>producunt flores, frondes et fructus; et</I></L>
<L><I>tu de te lendes, pediculos et lumbricos.</I></L>
<L><I>Ille diffundunt oleum, vinum, et balsamum; et</I></L>
<L N="640"><I>tu de te sputum, urinam, et stercus: Ille</I></L>
<L><I>de se spirant suavitatem odoris; et tu</I></L>
<L><I>de te reddis abhominationem fetoris.</I></L>
<L><I>Qualis est arbor, talis est fructus.</I></L>
<L N="644">&THORN;is gret clerk telles &thorn;us in a buke:</L>
<L>"Behalde", he says, "graythely and loke,</L>
<L>Herbes and trese &thorn;at &thorn;ou sees spryng,</L>
<L>And take gude kepe what &thorn;ai forth bryng;
<PB REF="00000063.tif" N="19"></L>
<L N="648">Herbes forth bringes floures and sede,</L>
<L>And tres fair fruyt and braunches to spede,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Sprede (MS. Harl. 4196).</NOTE></L>
<L>And &thorn;ou forth bringes of &thorn;i-self here</L>
<L>Nites, lyse, and other vermyn sere.</L>
<L N="652">Of herbes and tres, springes baum ful gude,</L>
<L>And oyle and wyne for mans fude;</L>
<L>And of &thorn;e comes mykel foul thyng,</L>
<L>Als fen, and uryn and spyttyng;</L>
<L N="656">Of herbes and tres comes swete savour,</L>
<L>And of &thorn;e comes wlatsome stynk, and sour;</L>
<L>Swilk als &thorn;e tre es with bowes,</L>
<L>Swilk es &thorn;e fruyt &thorn;at on it growes."</L>
<L N="660">An ille tre may na gude fruyt bere,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at knawes ilk gude gardynere.</L>
<L>A man es a tre, &thorn;at standes noght harde,</L>
<L>Of whilk &thorn;e crop es turned donward,</L>
<L N="664">And &thorn;e rote to-ward &thorn;e firmament,</L>
<L>Als says &thorn;e grete clerk Innocent:</L>
<L><I>Quid est homo, secundum formam, nisi quedam</I></L>
<L><I>arbor eversa, cujus radices sunt crines;</I></L>
<L N="668"><I>truncus est caput cum collo; stipis estpectus cum</I></L>
<L><I>alvo, rami sunt ulne cum tibiis; frondes sunt</I></L>
<L><I>digiti cum articulis; hoc est folium quod a ven|</I></L>
<L><I>to rapitur, et stipula a sole siccatur.</I></L>
<L N="672">He says, "what es man in shap bot a tre</L>
<L>Turned up &thorn;at es doun, als men may se,</L>
<L>Of whilk &thorn;e rotes &thorn;at of it springes,</L>
<L>Er &thorn;e hares &thorn;at on &thorn;e heved hynges;</L>
<L N="676">&THORN;e stok nest &thorn;e rot growand</L>
<L>Es &thorn;e heved with nek folowand;</L>
<L>&THORN;e body of &thorn;at tre &thorn;ar-by</L>
<L>Es &thorn;e brest with &thorn;e bely;</L>
<L N="680">&THORN;e bughes er &thorn;e armes with &thorn;e handes</L>
<L>And &thorn;e legges with &thorn;e fete &thorn;at standes:</L>
<L>&THORN;e braunches men may by skille call</L>
<L>&THORN;e tas and &thorn;e fyngers alle;</L>
<L N="684">&THORN;is es &thorn;e leef &thorn;at hanges noght faste,</L>
<L>&THORN;at es blawen away thurgh a wynd blaste,
<PB REF="00000064.tif" N="20"></L>
<L>And &thorn;e body alswa of &thorn;e tre,</L>
<L>&THORN;at thurgh &thorn;e son may dried be."</L>
<L N="688">A man &thorn;at es yhung and light,</L>
<L>Be he never swa stalworth and wyght,</L>
<L>And comly of shap, lufly and fayre,</L>
<L>Angers and yvels may hym appayre,</L>
<L N="692">And his beut&eacute; and his streng[th] abate,</L>
<L>And mak hym in ful wayk state,</L>
<L>And chaunge alle fayre colour,</L>
<L>&THORN;at son fayles and fades, als dos &thorn;e flour.</L>
<L N="696">For a flour &thorn;at semes fayre and bright,</L>
<L>Thurgh stormes fades, and tynes &thorn;e myght.</L>
<L>Many yvels, angers, and mescheefes</L>
<L>Oft comes til man &thorn;at here lyves,</L>
<L N="700">Als fevyr, dropsy, and Iaunys,</L>
<L>Tysyk, goute, and other maladys,</L>
<L>&THORN;at hym mas streng[th] and fayrnes tyne,</L>
<L>Als grete stormes dose a flour to dwyne;</L>
<L N="704">&THORN;arfor a man may likend be</L>
<L>Til a flour, &thorn;at es fayre to se,</L>
<L>&THORN;an son aftir &thorn;at it es forth broght,</L>
<L>Welkes and dwynes til it be noght;</L>
<L N="708">&THORN;is aught to be ensample til us;</L>
<L>For-whi Iob, in a boke, says &thorn;us:</L>
<L><I>Homo, quasi flos, egreditur et conteritur, et fugit ve|</I></L>
<L><I>lud umbra et nunquam in eodem statu permanet.</I></L>
<L N="712">"Man", he says, "als a flour bright,</L>
<L>First forth comes here til &thorn;is light,</L>
<L>And es sone broken and passes away,</L>
<L>Als a shadu on &thorn;e somers day;</L>
<L N="716">And never mare in &thorn;e same state duelles,"</L>
<L>Bot ay passand, als Iob telles;</L>
<L>Of &thorn;is &thorn;e prophet witnes beres,</L>
<L>In a psalme of &thorn;e psauter, thurgh &thorn;is vers</L>
<L N="720"><I>Mane, sicut herba, transeat, mane floreat</I></L>
<L><I>et transeat; vespere decidat, indurat</I><NOTE PLACE="foot">indurescat?</NOTE> <I>et arescat.</I>
<PB REF="00000065.tif" N="21"></L>
<L>The prophet says &thorn;us, als writen es,</L>
<L>"Arely a man passes als &thorn;e gres,</L>
<L N="724">Arely at &thorn;e bygynnyng of &thorn;e day,</L>
<L>He floresshe and passes away;</L>
<L>At even late he is doun broght,</L>
<L>And fayles, and dries, and dwynes to noght.</L>
<L N="728">In &thorn;e first bygynnyng of &thorn;e kynd of man</L>
<L>Neghen hundreth wynter man lyfed &thorn;an,</L>
<L>Als clerkes in bukes bers witnes;</L>
<L>Bot sythen bycom mans lyf les</L>
<L N="732">And swa wald God at it suld be;</L>
<L>For-whi he sayd &thorn;us til Noe:</L>
<L><I>Non permanebit spiritus meus</I></L>
<L><I>in homine in eternum, quia caro</I></L>
<L N="736"><I>est, erunt dies illius centum</I></L>
<L><I>viginti annorum.</I></L>
<L>"My gast," he says, "sal noght ay dwelle</L>
<L>In man, for he is flesshe and felle;</L>
<L N="740">Hys days sal be for to life here</L>
<L>An hundreth and twenti yhere."</L>
<L>Bot swa grete elde may nane now bere,</L>
<L>For sythen mans lyfe bycom shortere.</L>
<L N="744">For-whi &thorn;e complection of ilk man</L>
<L>Was sythen febler &thorn;an it was &thorn;an;</L>
<L>Now es it alther-feblest to se,</L>
<L>&THORN;arfor mans life short byhoves be;</L>
<L N="748">For ay &thorn;e langer &thorn;at man may lyfe,</L>
<L>&THORN;e mare his lyfe sal hym now griefe,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e les him sal thynk his lyf swete,</L>
<L>Als in a psalme, says &thorn;e prophete:</L>
<L N="752"><I>Si autem in potentatibus octogynta an|</I></L>
<L><I>ni, et amplius eorum labor et dolor.</I></L>
<L>"If in myghtfulnes four scor yhere falle,</L>
<L>Mare es &thorn;air swynk and sorow with-alle."</L>
<L N="756">For seldom a man &thorn;at has &thorn;at held,<NOTE PLACE="foot">held = 'eld'.</NOTE></L>
<L>Hele has, and him-self may weld;
<PB REF="00000066.tif" N="22"></L>
<L>Bot now falles yhit shorter mans dayes,</L>
<L>Als Iob, &thorn;e haly man, &thorn;us says:</L>
<L N="760"><I>Nunc paucitas dierum meorum</I></L>
<L><I>finietur brevi.</I></L>
<L>"Now," he says, "my fon days sere</L>
<L>Sal enden with a short tyme here."</L>
<L N="764">Fone men may now fourty yhere pas,</L>
<L>And foner fifty als in somtym was;</L>
<L>Bot als tyte als a man waxes alde,</L>
<L>&THORN;an waxes his kynde wayke and calde,</L>
<L N="768">&THORN;an chaunges his complexcion</L>
<L>And his maners and his condicion;</L>
<L>Than waxes his hert hard and hevy,</L>
<L>And his heved feble and dysy;</L>
<L N="772">&THORN;an waxes his gaste seke and sare,</L>
<L>And his face rouncles, ay mare and mare;</L>
<L>His mynde es short when he oght thynkes,</L>
<L>His nese ofte droppes, his hand<NOTE PLACE="foot">i. e. <I>and</I> = breath.</NOTE> stynkes,</L>
<L N="776">His sight wax dym &thorn;at he has,</L>
<L>His bak waxes croked, stoupand he gas</L>
<L>Fyngers and taes, fote and hande,</L>
<L>Alle his touches<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. Lansd. 348 reads 'lymmes'.</NOTE> er tremblande:</L>
<L N="780">His werkes for-worthes &thorn;at he bygynnes,<NOTE PLACE="foot">'His werkes forweren that he bygynneth'. MS. Addit 11305.</NOTE></L>
<L>His haire moutes, his eghen rynnes;</L>
<L>His eres waxes deef, and hard to here,</L>
<L>His tung fayles, his speche is noght clere.</L>
<L N="784">His mouthe slavers, his tethe rotes,</L>
<L>His wyttes fayles, and he ofte dotes;</L>
<L>He is lyghtly wrath, and waxes fraward,</L>
<L>Bot to turne hym fra wrethe it es hard;</L>
<L N="788">He souches and trowes sone a thyng,</L>
<L>Bot ful late he turnes fra &thorn;at trowyng;</L>
<L>He es covatous and hard haldand,</L>
<L>His chere es drery and his sembland;
<PB REF="00000067.tif" N="23"></L>
<L N="792">He es swyft to spek on his manere</L>
<L>And latsom and slaw for to here;</L>
<L>He prayses ald men and haldes &thorn;am wyse,</L>
<L>And yhung men list him oft despyse;</L>
<L N="796">He loves men &thorn;at in ald tyme has bene,</L>
<L>He lakes &thorn;a men &thorn;at now are sene;</L>
<L>He is ofte seke and ay granand,</L>
<L>And ofte angerd, and ay pleynand;</L>
<L N="800">Alle &thorn;ir, thurgh kynd, to an ald man falles,</L>
<L>&THORN;at clerkes propert&eacute;s of eld calles.</L>
<L>Yhit er &thorn;ar ma &thorn;an I haf talde,</L>
<L>&THORN;at falles to a man &thorn;at es alde.</L>
<L N="804">&THORN;us may men se, wha-so can,</L>
<L>What &thorn;e condicions er of an ald man.</L>
<L>&THORN;e last ende of mans lyfe es hard,</L>
<L>&THORN;at es, when he drawes to ded-ward.</L>
<L N="808">For when he is seke, and bedreden lys,</L>
<L>And swa feble &thorn;at he may noght rys,</L>
<L>&THORN;an er men in dout and noght certayn,</L>
<L>Wethir he sal ever cover agayn.</L>
<L N="812">Bot yhit can som men, &thorn;at er sleghe,</L>
<L>Witte if he sal of &thorn;at yvel deghe</L>
<L>By certayne takens, als yhe sal here,</L>
<L>&THORN;at byfalles when &thorn;e ded es nere;</L>
<L N="816">&THORN;an bygynnes his frount dounward falle,</L>
<L>And his browes heldes doun wyth-alle;</L>
<L>&THORN;e lefte eghe of hym &thorn;an semes les,</L>
<L>And narower &thorn;an &thorn;e right eghe es;</L>
<L N="820">Hys nese, at &thorn;e poynt, es sharp and smalle,</L>
<L>&THORN;an bygynnes his chyn to falle;</L>
<L>His pouce es stille, with-outen styringes,</L>
<L>His fete waxes calde, his bely clynges.</L>
<L N="824">And if nere &thorn;e dede be a yhung man,</L>
<L>He ay wakes, and may noght slepe &thorn;an;</L>
<L>And an aldeman to dede drawand</L>
<L>May noght wake, bot es ay slepand;</L>
<L N="828">Men says, al &thorn;ir takens sere</L>
<L>Er of a man &thorn;at &thorn;e dede es nere.
<PB REF="00000068.tif" N="24"></L>
<L>Whiles a man lyves he is lyke a man;</L>
<L>When he es dede what es he lyke &thorn;an?</L>
<L N="832">&THORN;an may men his liknes se</L>
<L>Chaunged, als it had never bene he;</L>
<L>And when his lyf es broght to &thorn;e ende,</L>
<L>&THORN;an sal he on &thorn;e same wys hethen wende,</L>
<L N="836">Pure and naked, right als he cam</L>
<L>&THORN;e first day fra his moder wam.</L>
<L>For he broght with him nathyng &thorn;at day,</L>
<L>And noght sal he bere with him away,</L>
<L N="840">Bot it be a wyndyng clathe anely,</L>
<L>&THORN;at sal be lapped obout his body;</L>
<L>&THORN;us wrechedly endes &thorn;e lyf of man.</L>
<L>And if we behalde what he es &thorn;an,</L>
<L N="844">When &thorn;e lyfe of hym passes oway,</L>
<L>&THORN;an es he noght bot erthe and clay</L>
<L>&THORN;at turnes til mare corrupcion,</L>
<L>&THORN;an ever had stynkand carion.</L>
<L N="848">For &thorn;e corrupcion of his body,</L>
<L>Yf it suld lang oboven erthe ly,</L>
<L>It myght &thorn;e ayr swa corrumpud mak,</L>
<L>&THORN;at men &thorn;arof &thorn;e dede suld take,</L>
<L N="852">Swa vile it es and violent;</L>
<L>&THORN;arfor &thorn;e gret clerk says, Innocent:</L>
<L><I>Quid enim fetidius humano cadavere,</I></L>
<L><I>quid horibilius homine mortuo.</I></L>
<L N="856">He says, "What-kyn thyng may fouler be</L>
<L>&THORN;an a mans carion es to se:</L>
<L>And what es mar horibel in stede</L>
<L>&THORN;an a man es when he es dede?"</L>
<L N="860">Alswa [I] say, nathyng es swa ugly,</L>
<L>Als here es a mans dede body;</L>
<L>And when it es in erth layd lawe,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'And whan it es in erthe bywounde,</L>
<L>Wormes wol him gnawe on every stounde'. MS. Addit 11305.</L>
</LG></NOTE></L>
<L>Wormes &thorn;an sal it al to-gnaw,</L>
<L N="864">Til &thorn;e flesshe be gnawen oway and byten;</L>
<L>For-why we fynde &thorn;os in buk writen:
<PB REF="00000069.tif" N="25"></L>
<L><I>Cum autem morietur homo, heredita|</I></L>
<L><I>bit vermes et serpentes.</I></L>
<L N="868">&THORN;e buk says &thorn;us, "&thorn;at when a man</L>
<L>Sal dighe he sal enherite &thorn;an</L>
<L>Wormes and nedders," ugly in sight,</L>
<L>Til wham falles mans flessh, thurgh right,</L>
<L N="872">&THORN;arfor in erthe man sal slepe,</L>
<L>Oman[g] wormes, &thorn;at on hym sal crepe,</L>
<L>And gnaw on &thorn;at stynkand carcays,</L>
<L>Als es wryten in a bok &thorn;at says:</L>
<L N="876"><I>Omnes in pulvere dormient, et</I></L>
<L><I>vermes operient eos.</I></L>
<L>&THORN;at es "in pouder sal slepe ilk man,</L>
<L>And wormes sal cover hym &thorn;an;"</L>
<L N="880">For in &thorn;is world es nane swa witty,</L>
<L>Swa fair, swa strang, ne swa myghty,</L>
<L>Emperour, kyng, duke, ne caysere,</L>
<L>Ne other &thorn;at bers grete state here,</L>
<L N="884">Ne riche, ne pure, bond ne fre,</L>
<L>Lered or lawed, what-swa he be,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he ne sal turne at &thorn;e last oway,</L>
<L>Til poudre and erthe and vyle clay;</L>
<L N="888">And wormes sal ryve hym in sondre;</L>
<L>And &thorn;arfor haf I mykel wondere</L>
<L>&THORN;at unnethes any man wille se</L>
<L>What he was, and what he sal be.</L>
<L N="892">Bot wha-so wald in hert cast</L>
<L>What he was, and sal be at &thorn;e last,</L>
<L>And what he es, whyles he lyves here,</L>
<L>He suld fynd ful litel matere</L>
<L N="896">To mak ioy whilles he here duelles,</L>
<L>Als a versifiour in metre &thorn;us telles:</L>
<L><I>Si quis sentiret, quo tendit, et unde veniret,</I></L>
<L><I>Nunquam gauderet, sed in omne tempore fleret.</I></L>
<L N="900">He says, "wha-so wille fele and se,</L>
<L>Wethen he com and whider sal he,</L>
<L>Suld never be blythe bot ioy forsake,</L>
<L>And alle tyme grete and sorow make."
<PB REF="00000070.tif" N="26"></L>
<L N="904">Whar-to &thorn;an es man here swa myry,</L>
<L>And swa tendre of his vile body,</L>
<L>&THORN;at sal rote and with wormes be gnawen,</L>
<L>And swa ugly to syght may be knawen?</L>
<L N="908">Loverd wha-so of him &thorn;an had syght,</L>
<L>Aftir &thorn;at wormes him swa had dight,</L>
<L>And gnawen his flesshe un to &thorn;e bane,</L>
<L>Swa grysly a sight saw he never nane,</L>
<L N="912">Als he myght se of &thorn;at vile carcays:</L>
<L>For Saynt Bernard &thorn;os in metre says:</L>
<L><I>Post hominem vermis, post vermem, fetor et horror,</I></L>
<L><I>Et sic, in non hominem vertitur omnis homo.</I></L>
<L N="916">"Aftir man", he says, "vermyn es,</L>
<L>And aftir vermyn stynkand uglynes;</L>
<L>And swa sal ilk man turned be &thorn;an</L>
<L>Fra a man intil na man."</L>
<L N="920">&THORN;os may ilk man in &thorn;is parte se,</L>
<L>What he was, and what he sal be,</L>
<L>And what he es ay whils he here lyfes,</L>
<L>And whatkyn fruyt his kynd here gyves.</L>
<L N="924">Here may men se, als writen es,</L>
<L>Mikel of mans wrechednes,</L>
<L>And mykel mare yhit may men telle,</L>
<L>Bot here-on wille I na langer duelle.</L>
<L N="928">Ga we now forther-mar and luke,</L>
<L>To &thorn;e secund part of &thorn;is buke,</L>
<L>In whilk men may haf understandyng</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e world, and of worldysshe lyfyng.</L>
</LG>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 N="2" TYPE="book">
<HEAD>Here bygynnes &thorn;e secunde part &thorn;at es of &thorn;e world.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Alle &thorn;e world so wyde and brade,</L>
<L>Our Lord speciali for man made,</L>
<L N="936">And al other thynge, als clerkes can profe,</L>
<L>He made anly to mans by-hove.</L>
<L>Sen he al &thorn;e world and alle thynge wroght</L>
<L>Til mans by-hove, &thorn;an man aght noght</L>
<L N="940">Lufe nowther worldisshe thyng ne bodily,</L>
<L>Mare &thorn;an our Lord God almyghty,
<PB REF="00000071.tif" N="27"></L>
<L>Ne als mykel as God, &thorn;ogh &thorn;at war les;</L>
<L>And wha-so dos, unkynd he es;</L>
<L N="944">For God war worthy mare to be lufed</L>
<L>&THORN;an any creature, and swa byhufed,</L>
<L>Syn he es maker of althynge,</L>
<L>And of alle creatures &thorn;e bygynnynge.</L>
<L N="948">&THORN;is say [I] by men &thorn;at gyves &thorn;am mykel</L>
<L>Til &thorn;is world, &thorn;at es fals and fikel,</L>
<L>And lufes alle thynge &thorn;at til it falles;</L>
<L>Swilk men worldisshe men, men calles</L>
<L N="952">&THORN;at &thorn;air luf mast on &thorn;e world settes,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at luf, &thorn;e luf of God lettes.</L>
<L>&THORN;arfor gude it es &thorn;at a man him kepe,</L>
<L>Fra worldisshe luf and vany worshepe.</L>
<L N="956">For thurgh luf of &thorn;is world and vanit&eacute;,</L>
<L>A man at &thorn;e last forbard may be,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e blisful world &thorn;ar al ioy es,</L>
<L>Whar &thorn;e lyfe of man sal be endles,</L>
<L N="960">&THORN;at dos to God here &thorn;at hym falles,</L>
<L>&THORN;at world &thorn;er clerkes 'world of world' calles.</L>
<L>Whi<NOTE PLACE="foot">For-whi?</NOTE> alle &thorn;e world &thorn;at God walde make</L>
<L>For man, of whilk I byfor spake,</L>
<L N="964">&THORN;at swa generaly here is tane,</L>
<L>May be undirstanden ma worldes &thorn;an ane;</L>
<L>For a grete clerk says, &thorn;at hight Berthelmewe,</L>
<L>&THORN;at twa worldes er principaly to shewe,</L>
<L N="968">&THORN;at &thorn;e elementes and al &thorn;e hevens</L>
<L>Contenes, als he &thorn;am in boke nevens,</L>
<L>And alle &thorn;e creatures &thorn;at God wroght,</L>
<L>Swa &thorn;at withouten &thorn;a worldes es noght.</L>
<L N="972">&THORN;e tan es gastly, invisile and clene,</L>
<L>&THORN;e tother es bodyly and may be sene.</L>
<L>&THORN;e gastly world, &thorn;at na man may se,</L>
<L>Es heven, whar God syttes in trinit&eacute;,</L>
<L N="976">And &thorn;e neghen ordres of angels,</L>
<L>And haly spirytes in &thorn;at world duelles,
<PB REF="00000072.tif" N="28"></L>
<L>And &thorn;ider sal we com and &thorn;ar lyf ay,</L>
<L>If we &thorn;ederward hald &thorn;e right way.</L>
<L N="980">&THORN;at world was made for mans wonnyng</L>
<L>Omang angels in ioy and lykyng,</L>
<L>Evermare &thorn;ar-in for to duelle,</L>
<L>As men may here &thorn;er clerkes telle.</L>
<L N="984">Now heir-on wille I na langer stand,</L>
<L>For after-ward commes &thorn;is matere til hand.</L>
<L>&THORN;e tother world &thorn;at men may se,</L>
<L>In twa partes divised may be,</L>
<L N="988">&THORN;e whilk alle bodily thyng may hald,</L>
<L>And ayther part may a world be cald,</L>
<L>And bathe men may se and knawe;</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;e tan es heghe, and &thorn;e tother lawe;</L>
<L N="992">&THORN;e hegher reches fra &thorn;e mon even</L>
<L>Til &thorn;e heghest of &thorn;e sterned heven;</L>
<L>&THORN;at werld is ful bright and fayre,</L>
<L>For &thorn;ar es na corrupcion, bot cler ayre,</L>
<L N="996">And &thorn;e planettes and sternes shynand,</L>
<L>And sere signes and noght elles &thorn;ar wonand.</L>
<L>&THORN;e lawer werld, &thorn;at lawest may falle,</L>
<L>Contenes haly &thorn;e elementes alle,</L>
<L N="1000">&THORN;at on &thorn;e erthe and about &thorn;e erthe standes,</L>
<L>Whar sere manere of men wonnes in sere landes.</L>
<L>In &thorn;is werld es bothe wele and wa,</L>
<L>&THORN;at es ofte chaunged to and fra,</L>
<L N="1004">&THORN;at til som es softe and til sum harde,</L>
<L>Als yhe may here or se aftirwarde.</L>
<L>&THORN;ir worldes byfor als was Goddes wille,</L>
<L>For man was made for certayn skille;</L>
<L N="1008">&THORN;e heghest world, &thorn;at passes alle thyng,</L>
<L>Was made for mans endles wonnyng;</L>
<L>For ilk man sal hafe &thorn;ar a place</L>
<L>To wone ay in ioy, &thorn;at here has grace.</L>
<L N="1012">&THORN;at world was made to our most avantage,</L>
<L>For &thorn;ar falles to be our right heritage.</L>
<L>&THORN;e tother world, &thorn;at is lawer,</L>
<L>Whare &thorn;e sternes and planets er,
<PB REF="00000073.tif" N="29"></L>
<L N="1016">God ord[a]ynd anly for our byhufe,</L>
<L>By &thorn;is skille, als I can prufe.</L>
<L>&THORN;e ayre fra &thorn;e&thorn;en, and &thorn;e heat of &thorn;e son</L>
<L>Sustayns &thorn;e erthe here, &thorn;ar we won,</L>
<L N="1020">And nurisshes alle thyng &thorn;at fruyt gyves,</L>
<L>And confortes best, and man, and alle &thorn;at lyves;</L>
<L>And tempers our kynde and our complexioun,</L>
<L>And settes &thorn;e tymes of yhere in seson,</L>
<L N="1024">And gyfes us light here, whar we duelle,</L>
<L>Elles war &thorn;is world myrk als helle;</L>
<L>Yhit &thorn;e bodys of &thorn;e world in &thorn;air kynde,</L>
<L>Shewes us for bisens to haf in mynde,</L>
<L N="1028">How we suld serve God in our kynde here,</L>
<L>Als &thorn;ai do &thorn;ar, on &thorn;air manere.</L>
<L>&THORN;e lawest world was alswa made for man,</L>
<L>For &thorn;is skylle, als clerkes shew can;</L>
<L N="1032">For &thorn;at man suld be &thorn;ar-in wonnand,</L>
<L>Goddes werkes to se and undirstand,</L>
<L>And his commandmentes and his wille</L>
<L>To knawe, and kepe, and to fulfille,</L>
<L N="1036">And to be proved here in gastly batayls,</L>
<L>Of gastly enmys &thorn;at man oft assayls;</L>
<L>Swa &thorn;at &thorn;urgh gastly strenth and victori,</L>
<L>He may be made in &thorn;is world worthy</L>
<L N="1040">To haf &thorn;e coroun of blisse endeles</L>
<L>In &thorn;e blisful world &thorn;at heghest es.</L>
<L>Twa worldes here to-gyder may falle</L>
<L>&THORN;at men may erthely worldes calle.</L>
<L N="1044">An es &thorn;is dale, whar we er wonnand,</L>
<L>Another es man &thorn;ar-in lyfand;</L>
<L>&THORN;is dale whar we won thurgh, clerkes caldes</L>
<L>&THORN;e mare world, and &thorn;e man &thorn;e les.</L>
<L N="1048">Of &thorn;e les world wil I noght speke yhit,</L>
<L>For aftirward I sal speke of it;</L>
<L>Bot of &thorn;e mare world yhit wil I mare say,</L>
<L>Ar I pas fra &thorn;is matir away;</L>
<L N="1052">&THORN;an wil I after shew, als falles,</L>
<L>Skille why men a man world calles.
<PB REF="00000074.tif" N="30"></L>
<L>&THORN;e mare world God wald law on erth sett,</L>
<L>For it suld be til man suggette,</L>
<L N="1056">For to serve man, and man noght it;</L>
<L>And &thorn;us ordand God, for mans profit.</L>
<L>Bot now &thorn;is world &thorn;at man lyfes in,</L>
<L>Waxes swa lither and ful of syn,</L>
<L N="1060">And of welthes &thorn;at are bot wayn,</L>
<L>&THORN;at many mas &thorn;e world &thorn;air soverayn,</L>
<L>And gyves &thorn;am &thorn;ar-to al &thorn;at &thorn;ai may,</L>
<L>And serves it bysily, nyght and day,</L>
<L N="1064">And mas &thorn;am-selfe &thorn;e worldes tharlles.</L>
<L>&THORN;as men worldesshe men men calles,</L>
<L>For about worldisshe thynges &thorn;ai here travaile</L>
<L>Ful bysily, &thorn;at at &thorn;e last sal fayle;</L>
<L N="1068">Bot wald &thorn;ai do half swilk bysines</L>
<L>About goddes<NOTE PLACE="foot">gudes (MS. Harl. 4196).</NOTE> of heven, &thorn;ar al gude es,</L>
<L>&THORN;ai suld haf alle &thorn;at gude es &thorn;are,</L>
<L>&THORN;at never sal faille, bot last ever mare.</L>
<L N="1072">&THORN;e world &thorn;at es here, es noght elles,</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;e maners of men &thorn;at &thorn;ar-in dwelles;</L>
<L>For &thorn;is world men may noght ken,</L>
<L>Bot by &thorn;e condicions of &thorn;e worldis men.</L>
<L N="1076">For what mught men by &thorn;e world understand</L>
<L>If na worldishmen war &thorn;ar-in dwelland?</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;as men &thorn;at &thorn;e world mast dauntes,</L>
<L>Mast bisily &thorn;e world here hauntes;</L>
<L N="1080">And &thorn;as &thorn;at &thorn;e world serves and loves,</L>
<L>Serves &thorn;e devel, as &thorn;e buk proves;</L>
<L>For &thorn;e world here, es &thorn;e devels servand,</L>
<L>&THORN;at brynges his servauntes til his hand;</L>
<L N="1084">&THORN;arfor God him prince of &thorn;e world calles,</L>
<L>&THORN;at es of worldismen &thorn;at to him falles;</L>
<L>For-&thorn;i &thorn;is world es perillius to lufe,</L>
<L>By many skilles, as clerkes prove.</L>
<L N="1088">&THORN;is worlde es fikel and desayvable,</L>
<L>And fals and unsiker and unstabel.</L>
<L>Many men &thorn;e world here fraistes,</L>
<L>Bot he is noght wise &thorn;at &thorn;ar-in traystes:
<PB REF="00000075.tif" N="31"></L>
<L N="1092">For &thorn;e world laghes on man and smyles,</L>
<L>Bot at &thorn;e last it him bygyles;</L>
<L>&THORN;arfor I hald &thorn;at man noght witty</L>
<L>&THORN;at about &thorn;e world is over bysy;</L>
<L N="1096">For a man may noght Goddes servand be,</L>
<L>Bot he &thorn;e maners of &thorn;e world fle,</L>
<L>Ne lofe God, bot [he] &thorn;e world despise,</L>
<L>For &thorn;e godspel says on &thorn;is wyse:</L>
<L N="1100"><I>Nemo potest duobus dominis ser|</I></L>
<L><I>vire, quia aut enim unum odio ha|</I></L>
<L><I>bebit et alterum diliget, aut unum</I></L>
<L><I>sustinebit et alterum contempnet.</I></L>
<L N="1104">He says "na man may serve rightly</L>
<L>Twa lordes to-gedir, &thorn;at er contrary,</L>
<L>For outher he sal &thorn;e tane hate</L>
<L>And &thorn;e tother luf aftir his state,</L>
<L N="1108">Or he sal &thorn;e tane of &thorn;am mayntene,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e tother despyse", &thorn;us es ofte sene.</L>
<L>&THORN;e world es Goddes enmy by skille,</L>
<L>&THORN;at contrarius es to Goddes wille;</L>
<L N="1112">And swa er al &thorn;at &thorn;e world lufes,</L>
<L>Als &thorn;e apostel says &thorn;us and profes:</L>
<L><I>Qui vnlt esse amicus hujus mundi,</I></L>
<L><I>inimicus dei constituitur.</I></L>
<L N="1116">He says, "wha-so &thorn;e werldes frend wil be,</L>
<L>Goddes enemy &thorn;an es he;"</L>
<L>&THORN;an suld we noght assent &thorn;ar-to,</L>
<L>Ne nathyng &thorn;at lykes til &thorn;e world do;</L>
<L N="1120">For worldisshe men here God mysprays,</L>
<L>&THORN;arfor &thorn;e apostel yhit, &thorn;us says:</L>
<L><I>Nolite diligere mundum, nec ea</I></L>
<L><I>que sunt in mundo.</I></L>
<L N="1124">"Lufes noght &thorn;e world here", says he,</L>
<L>"Ne &thorn;at, &thorn;at yhe in world may se;"</L>
<L>For al &thorn;at in world men tel can,</L>
<L>Es outher yhernyng of &thorn;e flesshe of man,</L>
<L N="1128">Or yhernyng of eghe, &thorn;at may luke,</L>
<L>Or pride of lyfe, als says &thorn;e buke:
<PB REF="00000076.tif" N="32"></L>
<L><I>Omne quod est in mundo, aut</I></L>
<L><I>est concupiscencia carnis, aut</I></L>
<L N="1132"><I>concupiscencia oculorum, aut</I></L>
<L><I>superbia vite.</I></L>
<L>"Yhernyng of flesshe es a thyng</L>
<L>&THORN;at falles til lust and flesshe lykyng;</L>
<L N="1136">Yhernyng of eghe, als I can gese</L>
<L>Falles to worldes rychese;</L>
<L>Pride of lyf &thorn;at some in hert kepes,</L>
<L>Falles to honours and worshepes;</L>
<L N="1140">Lust and lykyng, &thorn;at es flesshely,</L>
<L>Engendres &thorn;e syn of lychery;</L>
<L>Worldes riches of grete pryse</L>
<L>Engendres the syn of covatyse;</L>
<L N="1144">Honours nuryshes, als men may se,</L>
<L>Vayn glory, vauntyng and vanit&eacute;.</L>
<L><I>De Eremita qui quidem sequebatur</I><NOTE PLACE="foot">This quotation is absent from most of the MSS.</NOTE></L>
<L><I>mundum a se fugientem, et postea</I></L>
<L N="1148"><I>fugiebat mundum tunc se sequentem;</I></L>
<L><I>munde vale! tibi ve! fugiens me, dum</I></L>
<L><I>sequerer te, Tu sequeris modo me,</I></L>
<L><I>iam respuo despiciens te.</I></L>
<L N="1152">Sen God made &thorn;e world, als says haly writ,</L>
<L>To serve man, and noght man to serve it,</L>
<L>Whar-to serves man &thorn;e world &thorn;an,</L>
<L>And mas hym &thorn;e worldes bondman,</L>
<L N="1156">When he may serve God and be fre,</L>
<L>And oute of servage of &thorn;e world be?</L>
<L>Bot wald a man ryght knaw and fele</L>
<L>What &thorn;e world es, and byhald it wele,</L>
<L N="1160">Hym suld noght lyst, als I understand,</L>
<L>Make &thorn;e world na glade sembland,</L>
<L>For lo! what says Barthelmew</L>
<L>&THORN;at spekes of &thorn;e world, als I wil shew:</L>
<L N="1164">He says, "&thorn;e world es na thyng elles</L>
<L>Bot an hard exil, in qwilk men duelles,"
<PB REF="00000077.tif" N="33"></L>
<L>And alswa a dym dulful dale,</L>
<L>&THORN;at es ful of sorow and bale,</L>
<L N="1168">And a sted of mykel wrechednes,</L>
<L>Of travail and angers, &thorn;at here ay es,</L>
<L>Of payne, of syn and of foly,</L>
<L>Of shens[h]epe and of velany,</L>
<L N="1172">Of lettyng and of tarying,</L>
<L>Of frawardnes and of strivyng,</L>
<L>Of filthe and of corrupcion,</L>
<L>Of violence and of oppression,</L>
<L N="1176">Of gilry and of falshede,</L>
<L>Of treson, discorde and of drede;</L>
<L>In &thorn;e world, he says, noght elles we se</L>
<L>Bot wrechednes and vanit&eacute;,</L>
<L N="1180">Pride and pompe and covatyse,</L>
<L>And vayn sleghtes, and qwayntyse;</L>
<L>&THORN;e world, he says, tyl hym drawes<NOTE PLACE="foot"><LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'Thus &thorn;e world draweth in to his route,</L>
<L>All men that to him wol allowte,</L>
<L>And many greveth and fewe availeth</L>
<L>For his lovyers he deceyveth and failith.' MS. Addit. 11305.</L>
</LG></NOTE></L>
<L>And tilles, and lufes &thorn;am, &thorn;at him knawes;</L>
<L N="1184">And many he nuyes and fon avayles.</L>
<L>His lufers he desayves and fayles;</L>
<L>His despisers he waytes ay,</L>
<L>Als shadow to tak to his pray;</L>
<L N="1188">Bot &thorn;a &thorn;at wille him folow, he ledes</L>
<L>And &thorn;am scornes and taries in his nedes;</L>
<L>&THORN;e whilk a while he here socours,</L>
<L>And &thorn;am heghes with ryches and honours.</L>
<L N="1192">Bot he waytes to bygille &thorn;am at &thorn;e laste,</L>
<L>And in to povert agayn &thorn;am cast;</L>
<L>Whar-for worldes worshepe may be cald</L>
<L>Noght elles but vanit&eacute;, and swa I it hald.</L>
<L N="1196">And worlisshe riches, how-swa &thorn;ai come,</L>
<L>I hald noght elles bot filth and fantome.</L>
<L>&THORN;e world has many with vanit&eacute; filed,</L>
<L>And with pride and pompe &thorn;am ofte bygyled,
<PB REF="00000078.tif" N="34"></L>
<L N="1200">&THORN;arfor an haly man, als yhe may here,</L>
<L>Spekes to &thorn;e world on &thorn;is manere:</L>
<L><I>O munde immmunde, utinam esses ita immundus, ut me</I></L>
<L><I>non tangeres, aut ita mundus, ut</I></L>
<L N="1204"><I>me non coinquinares!</I></L>
<L>&THORN;is es on Inglishe &thorn;us to bymene:</L>
<L>"O &thorn;ou world", he says, "unclene,</L>
<L>Whyn mught &thorn;ou swa unclen be,<NOTE PLACE="foot">'Whyne moght &thorn;ou swa unclene be.' MS. Harl. 4196.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1208">&THORN;at suld never mare neghe me,</L>
<L>Or be swa clene and noght vile,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou suld never mare me file."</L>
<L>&THORN;e world here who-so wille</L>
<L N="1212">Un-to four thinges may liken by skille.<NOTE PLACE="foot">'Unto four thinges may lykend be, bi skyll.' MS. Harl. 4196.</NOTE></L>
<L>First &thorn;e world may lykend be,</L>
<L>Mast properly, unto &thorn;e se;</L>
<L>For &thorn;e se, aftir &thorn;e tydes certayn,</L>
<L N="1216">Ebbes and flowes, and falles agayn,</L>
<L>And waxes ful ken, thurgh stormes &thorn;at blawes,</L>
<L>And castes up and doun many gret wawes;</L>
<L>Swa castes &thorn;e world, thurgh favour,</L>
<L N="1220">A man to riches and honour.</L>
<L>And fra &thorn;at agayn he castes hym doun</L>
<L>Til povert and to tribulacioun.</L>
<L>And &thorn;a er &thorn;e grete stormes kene</L>
<L N="1224">And &thorn;e wawes, &thorn;at in &thorn;e world er sene.</L>
<L>Yhit may &thorn;e world here &thorn;at wyde es,</L>
<L>Be likend to a wildernes,</L>
<L>&THORN;at ful of wild bestes es sene,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'The whilk is ful of bestes unmylde,</L>
<L>The whilke wol a man strangly and destrye.' MS. Addit 11305.</L>
</LG></NOTE></L>
<L N="1228">Als lyons, libardes and wolwes kene,</L>
<L>&THORN;at wald worow men bylyve,</L>
<L>And rogg &thorn;am in sonder and ryve;</L>
<L>Swa &thorn;e world es ful of mysdoers</L>
<L N="1232">And of tyrauntes &thorn;at men ofte ders,
<PB REF="00000079.tif" N="35"></L>
<L>&THORN;e whilk er bisy, nyght and day,</L>
<L>To nuye men in alle &thorn;at &thorn;ai may.</L>
<L>&THORN;e world alswa may lykend be</L>
<L N="1236">Til a forest, in a wilde cuntr&eacute;,</L>
<L>&THORN;at es ful of thefs and outlawes,</L>
<L>&THORN;at, commonly, til forestes drawes,</L>
<L>&THORN;at hald pases, and robbes and reves</L>
<L N="1240">Men of &thorn;at &thorn;ai have, and noght &thorn;am leves;</L>
<L>Swa es &thorn;e world here &thorn;ar we duelle,</L>
<L>Ful of thefs, &thorn;at er devels of helle;</L>
<L>&THORN;at ay us waytes, and er bysy</L>
<L N="1244">To robbe us of our gudes gastly.</L>
<L>&THORN;e world may yhit, als yhe sal here,</L>
<L>Be lykend, on &thorn;e fierth manere,</L>
<L>To a feld ful of batailles</L>
<L N="1248">Of enemys, &thorn;at ilk day men assayles.</L>
<L>For-why here we er on many wyse</L>
<L>Alle umset with sere enmys,</L>
<L>And, speciali, with enmys thre,</L>
<L N="1252">Agaynes wham us byhoves armed be:</L>
<L>&THORN;a er &thorn;e world, &thorn;e fende, our flesshe,</L>
<L>&THORN;at, to assayle us here, er ay freshe;</L>
<L>And &thorn;ar-for byhoves us, day and nyght,</L>
<L N="1256">Whilles we lif here, agayn &thorn;am fight.</L>
<L>&THORN;e world, als clerkes understandes,</L>
<L>Agayn us fightes with twa handes,</L>
<L>With &thorn;e right hand and &thorn;e left; &thorn;ere twa</L>
<L N="1260">May be taken, bathe wele and wa;</L>
<L>&THORN;e right hand es welthe, als I halde,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e lefte hand es angre calde;</L>
<L>For &thorn;e worlde assayles sum men awhile,</L>
<L N="1264">With &thorn;e right hand &thorn;am to bygile;</L>
<L>&THORN;at es welth, als I sayde before,</L>
<L>Of worldly riches and tresore;</L>
<L>And assayles men, nyght and day,</L>
<L N="1268">With &thorn;e left hand &thorn;am to flay;</L>
<L>&THORN;at es with angre and tribulacion,</L>
<L>And povert, and persecucion,
<PB REF="00000080.tif" N="36"></L>
<L>&THORN;e whilk &thorn;er clerkes &thorn;e left hand calles</L>
<L N="1272">Of &thorn;e world, &thorn;at ofte sythes falles.</L>
<L>Bot with &thorn;e world comes dam fortone,</L>
<L>&THORN;at ayther hand may chaung sone;</L>
<L>For sho turnes about ay hir whele,</L>
<L N="1276">Up and doune, als many may fele;</L>
<L>When sho hir whele lates obout ga,</L>
<L>Sho turnes sum doune fra wele to wa,</L>
<L>And, eft agaynward, fra wa to wele;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'And efte sone from wo in-to much blisse</L>
<L>So &thorn;at hir whele hath never lysse. MS. Addit 11305.</L>
</LG></NOTE></L>
<L N="1280">&THORN;us turnes sho obout oft hir whele,</L>
<L>&THORN;e whilk &thorn;ir clerkes noght elles calles,</L>
<L>Bot happe or chaunce, &thorn;at sodanli falles,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at men haldes here noght elles,</L>
<L N="1284">Bot welthe and angre in whilk men dwelles.</L>
<L>&THORN;arfor worldly happe es ay in dout,</L>
<L>Whilles dam fortune turnes hir whele about.</L>
<L>Angre men dredes and walde it fle,</L>
<L N="1288">And in welthe men wald ay be;</L>
<L>Bot parfit men, &thorn;at &thorn;air lif right ledes,</L>
<L>Welthe of &thorn;e worlde ay flese and dredes;</L>
<L>For welthe drawes a man fra &thorn;e right way</L>
<L N="1292">&THORN;at ledes til &thorn;e blisse &thorn;at lastes ay,</L>
<L>Us aght to drede worldly welthe &thorn;an</L>
<L>For Saynt Ierom says, &thorn;e haly man:</L>
<L><I>Quanto in virtutibus crescimus,</I></L>
<L N="1296"><I>tanto amplius timere debea|</I></L>
<L><I>mus, ne de sublimiori corruamus.</I></L>
<L>"&THORN;e mare", he says, "&thorn;at we wax upright</L>
<L>In welthe, and in worldly myght,</L>
<L N="1300">&THORN;e mare we suld have drede in thoght,</L>
<L>&THORN;at we fra &thorn;e hegher fal noght;"</L>
<L>Tyl &thorn;is acordes &thorn;e wordes of Senek,</L>
<L>&THORN;at says &thorn;us, als yhe here me spek:</L>
<L N="1304"><I>Tunc tibi salubria consilia advoca,</I></L>
<L><I>cum tibi alludit prosperitas mundi.</I>
<PB REF="00000081.tif" N="37"></L>
<L>Senek on &thorn;is maner says:</L>
<L>"When welthe of &thorn;e worlde with &thorn;e plays,</L>
<L N="1308">Sek &thorn;an gude consayl wyth-alle."</L>
<L>For welthe mas men in perils falle,</L>
<L>&THORN;an es worldes welthe to drede &thorn;arfor,</L>
<L>Als says &thorn;e grete clerk, Saynt Gregor:</L>
<L N="1312"><I>Si omnis fortuna timenda est, ma|</I></L>
<L><I>gis tamen prospera quam adversa.</I></L>
<L>Saint Gregor says on &thorn;is manere:</L>
<L>"If ilka chaunce be to drede here,</L>
<L N="1316">Yhit es happe of welthe to drede mare</L>
<L>&THORN;an chaunce of angre," &thorn;at smertes sare.</L>
<L>For angres mans lyf clenses, and proves,</L>
<L>And welthes his lif trobles and droves,</L>
<L N="1320">And &thorn;e saul of man may lightly spille;</L>
<L>For welthes, &thorn;at men has here at wille,</L>
<L>Semes tokenyng of endeles pyn.</L>
<L>For lo! what says here Saynt Austyn:</L>
<L N="1324"><I>Sanitas continua et rerum habundan|</I></L>
<L><I>cia, sunt eterne dampnacionis indicia.</I></L>
<L>He says, "continuel hele here</L>
<L>And plent&eacute; of worldly gudes sere,</L>
<L N="1328">Er taknes, als in boke writen es,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e dampnacion &thorn;at es endles."</L>
<L>And to &thorn;is<NOTE PLACE="foot">&THORN;es. MS. Harl. 4196.</NOTE> wordes, &thorn;at sum men myspays,</L>
<L>Acordes Saynt Gregor, &thorn;at &thorn;us says:</L>
<L N="1332"><I>Continuus successus temporalium, fu|</I></L>
<L><I>ture dampnacionis est indicium.</I></L>
<L>He says, "continuel happy commyng</L>
<L>Of worldly gudes, es a takenyng</L>
<L N="1336">Of &thorn;e dampnacion &thorn;at sal be,"</L>
<L>At &thorn;e last day, with-outen pit&eacute;.</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;e world prayses nan, bot &thorn;a anly</L>
<L>&THORN;at til alle worldes welthes er happy,</L>
<L N="1340">And on worldly thynges settes &thorn;air hert,</L>
<L>And flese ay &thorn;e state of povert;
<PB REF="00000082.tif" N="38"></L>
<L>Swilk men purchaces and gaders fast,</L>
<L>And fares als &thorn;is lyfe suld ay last;</L>
<L N="1344">Til &thorn;am &thorn;e world es favorabel</L>
<L>In alle &thorn;at &thorn;am thynk profitabel.</L>
<L>&THORN;e world &thorn;am lofes, and &thorn;ai luf it,</L>
<L>And for &thorn;ai folow &thorn;e worldes wit,</L>
<L N="1348">And mykel can of worldes qwayntys,</L>
<L>&THORN;e world &thorn;am haldes gude men and wys,</L>
<L>Til &thorn;am commes gudes here many-falde</L>
<L>To &thorn;air dampnacion, als I talde.</L>
<L N="1352">For-why til heven may na man come,</L>
<L>&THORN;at folowes &thorn;e worlde and worldes wysdome,</L>
<L>&THORN;e quilk, als says wyse men and witty,</L>
<L>Onence God es bot foly.</L>
<L N="1356"><I>Sapiencia huius mundi est</I></L>
<L><I>stultitia apud Deum.</I></L>
<L>Many men &thorn;e world here fraystes,</L>
<L>Bot he es noght wyse &thorn;at &thorn;ar-in traistes;</L>
<L N="1360">For it ledes a man with wrenkes and wyles,</L>
<L>And at the last it hym bygyles;</L>
<L>Bot he may be called witty and wyse,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e world can fle and dispise,</L>
<L N="1364">And hates &thorn;e maners &thorn;at it loffes,</L>
<L>And thynkes ay whyder hym byhoves;</L>
<L>And on &thorn;is lyfe here traystes noght,</L>
<L>Bot on &thorn;e tother settes his thoght.</L>
<L N="1368">For na syker duellyng fynde we here,</L>
<L>Als &thorn;e apostel says on &thorn;is manere:</L>
<L><I>Non habemus manentem civitatem,</I></L>
<L><I>sed futurum inquirimus.</I></L>
<L N="1372">"Na syker wonnyng-sted here haf we,</L>
<L>Bot we seke ane, &thorn;at sal ay be."</L>
<L>For als gestes we here soiourne</L>
<L>Awhile, til we sal hethen tourne;</L>
<L N="1376">&THORN;at may fal soner &thorn;an som wenes,</L>
<L>For we duelle here als aliens,</L>
<L>To travail, here in &thorn;e way, our lyms,</L>
<L>Til our countr&eacute;-warde, als pilgryms.
<PB REF="00000083.tif" N="39"></L>
<L N="1380">&THORN;arfor &thorn;e prophet says til God thus,</L>
<L>Als &thorn;is vers in &thorn;e psauter shewes us:</L>
<L><I>Ne sileas, quoniam advena ego sum apud</I></L>
<L><I>te et peregrinus, sicut omnes patres mei.</I></L>
<L N="1384">"Be noght stille Loverd" says he,</L>
<L>"For I am a commelyng towarde &thorn;e,</L>
<L>And pilgrym, als alle my faders was."</L>
<L>&THORN;us may al say &thorn;at in &thorn;is world sal pas,</L>
<L N="1388">&THORN;at es to say, be noght swa stille,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ow ne make me here knaw &thorn;i wille;</L>
<L>And swilk comfort to my saul shew swythe,</L>
<L>&THORN;at mught make it in &thorn;e glade and blythe:</L>
<L N="1392">And say thos to it: "I am thy hele,</L>
<L>For &thorn;ou ert my pilgrim lele."</L>
<L>&THORN;is world es &thorn;e way and passage,</L>
<L>&THORN;urgh whilk lyes our pilgrimage;</L>
<L N="1396">By &thorn;is way byhoves us al gang,</L>
<L>Bot be we war we ga noght wrang.</L>
<L>For in &thorn;is world liggis twa ways,</L>
<L>Als men may fynd &thorn;at &thorn;am assays;</L>
<L N="1400">&THORN;e tane es way of the dede calde,</L>
<L>&THORN;e tother es way of lyfe to halde,</L>
<L>&THORN;e way of dede semes large and eesy,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at may lede us over-lightly,</L>
<L N="1404">Until &thorn;e grysly land of mirknes,</L>
<L>&THORN;ar sorow and pyn ever-mare es.</L>
<L>&THORN;e way of lyfe semes narow and harde</L>
<L>&THORN;at ledes us til our contr&eacute;-warde</L>
<L N="1408">&THORN;at es &thorn;e kyngdom of heven bright,</L>
<L>Whare we sal won ay in Goddes sight</L>
<L>And Goddes awen sons &thorn;an be calde,</L>
<L>If we &thorn;e way of lyfe here halde.</L>
<L N="1412">&THORN;e life of &thorn;is world es ful unstable,</L>
<L>And ful variand and chaungeable</L>
<L>Als es sene in contrarius manere,</L>
<L>By the tymes and vedirs and sesons here.</L>
<L N="1416">For &thorn;e world and worldis life to-gider,</L>
<L>Chaunges and turnes ofte h&iacute;der and &thorn;ider,
<PB REF="00000084.tif" N="40"></L>
<L>And in a state duelles ful short while,</L>
<L>Unnethes, &thorn;e space of a myle.</L>
<L N="1420">And for-&thorn;i &thorn;at &thorn;e worlde is swa unstable,</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;at men sese &thorn;ar-in es chaungeable;</L>
<L>For God ordayns here, als es his wille,</L>
<L>Sere variaunce, for certayn skille,</L>
<L N="1424">Of &thorn;e tyms and wedirs and sesons,</L>
<L>In taken of &thorn;e worldes condicions,</L>
<L>&THORN;at swa unstable er and variande,</L>
<L>&THORN;at ful short while may in a state stande.</L>
<L N="1428">For God wille men se, thurgh swilk takens sere,</L>
<L>How unstable &thorn;is world es here,</L>
<L>Swa &thorn;at men suld mare drede and be abayste,</L>
<L>Over mykel in &thorn;e world here to trayste.</L>
<L N="1432">Ofte chaunges &thorn;e tymes here, als men wele wate,</L>
<L>Als thus, now es arly, now es late,</L>
<L>Now es day, now es nyght,</L>
<L>Now es myrk, now es light,</L>
<L N="1436">And &thorn;e wedirs chaunges and &thorn;e sesons,</L>
<L>&THORN;us aftir &thorn;e worldes condicions;</L>
<L>For now es cald, now es hete,</L>
<L>Now es dry, and now es wete.</L>
<L N="1440">For now es snaw, hail or rayn,</L>
<L>And now es fair wedir agayn;</L>
<L>Now es &thorn;e wedir bright and shynand,</L>
<L>And now waxes it alle douiland;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><P>MS. Harl. 4196 reads <I>domland.</I>&mdash;MS. Lands. 348 has the following reading:</P><LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'Now is wedir bryght and schinonde</L>
<L>Now is dym <I>droubelonde</I>.'</L>
</LG></NOTE></L>
<L N="1444">Now se we &thorn;e lyfte clere and faire,</L>
<L>Now gadirs mystes and cloudes in &thorn;e ayre.</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;er variance to understande</L>
<L>May be takens of &thorn;is world swa variande;</L>
<L N="1448">And yhit er &thorn;ar other ma takens sere</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e unstablenes of &thorn;is life here.</L>
<L>For now es mirthe, now es murnyng,</L>
<L>Now es laghter and now es gretyng;
<PB REF="00000085.tif" N="41"></L>
<L N="1452">Now er men wele, now er men wa,</L>
<L>Now es a man frende, now es he faa;</L>
<L>Now es a man light, now es [he] hevy,</L>
<L>Now es he blithe, now es he drery;</L>
<L N="1456">Now haf we ioy, now haf we pyn,</L>
<L>Now we wyn, now we tyn;</L>
<L>Now er we ryche, now er we pur,</L>
<L>Now haf we or litel, now pas we mesur;</L>
<L N="1460">Now er we bigg, now er we bare,<NOTE PLACE="foot">'Now es he <I>riche</I> and now es he bare.' MS. Addit 11305.</NOTE></L>
<L>Now er we hale, now seke and sare;</L>
<L>Now haf we rest and now travail,</L>
<L>Now we fande our force, now we fail;</L>
<L N="1464">Now er we smert, now er we slawe,</L>
<L>Now er we heghe, now er we lawe;</L>
<L>Now haf we ynogh, now haf we noght,</L>
<L>Now er we aboven, and now doun broght;</L>
<L N="1468">Now haf we pees, now haf we were,</L>
<L>Now eese us a thyng, now fele we it dere;</L>
<L>Now lofe we, now hate, now saghtel, now strife.</L>
<L>&THORN;er er &thorn;e maners here of &thorn;is lyfe,</L>
<L N="1472">&THORN;e whilk er takens of [&thorn;e] unstabelnes</L>
<L>Of &thorn;is worldis lyfe, &thorn;at chaungeable es.</L>
<L>Bot als &thorn;is lyfe es ay passand,</L>
<L>Swa es &thorn;e worlde, ilk day, apayrand;</L>
<L N="1476">For &thorn;e world til &thorn;e endewarde fast drawes,</L>
<L>Als clerkes by many takens knawes.</L>
<L>&THORN;arfor &thorn;e world, &thorn;at clerkes sees &thorn;us helde,</L>
<L>Es als mykel to say als &thorn;e wer elde.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'&THORN;is world &thorn;at we seo &thorn;us helde</L>
<L>Is not but &thorn;is worldes elde.' MS. Addit 11305.</L>
</LG></NOTE></L>
<L N="1480">Twa erthely worldes til &thorn;is life falles,</L>
<L>Als es sayd by-for, &thorn;at clerkes calles</L>
<L>&THORN;e mare world of erthe, and &thorn;e les;</L>
<L>Ful chaungeable ayther world es.</L>
<L N="1484">&THORN;e mare world es &thorn;is world brade,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e les es man, for wham it es made,
<PB REF="00000086.tif" N="42"></L>
<L>And als the mare world es round sette,</L>
<L>Swa es &thorn;e les world man round for to mette,</L>
<L N="1488">For in &thorn;e brede of man es contende,</L>
<L>Als lang space fra &thorn;e lang fynger ende</L>
<L>Of&thorn;e right hande, with armes out spredande,</L>
<L>Til &thorn;e same fynger ende of &thorn;e left hande,</L>
<L N="1492">Als fra &thorn;e haterel oboven &thorn;e croun,</L>
<L>Es sene tyl &thorn;e sole of &thorn;e fot doun.</L>
<L>&THORN;an if a man [h]is armes out sprede</L>
<L>Na mar es &thorn;e lengthe, &thorn;an &thorn;e brede;</L>
<L N="1496">Swa may men mette a man with-oute,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And so may a man be yemed without.</L>
<L>Right as a compas is. rownd aboute. MS. Addit 11305.</L>
</LG></NOTE></L>
<L>Als a compas round aboute.</L>
<L>&THORN;os has &thorn;e les world &thorn;at man es,</L>
<L>Shap of &thorn;e mare world and liknes;</L>
<L N="1500">Bathe &thorn;er worldes, I dar wele say,</L>
<L>Sal fail atte &thorn;e last and passe away;</L>
<L>For ay &thorn;e mare elde &thorn;at &thorn;ai bere,</L>
<L>&THORN;e mare &thorn;ai appair and er feblere,</L>
<L N="1504">Als men sees &thorn;at til &thorn;am tas tent,</L>
<L>And &thorn;arfor says &thorn;us Innocent:</L>
<L><I>Senuit iam mundus, uterque macrocosmus [et]</I></L>
<L><I>major mundus, et microcosmus et minor mun|</I></L>
<L N="1508"><I>dus, et quanto prolixius utriusque senectus producitur,</I></L>
<L><I>tanto dexterius utriusque natura turbatur</I></L>
<L>He says &thorn;us, als in Latyn es talde,</L>
<L>"Ayther worlde now waxes alde,</L>
<L N="1512">And &thorn;e langer &thorn;at &thorn;air tym es soght,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e elde of ayther of &thorn;am forth broght,</L>
<L>&THORN;e mare in malys and febelnes</L>
<L>&THORN;e kynd of ayther trobled es."</L>
<L N="1516">Of bathe &thorn;er worldes gret outrage we se</L>
<L>In pompe and pride and vanit&eacute;,</L>
<L>In selcouthe maners and sere degyse</L>
<L>&THORN;at now es used of many wyse,</L>
<L N="1520">In worldis havyng and beryng,</L>
<L>In vayn apparail and in weryng,
<PB REF="00000087.tif" N="43"></L>
<L>&THORN;as tas over mykel vayn costage,</L>
<L>And tornes al until outrage.</L>
<L N="1524">For swilk degises and suilk maners,</L>
<L>Als yhong men now hauntes and lers</L>
<L>And ilk day es comonly sen,</L>
<L>Byfor &thorn;is tyme ne has noght ben;</L>
<L N="1528">For &thorn;at somtyme men held velany</L>
<L>Now yhung men haldes curtasy;</L>
<L>And &thorn;at som tyme was curtasy cald,</L>
<L>Now wille yhong men velany hald.</L>
<L N="1532">Now many men se ofte chaungyng</L>
<L>Of sere maners of gys of clethyng;</L>
<L>For now wers men short and now syde,</L>
<L>Now uses men narow and now wyde;</L>
<L N="1536">Som has &thorn;air clethyng hyngand als stoles,</L>
<L>Som gas tatird als tatird foles;</L>
<L>Some gase wrynchand to and fra,</L>
<L>And some gas hypand als a ka;</L>
<L N="1540">&THORN;us uses yhong men all new gett,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e world &thorn;ai all awkeward sett,</L>
<L>Thurgh swylk uncomly pomp and pryde,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ai schew whe&thorn;er &thorn;ai gang or ryde;</L>
<L N="1544">Swa mykell pryde, als now es, I wene,</L>
<L>Was never bifore &thorn;is tyme sene,</L>
<L>Of swilk comes &thorn;ir gyses &thorn;at we se.</L>
<L>Bot I dred &thorn;at &thorn;ai may takens be</L>
<L N="1548">Of gret hasty myscheves to understand</L>
<L>&THORN;at tyll &thorn;e world er nere command.</L>
<L>&THORN;arfore in &thorn;air gyses &thorn;ai sall fall,</L>
<L>Ffor &thorn;are-wyth &thorn;ai wreth God &thorn;at sese all;</L>
<L N="1552">And his wreth at &thorn;e last sall with &thorn;am mete,</L>
<L>Wharfore &thorn;us says David &thorn;e prophete:</L>
<L><I>Et irritaverunt eum in advencionibus suis,</I></L>
<L><I>et multiplicata est in eis ruina,</I></L>
<L N="1556">"And &thorn;ai styrd God tyll wreth", sais he,</L>
<L>In &thorn;air new fyndynges of vanit&eacute;,</L>
<L>And in &thorn;am is fallyng many-fald,"</L>
<L>And &thorn;at es thurgh pryde &thorn;at I of tald;
<PB REF="00000088.tif" N="44"></L>
<L N="1560">&THORN;is may be said, als &thorn;e boke proves</L>
<L>Be &thorn;am &thorn;at new gyses controves.</L>
<L>Ffor &thorn;ai do swa &thorn;e worlde to plese,</L>
<L>Ffor pryde mare &thorn;an for &thorn;air eese.</L>
<L N="1564">And &thorn;a, &thorn;at with swylk gyses God greves,</L>
<L>Sall fall in many grevos myscheves;</L>
<L>And for &thorn;ai will noght be led with skyll,</L>
<L>God lates &thorn;am awhile have &thorn;air will;</L>
<L N="1568">Bot at &thorn;e last on &thorn;am will sende</L>
<L>Veng[e]aunce, bot if &thorn;ai &thorn;am here amende:</L>
<L>&THORN;an most &thorn;ai bifore schew som taken,</L>
<L>&THORN;at God has &thorn;am left and forsaken;</L>
<L N="1572">And &thorn;at may be knawen bi sere gyse.</L>
<L>&THORN;arfor says David in &thorn;is wyse:</L>
<L><I>Et dimisi eos secundum desideria cordis eorum,</I></L>
<L><I>ibunt in advencionibus suis.</I></L>
<L N="1576">&THORN;e prophet David here spekes &thorn;us,</L>
<L>In Godes name, als &thorn;es verses shewes us.</L>
<L>"I left &thorn;am", he says, "out of covert,</L>
<L>After &thorn;e yhernynges of &thorn;air hert,</L>
<L N="1580">In &thorn;air fyndynges sall &thorn;ai ga."</L>
<L>&THORN;is may be said be all &thorn;a</L>
<L>&THORN;at God suffers folow vanytese,</L>
<L>After &thorn;air lykyng &thorn;at &thorn;ai chese;</L>
<L N="1584">&THORN;e whilk tyll &thorn;e world mase &thorn;am gay,</L>
<L>And turnes &thorn;am al fra God oway,</L>
<L>&THORN;ai sall at &thorn;e last fro hethen wende</L>
<L>In &thorn;air syn, tyll pyne with-outen ende,</L>
<L N="1588">Bot &thorn;ai swylk vanytese forsake</L>
<L>And amendes here be tyme make;</L>
<L>Yhit has &thorn;e world, als men sese and heres,</L>
<L>Ma other contrarius maneres;</L>
<L N="1592">For now es vertow turned to vyce,</L>
<L>And play and bourd untyll malice;</L>
<L>Now es devocyon, on som syde,</L>
<L>Turned tyll pomp and to pryde;</L>
<L N="1596">Now es wysdom halden foly</L>
<L>And turned intyll trechery.
<PB REF="00000089.tif" N="45"></L>
<L>And foly is halden [now] wysdome,</L>
<L>With proud men and unbowsome.</L>
<L N="1600">Now es luff turned tyll lychery,</L>
<L>And ryghtwisnes tyll tyrauntry;</L>
<L>&THORN;us es &thorn;is world turned up &thorn;at es doune,</L>
<L>Tyll many mans dampnacyoune,</L>
<L N="1604">&THORN;e wilk folowes &thorn;e worlde swa fraward;</L>
<L>And &thorn;arfore &thorn;ai mon fele payne ful hard,</L>
<L>After &thorn;is lyfe &thorn;at &thorn;ai here lede,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at aght &thorn;am gretly to drede.</L>
<L N="1608">Bot it semes &thorn;at swilk men er wode,</L>
<L>For &thorn;ai hald gud thing evell and evell gude;</L>
<L>Wa sall &thorn;am be, als we here clerkes tell,</L>
<L>Fforwhi Crist says in &thorn;e gosspell:</L>
<L N="1612"><I>Ve vobis qui dicitis malum bonum,</I></L>
<L><I>et bonum malum!</I></L>
<L>He says: "wa till yhow &thorn;at says with will</L>
<L>&THORN;at ille es gud and gud es ill;"</L>
<L N="1616">&THORN;at es to say &thorn;am sall be wa</L>
<L>&THORN;at here mysturnes &thorn;air lyfe swa.</L>
<L>&THORN;us es &thorn;e world, and &thorn;e lyfe &thorn;are-in,</L>
<L>Fful of vanyt&eacute; and of syn.</L>
<L N="1620">Bot som men lufes &thorn;is lyfe swa mykell</L>
<L>And &thorn;e world &thorn;at is swa fykell,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ai wald never part &thorn;ar-fra,</L>
<L>Bot lyfe here ay, if it moght be swa;</L>
<L N="1624">For &thorn;ai luf swa &thorn;is worldes vanyt&eacute;</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ai wald never other lyfe suld be.</L>
<L>&THORN;ai will noght knaw &thorn;e peryls all</L>
<L>Of &thorn;is lyfe, ne what after sall fall;</L>
<L N="1628">Bot for &thorn;ai life here in delices sere</L>
<L>&THORN;ai think no hevene es bot here,</L>
<L>Bot at &thorn;e last, when &thorn;air lyfe sall stynt,</L>
<L>&THORN;an sall all ioy be fra &thorn;am tynt.</L>
<L N="1632">Bot wald a man understand wele</L>
<L>What &thorn;is world es and what he sall fele,</L>
<L>When he sall wend fra &thorn;is world oway,</L>
<L>Him suld noght lyst, nouther nyght ne day,
<PB REF="00000090.tif" N="46"></L>
<L N="1636">Myrthe here ne blythe chere make,</L>
<L>Bot all &thorn;e welthes of &thorn;is world forsake,</L>
<L>And lyf in penaunce and in povert,</L>
<L>Ffor &thorn;e dred &thorn;at he suld hafe in hert,</L>
<L N="1640">If he wald knaw and trow how hard</L>
<L>Him bihoved suffer afterward;</L>
<L>Bot ogayne &thorn;at dred yhit moght he,</L>
<L>Thurgh hope of hert, conforted be,</L>
<L N="1644">If he think wele of heven bryght,</L>
<L>Whare he sall won if he here lyf ryght,</L>
<L>&THORN;us may ilk man do and thynk,</L>
<L>In whase hert grace of God may synk.</L>
<L N="1648">And he &thorn;at will noght thynk of this</L>
<L>And yhernes to have nane other blys,</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;is wreched lyfe &thorn;at him thynk gude,</L>
<L>He es outher clomsed,<NOTE PLACE="foot">For clomsed. Harl. MS. 6923 reads: <I>glomsede</I>. MSS. Lands. 348, Ad|dit 22283 read <I>cursed</I> for <I>clomsede</I>.</NOTE> or wode;</L>
<L N="1652">Or it es a signe of suspecyon</L>
<L>&THORN;at he es in way of dampnacyon.</L>
<L>Here have I shewed on sere manere</L>
<L>&THORN;e condicyons of &thorn;is world here,</L>
<L N="1656">And of &thorn;e worldes unstabilnes,</L>
<L>And of &thorn;e maners &thorn;at in &thorn;e world es;</L>
<L>And now will I pass, forther-mare</L>
<L>To &thorn;e thred part and se what es &thorn;are;</L>
<L N="1660">Ffor &thorn;at part now will I begyn</L>
<L>To shew yhow maters &thorn;at er within,</L>
<L>&THORN;at specialy spekes, as I sall rede</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e ded, and whi it es to drede.</L>
</LG>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 N="3" TYPE="book">
<HEAD>Here bigynnes &thorn;e thred part &thorn;at es of &thorn;e ded.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ded es &thorn;e mast dred thing &thorn;at es</L>
<L>In all &thorn;is world, als &thorn;e boke witnes;</L>
<L N="1668">Ffor here es na qwyk creature lyfand</L>
<L>&THORN;at it ne es for &thorn;e ded dredand
<PB REF="00000091.tif" N="47"></L>
<L>And flese &thorn;e ded ay whils it may</L>
<L>Bot at &thorn;e last he most be &thorn;e dedes pray.</L>
<L N="1672">Ded, of all &thorn;at it comes to, abates</L>
<L>And chaunges all myghtes and states,</L>
<L>No man may wele ogayn it stand;</L>
<L>Whare &thorn;at it comes in any land,</L>
<L N="1676">&THORN;at es to say, bodily ded,</L>
<L>Ogayns &thorn;e whilk no man may help ne red,</L>
<L>Ffor all &thorn;at lyf has bihoves it fele,</L>
<L>&THORN;at aght ilk man to knaw wele.</L>
<L N="1680">Bot bi &thorn;e name of ded may be tane,</L>
<L>And understanden ma dedes &thorn;an ane,</L>
<L>Ffor als &thorn;ir clerkes fyndes writen and redes,</L>
<L>Thre maners of dedes er &thorn;at men dredes.</L>
<L N="1684">Ane es bodily ded, &thorn;at thurgh kynd es,</L>
<L>Ane other gastely, &thorn;e thred endeles.</L>
<L>Bodily ded, &thorn;at is kyndely,</L>
<L>Es twynyng betwene &thorn;e saule and &thorn;e body;</L>
<L N="1688">And &thorn;at ded es full bytter and hard,</L>
<L>Of whilk I sall schew yhow afterward.</L>
<L>Gastely ded es twynyng thurgh synne,</L>
<L>Bitwene God and man saule within;</L>
<L N="1692">Ffor als &thorn;e saule es lyf of &thorn;e body,</L>
<L>Swa &thorn;e lyfe of &thorn;e saule es God allmyghty;</L>
<L>And als &thorn;e body, with-outen dout,</L>
<L>Es ded when &thorn;e saule es passed out,</L>
<L N="1696">&THORN;e saule of man es ded ryght swa,</L>
<L>When God es departed &thorn;arefra;</L>
<L>For whare syn es, es &thorn;e devell of hell,</L>
<L>And &thorn;are whare &thorn;ai er, will God noght dwell.</L>
<L N="1700">For dedely syn and &thorn;e devell and he</L>
<L>In a stede may noght to-gyder be;</L>
<L>&THORN;arfor when &thorn;e saule es wounded with syn,</L>
<L>God passes out, and &thorn;e fende gase in;</L>
<L N="1704">&THORN;an es &thorn;e saule onence God ded,</L>
<L>Ay whils syn and &thorn;e devell dwelles in &thorn;at stede;</L>
<L>And als &thorn;e body may be slayne</L>
<L>Thurgh wapen &thorn;at men may ordayne,
<PB REF="00000092.tif" N="48"></L>
<L N="1708">Swa es &thorn;e saule slane thurgh syn;</L>
<L>Wharfor God and it bihoves twyn.</L>
<L>&THORN;an es gastly ded to dred wele mare,</L>
<L>&THORN;an bodily ded &thorn;at nane will spare,</L>
<L N="1712">In-als-mykell as &thorn;e saule namely</L>
<L>Es better and mare worthy &thorn;an &thorn;e body;</L>
<L>Ffor all-if &thorn;e saule thurgh syn be dede</L>
<L>Fra God allmyghty &thorn;at es the hede,</L>
<L N="1716">Yhit may it ay lyf and be pyned,</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;e body es dedly here thurgh kynde.</L>
<L>Of bodily ded es no gayn-turnyng,</L>
<L>Ffor of erthly lyf it es endyng,</L>
<L N="1720">And ryght entr&eacute; and way it es</L>
<L>Till ioy or payn &thorn;at es endeles.</L>
<L>Yhit if &thorn;e saule thurgh syn be slayne.</L>
<L>It may thurgh grace qwyken ogayne,</L>
<L N="1724">And &thorn;e gastly woundes of syn</L>
<L>Thurgh penaunce may be heled within;</L>
<L>Ffor all-if God be ryghtwyse and myghty</L>
<L>He es full of gudenes and of mercy,</L>
<L N="1728">And to turne him tyll man mare redy es he</L>
<L>&THORN;an any man till him will be;</L>
<L>For all-if he &thorn;e dede of body that greves</L>
<L>Ordaynd til alle &thorn;at here lyfes,</L>
<L N="1732">&THORN;e dede of saul wild noght he</L>
<L>Of na man &thorn;ogh he synful be;</L>
<L>For &thorn;e life of &thorn;e saule mare him pays</L>
<L>&THORN;an &thorn;e dede, for &thorn;us him-self says:</L>
<L N="1736"><I>Nolo mortem peccatoris, sed ut magis</I></L>
<L><I>convertatur et vivat.</I></L>
<L>"I wille noght &thorn;e ded of synful man,</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;at he may be turned and lyf &thorn;an;"</L>
<L N="1740">&THORN;an may &thorn;e synful &thorn;at his saul has slayn</L>
<L>Be turned &thorn;urgh grace, and lyf ogayn.</L>
<L>Endles dede es &thorn;e dede of helle</L>
<L>That es mast bitter and mast felle.</L>
<L N="1744">Helle es halden a full hidos stede,</L>
<L>&THORN;e whilk es full of endeles dede,
<PB REF="00000093.tif" N="49"></L>
<L>And of paynes and sorow &thorn;at never sal blyn,</L>
<L>And yhit may nan dighe &thorn;at es &thorn;ar-in;</L>
<L N="1748">Bot if &thorn;ai mught dighe, als body here may,</L>
<L>Of alle sorow &thorn;an delyverd war &thorn;ay;</L>
<L>&THORN;ai sal fele &thorn;ar many a ded brayde,</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;ai sal ay lyf &thorn;ar-with, als I sayde;</L>
<L N="1752">For &thorn;e ded of helle es a lif ay dyand,</L>
<L>And a ded &thorn;at es ay lifand.</L>
<L>Dede of helle es noght elles to say,</L>
<L>Bot payns and sorow &thorn;at sal last ay,</L>
<L N="1756">&THORN;e whilk saules sal fele with-outen ende,</L>
<L>&THORN;at tille &thorn;at grisely sted sal wende.</L>
<L>Of &thorn;is ded may men rede and luke</L>
<L>Ynoghe, in &thorn;e sexte part of &thorn;is buke,</L>
<L N="1760">&THORN;at spekes of &thorn;e payns of helle;</L>
<L>&THORN;arfor here-on I wille na langer duelle,</L>
<L>Bot of bodily dede I wille spek mare</L>
<L>&THORN;at es entr&eacute; and way, als I sayd are.</L>
<L N="1764">Til lyf or ded &thorn;at has nan hende,</L>
<L>Als es aftirward in &thorn;is part contende.</L>
<L>Bodily dede here dredes ful many,</L>
<L>For twa skilles principaly;</L>
<L N="1768">Ane es for &thorn;e payne &thorn;at a man has,</L>
<L>When &thorn;e dede hym assayls, and slas.</L>
<L>&THORN;e tother es, for when his lif sal here ende,</L>
<L>He what never whider he sal wende;</L>
<L N="1772">For in dout he es and uncertayn</L>
<L>Whether he sal til ioy or payn;</L>
<L>Bot how-swa he sal aftir fare,</L>
<L>&THORN;e payn of dede here es bitter and sare;</L>
<L N="1776">&THORN;arfor ilk man &thorn;at of dede has mynde</L>
<L>Dredes gretely &thorn;e dede here thurgh kynde;</L>
<L>And swa it semed, als says &thorn;e boke</L>
<L>&THORN;at Crist did in manhede &thorn;at he toke,</L>
<L N="1780">For he byfor, ar he deyghed on &thorn;e rode,</L>
<L>For drede of dede he swet blode;</L>
<L>For he wyst, ar he til &thorn;e dede suld passe,</L>
<L>What &thorn;e payn of &thorn;e dede wasse,
<PB REF="00000094.tif" N="50"></L>
<L N="1784">&THORN;an may we &thorn;arby trow right wele</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e payn of &thorn;e dede es hard to fele.</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e dede here men may thynk wonder.</L>
<L>For alle thyng it brestes in sonder,</L>
<L N="1788">Als it sculkes<NOTE PLACE="foot">stalkes (Lands. MS. 348).</NOTE> by diverse ways;</L>
<L>&THORN;arfor &thorn;e haly man in boke &thorn;us says:</L>
<L><I>Mors omnia</I></L>
<L><I>Solvit.</I></L>
<L N="1792">"&THORN;e dede", he says, "louses alle thyng</L>
<L>And of ilk mans lif mas endyng."</L>
<L>&THORN;e dede es swa sutil and pryv&eacute;,</L>
<L>&THORN;at na man may it properly se;</L>
<L N="1796">And for-&thorn;y &thorn;at na man may se it,</L>
<L>&THORN;arfor may na man knaw ne witt,</L>
<L>Ne ymagyn thurgh witte what it es,</L>
<L>Ne what shappe it has and lyknes.</L>
<L N="1800">Bot what dede es properly to say,</L>
<L>Wha-swa wille, shortly wite he may.</L>
<L>Dede es noght elles to telle shortly,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Dethe is nothing elles to telle sothly,</L>
<L>Bot a departyng of the soule and the body. (MS. Addit 11305.)</L>
</LG></NOTE></L>
<L>Bot a partyng of &thorn;e saul and body,</L>
<L N="1804">Als I byfor aparty sayde.</L>
<L>&THORN;is may be calde &thorn;e dedis brayde,</L>
<L>And a privacion of &thorn;e life,</L>
<L>When it partes fra &thorn;e body in strife.</L>
<L N="1808">And als yhe may se and wate wele,</L>
<L>&THORN;at myrknes kyndly es noght to fele,</L>
<L>Bot overalle whar na light es</L>
<L>&THORN;ar es properly myrknes;</L>
<L N="1812">Right swa &thorn;e dede es noght elles</L>
<L>Bot a pryvyng of lyf, als clerkes telles;</L>
<L>For whar-swa-ever &thorn;e lyf fayles</L>
<L>&THORN;ar es &thorn;e dede &thorn;at &thorn;an assayles.</L>
<L N="1816">&THORN;us &thorn;e dede &thorn;at men dredes mast,</L>
<L>When &thorn;e lyf fayles men byhoves tast.
<PB REF="00000095.tif" N="51"></L>
<L>Four skilles I fynd writen in som stede,</L>
<L>Why men suld specialy drede &thorn;e dede:</L>
<L N="1820">An es for &thorn;e dede stoure swa felle</L>
<L>&THORN;at es mare payne &thorn;an man can telle,</L>
<L>&THORN;e whilk ilk man sal fele with-in,</L>
<L>When &thorn;e body and &thorn;e saule salle twyn.</L>
<L N="1824">Another es for &thorn;e sight &thorn;at he sal se</L>
<L>Of devels, &thorn;at about hym &thorn;an sal be.</L>
<L>&THORN;e thred es for &thorn;e acount &thorn;at he sal yheld</L>
<L>Of alle his lyf, of yhouthe and elde.</L>
<L N="1828">&THORN;e ferth es, for he es uncertayne</L>
<L>Whether he sal wend til ioy or payne;</L>
<L>Wha-swa wil of &thorn;er four take hede,</L>
<L>Hym aght gretely here &thorn;e dede to drede.</L>
<L N="1832">Of twa of &thorn;ere four, byfore I spake,</L>
<L>Now wil I other twa til &thorn;am take;</L>
<L>For of twa I spak first generaly,</L>
<L>Now I wille with other twa &thorn;am specify.</L>
<L N="1836">First aght men drede &thorn;e ded in hert,</L>
<L>For &thorn;e payn of &thorn;e dede &thorn;at es swa smert,</L>
<L>&THORN;at es &thorn;e hard stour at &thorn;e last ende,</L>
<L>When &thorn;e saule sal fra &thorn;e body wende;</L>
<L N="1840">A doleful partyng es &thorn;at to telle,</L>
<L>For &thorn;ai luf ay togyder to duelle;</L>
<L>Nouther of &thorn;am wald other forga</L>
<L>Swa mykel lof es bytwen &thorn;am twa;</L>
<L N="1844">And &thorn;e mare &thorn;at twa togyder lufes,</L>
<L>Als a man and his wyfe oft pruves,</L>
<L>&THORN;e mare sorow and murnyng</L>
<L>Byhoves be at &thorn;air departyng.</L>
<L N="1848">Bot &thorn;e body and &thorn;e saul with &thorn;e lyfe</L>
<L>Lufes mare samen &thorn;an man and hys wyfe,</L>
<L>Whether &thorn;ai be in gude way or ille,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at es for many sere skylle.</L>
<L N="1852">A skylle es, als yhe sal now se,</L>
<L>Why &thorn;ai wald ay togyder be;</L>
<L>For-&thorn;y &thorn;at God, als says haly writ,</L>
<L>First body and saul togyder knyt;
<PB REF="00000096.tif" N="52"></L>
<L N="1856">Another for the tane may noght do</L>
<L>Bot if &thorn;e tother help &thorn;ar-to;</L>
<L>&THORN;e thred for &thorn;ai bathe togider sal come</L>
<L>Byfor God at &thorn;e day of dome;</L>
<L N="1860">&THORN;e ferthe, for when &thorn;ai er comen theder,</L>
<L>&THORN;ai sal ay after duel togider.</L>
<L>&THORN;arfor &thorn;air payne and sorow es mare</L>
<L>When &thorn;e tane sal fra &thorn;e tother fare.</L>
<L N="1864">&THORN;is twynnyng may be cald &thorn;e dede,</L>
<L>&THORN;at fleyghes about fra sted til stede</L>
<L>Thurgh alle landes, fer and nere,</L>
<L>And spares nan of wham he has powere,</L>
<L N="1868">For prayer ne gyfte &thorn;at men may gyfe.</L>
<L>Whare he comes he lattes nane lyfe,</L>
<L>Ne for luf ne awe er nane sparde;</L>
<L>For &thorn;e dede til na man tas rewarde,</L>
<L N="1872">Ne riche ne pover he spars, hegh ne law,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he ne &thorn;e lyf wil fra &thorn;am draw,</L>
<L>&THORN;e dede has mercy of na wight,</L>
<L>Als Saynt Bernard &thorn;us shewes right:</L>
<L N="1876"><I>Non miseretur mors inopie,</I></L>
<L><I>non reveretur diviciis, non sa|</I></L>
<L><I>piencie, non moribus,</I></L>
<L><I>non etati.</I></L>
<L N="1880">He says "&thorn;e dede of povert na mercy has,</L>
<L>Ne to ryches ne<NOTE PLACE="foot">No (MS. Harl. 4196).</NOTE> reward tas,</L>
<L>Ne til wysdom &thorn;at wyse men schewes,</L>
<L>Ne til elde of man ne til gude thewes."</L>
<L N="1884">Dede wil na frendshepe do ne favour,</L>
<L>Ne reverence til kyng ne til emperour,</L>
<L>Ne til pape, ne til bisshope, ne na prelate,</L>
<L>Ne til nan other man of heghe estate,</L>
<L N="1888">Ne til na religiouse, ne til na seculere,</L>
<L>For dede over al men has powere.</L>
<L>And thurgh &thorn;e dede hand al sal pas,</L>
<L>Als Salamon says, &thorn;at wyse was:</L>
<L N="1892"><I>Communionem</I></L>
<L><I>mortis scito.</I>
<PB REF="00000097.tif" N="53"></L>
<L>"Knaw &thorn;ow," he says, &thorn;at &thorn;e dede es</L>
<L>Comon to al men, bathe mare and les."</L>
<L N="1896">&THORN;us sal dede visite ilk man,</L>
<L>And yhit na man discryve it can,</L>
<L>For here lyves nan, under hevenryke,</L>
<L>&THORN;at can telle til what &thorn;e ded es lyke.</L>
<L N="1900">Bot &thorn;e payn of dede &thorn;at al sal fele</L>
<L>A philosopher &thorn;us discrived wele;</L>
<L>For he lykend mans lyf til a tre</L>
<L>&THORN;at war growand, if it swa mught be,</L>
<L N="1904">Thurgh a mans hert and swa shuld sprynge,</L>
<L>&THORN;at obout war lapped with &thorn;e hert strynge,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e croppe out at his mouth mught<NOTE PLACE="foot">The MS. reads: 'And &thorn;e croppe out at his <I>mught mught</I> shote'.</NOTE> shote,</L>
<L>And to ilka ioynt war fested a rote;</L>
<L N="1908">And ilka vayne of &thorn;e mans body</L>
<L>Had a rote festend fast &thorn;arby,</L>
<L>And in ilka taa and fynger of hand</L>
<L>War a rote fra &thorn;at tre growand;</L>
<L N="1912">And ilka lym on ilka syde</L>
<L>With rotes of &thorn;at tre war occupyde;</L>
<L>Yf &thorn;at tre war tite pulled oute</L>
<L>At a titte with al &thorn;e rotes oboute,</L>
<L N="1916">&THORN;e rotes suld &thorn;an rayse &thorn;ar-with</L>
<L>Ilka vayn and ilka synoghe and lith.</L>
<L>A mare payne couthe na man in hert cast</L>
<L>&THORN;an &thorn;is war, als lang als it suld last.</L>
<L N="1920">And yhit halde I &thorn;e payne of dede mare</L>
<L>And mare strang and hard, &thorn;an &thorn;is payn ware;</L>
<L>&THORN;os a philosopher when he lyfed,</L>
<L>&THORN;e payn of &thorn;e dede here discrived.</L>
<L N="1924">&THORN;arfor ilk man, als I byfor sayde,</L>
<L>Aght to drede &thorn;e bitter dedes brayde,</L>
<L>For bathe gode and ille sal it taste;</L>
<L>Bot ille men aght drede it maste,</L>
<L N="1928">For dred of ded mast pyns wythin</L>
<L>A man &thorn;at here es ful of syn,</L>
<L>&THORN;arfor &thorn;e prophet says in a stede,</L>
<L>And spekes &thorn;us un-til &thorn;e dede:
<PB REF="00000098.tif" N="54"></L>
<L N="1932"><I>O mors quam amara memoria</I></L>
<L><I>tua homini iniusto.</I></L>
<L>"O &thorn;ou grysely dede," says he,</L>
<L>"Ful bitter es &thorn;e mynde of &thorn;e,</L>
<L N="1936">Until &thorn;e synful man" namly,</L>
<L>&THORN;at for his syn es paynworthy;</L>
<L>&THORN;arfor me thynk he es unsleghe</L>
<L>&THORN;at mas hym noght here redy to deghe;</L>
<L N="1940">For &thorn;e dede es privy and sodayne,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e tyme of his commyng uncertayne.</L>
<L>A man for certayne sal dighe at &thorn;e last,</L>
<L>For his lyf is noght bot als a wynd blast,</L>
<L N="1944">Bot he wayte never what tyme ne whan;</L>
<L>For swa certayne es here na man</L>
<L>&THORN;at can &thorn;e tyme of &thorn;e dede forluke,</L>
<L>For&thorn;i says Saynt Bernard in a boke:</L>
<L N="1948"><I>Quid in rebus humanis cercius est</I></L>
<L><I>morte; quid incercius hora mortis invenitur.</I></L>
<L>He says: "What es til man mare certayn</L>
<L>&THORN;an &thorn;e dede es &thorn;at es swa sodayn;</L>
<L N="1952">And what es mare uncertayn thyng,</L>
<L>&THORN;an es &thorn;e tyme of the dede commyng",</L>
<L>Alswa say nathyng &thorn;at may be<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Als wha</I> say na thyng that may be. (MS. Harl. 6923.)</NOTE>;</L>
<L>&THORN;an may na man here &thorn;e dede fle.</L>
<L N="1956">&THORN;arfor a man hym suld redy make,</L>
<L>Byfor ar &thorn;e dede com hym to take,</L>
<L>And put hym byfor and ded byhynde,</L>
<L>Swa &thorn;at ded may hym redy fynde;</L>
<L N="1960">&THORN;arfor Saynt Austyn &thorn;e haly man</L>
<L>Says &thorn;us, als I shew yhow can:</L>
<L><I>Nescis qua hora veniat mors,</I></L>
<L><I>semper vigila, ut, quod nescis quando</I></L>
<L N="1964"><I>veniat, paratum te inveniat</I></L>
<L><I>cum venerit, et adhoc forte</I></L>
<L><I>nescis quando veniat, ut semper</I></L>
<L><I>sis paratus.</I></L>
<L N="1968">"Man &thorn;an knawes noght," says he,</L>
<L>"What tyme &thorn;e dedes comyng sal be;
<PB REF="00000099.tif" N="55"></L>
<L>Wake ay als &thorn;ou had na knawyng</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e tyme of dedys commyng,</L>
<L N="1972">&THORN;at &thorn;e dede may fynd &thorn;e, when it sal com,</L>
<L>Ay redy til God and bugh[so]m;</L>
<L>And to &thorn;at perchaunce knaw &thorn;ou ne may</L>
<L>&THORN;e commyng, for &thorn;ou shuld be redy ay."</L>
<L N="1976">&THORN;an byhoved us our lyf swa cast</L>
<L>Als ilk day of our lif war &thorn;e last;</L>
<L>And ilk day be redy and lif wele,</L>
<L>Als we suld ilk day &thorn;e ded fele,</L>
<L N="1980">And byde noght til &thorn;e dede us vyset,</L>
<L>&THORN;arfor &thorn;os says Saynt Austyn yhet:</L>
<L><I>Latet ultimus dies, ut observentur</I></L>
<L><I>omnes dies, sero parantur reme|</I></L>
<L N="1984"><I>dia cum mortis imminent</I></L>
<L><I>pericula.</I></L>
<L>"&THORN;e last day of man is hyd", he says,</L>
<L>"For he shuld kepe wele al &thorn;e other dayes,</L>
<L N="1988">For over late men ordayns remedy,</L>
<L>When perels of dede comes sodanly."</L>
<L>For if a man &thorn;at unredy es,</L>
<L>Be tane with dede in his wykednes,</L>
<L N="1992">Turne agayne &thorn;an may he noght</L>
<L>For to amend &thorn;at he has myswroght;</L>
<L>In &thorn;at state, &thorn;at he es in tane,</L>
<L>He sal be demed when he es gane;</L>
<L N="1996">Wharfor a man for drede of lettyng</L>
<L>Shuld noght abyde &thorn;e dedes commyng,</L>
<L>Bot make hym redy, ar he fel harde,</L>
<L>And kepe hym ay wele aftirwarde,</L>
<L N="2000">For when &thorn;e dede es at &thorn;e yhate,</L>
<L>&THORN;an es he warned over late.</L>
<L>&THORN;e dede fra a man his mynd reves</L>
<L>And na kyndely witte with hym leves,</L>
<L N="2004">For &thorn;an sal he fele swilk payn and drede,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he ne may thynk of na mysdede,</L>
<L>Bot of his payn and of noght elles,</L>
<L>Als &thorn;is grete clerk Saynt Austyn telles:
<PB REF="00000100.tif" N="56"></L>
<L N="2008"><I>Tymor mortis totam animam sibi vendicat,</I></L>
<L><I>ut nec de peccatis tunc libeat cogitare.</I></L>
<L>&THORN;e drede of &thorn;e ded when it flayes a man,</L>
<L>Chalanges al &thorn;e saul tyl it &thorn;an;</L>
<L N="2012">Swa &thorn;at hym liste &thorn;an haf na thoght</L>
<L>Of his synnes &thorn;at he here has wroght.</L>
<L>&THORN;an folowes &thorn;at man na wys rede</L>
<L>&THORN;at abydes &thorn;e commyng of &thorn;e dede,</L>
<L N="2016">And hastes hym noght to clense hym sone</L>
<L>Of al his syns &thorn;at [he] has done;</L>
<L>For when &thorn;e dede comes til a man</L>
<L>It es over late to bygyn &thorn;an;</L>
<L N="2020">Bot I rede a man he amend hym here,</L>
<L>Or &thorn;e dede come, or his messangere;<NOTE PLACE="foot">The MS. reads <I>mensangere</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>For if he wille swa byfor be war.</L>
<L>&THORN;e dede &thorn;an wele les drede hym &thorn;ar;</L>
<L N="2024">His messangere may be called sekenes,</L>
<L>&THORN;at comes byfor als ofte felled es;</L>
<L>For sekenes ofte a man swa pynes</L>
<L>&THORN;at thurgh &thorn;at payn hys mynd he tynes,</L>
<L N="2028">For he may &thorn;an thynk on noght elles</L>
<L>Bot of &thorn;e payn &thorn;at with hym duelles.</L>
<L>Bot when &thorn;e ded comes aftirward</L>
<L>And hym byhoves fele mare hard,</L>
<L N="2032">&THORN;an sal he be in swylk drede sette,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he sal God and hymself forget,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at es skylle for he wil noght,</L>
<L>Whyles he has hele, haf God in thoght,</L>
<L N="2036">&THORN;arfor he sal &thorn;an his mynde tyne</L>
<L>And &thorn;arfor &thorn;us says Saynt Austyne:</L>
<L><I>Hac animaversione percutitur</I></L>
<L><I>peccator, ut moriens obliviscatur</I></L>
<L N="2040"><I>sui, qui dum viveret oblitus</I></L>
<L><I>est Dei.</I></L>
<L>"&THORN;e synful", he says, als es writen,</L>
<L>"With pyne of &thorn;e dede es smyten,</L>
<L N="2044">&THORN;at he thurgh payn &thorn;at him byhoves drighe,</L>
<L>Hym-self forgetis when he sal dighe,
<PB REF="00000101.tif" N="57"></L>
<L>&THORN;at whylles he mught lif here bodyly,</L>
<L>Forgatte his God &thorn;at es almyghty."</L>
<L N="2048">Many synful has here na grace</L>
<L>To haf tyme of repentance, ne space;</L>
<L>For whiles &thorn;ai lyf &thorn;ai have na mynde</L>
<L>Of God, bot forgettes hym, als ay unkynde.</L>
<L N="2052">Me thyn[k] &thorn;an &thorn;at it es skille and right</L>
<L>&THORN;at thurgh dede God reve &thorn;am mynd and myght;</L>
<L>&THORN;us sal &thorn;ai dyghe and heven blis tyne</L>
<L>And be putted til endeles pyne,</L>
<L N="2056">&THORN;at til God here er swa uncurtays,</L>
<L>&THORN;arfor David in &thorn;e psauter says:</L>
<L><I>Vos sicut homines moriemini, et</I></L>
<L><I>sicut unus de principibus cadetis.</I></L>
<L N="2060">He says: "Als men yhe sal digh alle,</L>
<L>And als ane of &thorn;e princes yhe sal falle."</L>
<L>&THORN;at es yhe sal dighe of &thorn;e same manere,</L>
<L>Als men dighes in &thorn;is world here,</L>
<L N="2064">And als &thorn;e spyrites &thorn;at fra heven felle,</L>
<L>Be casten don intille helle.</L>
<L>&THORN;arfor til a man it war wysdome</L>
<L>To repente hym or &thorn;e dede come,</L>
<L N="2068">And haf God in mynde whyles he lyfes here,</L>
<L>Als &thorn;e prophet biddes on &thorn;is manere:</L>
<L><I>Memento creatoris tui antequam ve|</I></L>
<L><I>niat tempus visitacionis sue.</I></L>
<L N="2072">"Thynk," he says, "and haf in &thorn;i thoght</L>
<L>Of hym &thorn;at made &thorn;e first of noght,</L>
<L>Whilles &thorn;ou lyffes, ar &thorn;e tyme sal be,</L>
<L>When he with &thorn;e dede sal viset &thorn;e."</L>
<L N="2076">For when dede here assayles a man</L>
<L>He may noght thynk wele on God &thorn;an,</L>
<L>For &thorn;e dede his mynde away &thorn;an brekes,</L>
<L>And &thorn;arfor David &thorn;os til God spekes:</L>
<L N="2080"><I>Quoniam non est in morte</I></L>
<L><I>qui memor sit tui.</I></L>
<L>"Lord", he says, "&thorn;at man es noght</L>
<L>In dede, &thorn;at of &thorn;e here has thoght."
<PB REF="00000102.tif" N="58"></L>
<L N="2084">Bot men may understand hereby</L>
<L>Dede of saule thurgh syn namly;</L>
<L>For he &thorn;at has ay God in thoght,</L>
<L>In dede of saul semes he noght;</L>
<L N="2088">And he &thorn;at of God es myndles</L>
<L>It semes &thorn;at he in saul dede es.</L>
<L>God visites us in ilka stede</L>
<L>Whare we may fele takens of dede,</L>
<L N="2092">And if we couthe understand wele,</L>
<L>Ilk day we may takens of dede fele;</L>
<L>&THORN;arfor me thynk alle this lif here semes</L>
<L>Mar dede &thorn;an lyf, &thorn;us wysmen demes;</L>
<L N="2096">For &thorn;e boke says, als it beres wyttenes,</L>
<L>&THORN;at a man, when he first borne es,</L>
<L>Bygynnes towarde &thorn;e dede to drawe</L>
<L>And feles here many a dede thraw,</L>
<L N="2100">Als sere yvels and angers when &thorn;ai byfalle,</L>
<L>&THORN;at men may &thorn;e dede thrawes calle,</L>
<L>And other perils and quathes many,</L>
<L>&THORN;at commes to men ofte sodanly.</L>
<L N="2104">&THORN;an es our birthe here bygynnyng</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e dede &thorn;at es our endyng;</L>
<L>For ay &thorn;e mare &thorn;at we wax alde</L>
<L>&THORN;e mare our lif may be ded talde.</L>
<L N="2108">&THORN;arfor whylles we er here lyffand</L>
<L>Ilk day er we &thorn;os dighand;</L>
<L>&THORN;an semes our lyf nathyng elles</L>
<L>Bot als a dede, als &thorn;e bok telles,</L>
<L N="2112">And til other lyf wyn we noght,</L>
<L>Til &thorn;e dede &thorn;is life til ende haf broght;</L>
<L>Bot when &thorn;e dede has made ende,</L>
<L>&THORN;an wate we never whyder we sal wende;</L>
<L N="2116">Wether we sal til wele or wa,</L>
<L>Bot til &thorn;e tane byhoves us ga.</L>
<L>For-why til gude men &thorn;e dede es way</L>
<L>Til &thorn;e blisse of heven &thorn;at lastes ay,</L>
<L N="2120">And til ille men yhate and entree</L>
<L>Til &thorn;e pyn of helle &thorn;at ay sal be;
<PB REF="00000103.tif" N="59"></L>
<L>&THORN;arfor David, &thorn;at was swa haly,</L>
<L>Spekes &thorn;us til God almyghty:</L>
<L N="2124"><I>Qui exaltas me de portis mortis, ut an|</I></L>
<L><I>nunciem omnes laudaciones tuas, in portis filie Syon.</I></L>
<L>"Loverd", says David, "&thorn;ou ert he</L>
<L>&THORN;at fra &thorn;e yhates of dede liftes me,</L>
<L N="2128">&THORN;at I may shew over alle thynges</L>
<L>Specialy alle &thorn;i lovynges,</L>
<L>In &thorn;e yhates of doghter Syon."</L>
<L>&THORN;at, als clerkes says &thorn;at can &thorn;ar-on,</L>
<L N="2132">Es haly kyrk &thorn;at God first ches,</L>
<L>Thurgh whilk men commes to &thorn;e sight of pes.</L>
<L>By &thorn;e yhates of dede, als men may se,</L>
<L>&THORN;e dede of helle may understanden be</L>
<L N="2136">Fra wilk God liftes us day and nyght,</L>
<L>To shewe his lovynges with alle our myght,</L>
<L>And to serve hym and his werkes to wyrk</L>
<L>In stedfast trouthe of haly kyrk,</L>
<L N="2140">Swa &thorn;at we may afterwarde wende</L>
<L>Til &thorn;e sight of pees &thorn;at has nan ende.</L>
<L>Heghe in heven es &thorn;at fair sight,</L>
<L>&THORN;at alle sal se &thorn;at here lyves ryght;</L>
<L N="2144">Bot alle &thorn;at sal com til &thorn;at stede</L>
<L>Byhoves passe hethen thurgh bodily dede;</L>
<L>For &thorn;at dede to &thorn;am es noght ille</L>
<L>&THORN;at lyffes here after Goddes wille,</L>
<L N="2148">And in &thorn;at lif stedfastly duelles;</L>
<L>And &thorn;arfor Saynt Austyn &thorn;us telles:</L>
<L><I>Mala mors putanda non est quam</I></L>
<L><I>bona vita precessit, neque enim facit</I></L>
<L N="2152"><I>malam mortem, nisi quod sequitur</I></L>
<L><I>ipsam mortem.</I></L>
<L>He says: "na man ille dede shuld wene</L>
<L>&THORN;ar, whar gude lyf byfor has bene;</L>
<L N="2156">For nathyng mas ille dede to tast,</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;at &thorn;at folows &thorn;e dede mast",</L>
<L>&THORN;at es dedely dedes &thorn;at sum wille do,</L>
<L>And yhit says Sayn[t] Austyn &thorn;os &thorn;arto:
<PB REF="00000104.tif" N="60"></L>
<L N="2160"><I>Non potest male mori qui bene vixit,</I></L>
<L><I>Et vix bene moritur qui male vixit.</I></L>
<L>He says: "he may noght ille dede fele</L>
<L>&THORN;at in Goddes laghe has lyfed wele;</L>
<L N="2164">And unnethes may men se by skille,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he dyghes wele &thorn;at hafes lyfed ille."</L>
<L>Bot he &thorn;at hates &thorn;is lyfes lykyng</L>
<L>Thar noght drede &thorn;e dedes commyng;</L>
<L N="2168">For aftir his dede na payn hym ders,</L>
<L>&THORN;arfor says Caton &thorn;us in a vers:</L>
<L><I>Non metuit mortem,</I></L>
<L><I>qui sit contempnere vitam.</I></L>
<L N="2172">He says: "he &thorn;at &thorn;is lif despyse</L>
<L>Thar dred &thorn;e dede here on na wyse;"</L>
<L>Swa did martirs &thorn;at &thorn;e dede soght,<NOTE PLACE="foot">The MS. reads <I>soghot</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>For by &thorn;is lyf sette &thorn;ai right noght;</L>
<L N="2176">And other halymen yherned to dyghe</L>
<L>For to be with God in heven hyghe,</L>
<L>Als &thorn;e boke of &thorn;air lyfes shewes us,</L>
<L>And swa did Saynt Paul &thorn;at says &thorn;us:</L>
<L N="2180"><I>Cupio dissolvi</I></L>
<L><I>et esse cum Cristo.</I></L>
<L>"I yhern", he says. "be loused away</L>
<L>Fra &thorn;is life and be with Crist ay."</L>
<L N="2184">Haly men thogh[t] &thorn;is lyf bot wast,</L>
<L>&THORN;arfor &thorn;air yhernyng til God was mast;</L>
<L>And for-&thorn;i &thorn;at &thorn;am thoght alle &thorn;is lyfe</L>
<L>Noght bot travail, angre, and strife,</L>
<L N="2188">&THORN;ai yherned &thorn;e ende of &thorn;air lyf days,</L>
<L>And &thorn;arfor &thorn;e haly man &thorn;os says:</L>
<L><I>Melius est dies mortis</I></L>
<L><I>quam dies nativitatis.</I></L>
<L N="2192">He says: "better es &thorn;e day of dede</L>
<L>&THORN;an &thorn;e day of burthe", and mare standes in stede.</L>
<L>For-why a gude man dighes to wend to rest,</L>
<L>Whare his lyf sal be alther-best
<PB REF="00000105.tif" N="61"></L>
<L N="2196">When &thorn;e saul fra &thorn;e body swippes,</L>
<L>Als Saynt Johan says in &thorn;e Appocalippes:</L>
<L><I>Beati mortui qui in domino</I></L>
<L><I>moriuntur.</I></L>
<L N="2200">"Blessed be alle &thorn;as &thorn;at in body</L>
<L>Dighes here in God alle-myghty."</L>
<L>For &thorn;as &thorn;at men sese in gude lyfe ende</L>
<L>Dighes in God, and &thorn;ai sal wende</L>
<L N="2204">Til &thorn;e blisse of heven &thorn;at es swa hyghe,</L>
<L>Wele es hym &thorn;an &thorn;at swa may dighe.</L>
<L>Bot alle-yf haly men may digh wele,</L>
<L>Yhit &thorn;e payn of dede byhoves &thorn;am fele,</L>
<L N="2208">&THORN;at es mare &thorn;an man can ymagyn</L>
<L>When &thorn;e body and &thorn;e saule sal twyn;</L>
<L>&THORN;e wilk &thorn;am aght dred aparty,</L>
<L>Thurgh manskynd or elles war ferly:</L>
<L N="2212">For sen Crist, als I sayd befor, had dred</L>
<L>Of the ded, thurgh kynd of his manhed,</L>
<L>&THORN;an aght ilkman, bathe mare and les,</L>
<L>Drede &thorn;e dede here &thorn;at swa bitter es.</L>
<L N="2216">&THORN;e secund skil, als byfor es redde,</L>
<L>Why &thorn;e dede es swa gretely drede,</L>
<L>Es for &thorn;e grisly syght of fendes</L>
<L>&THORN;at a man sal se when his lyf endes.</L>
<L N="2220">For when &thorn;e lyf sal pas fra a man</L>
<L>Devels sal gadir obout hym &thorn;an,</L>
<L>To ravissche &thorn;e saul with &thorn;am away</L>
<L>Tyl pyne of helle, if &thorn;ai may.</L>
<L N="2224">Als wode lyons &thorn;ai sal &thorn;an fare</L>
<L>And raumpe on hym, and skoul, and stare,</L>
<L>And grymly gryn on hym and blere,</L>
<L>And hydus braydes mak hym to fere;</L>
<L N="2228">&THORN;ai sal fande at his last endyng</L>
<L>Hym in-to wanhope for to bring,</L>
<L>Thurgh thretynges &thorn;at &thorn;ai sal mak,</L>
<L>And thurgh &thorn;e ferdnes &thorn;at he sal tak.</L>
<L N="2232">Ful hydus sightes &thorn;ai sal shew hym</L>
<L>&THORN;at his chere sal make grisly and grym.
<PB REF="00000106.tif" N="62"></L>
<L>&THORN;at sight he sal se with gastly eghe</L>
<L>With payn of dede &thorn;at he most dreghe.</L>
<L N="2236">Here-of &thorn;e prophet Ieremy</L>
<L>Spekes &thorn;us in his prophecy:</L>
<L><I>Omnes inimici eius apprehenderunt</I></L>
<L><I>eum inter angustias.</I></L>
<L N="2240">He says: "omang his grete anguys</L>
<L>Hym &thorn;ai sal tak al hys enmys."</L>
<L>Na vonder es if &thorn;e devels com &thorn;an</L>
<L>In &thorn;e ende obout a synful man,</L>
<L N="2244">For to flay hym and tempte and pyn,</L>
<L>When &thorn;e devel com to Saynt Martyn</L>
<L>In &thorn;e tyme of dede at his last day</L>
<L>Hym for to tempte and for to flay:</L>
<L N="2248">And in &thorn;e life of Saynt Bernard</L>
<L>We rede &thorn;at when he drogh til dedeward,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e devel &thorn;at es grisely and grym,</L>
<L>Til hym come and asked hym,</L>
<L N="2252">By what skille he wald, and bi<NOTE PLACE="foot">The MS. reads <I>be</I>.</NOTE> what ryght;</L>
<L>Chalange &thorn;e kyngdom of heven bright,</L>
<L>&THORN;an answerd Bernard &thorn;us mekely,</L>
<L>And sayd: "I knaw &thorn;at I am unworthy,</L>
<L N="2256">Thurgh myn-awen desert, to haf it</L>
<L>When I sal out of &thorn;is world flit.</L>
<L>Bot my Lorde Ihesu Crist ful of myght,</L>
<L>&THORN;at it has and weldes thurgh doble ryght,</L>
<L N="2260">Thurgh right of his faders heritage,</L>
<L>And alswa for our grete avauntage,</L>
<L>Thurgh right of hys hard passion,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he tholed for our raunson,</L>
<L N="2264">&THORN;e ta right frely he graunted me,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e tother til hym-self held he;</L>
<L>Of was gyfte I chala[n]ge it by skille,</L>
<L>Als &thorn;e lagh of his mercy wille."</L>
<L N="2268">And when &thorn;e devel herd hym &thorn;us say,</L>
<L>Alle skomfit he vanyst oway;</L>
<L>And &thorn;e halyman when &thorn;is was done</L>
<L>Torned ogayne til hym-self sone,
<PB REF="00000107.tif" N="63"></L>
<L N="2272">And he yhelded &thorn;e gast to God and dyghed,</L>
<L>And swa &thorn;e saul til heven flyghed.</L>
<L>And yhit es mare wonder to telle</L>
<L>&THORN;at God wald suffer &thorn;e devel of helle,</L>
<L N="2276">Apere til hymself &thorn;at es of myght mast,</L>
<L>When he suld dygh and yheld &thorn;e gast,</L>
<L>Als docturs says of haly writ,</L>
<L>In bukes thurgh whilk men may knaw it.</L>
<L N="2280">&THORN;an semes it wele &thorn;at God wil &thorn;us</L>
<L>Suffer &thorn;e devel apere til us</L>
<L>In tyme of dede, at our last ende,</L>
<L>When we sal out of &thorn;is world wende,</L>
<L N="2284">Sen haly men &thorn;at here liffed right</L>
<L>Mught noght dygh with-outen &thorn;at sight,</L>
<L>Ne godys moder &thorn;at he loffed mare,</L>
<L>Wald noght fra &thorn;at syght spare,</L>
<L N="2288">Bot &thorn;at he graunted at hir askyng</L>
<L>&THORN;at in &thorn;e tyme of hir passyng</L>
<L>&THORN;ai suld na power haf hir to dere,</L>
<L>Ne &thorn;at &thorn;e syght of &thorn;am shuld hir fere;</L>
<L N="2292">And yhit sen God hymself spard noght,</L>
<L>For at his dede &thorn;e devel til hym soght</L>
<L>In his manhede for swa &thorn;an he walde,</L>
<L>Als men says &thorn;at er gret clerkes calde.</L>
<L N="2296">&THORN;an er we certayn, with-outen were</L>
<L>&THORN;at at our last ende &thorn;ai sal apere.</L>
<L>Bot a gret payne &thorn;an til us sal &thorn;is be</L>
<L>&THORN;e sight of &thorn;am when we &thorn;am se;</L>
<L N="2300">For &thorn;ai er swa grisely, als says &thorn;e buke,</L>
<L>And swa blak and foule on to loke,</L>
<L>&THORN;at al &thorn;e men here of mydlerd</L>
<L>Of &thorn;at sight mught be aferd;</L>
<L N="2304">For al &thorn;e men here of &thorn;is lyfe</L>
<L>Swa grysely a sight couth noght descryfe,</L>
<L>Ne thurgh wyt ymagyn ne deme,</L>
<L>Als &thorn;ai sal in tyme of dede seme,</L>
<L N="2308">Ne swa sleygh payntur never nan was,</L>
<L>&THORN;ogh his sleght mught alle other pas,
<PB REF="00000108.tif" N="64"></L>
<L>&THORN;at couthe ymagyn of &thorn;air gryslynes</L>
<L>Or paynt a poynt aftir &thorn;air liknes;</L>
<L N="2312">For in &thorn;is lif here may na man</L>
<L>Se &thorn;am in &thorn;e fourme &thorn;at &thorn;ai haf &thorn;an,</L>
<L>For if &thorn;ai had swa large powere,</L>
<L>In swilk forme to shew &thorn;am here,</L>
<L N="2316">Out of witte &thorn;an &thorn;ai shuld men flay,</L>
<L>Swa orrible and swa foul er &thorn;ai;</L>
<L>For-why swa hardy man here es nane</L>
<L>Ne &thorn;at ever was liffand in flesshe and bane,</L>
<L N="2320">&THORN;at saghe a devel in his fygur right,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he ne for ferdnes of &thorn;at sight</L>
<L>Shuld dighe, or at &thorn;e leste tyn his witt,</L>
<L>Als son after als he had sene it;</L>
<L N="2324">Bot in swilk fourme, als I undirstand,</L>
<L>&THORN;ai shew &thorn;am til na man liffand,</L>
<L>Bot til &thorn;am til wham &thorn;e dede es nere;</L>
<L>For God has restreyned &thorn;ai[r] powere</L>
<L N="2328">&THORN;at &thorn;ai may na man tempte ne greve,</L>
<L>Ferrer forthe, &thorn;an &thorn;ai hafe leve.</L>
<L>Bot when &thorn;e ded assaylles a man,</L>
<L>In &thorn;e foulest figure &thorn;ai apere &thorn;an;</L>
<L N="2332">&THORN;arfor aght ilk man dredand be</L>
<L>Agayne &thorn;e tyme when he sal &thorn;am se.</L>
<L>Bot I wille shew yhow aparty</L>
<L>Why &thorn;ai er swa foul and grisly,</L>
<L N="2336">For sum tyme &thorn;ai war bright angels,</L>
<L>Als &thorn;a er &thorn;at now in heven duels,</L>
<L>Fra &thorn;at blisful place thurgh syn &thorn;ai felle,</L>
<L>And bycome &thorn;an foule devels of helle,</L>
<L N="2340">And horribely defygurd, thurgh syn</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ai war wyth-fild and hardened &thorn;arin.</L>
<L>For warne syn war &thorn;ai had ay bene</L>
<L>Bright aungels, als &thorn;ai war first sene;</L>
<L N="2344">And now er &thorn;ai made foule and ugly</L>
<L>Thurgh fylyng of &thorn;air syn anly,</L>
<L>&THORN;an es syn mar foule and wlatsome,</L>
<L>&THORN;an any devel &thorn;at out of helle may come;
<PB REF="00000109.tif" N="65"></L>
<L N="2348">For a thyng es fouler &thorn;at may file,</L>
<L>&THORN;an &thorn;e thyng &thorn;at it fyles, and mare vile,</L>
<L>&THORN;arfor says clerkes of grete cunnyng,</L>
<L>&THORN;at syn es swa foule and swa grisly thyng,</L>
<L N="2352">&THORN;at if a man mught properly se his syn</L>
<L>In &thorn;e kynd lyknes &thorn;at it falles be in,</L>
<L>He shuld for ferdnes titter it fle</L>
<L>&THORN;an any devel &thorn;at he mught se;</L>
<L N="2356">Here may men se and undirstande</L>
<L>How foul es syn and how fylande.</L>
<L>Bot men sese noght ne knawes what it es,</L>
<L>&THORN;arfor men dredes it wele &thorn;e les.</L>
<L N="2360">Bot if a synful myght se with-oute</L>
<L>How foul &thorn;e syn es, &thorn;at he bers oboute,</L>
<L>He suld never make ioy ne haf lykyng,</L>
<L>Until he war delyverd of &thorn;at foul thyng.</L>
<L N="2364">Sen<NOTE PLACE="foot">The MS. reads <I>Syn</I>.</NOTE> &thorn;e devel &thorn;us has tane his uglines</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e filth of syn, &thorn;at swa filand es,</L>
<L>&THORN;an aght &thorn;e saul of synful with-in</L>
<L>Be ful foule &thorn;at es alle slotered in syn;</L>
<L N="2368">&THORN;arfor a man aght, war-so he wendes,</L>
<L>Mare drede syn &thorn;an &thorn;e syght of fendes,</L>
<L>&THORN;at sal aper til hym at his dede day.</L>
<L>Bot his syn he sal se fouler &thorn;an &thorn;ay,</L>
<L N="2372">Of whilk he wald noght hym right shrife.</L>
<L>Ne repent hym here in his lyfe.</L>
<L>&THORN;e thred skill til our undirstandyng</L>
<L>Why us aght drede &thorn;e dede commyng,</L>
<L N="2376">Es for &thorn;e acont ful strayt and harde,</L>
<L>Of alle our lif &thorn;at has bene frawarde,</L>
<L>&THORN;at us byhoves yheld in God sight</L>
<L>Als wele of wrang als of right,</L>
<L N="2380">Of alle thyng &thorn;at ever we wroght,</L>
<L>In werk, in worde, in wille, in thoght,</L>
<L>And of alle &thorn;e tymes &thorn;at passes oway</L>
<L>Fra our bygynnyng to our last day,</L>
<L N="2384">Alle sal &thorn;an be shewed and sene,</L>
<L>Bathe gude and ille, foul and clene,
<PB REF="00000110.tif" N="66"></L>
<L>And be reherced als &thorn;e buke telles,</L>
<L>Bytwene grysely fendes and bright angels;</L>
<L N="2388">&THORN;ai sal dispute &thorn;an of our life</L>
<L>With grete discorde and grete strife.</L>
<L>&THORN;e aungels sal reherce &thorn;e gude,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e devels &thorn;e yvel, with grete mude.<NOTE PLACE="foot">'eger mode' (MS. Harl. 6923).</NOTE></L>
<L N="2392">Alle &thorn;e werkes &thorn;at we here haf wroght,</L>
<L>Bytwene &thorn;am &thorn;an sal be out soght,</L>
<L>And ilka thoght and ilka wille,</L>
<L>Als wele &thorn;e gude als &thorn;e ille;</L>
<L N="2396">And ilka worde &thorn;at spoken haf we</L>
<L>Gude or ille whether &thorn;ai be,</L>
<L>Alle sal be reherced, als I sayde are.</L>
<L>Bytwen &thorn;am &thorn;an &thorn;ai sal nan spare,</L>
<L N="2400">Bot anly syn &thorn;at es wele clensed here,</L>
<L>And gude dede &thorn;at es don on right manere.</L>
<L>&THORN;an sal we bathe here and se</L>
<L>Al &thorn;e privetese &thorn;at ever did we,</L>
<L N="2404">&THORN;arfor says God in &thorn;e godspelle,</L>
<L>On &thorn;is manere, als I wille yow telle:</L>
<L><I>Nichil est opertum quod non reveletur, nec</I></L>
<L><I>occultum quod non sciatur.</I></L>
<L N="2408">Nathyng here swa covered and hydde,</L>
<L>&THORN;at sal noght &thorn;an be shewed and kydde,</L>
<L>Ne swa priv&eacute; es nathyng &thorn;at touches man,</L>
<L>&THORN;at sal noght be knawen &thorn;an.</L>
<L N="2412">&THORN;an most us abyde, we may noght fle,</L>
<L>Until al our lyf examynd be,</L>
<L>And alle our dedys, bathe gude and ille,</L>
<L>Be discussed, after Goddes wille;</L>
<L N="2416">&THORN;an sal we se alle our syn halely</L>
<L>And what we er for our syn worthy.</L>
<L>And alle our dedys &thorn;at gud here semed</L>
<L>&THORN;an sal be discussed haly and demed,</L>
<L N="2420">Swa &thorn;at we may se and knaw by sight,</L>
<L>Whether we &thorn;am dide wrang or ryght;</L>
<L>And wilk was don on wrang manere,</L>
<L>And wilk we dyd parfitely here;
<PB REF="00000111.tif" N="67"></L>
<L N="2424">&THORN;arfor Seynt Anselme, als &thorn;e buke shewes us,</L>
<L>Spekes tyl &thorn;e saul and says &thorn;us:</L>
<L>"Wreched saul," he says, "what may thou say</L>
<L>When &thorn;ou partes fra &thorn;e body away,</L>
<L N="2428">&THORN;an &thorn;e byhoves acounte yhelde</L>
<L>Of alle &thorn;i lyf of youthe and elde,</L>
<L>How &thorn;ow has here led &thorn;i lyfe,</L>
<L>And how &thorn;ow has spendyd &thorn;i wittes fife,</L>
<L N="2432">Fra &thorn;e first day &thorn;at [&thorn;ou] had witte</L>
<L>Unto &thorn;e last day &thorn;ow shuld hethen flite.</L>
<L>&THORN;an sal walaway be &thorn;i sang,</L>
<L>For &thorn;ou here dispended &thorn;i tym wrang,</L>
<L N="2436">Bathe in werk and word, in thogh[t] and wille,</L>
<L>And yhit when &thorn;ou mught helpe, &thorn;ou held the stille.</L>
<L>&THORN;ou has done many synful dede,</L>
<L>To greve God &thorn;ou had na drede;</L>
<L N="2440">Bot when you sese alle &thorn;i trespas</L>
<L>&THORN;an sal &thorn;ou say 'allas! allas!'</L>
<L>When alle &thorn;i life sal be thurgh soght</L>
<L>Unto &thorn;e lest thyng, &thorn;at ever &thorn;ou wroght,</L>
<L N="2444">Whether &thorn;ou be lered or &thorn;ou be lewed;</L>
<L>&THORN;i syns sal &thorn;an be many shewed,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ow has done here in &thorn;e life</L>
<L>Of whilk &thorn;ou couthe &thorn;e never shrife;</L>
<L N="2448">And &thorn;a sal be shewed byfor &thorn;e</L>
<L>Ful foule and ugly syns to se,</L>
<L>Of whilk &thorn;ou sal haf mare drede and awe,</L>
<L>&THORN;an of &thorn;a &thorn;at &thorn;ou mught here knawe.</L>
<L N="2452">Yhit som dedys &thorn;at &thorn;e thoght here don wele</L>
<L>&THORN;ou sal &thorn;an se foul syns and fele,</L>
<L>&THORN;an byhoves &thorn;e resayve sone</L>
<L>Efter &thorn;i werkes &thorn;at &thorn;ou has done;</L>
<L N="2456">&THORN;at es to say outher ioy or payne,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou may on nawyse be &thorn;ar agayne."</L>
<L>&THORN;os sal ilk man, at his endyng,</L>
<L>Be putted til an hard rekenyng,</L>
<L N="2460">And be aresoned, als right es</L>
<L>Of alle his mysdedys, mare and les.
<PB REF="00000112.tif" N="68"></L>
<L>Na syn &thorn;an unrekend sal be,</L>
<L>&THORN;ogh it war never swa priv&eacute;.</L>
<L N="2464">Alle &thorn;e gud dedys &thorn;at we haf done</L>
<L>Onence our syns sal &thorn;an sem fone;</L>
<L>And yhit we er unsyker in thoght</L>
<L>Wether &thorn;ai sal be alowed or noght;</L>
<L N="2468">For I fynd wryten thre skills why</L>
<L>&THORN;at na man may trayste sikerly</L>
<L>In hys gude dedys, &thorn;at he dus here.</L>
<L>&THORN;ir thre skils er gude to lere,</L>
<L N="2472">Ane es forthy &thorn;at alle thynges</L>
<L>&THORN;at gude er, anly of God springes,</L>
<L>&THORN;an er al gude dedys &thorn;at er wroght</L>
<L>Goddes awen dedys and ours noght;</L>
<L N="2476">Bot alle our syns &thorn;at may be knawen,</L>
<L>Commes of our-selven &thorn;a er our-awen,</L>
<L>For-why, with-outen God we syn sone,</L>
<L>Bot na gude with-outen God es done.</L>
<L N="2480">Another skille es alswa for&thorn;i,</L>
<L>&THORN;at we er comonly mare redy</L>
<L>An hondreth sythes here for to syn,</L>
<L>&THORN;an anes a gude dede for to bygyn;</L>
<L N="2484">Swa may we ay rekken and rede</L>
<L>An hondreth syns agayne a gude dede.</L>
<L>&THORN;e thred skille es &thorn;is to shew omang,</L>
<L>For our gude dedys er ofte done wrang,</L>
<L N="2488">Noght of right maner als &thorn;ai suld be</L>
<L>Or parchaunce done oute of charit&eacute;.</L>
<L>Alle our syns er here certayne</L>
<L>And by right and skille er worthy payne:</L>
<L N="2492">Bot for our gude dedys certanly</L>
<L>We wate noght what we er worthy;</L>
<L>Wharfor our gude dedys we shuld noght prayse</L>
<L>And &thorn;arfor &thorn;us Saynt Austyn sayse:</L>
<L N="2496"><I>Mala nostra sunt pura mala, sed bona</I></L>
<L><I>nostra non sunt pura bona.</I></L>
<L>He says "our ille dedys er pur ille wroght,</L>
<L>Bot our gud dedis pur gud er noght."
<PB REF="00000113.tif" N="69"></L>
<L N="2500">Here to acordes, als &thorn;e buk telles us,</L>
<L>Ysidre &thorn;e grete clerk, &thorn;at says &thorn;us:</L>
<L><I>Omnes iusticie nostre quasi pannus</I></L>
<L><I>menstruale.</I></L>
<L N="2504">He says "alle our ryghtwysnes er sene</L>
<L>Als a clathe, filed of thyng unclene;"</L>
<L>Wharfor certanly here wate nane</L>
<L>How he sal fare, when he es hethen gane.</L>
<L N="2508">Bot comfort of gud hope may he fele,</L>
<L>&THORN;at here lyves wele, to fare wele;</L>
<L>For we awe to trow, with-outen were,</L>
<L>&THORN;at God sal hym yhelde &thorn;at dose wele here.</L>
<L N="2512">Bot yhit es he noght syker in &thorn;ir days,</L>
<L>For-why, &thorn;e haly man &thorn;os says,</L>
<L><I>Nescit homo utrum dignus sit</I></L>
<L><I>odio vel amore.</I></L>
<L N="2516">For certayn, he says, "a man what noght,"</L>
<L>&THORN;ogh he had never swa mykel gude wroght,</L>
<L>"Whether he war worthy after his dede</L>
<L>To hafe luf of God or hatrede."</L>
<L N="2520">And Isidre, als a buke shewes us,</L>
<L>Acordes &thorn;ar-to, &thorn;at says &thorn;us:</L>
<L><I>Servus dei dum bonum agit, utrum</I></L>
<L><I>sit ei ad bonum incertus est.</I></L>
<L N="2524">He says, "he &thorn;at es God servand,</L>
<L>When he gude dus, outher with tung or hand,</L>
<L>He es noght certayne yhit in thoght,</L>
<L>Wether it be gude til hym or noght."</L>
<L N="2528">Wharfor our lyfyng here es harde,</L>
<L>Als &thorn;e haly man says, Saynt Bernarde:</L>
<L><I>Quis, sine trepidacione et timore,</I></L>
<L><I>hanc vitam ducere potest?</I></L>
<L N="2532">"Wha," he says, "may &thorn;is lyfe here lede</L>
<L>With-outen tremblyng and drede?"</L>
<L>Alswa<NOTE PLACE="foot">'Als wha' (MS. Harl. 6923).</NOTE> say here, may lyf na man</L>
<L>With-outen drede, &thorn;at witte can;</L>
<L N="2536">For al-if a man here afforce him ay</L>
<L>For to do alle &thorn;e gude &thorn;at he may,
<PB REF="00000114.tif" N="70"></L>
<L>Yhit may his gude dedis be swa wroght,</L>
<L>&THORN;at parchaunce God allowes &thorn;am noght;</L>
<L N="2540">And &thorn;arfor Saint Bernard pleyned him here</L>
<L>Of his lyf, &thorn;at says &thorn;us on &thorn;is manere.</L>
<L><I>Terret me tota vita mea, qua diligenter discussa,</I></L>
<L><I>apparet mihi aut peccatum aut sterilitas;</I></L>
<L N="2544"><I>Et si quis in ea fructus videtur, sic est</I></L>
<L><I>aut simulatum, aut imperfectum, aut alio</I></L>
<L><I>modo corruptum, ut possit aut non placere</I></L>
<L><I>deo aut displicere.</I></L>
<L N="2548">&THORN;er er Bernard wordes &thorn;at says:</L>
<L>"Al my lyfe here me flays,</L>
<L>For if it ententyfly discussed be,</L>
<L>It semes noght elles here until me</L>
<L N="2552">Bot owther syn, &thorn;at &thorn;e saul mast deres,</L>
<L>Or barran thyng, &thorn;at na fruyt beres;</L>
<L>And if any fruyt &thorn;ar-in seme,</L>
<L>It may be &thorn;us be<NOTE PLACE="foot">'bi' (Harl. MS. 4196).</NOTE> skil to deme,</L>
<L N="2556">Outher feyned thyng to shew in syght,</L>
<L>Or thyng, &thorn;at es noght alle done ryght,</L>
<L>Or, on other wyse, corrumped with-in,</L>
<L>&THORN;at es to say, filed with syn;</L>
<L N="2560">Swa &thorn;at outher &thorn;an may it noght</L>
<L>Pay God almyghty, &thorn;at es swa wroght,</L>
<L>Or paraunter it hym myspays;"</L>
<L>&THORN;os &thorn;e haly man, Saynt Barnard, says.</L>
<L N="2564">What may a synful man say &thorn;an,</L>
<L>When he, &thorn;at was swa haly a man,</L>
<L>Couth na fruyt here in his life se?</L>
<L>&THORN;an aght &thorn;e synful dredand be</L>
<L N="2568">Of [th]is life here, &thorn;at es unclene,</L>
<L>In whilk na fruyt may be sene.</L>
<L>&THORN;e ferth skille and &thorn;e last to telle,</L>
<L>Why man dredis &thorn;e dede swa felle,</L>
<L N="2572">Es for he wate noght whether he sal wende</L>
<L>Tylle ioy or payne aftir his lyfes ende.</L>
<L>For swa wyse and witty man es nane,</L>
<L>&THORN;at wate, when &thorn;e dede him has tane,
<PB REF="00000115.tif" N="71"></L>
<L N="2576">For certayn, whederward he sal ga,</L>
<L>Whether he sal wend til wele or wa.</L>
<L>&THORN;an aght ilk man, bathe yong and alde,</L>
<L>Haf drede for &thorn;is skille &thorn;at I talde.</L>
<L N="2580">For when &thorn;e devels and &thorn;e angels</L>
<L>Has desputed our lif, als &thorn;e buk telles,</L>
<L>And discucion made, als fals to be,</L>
<L>&THORN;an sal we certanly here and se</L>
<L N="2584">Our certayne dome, &thorn;at we sal have;</L>
<L>Wether we sal be dampned or save,</L>
<L>And outher &thorn;an wend to ioy or pyne;</L>
<L>&THORN;arfor &thorn;e haly man says, Saynt Austyne:</L>
<L N="2588"><I>Bene unusquisque de die novissimo</I></L>
<L><I>formidare debet, quia unum quemque</I></L>
<L><I>in quo invenerit suus novissimus dies,</I></L>
<L><I>cum de hoc seculo egreditur, talis in die</I></L>
<L N="2592"><I>novissimo indicatur.</I></L>
<L>"Ilk man" he says, "&thorn;at sal pas away</L>
<L>Shuld haf drede of hys last day;</L>
<L>For in what state swa he be &thorn;an,</L>
<L N="2596">Swilk als his last day fyndes a man,</L>
<L>When he sal out of &thorn;is werld wende,</L>
<L>Swilk mon he be demed at &thorn;e ende."</L>
<L>&THORN;arfor our last day &thorn;at sal falle,</L>
<L N="2600">Our day of dome we may calle.</L>
<L>Bot at &thorn;e general day of dome</L>
<L>With our bodys we sal come,</L>
<L>Byfor Ihesu Cryst allemyghty kyng,</L>
<L N="2604">&THORN;at sal &thorn;at day deme alle thyng.</L>
<L>&THORN;an sal he deme ilka nacyon,</L>
<L>And mak a fynal declaracyon</L>
<L>Of alle &thorn;e domes byfor shewed,</L>
<L N="2608">In tyme of dede, to lered and lewed.</L>
<L>For &thorn;e bodys sal wend to &thorn;e same stede</L>
<L>Til whilk &thorn;e saul es demed aftir &thorn;e dede;</L>
<L>And outher &thorn;an h ave ful ioy togyder,</L>
<L N="2612">Or ful sorow when &thorn;ai com thyder,</L>
<L>And ever-mare aftir togyder duelle,</L>
<L>Whethir &thorn;ai wend to heven or helle.
<PB REF="00000116.tif" N="72"></L>
<L>Bot in erthe sal duelle &thorn;e bodis alle,</L>
<L N="2616">Until &thorn;at dredful day sal falle,</L>
<L>When &thorn;e dome sal be mast strayt and harde,</L>
<L>Als &thorn;is buke shewes aftirwarde.</L>
<L>Bot first, als sone als &thorn;e saul namly,</L>
<L N="2620">Thurgh &thorn;e dede es passed fra &thorn;e body,</L>
<L>It sal be demed, aftir his werkes,</L>
<L>Til ioy or payne, als says &thorn;er clerkes.</L>
<L>&THORN;e synful saul &thorn;an gas strik to helle,</L>
<L N="2624">In pyne withouten ende to duelle;</L>
<L>&THORN;e clene saul &thorn;an gas up even,</L>
<L>With-outen lettyng, til &thorn;e blis of hevene.</L>
<L>Bot many saules, &thorn;at er save,</L>
<L N="2628">Ar &thorn;ai com to blis, payne byhoves have</L>
<L>In purgatori, and duelle &thorn;ar-in</L>
<L>Until &thorn;ai be clensid of al syn,</L>
<L>&THORN;at er schrywen and noght clensed here,</L>
<L N="2632">And &thorn;ar be fyned als gold &thorn;at shynes clere.</L>
<L>For in heven may na saul be sene,</L>
<L>Unto it be fyned and clensed clene,</L>
<L>Outher here thurgh penaunce, als clerkes wate</L>
<L N="2636">Or in purgatori thurgh fire hate.</L>
<L>Wharfor &thorn;e saul &thorn;at es clensed wele</L>
<L>Of al dedely syn and of veniele,</L>
<L>Thurgh penaunce here and almusdede,</L>
<L N="2640">&THORN;e angels als tit &thorn;an sal lede,</L>
<L>When it es passed fra &thorn;e body away</L>
<L>Til &thorn;e blis of heven &thorn;at sal last ay;</L>
<L>&THORN;arfor whaswa wille folow wysdome,</L>
<L N="2644">He suld before, ar he saw &thorn;e dede come,</L>
<L>Mak him redy and clense hym clene</L>
<L>Of al spottes of syn &thorn;at mught be sene,</L>
<L>Thurgh shryfte of mouthe and repentance,</L>
<L N="2648">And thurgh almusdede and penaunce;</L>
<L>Swa &thorn;at dede fynd hym clene of syn,</L>
<L>When &thorn;e body and &thorn;e saul sal twyn.</L>
<L>And whyles he lyffes til he hethen wende,</L>
<L N="2652">Thynk he suld ay of his lyfes hende,
<PB REF="00000117.tif" N="73"></L>
<L>Swa may he hym kepe fra alle folys,</L>
<L>And &thorn;arfor says &thorn;us Salamon &thorn;e wys:</L>
<L><I>In omnibus operibus tuis, memorare</I></L>
<L N="2656"><I>novissima tua, et non peccabis</I></L>
<L><I>ineternum.</I></L>
<L>&THORN;at es on Inglis &thorn;os to say;</L>
<L>He says "Thynk on &thorn;i endyng day,</L>
<L N="2660">Ay when &thorn;ou sal any werk bygyn</L>
<L>And &thorn;an sal &thorn;ou never mare syn."</L>
<L>And &thorn;arfor &thorn;ou man<NOTE PLACE="foot">mon?</NOTE> in &thorn;i werk be slyghe,</L>
<L>And thynk ay wele &thorn;at &thorn;ou sal dighe;</L>
<L N="2664">Thynk &thorn;ou sal dyghe, &thorn;ou wate never whan,</L>
<L>Ne in what state &thorn;ou sal be &thorn;an,</L>
<L>Ne &thorn;ou whate never in what stede</L>
<L>&THORN;ou sal dyghe, ne of what dede.</L>
<L N="2668">&THORN;arfor at morne, when &thorn;ou sese lyght,</L>
<L>Thynk als &thorn;ou sal dygh ar nyght;</L>
<L>When &thorn;ou gas to slep, if &thorn;ou be wyse,</L>
<L>Thynk als &thorn;ou suld noght with &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;i?</NOTE> lyf ryse,</L>
<L N="2672">For Saynt Austyn says &thorn;us in a buke,</L>
<L>"Let ay &thorn;i hert on &thorn;i last day luke."</L>
<L>Wha-swa wille thynk ay on &thorn;is manere,</L>
<L>And be war, and make hym redy here,</L>
<L N="2676">And of alle hys syn clense hym wele,</L>
<L>Ar &thorn;e dede com &thorn;at hym byhoves fele,</L>
<L>&THORN;an may he eschape and passe lightly</L>
<L>&THORN;e bitter payn of purgatory,</L>
<L N="2680">And com til &thorn;e blisse of heven bright;</L>
<L>&THORN;ar ay es day, and never nyght.</L>
<L>Here es &thorn;e thred parte of &thorn;is buke spedde</L>
<L>&THORN;at spekes of &thorn;e dede, als I haf redde.</L>
<L N="2684">On &thorn;is part I wille na langer stand,</L>
<L>Bot passe to another neghest folowand;</L>
<L>&THORN;at es &thorn;e ferthe part for to specify,</L>
<L>&THORN;e whilk spekes of purgatory,</L>
<L N="2688">Whar many saules feles ful harde,</L>
<L>Als yhe sal here sone aftirwarde.</L>
</LG>


</DIV1>
<DIV1 N="4" TYPE="book"><PB REF="00000118.tif" N="74">
<HEAD>Here bygynnes &thorn;e ferth part &thorn;at es of purgatory.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="2692">Many spekes, and in buke redes</L>
<L>Of purgatory, but fon it dredes;</L>
<L>For many wate noght what it es,</L>
<L>&THORN;arfor &thorn;ai drede it wele &thorn;e les.</L>
<L N="2696">Bot if &thorn;ai knew wele what it ware,</L>
<L>Or trowed, &thorn;ai walde drede it &thorn;e mare.</L>
<L>And forthy &thorn;at sum has na knawyng</L>
<L>Of purgatory ne undirstandyng,</L>
<L N="2700">&THORN;arfor I wille now speke aparty,</L>
<L>In &thorn;is buke of purgatory.</L>
<L>And first shew yhow what it es,</L>
<L>And whare it es, als &thorn;e buke wittenes;</L>
<L N="2704">And whatkyn payns er &thorn;ar-in,</L>
<L>And whilk saules gas &thorn;eder, and for what syn;</L>
<L>And alswa what thyng es mast certayn,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;am mught help and slake &thorn;air payn.</L>
<L N="2708">Of &thorn;ir sex poyntes I wil spek and rede,</L>
<L>And swa I sal &thorn;is ferth part spede.</L>
<L>Purgatory es nathyng elles</L>
<L>Bot a clensyng sted &thorn;ar saules duelles,</L>
<L N="2712">&THORN;at has synned, and had contricyon,</L>
<L>And er in &thorn;e way of salvacion,</L>
<L>And er noght parfytly clensed here</L>
<L>Of al veniel syns sere.</L>
<L N="2716">Bot &thorn;ar byhoves &thorn;am payne fele,</L>
<L>Til &thorn;ai be clensed parfytely and wele</L>
<L>Of alkyn syn &thorn;at &thorn;ai ever wroght,</L>
<L>In worde, in dede, in wille or thoght.</L>
<L N="2720">For swa pured and fyned never gold was,</L>
<L>Als &thorn;ai sal be, ar &thorn;ai &thorn;ethen pas.</L>
<L>Wharfor &thorn;e payn &thorn;at &thorn;e saul &thorn;ar hentes</L>
<L>Er mare bitter &thorn;an alle &thorn;e tourmentes</L>
<L N="2724">&THORN;at alle &thorn;e marters in erthe tholed,</L>
<L>Sen God was for us boght and sold.</L>
<L>For &thorn;e lest payn of &thorn;e payns &thorn;ar sere</L>
<L>Es mare &thorn;an es &thorn;e mast payn here,
<PB REF="00000119.tif" N="75"></L>
<L N="2728">Als says a grete clerk &thorn;us shortly,</L>
<L>In a buke of &thorn;e payns of purgatory:</L>
<L><I>Minima pena purgatorii est major</I></L>
<L><I>maxima pena mundi.</I></L>
<L N="2732">He says, "&thorn;e lest payn &thorn;at es &thorn;are</L>
<L>In purgatori, es wele mare</L>
<L>&THORN;an &thorn;e mast payn &thorn;at may be</L>
<L>In al &thorn;is werld, to fele or se."</L>
<L N="2736">For &thorn;e payne &thorn;ar, es mare bitter and felle</L>
<L>&THORN;an hert may thynk, or tung telle,</L>
<L>Als &thorn;e buke says, trow wha swa wille.</L>
<L>For sum clerkes says, and pruves by skille</L>
<L N="2740">&THORN;at bytwen &thorn;e payne of helle namly</L>
<L>And &thorn;e payn of purgatory</L>
<L>Es na difference bot at &thorn;e tane</L>
<L>Has ende, and &thorn;e tother has nane.</L>
<L N="2744">&THORN;e payns of helle sal never sees,</L>
<L>Ne &thorn;e saules &thorn;ar-in never haf relees;</L>
<L>Bot in purgatori saules dueles stille</L>
<L>Until &thorn;ai be clensed of alle ille,</L>
<L N="2748">And mare payn fele, als I understande,</L>
<L>&THORN;an ever feled man here lyfande;</L>
<L>For &thorn;ai sal haf a day &thorn;are</L>
<L>Als mykel bitter payn or mare,</L>
<L N="2752">Als a man mnght thole here of penaunce</L>
<L>A yhere and fele als mykel grevaunce;</L>
<L>And als mykel drighe &thorn;ar fourty days,</L>
<L>Als fourty yhere here; &thorn;us clerkes says;</L>
<L N="2756">Swa es &thorn;e payn &thorn;ar a day to se</L>
<L>Als mykel als here a yhere may be.</L>
<L>Bot ever a day of penaunce here</L>
<L>May stand in-stede &thorn;ar for a yhere,</L>
<L N="2760">Als God says openly and wele,</L>
<L>Thurgh &thorn;e prophet Ezechyele:</L>
<L><I>Diem pro anno</I></L>
<L><I>dedi tibi.</I></L>
<L N="2764">&THORN;at es on Inglys &thorn;us to say,</L>
<L>"For a yhere I gyf &thorn;e day."
<PB REF="00000120.tif" N="76"></L>
<L>&THORN;e payn &thorn;ar &thorn;e saules avayles noght</L>
<L>When &thorn;ai til purgatori er broght,</L>
<L N="2768">Bot for to clense &thorn;e saul of syn,</L>
<L>And for na mede in heven to wyn;</L>
<L>&THORN;ogh &thorn;ai a thousand yhere war &thorn;are,</L>
<L>&THORN;air mede in heven shuld never be &thorn;e mare.</L>
<L N="2772">&THORN;an serves &thorn;at payne &thorn;ar, of noght elles</L>
<L>Bot to clense &thorn;am of syn, &thorn;at &thorn;are-in duelles.</L>
<L>Bot penaunce to thole here with gude wille,</L>
<L>Serves here til twa thynges by skille.</L>
<L N="2776">Ane es to clense here &thorn;e saule wele</L>
<L>Of dedly syn and of veniele;</L>
<L>Another to haf in heven mare mede;</L>
<L>Til &thorn;er twa may penaunce us lede.</L>
<L N="2780">For &thorn;e saul for ilka penaunce here,</L>
<L>Sal haf specyel ioy in heven swa clere,</L>
<L>&THORN;at with-outen ende sal laste,</L>
<L>If &thorn;ai thole payne here with hert stedfast.</L>
<L N="2784">Here may men se, als &thorn;e buke wittenes,</L>
<L>And understand what purgatori es.</L>
<L>Now wil I shew yow shortly</L>
<L>Whar, als clerkes says, es purgatory.</L>
<L N="2788">&THORN;e stede, &thorn;at purgatory es calde,</L>
<L>Under &thorn;e erthe es, als I halde,</L>
<L>Aboven &thorn;e stede, als som clerkes telles,</L>
<L>&THORN;ar crysom<NOTE PLACE="foot">uncristen (MS. Harl. 6923).</NOTE> dede childer duells,</L>
<L N="2792">&THORN;at fra &thorn;e sight of Goddes face</L>
<L>Er putted for ever, with-outen grace.</L>
<L>&THORN;at place es neghest aboven hel pitte,</L>
<L>Bytwen purgatory and itte.</L>
<L N="2796">&THORN;us standes &thorn;e stede of purgatory,</L>
<L>Oboven &thorn;am bathe in &thorn;at party.</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;at er &thorn;ar payn byhoves hafe,</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;ai haf grace and er save.</L>
<L N="2800">Bot fra &thorn;e other stedes, til &thorn;e day of dome,</L>
<L>Sal never mare saule out come;
<PB REF="00000121.tif" N="77"></L>
<L>For &thorn;an sal &thorn;ai come til &thorn;e last iugement,</L>
<L>And with &thorn;e bodys agayn til helle be hent.</L>
<L N="2804">Bot fra purgatory saules may wynne</L>
<L>Til blisse when &thorn;ai er clensed of synne.</L>
<L>Aboven &thorn;at yhit es &thorn;e ferthe stede,</L>
<L>&THORN;at Crist visited when he was dede;</L>
<L N="2808">And &thorn;a &thorn;at &thorn;ar war with hym out tuke</L>
<L>And left nane &thorn;aryn, als says &thorn;e buke.</L>
<L>Ne fra &thorn;at tyme als we here clerkes telle</L>
<L>Com never nan yhit &thorn;eder to duelle,</L>
<L N="2812">Ne never nan forthward sal com;</L>
<L>And &thorn;at stede clerkes calles <I>lymbus patrum</I></L>
<L>&THORN;e whilk a fre preson on Inglys es,</L>
<L>Whare &thorn;e haly faders duelled in myrknes.</L>
<L N="2816">Alle &thorn;ir four stedes men may helle calle,</L>
<L>For &thorn;ai er closed with-in &thorn;e erthe alle;</L>
<L>And for helle &thorn;ai may alle be tane,</L>
<L>Of whilk four purgatory es ane.</L>
<L N="2820">&THORN;arfor haly kyrk &thorn;at for saules prays,</L>
<L>Calles purgatory helle, &thorn;at &thorn;us says:</L>
<L><I>Domine Ihesu Criste libera animas</I></L>
<L><I>omnium fidelium defunctorum, de</I></L>
<L N="2824"><I>manu inferni!</I></L>
<L>"Loverd deliver out of helles hande</L>
<L>Alle crysten saules &thorn;at &thorn;ar er duellande;"</L>
<L>&THORN;at es to say, out [of] purgatory</L>
<L N="2828">&THORN;ar &thorn;e saules er clensed parfytely.</L>
<L>Bot fra &thorn;e lawest helle, with-outen dout,</L>
<L>Na saul may be delyverd out;</L>
<L>For of mercy &thorn;ar es na hope;</L>
<L N="2832">&THORN;arfor &thorn;us says &thorn;e haly man Iobe.</L>
<L><I>Quia in inferno nulla est redempcio.</I></L>
<L>"In helle", he says, "es na raunceon."</L>
<L>For na helpe may be in &thorn;at dungeon,</L>
<L N="2836">&THORN;at es to say, in &thorn;e lawest helle,</L>
<L>Whar &thorn;e dampned saules sal ay duelle,</L>
<L>Whar messe ne prayer helpes noght,</L>
<L>Til &thorn;am &thorn;at er &thorn;eder broght.
<PB REF="00000122.tif" N="78"></L>
<L N="2840">For na thyng may abate &thorn;air pyne,</L>
<L>And &thorn;arfor &thorn;us says Saynt Austyne,</L>
<L><I>Si scirem patrem meum aut matrem</I></L>
<L><I>in inferno, pro eis non orarem.</I></L>
<L N="2844">He says, "if my fader or moder ware</L>
<L>In helle, and I wist &thorn;am &thorn;are,</L>
<L>I wald nouther nyght ne day,</L>
<L>For &thorn;am byd bede here, ne pray."</L>
<L N="2848">For-why, almusdede, ne messe, ne prayers</L>
<L>Helpes na saul &thorn;ar, bot parchaunce ders,</L>
<L>&THORN;e twa lawest stedes, &thorn;at I nevend ar,</L>
<L>Er &thorn;e helles &thorn;at sal last ever mar.</L>
<L N="2852">Bot purgatory sal noght last ay;</L>
<L>It lastes na langer &thorn;an to domesday,</L>
<L>For aftir &thorn;at day, als clerkes can se,</L>
<L>Na stede of purgatory sal be,</L>
<L N="2856">Bot helle, ful of devels with in,</L>
<L>Sal ay last, for vengeaunce of syn.</L>
<L>Now som has wonder, and may ask why</L>
<L>God has swa ordayned purgatory,</L>
<L N="2860">And helle ymyddes &thorn;e erthe swa law;</L>
<L>&THORN;e skylle why may be &thorn;is to knaw;</L>
<L>&THORN;e syn &thorn;at es in erthe wroght</L>
<L>Fra erthe unpunyst passes noght.</L>
<L N="2864">&THORN;an nedly byhoves be punyst syn,</L>
<L>Outher opon erthe or with-in,</L>
<L>&THORN;at es outher here &thorn;ar we duelle,</L>
<L>Or in purgatory or in helle;</L>
<L N="2868">For syn es swa hevy and swa harde,</L>
<L>&THORN;at it drawes &thorn;e saul ay dunwarde;</L>
<L>Until payn and penaunce haf wasted &thorn;at syn</L>
<L>&THORN;e saul may never tylle heven wyn;</L>
<L N="2972">Yhit says &thorn;ir grete clerkes namly,</L>
<L>&THORN;at twa stedes er of purgatory;</L>
<L>&THORN;e tane es comon, als yhe herd me telle,</L>
<L>&THORN;at with-in erthe es, oboven helle;</L>
<L N="2876">And &thorn;e tother es speciele, thurgh grace,</L>
<L>&THORN;at es oboven erthe, in sere place.
<PB REF="00000123.tif" N="79"></L>
<L>For in &thorn;e comon stede som er noght ay,</L>
<L>Bot er here punyst, outher nyght or day,</L>
<L N="2880">In sere stedes specialy in gast,</L>
<L>Whar &thorn;ai haf synned in body mast.</L>
<L>And &thorn;at may be thurgh helpe and spede</L>
<L>Of prayer of frendes and almusdede,</L>
<L N="2884">Til wham &thorn;ai ofte in gast apere,</L>
<L>Thurgh speciel grace, in sere stedes here,</L>
<L>For to hast &thorn;air deliverance</L>
<L>Out of &thorn;air payn and &thorn;air penaunce,</L>
<L N="2888">&THORN;at, als I ar sayde, gretely greves,</L>
<L>And for warnyng of frendes &thorn;at lyefes.</L>
<L>Here may men properly by skille se</L>
<L>What purgatory falles to be.</L>
<L N="2892">Now wille I rede forthermare,</L>
<L>And shew yhow of sum paynes &thorn;at er &thorn;are.</L>
<L>In purgatory, als &thorn;e buke wittenes,</L>
<L>Es diverse payns, som mar, som les,</L>
<L N="2896">And many mare &thorn;an I can neven;</L>
<L>Bot I fynd wryten payns seven,</L>
<L>&THORN;at may be called payns of purgatory;</L>
<L>And &thorn;a seven I wille here specefy,</L>
<L N="2900">Of whilk men sal som fele and se,</L>
<L>Als tite als &thorn;e ded-comyng sal be,</L>
<L>&THORN;e first payn es of &thorn;a seven,</L>
<L>Als yhe herd me byfor neven,</L>
<L N="2904">&THORN;e grete drede &thorn;at &thorn;e saul es in</L>
<L>When &thorn;e body at<NOTE PLACE="foot">And it (MS. Harl. 6923).</NOTE> it sal twyn;</L>
<L>For &thorn;e saul sese &thorn;an about it stande</L>
<L>Grysly devels agayn it raumpande,</L>
<L N="2908">Als wode lyons to wayt &thorn;air pray,</L>
<L>And to ravisshe it with &thorn;am away.</L>
<L>And &thorn;at syght es a payn ful grevous;</L>
<L>For &thorn;e devels er swa foul and ydous,</L>
<L N="2912">&THORN;at swa hardy man was never nane</L>
<L>Lyfand here in flesshe and bane,
<PB REF="00000124.tif" N="80"></L>
<L>&THORN;at saw &thorn;e syght &thorn;at &thorn;e saul &thorn;an sese,</L>
<L>&THORN;at ne he for ferdelayk is witte shuld lese,</L>
<L N="2916">Thogh he war never of hert swa balde,</L>
<L>Als in &thorn;e thred parte of &thorn;is boke was talde.</L>
<L>A grete payn aght &thorn;is syght to be</L>
<L>Til &thorn;e saule &thorn;an, &thorn;at it sal se.</L>
<L N="2920">&THORN;e secunde payn neghest folowande</L>
<L>Es &thorn;e grete drede, to understande,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e saul sal hafe wyth dole and care,</L>
<L>Until &thorn;e dome be gyfen, how he sal fare.</L>
<L N="2924">For &thorn;e angels sal &thorn;are redy be</L>
<L>And &thorn;e devels swa grisly to se,</L>
<L>&THORN;at sal disput of alle his lyfe</L>
<L>Bytwen &thorn;am &thorn;ar, with grete stryfe.</L>
<L N="2928">His syns sal &thorn;an be shewed ful many,</L>
<L>Als I tald byfor in &thorn;e thred part namly.</L>
<L>&THORN;e saul &thorn;an sal bytwene &thorn;am stande,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e angels on his ryght hande,</L>
<L N="2932">And devels on &thorn;e lefte syde.</L>
<L>&THORN;an mot &thorn;e saul in grete dred abyde,</L>
<L>Until &thorn;at stryfe be broght to ende,</L>
<L>And til it witte whyder it sal wende,</L>
<L N="2936">And whether it sal be dampned or save;</L>
<L>&THORN;an sal &thorn;e saul a grete drede have,</L>
<L>Als a man &thorn;at es in myddes &thorn;e se</L>
<L>In grete perille, and may noght fle,</L>
<L N="2940">When tempestes falles and stormes smert,</L>
<L>&THORN;an has &thorn;at man grete drede in hert;</L>
<L>He mas &thorn;an vowes, and cryes on Crist,</L>
<L>For, he es afered &thorn;at he sal be peryst;</L>
<L N="2944">And &thorn;at drede til hym es a grete payn;</L>
<L>For of his lyf he es uncertayn;</L>
<L>And als a man has drede bodily,</L>
<L>When he es acouped of felony</L>
<L N="2948">Byfor kynges iustice, and &thorn;e cuntr&eacute;,</L>
<L>&THORN;at charged es if he gilty be,</L>
<L>He wate noght whether he sal be spilt,</L>
<L>Or be delyvered of &thorn;at gilt.
<PB REF="00000125.tif" N="81"></L>
<L N="2952">Until &thorn;ai have gyven &thorn;air verdite,</L>
<L>And outher &thorn;ar-of made hym qwyte</L>
<L>Als &thorn;e laghe walde, or made hym gilty.</L>
<L>If he &thorn;an haf drede, it es na ferly,</L>
<L N="2956">For in grete dout of lyfe es &thorn;at man.</L>
<L>Bot yhit has the saul mare drede &thorn;an,</L>
<L>Til &thorn;e dome be<NOTE PLACE="foot">The MS. reads <I>by</I>.</NOTE> gyven and it may se</L>
<L>Whether it sal dampned or saufe be.</L>
<L N="2960">For if it dome of damp[na]cion here,</L>
<L>It gas til helle with-outen recoverere;</L>
<L>And &thorn;e saul &thorn;at es dampned til &thorn;at place</L>
<L>Thar never hope to haf mercy ne grace.</L>
<L N="2964">What wonder es &thorn;an if &thorn;e saule drede have</L>
<L>&THORN;at doutes whethir he sal be dampned or save.</L>
<L>Of &thorn;es twa maners of payns of drede</L>
<L>Yhe herd me aparty byfor rede,</L>
<L N="2968">&THORN;e whilk es declared in a stede,</L>
<L>In &thorn;e thred part &thorn;at spekes of &thorn;e dede.</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;is matere men may se &thorn;are,</L>
<L>&THORN;arfor here I wil spek &thorn;ar-of na mare.</L>
<L N="2972">&THORN;e thred payn es a maner of exil</L>
<L>When &thorn;e saules here agayn &thorn;air wil</L>
<L>Er exild fra &thorn;is lyf til payn,</L>
<L>With-outen any turnyng agayn;</L>
<L N="2976">For &thorn;an sal &thorn;ai haf grete murnyng,</L>
<L>When &thorn;ai er flemed fra &thorn;air lykyng,</L>
<L>Fra alle &thorn;air frendes lefe and dere,</L>
<L>And fra alle &thorn;e delyces &thorn;at &thorn;ai had here.</L>
<L N="2980">&THORN;e murnyng &thorn;at &thorn;ai haf on &thorn;is wyse,</L>
<L>Til &thorn;am sal be grete payn and anguyse.</L>
<L>&THORN;e fereth payn es sere malady,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e sauls sal haf in purgatory.</L>
<L N="2984">For &thorn;ai sal haf &thorn;ar yvels sere,</L>
<L>For sere syns, &thorn;at er unclensed here;</L>
<L>Som for pride &thorn;at &thorn;ai haf here-in bene,</L>
<L>Sal haf &thorn;ar als a fever cotidiene,
<PB REF="00000126.tif" N="82"></L>
<L N="2988">&THORN;at &thorn;e saule sal pyn mar bitterly</L>
<L>&THORN;an ever fyver pyned here mans body.</L>
<L>Som sal haf &thorn;ar, for covatyse,</L>
<L>Als &thorn;e dropsy to grege<NOTE PLACE="foot">'eche' (Lands. MS. 348). agrege (Harl. 6923).</NOTE> &thorn;air angwyse.</L>
<L N="2992">Som sal haf in alle &thorn;air lymmes obout,</L>
<L>For sleuthe, als &thorn;e potagre and &thorn;e gout.</L>
<L>Som, for envy, sal haf in &thorn;air lyms,</L>
<L>Als kylles and felouns and apostyms.</L>
<L N="2996">Som for ire sal have als &thorn;e parlesy,</L>
<L>&THORN;at yvel &thorn;e saul sal grefe gretely.</L>
<L>Som for glotoni sal haf &thorn;are,</L>
<L>Als &thorn;e swynacy, &thorn;at greves ful sare.</L>
<L N="3000">And som, for &thorn;e syn of lechery,</L>
<L>Sal haf als &thorn;e yvel of meselry.</L>
<L>&THORN;us sal &thorn;e saules, als God vouches save,</L>
<L>For sere syns, sere maledys have,</L>
<L N="3004">&THORN;at here has hadde repentance</L>
<L>And has noght ful-filed here &thorn;air penaunce.</L>
<L>&THORN;ir maladies &thorn;ar &thorn;e saul mar greves,</L>
<L>&THORN;an it dos any body &thorn;at here lyves.</L>
<L N="3008">Thynk we what payn has &thorn;e body,</L>
<L>&THORN;at has here bot a malady</L>
<L>In &thorn;is lif, lastand alle a yhere,</L>
<L>Or noght bot thre days, or four here.</L>
<L N="3012">&THORN;at malady greves &thorn;e body sare,</L>
<L>Bot yhit it greves &thorn;e saul vele mare</L>
<L>In purgatory, &thorn;ar es it pynde,</L>
<L>For &thorn;e saul es of mare tender kynde;</L>
<L N="3016">For als a lytel thynd<NOTE PLACE="foot">thyng (Harl. MS. 6923).</NOTE> &thorn;in eghe lokand</L>
<L>May greve mare &thorn;an it may &thorn;i hand,</L>
<L>Swa feles &thorn;e saule mare penaunce</L>
<L>&THORN;an &thorn;e body, when it has grevaunce.</L>
<L N="3020">Bot now may som say here agayne,</L>
<L>And aske how &thorn;e saul may fele payne,</L>
<L>&THORN;at es noght elles bot a spirit,</L>
<L>&THORN;at may noght be feled, swylk es it;
<PB REF="00000127.tif" N="83"></L>
<L N="3024">For it es swa sutil, &thorn;at aftir &thorn;e dede,</L>
<L>It may occupy na stede.</L>
<L>Til &thorn;is, &thorn;us men answer may,</L>
<L>Als men may here grete clerkes say.</L>
<L N="3028">&THORN;e saule &thorn;e lyfe of &thorn;e body es</L>
<L>Of ilk man here, bathe mare and les.</L>
<L>And with-outen &thorn;e lyfe is na felyng,</L>
<L>For felyng may be in na dede thyng.</L>
<L N="3032">&THORN;an es alle &thorn;e felyng halely</L>
<L>In &thorn;e saul, and noght in &thorn;e body;</L>
<L>For when &thorn;e saul es passed away,</L>
<L>&THORN;e body es noght bot erthe and clay,</L>
<L N="3036">&THORN;at es a dede thyng, als a stane;</L>
<L>&THORN;e whilk may fele na thyng be<NOTE PLACE="foot">by?</NOTE> it ane.</L>
<L>Alswa yhit may som &thorn;os aske mare,</L>
<L>How may &thorn;e saule &thorn;at duelles &thorn;are,</L>
<L N="3040">Be pyned with sere maledy</L>
<L>&THORN;at falles til sere lymes of &thorn;e body,</L>
<L>Sen it has nouther body ne hede,</L>
<L>Ne lym &thorn;at may occupy stede.</L>
<L N="3044">Til &thorn;is, men may answer &thorn;us shortly:</L>
<L>&THORN;e saul, al-if it haf na body,</L>
<L>It sal be pyned als in lyms sere,</L>
<L>Thurgh whilk it has mast synned here.</L>
<L N="3048">Swa sal &thorn;e saul, fele payn and wa,</L>
<L>And til other saules it sal seme swa.</L>
<L>For ilkan til other sal seme &thorn;an,</L>
<L>Als &thorn;ai had shap of body of man;</L>
<L N="3052">&THORN;us sal ilka saul other se,</L>
<L>For nan of &thorn;am may feled be.</L>
<L>Na mar &thorn;an here a man ande may,</L>
<L>When it passes fra his mouthe away.</L>
<L N="3056">And &thorn;is may be pruved be<NOTE PLACE="foot">by?</NOTE> &thorn;e godspelle.</L>
<L>Thurgh &thorn;e ensampel of &thorn;e ryche man in helle,</L>
<L>And of Lazar &thorn;at he ward<NOTE PLACE="foot">And of &thorn;e lazar &thorn;at he <I>warned</I> mete. (MSS. Lands. 348, Addit 22283.)</NOTE> mete</L>
<L>&THORN;at in Abraham bosom had his sete.
<PB REF="00000128.tif" N="84"></L>
<L N="3060">Abraham bosom es nathyng elles,</L>
<L>Bot heven &thorn;ar haly spyrites duelles.</L>
<L>When &thorn;e ryche man, &thorn;at in helle sat lawe,</L>
<L>Lazar in Abraham bosom sawe,</L>
<L N="3064">He cryed til Abraham and prayed with-alle</L>
<L>&THORN;at a drope of calde water mught falle</L>
<L>Til his tung, fra Lazar fynger ende,</L>
<L>Als es in &thorn;e godspel contende.</L>
<L N="3068">Bot al-if he &thorn;us spak to hym,</L>
<L>Yhit had he na tung ne<NOTE PLACE="foot">The MS. reads <I>no</I>.</NOTE> other lym,</L>
<L>Ne Lazar, als yhe sal understande,</L>
<L>Had nouther fynger, ne fote, ne hande,</L>
<L N="3072">For &thorn;ai bathe war spirites anly,</L>
<L>&THORN;at nouther had lymmes ne body.</L>
<L>&THORN;e tane was in blis soverayne,</L>
<L>&THORN;e tother was in endles payne.</L>
<L N="3076">Bot &thorn;e ryche man saule feled in helle</L>
<L>Payne, als he had bene in flesshe and felle;</L>
<L>And Lazar saule til him semed &thorn;an</L>
<L>Als he had body and lymes of man.</L>
<L N="3080">Yhit has men herd som clerkes maynte[ne]</L>
<L>Swilk an opinion, als I wene,</L>
<L>&THORN;at a saule, &thorn;at es in purgatory</L>
<L>Or in helle, has of &thorn;e ayre a body</L>
<L N="3084">For to thole payne, in lyms sere,</L>
<L>After &thorn;at he has synned here.</L>
<L>Bot whether &thorn;e saul haf body or noght,</L>
<L>He sal fele payne, after he has wroght.</L>
<L N="3088">&THORN;e fifte payne es &thorn;e fire hate,</L>
<L>&THORN;at na maner of thing may abate,</L>
<L>Bot almusdede and messe and prayere,</L>
<L>&THORN;at frendes dus for &thorn;e saul here.</L>
<L N="3092">To abate &thorn;at fire, &thorn;a thre er best,</L>
<L>For &thorn;a thre may bring &thorn;e saul to rest.</L>
<L>&THORN;at fire is hatter and mare kene,</L>
<L>&THORN;an al &thorn;e fire &thorn;at here es sene;
<PB REF="00000129.tif" N="85"></L>
<L N="3096">For als &thorn;e fire of erthe, &thorn;ar we won,</L>
<L>Es hatter &thorn;an &thorn;e beme of &thorn;e son,</L>
<L>Ryght swa &thorn;at fire on &thorn;e same manere,</L>
<L>Es hatter &thorn;an &thorn;e fire es here.</L>
<L N="3100">Alle &thorn;e waters, &thorn;at men may rekken,</L>
<L>A spark &thorn;ar-of may noght sleken.</L>
<L>We se &thorn;e fire &thorn;at here es, greves sare</L>
<L>&THORN;e body, &thorn;at standes &thorn;ar-in bare;</L>
<L N="3104">Bot mare greves &thorn;e fire of purgatory</L>
<L>&THORN;e saul, &thorn;an &thorn;is fire dus &thorn;e body.</L>
<L>For &thorn;e fire here, of strenthe es les</L>
<L>&THORN;an &thorn;e fire of purgatory es;</L>
<L N="3108">And &thorn;e body with flesshe and bane,</L>
<L>Es harder &thorn;an &thorn;e saul by it ane;</L>
<L>And &thorn;e saul mare tender and nesshe</L>
<L>&THORN;an es &thorn;e body with &thorn;e flesshe.</L>
<L N="3112">Sen &thorn;at fire es mare hate &thorn;are</L>
<L>&THORN;an &thorn;e fire es here, als I sayd are,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e saul es swa tender of kynde,</L>
<L>&THORN;an semes it &thorn;at it es mare pynde</L>
<L N="3116">Thurgh &thorn;at fire, &thorn;an &thorn;e body mught be</L>
<L>With alle &thorn;e fire of Cristiant&eacute;;</L>
<L>For a spark of &thorn;at fire es mare hate</L>
<L>&THORN;an al &thorn;e fire of erthe, als clerkes wate.</L>
<L N="3120">Many saules duells in &thorn;at fire strang.</L>
<L>Bot sum duelles short wyle, and sum lang,</L>
<L>Aftir &thorn;air syn es mare or les,</L>
<L>And aftir &thorn;air penaunce fulfild es,</L>
<L N="3124">Bot na saul may &thorn;ethen pas,</L>
<L>Until it be als clene als it first was,</L>
<L>When he was hoven at funtstane</L>
<L>And his crestendome &thorn;ar had tane.</L>
<L N="3128">Som clerkes, &thorn;at spekes of purgatory,</L>
<L>Says &thorn;at &thorn;e fire &thorn;are is bodily,</L>
<L>And noght gastly als &thorn;e saule es;</L>
<L>For &thorn;e saule, als &thorn;e boke bers wytnes,</L>
<L N="3132">May be pyned with fire bodily,</L>
<L>Als it may be with &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;y?</NOTE> awen body.
<PB REF="00000130.tif" N="86"></L>
<L>Bot &thorn;at fire wirkes noght thurgh kynde</L>
<L>In &thorn;e saule, &thorn;at &thorn;ar-with es pynde,</L>
<L N="3136">Als dos &thorn;e fire &thorn;at brinnes here,</L>
<L>Bot it wirkes on wonderful manere,</L>
<L>Als God has ordaynd, forwhy, it es</L>
<L>An instrument of Goddes ryghtwysnes,</L>
<L N="3140">Thurgh wilk &thorn;e saule most clensed be</L>
<L>In purgatory, ar it may God se.</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;e fire &thorn;at es &thorn;ar-in,</L>
<L>Es bot a maner of fyre to wast syn,</L>
<L N="3144">And noght divers fires, les and mare,</L>
<L>Bot a maner of fire, als I sayd are,</L>
<L>&THORN;at alle veniel syns &thorn;an sal waste,</L>
<L>&THORN;at es unclensed here, lest and maste.</L>
<L N="3148">For als fyre &thorn;at caffe son may bryn,</L>
<L>Gold may melt &thorn;at es lang &thorn;ar-in,</L>
<L>Ryght swa &thorn;e fyre &thorn;ar thurgh lang hete</L>
<L>&THORN;at wastes smale syns, may wast grete,</L>
<L N="3152">And als &thorn;e hete of &thorn;e son &thorn;at comon es,</L>
<L>Som men greves mare, and som men les,</L>
<L>Right swa &thorn;e fyre &thorn;at es &thorn;are,</L>
<L>Som sawles pyns les, and som mare;</L>
<L N="3156">For &thorn;e sawles byhoves duelle &thorn;ar-in,</L>
<L>Aftir &thorn;e charge es of &thorn;air syn.</L>
<L>Bot som sawles &thorn;ar sal be delyver[d] sone,</L>
<L>&THORN;at large penaunce here has done;</L>
<L N="3160">Som sal duel &thorn;ar many a yhere,</L>
<L>&THORN;at litel penaunce has don here.</L>
<L>And lang lygyn in &thorn;air syn;</L>
<L>And &thorn;arfor says &thorn;us Saynt Austyn:</L>
<L N="3164"><I>Necesse est quod tantum urat dolor,</I></L>
<L><I>quantum erat amor; tanto enim quisquis</I></L>
<L><I>torquetur diucius, quanto affectus eius</I></L>
<L><I>venialibus ahherebat forcius.</I></L>
<L N="3168">Saynt Austyn says "nedeful it es,</L>
<L>&THORN;at sorow war als mykel and na les</L>
<L>For ilka syn and ilka trespas,
<PB REF="00000131.tif" N="87"></L>
<L>Als luf and delyte in syn was."</L>
<L N="3172">And alswa he says on &thorn;is manere,</L>
<L>&THORN;at ay &thorn;e styther &thorn;at ilk man here</L>
<L>Gyves his lykyng and wille</L>
<L>Til veniel syns, outher loud or stille,</L>
<L N="3176">&THORN;e langer sal he pyned be</L>
<L>In purgatory;" &thorn;us says he.</L>
<L>&THORN;is fire, als byfore wryten es,</L>
<L>Som saules pynes mare, and sum les,</L>
<L N="3180">Aftir &thorn;at &thorn;ai &thorn;at commes &thorn;ar-in,</L>
<L>Brynges ought with &thorn;am &thorn;at may bryn.</L>
<L>For byfor ar &thorn;ai may God se</L>
<L>Byhoves als thre thynges brinned be,</L>
<L N="3184">&THORN;at es at say, als wodde, and hay,</L>
<L>And stubble, &thorn;at may sone wast away;</L>
<L>&THORN;a er veniel synnes &thorn;at may falle,</L>
<L>Bathe grete and smale, and men with-alle,</L>
<L N="3188">&THORN;e mast veniel syns sal &thorn;ar bryn langly,</L>
<L>Als wodde brinnes, &thorn;at es sadde and hevy,</L>
<L>&THORN;e lest veniel syns sal brin sone,</L>
<L>Als stobble, &thorn;at son brinnes and son es done.</L>
<L N="3192">Botswa son brinnes noght &thorn;e mene synnes;</L>
<L>&THORN;ai brin mar slawly als hay brynnes.</L>
<L>&THORN;us sal be brynned and wasted &thorn;are,</L>
<L>Als veniel syns, bathe les and mare;</L>
<L N="3196">And al dedly syns of wilk men er shryven,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e gilt God has forgyven,</L>
<L>For whilk &thorn;e penaunce es noght fulfilled here,</L>
<L>Sal &thorn;are be wasted on &thorn;e sam manere</L>
<L N="3200">And &thorn;e saules in &thorn;at fire be pyned</L>
<L>Unto &thorn;ai be als clene als gold fyned.</L>
<L>And when &thorn;ai er fyned and made bright</L>
<L>&THORN;ai sal be broght befor Goddes sight,</L>
<L N="3204">Til hey Paraydise, &thorn;at blisful place</L>
<L>Whar ay es rest, ioy and solace.</L>
<L>&THORN;e sext payne es &thorn;is to telle;</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e saules unclensed, &thorn;at sal duelle
<PB REF="00000132.tif" N="88"></L>
<L N="3208">In purgatory, sal be bunden faste</L>
<L>With bandes of syn, whilles &thorn;ai may laste,</L>
<L>Als men &thorn;at er bonden in pryson,</L>
<L>&THORN;at na man may for gyf[t] ne raunson,</L>
<L N="3212">Out of &thorn;at hard payn &thorn;am wyn,</L>
<L>Until &thorn;e fire haf wasted &thorn;air bandes of syn.</L>
<L>&THORN;us er &thorn;ai bunden by hend and fete,</L>
<L>Alle bydonen<NOTE PLACE="foot">Albedene (MS. Harl. 6923).</NOTE>, in &thorn;at brinnand hete.</L>
<L N="3216">Me thynk &thorn;at na payne may be mare</L>
<L>&THORN;an &thorn;a saules has, whyles &thorn;ai er &thorn;are.</L>
<L>Grete dole &thorn;ay mak, somtyme, and sarowe;</L>
<L>For &thorn;ai may nathyng begg ne borowe,</L>
<L N="3220">To help &thorn;am, &thorn;at &thorn;ai war out broght,</L>
<L>Ne &thorn;air awen prayer help &thorn;am noght;</L>
<L>For &thorn;ar es nouther stede ne space,</L>
<L>Helpe ne frenshepe to purchace;</L>
<L N="3224">Bot &thorn;e gude &thorn;at &thorn;ai did here, &thorn;ai sal &thorn;ar fele;</L>
<L>Or if &thorn;air frendes, &thorn;at luffes &thorn;am wele,</L>
<L>For &thorn;am here pray or do almus de[de];</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;at may help &thorn;am in &thorn;air nede.</L>
<L N="3228">Ful hard payn &thorn;ar &thorn;ai fele,</L>
<L>Bot at &thorn;ai er save &thorn;ai wate wele;</L>
<L>Bot sum tyme swa mykel pay[n] &thorn;ai hafe,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ai tak na kepe &thorn;at &thorn;ai er save;</L>
<L N="3232">Wharfor we shuld thynk, &thorn;at lyves here,</L>
<L>What payn it es, on &thorn;is manere,</L>
<L>To be swa pyned, and fele swa sare</L>
<L>Fourty wynter, outher les or mare,</L>
<L N="3236">Omang devels, &thorn;at &thorn;an has leve</L>
<L>Som tyme to turment &thorn;e saules and greve,</L>
<L>Ay whiles &thorn;ai haf any spot of syn;</L>
<L>For are, may &thorn;ai noght out of payn wyn,</L>
<L N="3240">Til &thorn;ai be clensed and made right clene</L>
<L>Of alle spottes of syn &thorn;at may be sene.</L>
<L>And when &thorn;ai er &thorn;us clensed wele</L>
<L>&THORN;an sal &thorn;ai namare payn fele,
<PB REF="00000133.tif" N="89"></L>
<L N="3244">Bot als tite &thorn;ar-efter &thorn;ai sal wende</L>
<L>Tille &thorn;e blis &thorn;at es with-outen ende.</L>
<L>&THORN;e sevend payn of purgatory es</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e saules er als in wildernes,</L>
<L N="3248">&THORN;ar defaut es of alkyn thyng</L>
<L>Of wilk man mught haf lykyng;</L>
<L>&THORN;air payn es turned manyfalde.</L>
<L>Now er &thorn;ai in hete, and now in calde;</L>
<L N="3252">For sumtyme &thorn;ai sal be pyned lang</L>
<L>With hete, and som tyme with cald omang.</L>
<L>&THORN;ai sal haf &thorn;are bathe hunger and threst,</L>
<L>And travayl grete, with-outen rest.</L>
<L N="3256">&THORN;ai er dungen &thorn;are, to eke &thorn;aire payn,</L>
<L>With smert stormes als of wynd and rayn,</L>
<L>And with stormes of hayle, sharpe and kene,</L>
<L>Swylk stormes was never here sene,</L>
<L N="3260">Als &thorn;e sauls sal &thorn;ar here and se.</L>
<L>&THORN;us sal &thorn;ai on sere-wyse pyned be,</L>
<L>Sum many wynter for &thorn;air syn,</L>
<L>Ar &thorn;ai til &thorn;e sight of God may wyn.</L>
<L N="3264">Swilk maner of payns &thorn;ai sal have &thorn;are,</L>
<L>With other ma, &thorn;at sal greve sare.</L>
<L>Bot a grete payn yhit &thorn;is sal be,</L>
<L>&THORN;e grete yhernyng &thorn;at &thorn;ai haf to se</L>
<L N="3268">&THORN;e face of God, &thorn;at es swa bright,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e lang tariyng fra &thorn;at syght.</L>
<L>Bot til &thorn;at sight &thorn;ai may never wyn,</L>
<L>Until &thorn;ai be clensed &thorn;ar of al syn.</L>
<L N="3272">Here haf I talde yhow aparty,</L>
<L>Of sum payns of purgatory.</L>
<L>Now I wille shew, als &thorn;e boke telles,</L>
<L>Whilk sauls in purgatory duelles.</L>
<L N="3276">&THORN;e saules &thorn;at to purgatory most wend</L>
<L>Aftir &thorn;e dede, when &thorn;is life has end,</L>
<L>Nedly byhoves dwelle &thorn;ar-in,</L>
<L>Unto &thorn;ai be clensed of al syn,</L>
<L N="3280">Thurgh bitter paynes &thorn;at er &thorn;are.</L>
<L>Bot sum sal fele les, and sum mare,
<PB REF="00000134.tif" N="90"></L>
<L>Aftir &thorn;air syn es mare or les,</L>
<L>Als in &thorn;is part byfor wryten es,</L>
<L N="3284">Or aftir &thorn;air syns er many or fone,</L>
<L>And aftir &thorn;ai haf here penaunce done.</L>
<L>Bot alle saules sal noght duelle in &thorn;at stede,</L>
<L>For sum here &thorn;at als tite aftir &thorn;air dede,</L>
<L N="3288">Sal wend strykly til heven blis,</L>
<L>Als Innocentes &thorn;at never dyd mys,</L>
<L>And other saules of men parfite,</L>
<L>&THORN;at in nathyng here has delyte,</L>
<L N="3292">Bot anly in God &thorn;at boght &thorn;am dere,</L>
<L>In<NOTE PLACE="foot">And (MS. Harl. 6923).</NOTE> lyffed ay in penaunce here.</L>
<L>Som &thorn;at &thorn;e dede here sodanly tas.</L>
<L>In dedely syn strik til helle gas;</L>
<L N="3296">And &thorn;at me thynk es na ferly,</L>
<L>Forwhy dedely syn es swa hevy</L>
<L>&THORN;at it may with-in a litel stonde</L>
<L>A saul draw doun til helle grounde.</L>
<L N="3300">Bot &thorn;e saul &thorn;at of dedly syn es shryven,</L>
<L>Swa &thorn;at &thorn;e gilt be here forgyven,</L>
<L>If &thorn;e penaunce &thorn;at es here aioynt</L>
<L>Be noght fulfilled at &thorn;e dedes poynt,</L>
<L N="3304">And &thorn;e saul &thorn;at es noght clensed welc</L>
<L>Of smale syns &thorn;at er veniele;</L>
<L>&THORN;is twa maners of saules er save,</L>
<L>Bot in purgatory &thorn;am byhoves have</L>
<L N="3308">Ful bitter payn, and duel stil &thorn;are</L>
<L>Unto &thorn;ai be clen, als I sayd are,</L>
<L>Als &thorn;ai war first when &thorn;ai had tane</L>
<L>Haly baptem at &thorn;e font stane.</L>
<L N="3312">Yhit says som clerkes on &thorn;is manere,</L>
<L>&THORN;at swa clen of syn es naman here,</L>
<L>Ne swa parfite in &thorn;e law of Crist,</L>
<L>Ne yhit a childe, &thorn;at es new baptist,</L>
<L N="3316">&THORN;at til heven sal wend aftir &thorn;e dede,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he ne sal pas forth by &thorn;at stede,
<PB REF="00000135.tif" N="91"></L>
<L>And se &thorn;e payns &thorn;ar ilkan.</L>
<L>Bot yhong Innocentes sal fele nan,</L>
<L N="3320">For &thorn;ai couthe never na syn wirk,</L>
<L>And passes<NOTE PLACE="foot">passede (MS. Harl. 6923).</NOTE> in &thorn;e trouthe of haly kyrk.</L>
<L>&THORN;arfor &thorn;ai swippe &thorn;urgh purgatory</L>
<L>Als a foul &thorn;at flyes smertly,</L>
<L N="3324">With-outen payn &thorn;at may dere,</L>
<L>Or any sight &thorn;at may &thorn;am fere,</L>
<L>Bot unnethes any other may</L>
<L>Passe qwyte thurgh purgatory away,</L>
<L N="3328">&THORN;at &thorn;e fire ne sal noght fynd in &thorn;am to bryn,</L>
<L>Ar &thorn;ai passe thurgh som veniel syn,</L>
<L>Swa strayt &thorn;ai sal be examynd &thorn;an;</L>
<L>For it es nan swa parfite man</L>
<L N="3332">&THORN;at he ne thynkes, some tyme, som vayn thoght</L>
<L>&THORN;at he lattes pas and charges it noght;</L>
<L>Of swilk hym byhoves clensed be</L>
<L>Or<NOTE PLACE="foot">ar?</NOTE> he may &thorn;e bright face of God se;</L>
<L N="3336">For als gold, &thorn;at shynes clere and bright,</L>
<L>Semes fyned clene ynoghe til mans sight,</L>
<L>Whar it put in fire to fyn mare</L>
<L>Yhit suld it leve sum dros &thorn;are;</L>
<L N="3340">Right swa &thorn;e saules, on &thorn;e same manere,</L>
<L>Of parfit men, &thorn;at semes clene here</L>
<L>Of al syn, and es to God redy,</L>
<L>Yhit when &thorn;ai sal pas thurgh purgatory,</L>
<L N="3344">&THORN;e fire &thorn;ar, &thorn;at es with in,</L>
<L>Sal fynd in &thorn;am sum dros of syn,</L>
<L>Als light speche, or thoght in vayn,</L>
<L>For whilk &thorn;am byhoves fele sum payn,</L>
<L N="3348">For swa fyned never na gold here was</L>
<L>Thurgh fire, als &thorn;ai sal be ar &thorn;ai pas.</L>
<L>Here haf I shewed swilk<NOTE PLACE="foot">wilk.</NOTE> saules sal be</L>
<L>In purgatory, als clerkes can se.</L>
<L N="3352">Now wille I som syns here specify</L>
<L>For whilk &thorn;ai duelle in purgatory.
<PB REF="00000136.tif" N="92"></L>
<L>Many maners of syns, &thorn;at greves,</L>
<L>Regnes omang men &thorn;at leves;</L>
<L N="3356">Of wilk sum er dedly to fele</L>
<L>And sum er noght bot veniele,</L>
<L>&THORN;a syns &thorn;at er cald dedly</L>
<L>Sal noght be purged in purgatory,</L>
<L N="3360">Bot &thorn;ai sal be punyst ay in helle;</L>
<L>And whilk &thorn;as er I wil yow telle.</L>
<L>&THORN;ir er &thorn;a hede syns &thorn;at er dedely;</L>
<L>Pride, hatreden, and envy;</L>
<L N="3364">Glotony and sleuthe in Goddes servise,</L>
<L>And lychery and covatyse,</L>
<L>Sacrilege, and fals wyttenessyng,</L>
<L>And slaghter and forsweryng,</L>
<L N="3368">Thefte alswa and ravyn,</L>
<L>Ilkan of &thorn;ir es a dedly syn.</L>
<L>And wreth es dedly syn omang,</L>
<L>If it be halden in hert lang;</L>
<L N="3372">And yhit drunkenes es dedly to fele,</L>
<L>If it be over continuele;</L>
<L>Wha-swa feles hym here gylty</L>
<L>In any of &thorn;ir syns dedly,</L>
<L N="3376">Bot-if he hym amende, ar he hethen wende,</L>
<L>He sal noght aftir his lyfes ende</L>
<L>Wend strek til purgatory,</L>
<L>Bot even til helle with-outen mercy.</L>
<L N="3380">Bot if he wille hym repent and shrife</L>
<L>Of alle swilk syns here in his lyfe,</L>
<L>Fra helle pyne &thorn;an es he save;</L>
<L>Bot payn and penaunce hym byhoves have</L>
<L N="3384">In purgatory, als I wene,</L>
<L>Until he be made of alle syn clene;</L>
<L>Forwhy penaunce for syn, als I sayd are,</L>
<L>Most be fulfilled outher here or &thorn;are.</L>
<L N="3388">Syns &thorn;at er veniele may dere,</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;ai er noght swa hevy to bere,</L>
<L>Als er dedly, for &thorn;ai may be here</L>
<L>Fordon on light manere.
<PB REF="00000137.tif" N="93"></L>
<L N="3392">For als men heres &thorn;er clerkes say,</L>
<L>Ilk man here lyghtly may</L>
<L>Swilk remedys thurgh grace wyn,</L>
<L>&THORN;at may fordo al veniel syn;</L>
<L N="3396">&THORN;at es to say, if he clene be</L>
<L>Of dedly syn, and wil it fle;</L>
<L>For I fynd writen ten thynges sere,</L>
<L>&THORN;at veniel syns fordus here.</L>
<L N="3400">&THORN;as ten er &thorn;ir &thorn;at I now rede;</L>
<L>Haly water and almusdede,</L>
<L>Fastyng, and housil of Goddes body,</L>
<L>Prayer of &thorn;e <I>Pater Noster</I> namly,</L>
<L N="3404">General shrifte, &thorn;at ilk day may be,</L>
<L>Benyssoun of bisshope of his dignit&eacute;;</L>
<L>And benyssoun of prest, &thorn;at gyyen es</L>
<L>Namly, in &thorn;e end of &thorn;e mes;</L>
<L N="3408">Knokyng of<NOTE PLACE="foot">On (MS. Harl. 6923).</NOTE> &thorn;e brest of man &thorn;at es meke,</L>
<L>Last enoyntyng gyven to &thorn;e seke.</L>
<L>&THORN;er ten puttes veniel syns away,</L>
<L>Als men may here &thorn;er clerkes say.</L>
<L N="3412">Bot swa many veniel syns sere</L>
<L>May be gadyrd atans togyder here,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ai may weghe on &thorn;e saul als hevy</L>
<L>Als a syn dus &thorn;at es dedly,</L>
<L N="3416">&THORN;at slas &thorn;e saul and God myspays;</L>
<L>And &thorn;arfor &thorn;e poet on &thorn;is wyse says:</L>
<L><I>De minimis granis fit</I></L>
<L><I>maxima summa caballo.</I></L>
<L N="3420">"Als of many smale cornes es made</L>
<L>Til a hors bak a mykel lade,"</L>
<L>Right swa may veniel syns many</L>
<L>Mak a mykel syn dedly.</L>
<L N="3424">For &thorn;ai gadir on &thorn;e saul ful thyk,</L>
<L>And cleves togyder als dos pyk,</L>
<L>Bot if &thorn;ai swythe be done oway,</L>
<L>Ay als &thorn;ai com, with-outen delay;
<PB REF="00000138.tif" N="94"></L>
<L N="3428">For swa parfitely may nane lyf here,</L>
<L>With-outen veniel syns sere.</L>
<L>For a man syns alday &thorn;at here duels</L>
<L>Als &thorn;e boke says &thorn;at &thorn;us tels.</L>
<L N="3432"><I>Septies in die cadit</I></L>
<L><I>iustus</I></L>
<L>"Seven sythes at &thorn;e lest o[f] &thorn;e day</L>
<L>&THORN;e ryghtwys falles," &thorn;at es to say,</L>
<L N="3436">In sere syns &thorn;at er veniel,</L>
<L>Bot som er mare, and som les to fel.</L>
<L>In swa many veniel syns we falle,</L>
<L>&THORN;at na man can reken &thorn;am alle;</L>
<L N="3440">Bot sum of &thorn;am reherce I can,</L>
<L>Als Saynt Austyn telles, &thorn;e haly men.</L>
<L>For in a boke he reherces som,</L>
<L>&THORN;at mast es used of custom,</L>
<L N="3444">And to telle &thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;as?</NOTE> syns he &thorn;us bygyns,</L>
<L>And says &thorn;at &thorn;er er veniel syns.</L>
<L>First when a man etes or drinkes mare</L>
<L>Anytime, &thorn;an myster ware;</L>
<L N="3448">When &thorn;ou may vaile thurgh wytte and skille</L>
<L>And wille noght help bot haldes &thorn;e stylle;</L>
<L>When &thorn;ou spekes sharppely til &thorn;e pure,</L>
<L>&THORN;at sum gode askes at &thorn;i dore;</L>
<L N="3452">When &thorn;ou erte hale and may wele last</L>
<L>And etes when tym es to fast;</L>
<L>When &thorn;e lyst slepe and wil noght ryse,</L>
<L>And comes overlate tyl Goddes servise;</L>
<L N="3456">Or when &thorn;ou ert in gude state</L>
<L>And says &thorn;i praers ever late;</L>
<L>Or when &thorn;ou says praier or orison</L>
<L>With over litel devocion;</L>
<L N="3460">When a man list dele in bed</L>
<L>With his wyfe &thorn;at he has wed,</L>
<L>Hys lust anly for to fulfille,</L>
<L>And to gette a child es noght in wille;
<PB REF="00000139.tif" N="95"></L>
<L N="3464">When &thorn;ou visites men overlate</L>
<L>&THORN;at sek er and in febel state,</L>
<L>Or men &thorn;at lyes in prison,</L>
<L>Or in any tribulacion,</L>
<L N="3468">Or men &thorn;at er synful and sary,</L>
<L>Or saules &thorn;at er in purgatory;</L>
<L>For to visite &thorn;am it war grete nede,</L>
<L>Thurgh praier and thurgh almusdede;</L>
<L N="3472">When &thorn;ou paynes &thorn;e noght aftir &thorn;i state</L>
<L>To accorde &thorn;am &thorn;at er at debate;</L>
<L>When &thorn;ou spekes over bitterly</L>
<L>Til any man with noyse or cry;</L>
<L N="3476">When &thorn;ou prayses any man mare</L>
<L>Thurgh flateryng, &thorn;an mister ware;</L>
<L>When &thorn;ou in kirk makes ianglyng,</L>
<L>Or thynkes in vayn anythyng;</L>
<L N="3480">Be it with-outen, be it with-in,</L>
<L>Yhit it es a veniel syn;</L>
<L>When &thorn;ou ert over lyghtly wrathe,</L>
<L>Or sweres and may noght hald &thorn;in athe;</L>
<L N="3484">When &thorn;ou bannes any man,</L>
<L>In wham &thorn;ou fyndes na gilt to ban;</L>
<L>When &thorn;ou supposes any wykkednes,</L>
<L>Thurgh suspecion &thorn;ar na es.</L>
<L N="3488">&THORN;ir smale syns Saynt Austyn telles,</L>
<L>Thurgh whilk many saules duelles</L>
<L>In purgatory, in payne and wa.</L>
<L>Bot yhit &thorn;ar er ful many ma</L>
<L N="3492">Of veniel syns, be<NOTE PLACE="foot">by?</NOTE> many a score,</L>
<L>Over &thorn;as &thorn;at I haf tald byfore.</L>
<L>Bot swa witty es nane erthely man,</L>
<L>&THORN;at alle veniel syns reken can;</L>
<L N="3496">For ofte sythes of &thorn;e day men falles</L>
<L>In syns, &thorn;at clerkes veniel calles,</L>
<L>Thurgh werk, or worde, or thoght in vayn,</L>
<L>And ilka syn es worthy payn,
<PB REF="00000140.tif" N="96"></L>
<L N="3500">&THORN;e whilk most be fordone clenly,</L>
<L>Outher here or in purgatory.</L>
<L>&THORN;arfor I rede ilk man, whyles he lyffes here,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he use &thorn;a ten thinges sere</L>
<L N="3504">&THORN;at fordus, als I sayde are,</L>
<L>Alle veniel syns, bathe les and mare.</L>
<L>And if any fal in dedly syn</L>
<L>Ryse he up, and ligg noght lang &thorn;ar-in,</L>
<L N="3508">And ga to &thorn;e prest hym to shrife,</L>
<L>And tak his penaunce in his life,</L>
<L>And haf he forthynkyng ay in thoght,</L>
<L>For &thorn;as syns &thorn;at he has wroght,</L>
<L N="3512">And do he penance with al his myght,</L>
<L>And be in prayers, bathe day and night,</L>
<L>And fast and ga wolwarde, and wake,</L>
<L>And thole hardes<NOTE PLACE="foot">hardnes (Harl. 6923).</NOTE> for Goddes sake;</L>
<L N="3516">For na man may to heven ga,</L>
<L>Bot-if he thole here anger and wa.</L>
<L>And when God sendes a man angwise</L>
<L>He suld thole it with-outen fayntise,</L>
<L N="3520">Be it sekenes, or oght elles &thorn;at greves,</L>
<L>Losse of catelle, or of fre[n]des &thorn;at lyves,</L>
<L>Or unkyndnes, fals[h]ed, or treson,</L>
<L>Or any other tribulacion,</L>
<L N="3524">Thole he it mekely and thynk in thoght</L>
<L>&THORN;at with-outen cause commes it noght.</L>
<L>Bot God wate wele &thorn;e cause why,</L>
<L>Parchaunce it es for his foly,</L>
<L N="3528">To chasty hym on swilk manere,</L>
<L>For his syns &thorn;at he dyd here,</L>
<L>Or it may be hym here to pruve,</L>
<L>Or to make hym mar drede God and lufe.</L>
<L N="3532">&THORN;arfor sen God ofte vouches save</L>
<L>&THORN;at a man here swilk angers have,</L>
<L>Outher for his syn or hym to fande;</L>
<L>Love he him &thorn;an of alle his sande,
<PB REF="00000141.tif" N="97"></L>
<L N="3536">And take mekely &thorn;at God him sendes,</L>
<L>And fle alle thyng &thorn;at he defendes.</L>
<L>For thurgh nuyes and angers sere,</L>
<L>He makes a man, als his preson here,</L>
<L N="3540">Payn to drighe for hys foly,</L>
<L>In &thorn;is lif als he es worthy.</L>
<L>And, if he it thole noght grotchand,</L>
<L>In-stede of penance it sal hym stand,</L>
<L N="3544">And yhit wille God him mare do,</L>
<L>He wil gif him mede &thorn;ar-to,</L>
<L>&THORN;at his ioy in heven sal heke,</L>
<L>If he thole angwyse with hert meke.</L>
<L N="3548">Als &thorn;e gude son tholes mekely</L>
<L>&THORN;e fader, when he wille hym chasty,</L>
<L>Swa suld ilk man thole and love God ay,</L>
<L>And do alle &thorn;e gude &thorn;at he may,</L>
<L N="3552">And specialy almusdede,</L>
<L>&THORN;e naked to clathe, and hungry to fede,</L>
<L>And other werkes of mercy wirke,</L>
<L>Als theches and preches haly kirke;</L>
<L N="3556">And kepe him clene, to his lyfes ende,</L>
<L>Fra syn, &thorn;an sal his saul wende</L>
<L>Til blis, and lyghtly pas alle payne</L>
<L>Of purgatori; &thorn;is es certayne.</L>
<L N="3560">Here haf I shewed yhow, on Inglys,</L>
<L>Som syns &thorn;at Saynt Austyn specifys.</L>
<L>Now wil I shew what help es certayne</L>
<L>For &thorn;am &thorn;at in purgatory has payne,</L>
<L N="3564">And what may mak &thorn;air payn cees</L>
<L>And &thorn;am of &thorn;air payn to haf relees.</L>
<L>&THORN;e saules, &thorn;at til purgatory wendes,</L>
<L>May be helped thurgh help of frendes,</L>
<L N="3568">&THORN;at almus for &thorn;am dus, and prays,</L>
<L>For &thorn;e haly man, Saynt Austyn says:</L>
<L><I>Non est negandum spiritus defunctorum, pietate</I></L>
<L><I>suorum viventium, posse relevari.</I></L>
<L N="3572">He says "men shuld not denye on na manere,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e saules of &thorn;am &thorn;at er dede here,
<PB REF="00000142.tif" N="98"></L>
<L>Of payn may relesed be</L>
<L>Thurgh frendes lyfand &thorn;at has pyt&eacute;."</L>
<L N="3576">For als &thorn;as &thorn;at passed, als I sayd are,</L>
<L>Til purgatory er pyned &thorn;are</L>
<L>For weniel syns, mare and lesse,</L>
<L>Aparty, thurgh Goddes rightwisnesse,</L>
<L N="3580">Right swa thurgh help &thorn;ai may aparty,</L>
<L>Be relesed &thorn;ar, thurgh Goddes mercy.</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;at men dus here, bathe les and mare,</L>
<L>For &thorn;e saules &thorn;at duelles &thorn;are</L>
<L N="3584">Avayles &thorn;am noght als to heven mede,</L>
<L>Bot for &thorn;air deliverance fra payn to spede.</L>
<L>Four maners of helpes er general,</L>
<L>&THORN;at in purgatory availes &thorn;am al,</L>
<L N="3588">&THORN;at es to say, prayer and fastyng,</L>
<L>And almus dede and messyng.</L>
<L>On twa maners, als clerkes can se,</L>
<L>&THORN;e saule fra payn deliverd may be;</L>
<L N="3592">&THORN;e tane by way of grace es,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e tother by way of rightwisnes,</L>
<L>By way of grace on twyn manere</L>
<L>Als es writen in &thorn;is boke here.</L>
<L N="3596">First thurgh prayer of Crist &thorn;at es hede,</L>
<L>When he es offerd in fourme of brede,</L>
<L>Thurgh prestes hande here at &thorn;e mes,</L>
<L>When &thorn;e sacrament swa made es.</L>
<L N="3600">Alswa thurgh prayer of his lyms,</L>
<L>&THORN;at es, of gude men &thorn;at toward heven clyms.</L>
<L>&THORN;an may &thorn;e saules in purgatory,</L>
<L>By way of grace specialy,</L>
<L N="3604">Be delivered of pyn &thorn;at ders,</L>
<L>Thurgh messes and rightwis men prayers.</L>
<L>By way of rightwysnes help may be</L>
<L>On twyn maners, als yhe may se.</L>
<L N="3608">First, through byhyng of paynes &thorn;at greves,</L>
<L>With almus, &thorn;at men to the pure gyves.</L>
<L>Another es here thurgh assethe makyng,</L>
<L>Als thurgh penance of fre[n]des and fastyng.
<PB REF="00000143.tif" N="99"></L>
<L N="3612">&THORN;us may saules, als &thorn;e buke beres wytnes,</L>
<L>By helpyd by way of rightwysnes,</L>
<L>&THORN;at es to say, &thorn;ai may in &thorn;at nede</L>
<L>Be boght fra payn thurgh almusdede;</L>
<L N="3616">And thurgh penance for &thorn;am here don,</L>
<L>&THORN;e dette of payn may be qwitte son,</L>
<L>Right als a man, &thorn;at duelles in prison</L>
<L>Til he haf payed a certayn raunson,</L>
<L N="3620">May be delyverd and broght away</L>
<L>Thurgh a frende, &thorn;at wille it for hym pay.</L>
<L>On &thorn;is wyse may &thorn;e saules &thorn;at wendes</L>
<L>Til purgatory, be helped thurgh fre[n]des.</L>
<L N="3624">Bot sum frende may help, and som noght,</L>
<L>&THORN;e saules &thorn;at til purgatory er broght.</L>
<L>Thurgh &thorn;as frendes may &thorn;ai helped be</L>
<L>&THORN;at here lyves thurgh ryght charit&eacute;.</L>
<L N="3628">Bot &thorn;e help of &thorn;am, &thorn;at charit&eacute; failles</L>
<L>Til &thorn;e saules &thorn;at er &thorn;ar noght availles,</L>
<L>For alle er als lymes of a body,</L>
<L>&THORN;at here er, and in purgatory;</L>
<L N="3632">And als we may se properly here</L>
<L>A body hafe many lymmes sere,</L>
<L>And ilkan of &thorn;am, bathe les and mare,</L>
<L>May help other &thorn;at feles sare;</L>
<L N="3636">Bot if a lym dighe, and &thorn;e myght faile,</L>
<L>&THORN;at lym may noght til &thorn;e others availe.</L>
<L>Right swa it fars on &thorn;e same wyse,</L>
<L>By &thorn;am [&thorn;at] in purgatory lyese,</L>
<L N="3640">And &thorn;at er here; for men may &thorn;am calle</L>
<L>Als lyms of a body alle.</L>
<L>Wha-swa in dedly syn es broght</L>
<L>And charit&eacute; in his hert has noght,</L>
<L N="3644">He es als dede in saul with-in;</L>
<L>Ay, whiles he es in dedly syn,</L>
<L>His help vailles noght, bot es in vayne</L>
<L>Als to &thorn;e saules &thorn;at er in payne.</L>
<L N="3648">His help thurgh hym-selfe standes in na stede,</L>
<L>For he es als a lym &thorn;at es dede;
<PB REF="00000144.tif" N="100"></L>
<L>Bot never-&thorn;e-latter, alle-if he swa be</L>
<L>In syn and out of charit&eacute;,</L>
<L N="3652">Yhit may he helpe &thorn;e saales &thorn;us,</L>
<L>If he til pure men gyf almus,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ai for &thorn;e saules pray specialy</L>
<L>And helpes &thorn;e saules in purgatory.</L>
<L N="3656">Yhit may &thorn;e help and &thorn;e travaile</L>
<L>Of sum synful men &thorn;e saules avayle,</L>
<L>If it thurgh biddyng done be</L>
<L>Of a frende &thorn;at es in charit&eacute;;</L>
<L N="3660">Or of<NOTE PLACE="foot">The MS. has 'if'.</NOTE> &thorn;e dede self &thorn;at has mast nede</L>
<L>Of help of prayer and almusdede;</L>
<L>&THORN;at help may avayle &thorn;e saules son</L>
<L>For his sake, &thorn;at biddes it be don,</L>
<L N="3664">&THORN;at charity in hert has knytt</L>
<L>And noght for his sake &thorn;at dos it,</L>
<L>For-why God wille noght do for his sake</L>
<L>&THORN;at charit&eacute; w&iacute;lle noght in hert take.</L>
<L N="3668">&THORN;is case ofte falles, als I understande,</L>
<L>Bytwen a loverd and his servande,</L>
<L>Whare &thorn;e loverd es gude and rightwys,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e servand ille and uses folys.</L>
<L N="3672">If &thorn;e servand do anythyng</L>
<L>&THORN;at es gude at his loverdys bydyng,</L>
<L>Yhit may it availle to a gude use,</L>
<L>Alle-if he be ille &thorn;at it duse;</L>
<L N="3676">And &thorn;at by reson of &thorn;e gudenes</L>
<L>Of hym of wham &thorn;e bygynnyng es.</L>
<L>For alle be it onence &thorn;e doer dede<NOTE PLACE="foot">Anence the doer if it be dede. (MS. Harl. 6923.)</NOTE>,</L>
<L>Onence &thorn;e bidder it standes in stede;</L>
<L N="8360">Bot if &thorn;ai bathe in charit&eacute; ware</L>
<L>&THORN;e helpe til &thorn;e dede war wele &thorn;e mare.</L>
<L>Alswa a prest alle-if he be</L>
<L>Synful and out of charit&eacute;,</L>
<L N="3684">He es Goddes minister and haly kirkes,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e sacrament of &thorn;e auter wirkes;
<PB REF="00000145.tif" N="101"></L>
<L>&THORN;e wilk es never-&thorn;e-les of myght,</L>
<L>Alle-if &thorn;e prest here lyf noght right.</L>
<L N="3688">For if a prest &thorn;at synges mes</L>
<L>Be never swa ful of wykednes,</L>
<L>&THORN;e sacrament, &thorn;at es swa haly,</L>
<L>May noght apayred be thurgh his foly.</L>
<L N="3692">&THORN;an may mes saules fra payn bring,</L>
<L>Alle-if a synful prest it syng.</L>
<L>For in Goddes name he synges &thorn;e mes,</L>
<L>Under wham in order he es.</L>
<L N="3696">Bot speciel prayers with gude entente,</L>
<L>&THORN;at es made besyde &thorn;e sacramente,</L>
<L>Of a gude prest er wele better</L>
<L>&THORN;an of an ille, and to God swetter;</L>
<L N="3700">Bot &thorn;e offeryng of Goddis body</L>
<L>Helpes &thorn;e saules principaly;</L>
<L>Wharfor it semes &thorn;at mes syngyng</L>
<L>May titest &thorn;e saul out of payn bryng,</L>
<L N="3704">&THORN;at passes hethen in charit&eacute;,</L>
<L>And in purgatory clensed suld be.</L>
<L>Bot til &thorn;am &thorn;at er dampned for ay</L>
<L>Na gude dede avayle ne help may,</L>
<L N="3708">Nouther almus dede, prayer, ne messe,</L>
<L>For &thorn;ai er, als &thorn;e buke bers witnesse,</L>
<L>Departed halely fra &thorn;e body of Criste,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e saules for ever er periste,</L>
<L N="3712">For als lymmes, &thorn;at er dede, er &thorn;ai</L>
<L>&THORN;at er hewed fra &thorn;e body oway.</L>
<L>And als nathyng may help kyndely</L>
<L>&THORN;e lymes &thorn;at er cutted fra &thorn;e body,</L>
<L N="3716">Right swa alle helpes &thorn;at men can telle,</L>
<L>Availles &thorn;am noght &thorn;at er in helle.</L>
<L>Yhit help of frendes here on sum wyse,</L>
<L>Availles &thorn;am &thorn;at er in paradise,</L>
<L N="3720">And alswa &thorn;am &thorn;at in helle duelles,</L>
<L>Als a grete clerk in boke telles.</L>
<L>&THORN;an availles almus, messe, and bedes,</L>
<L>To &thorn;e saules &thorn;at er in alle &thorn;re stedes;
<PB REF="00000146.tif" N="102"></L>
<L N="3724">&THORN;ai availe &thorn;e saules in purgatory</L>
<L>To spede &thorn;am out mare hastily.</L>
<L>&THORN;ai vaile &thorn;am &thorn;at in heven er;</L>
<L>For &thorn;ai multiplie &thorn;ar &thorn;e titter,</L>
<L N="3728">And &thorn;e ma &thorn;at gaders to &thorn;at place,</L>
<L>&THORN;e mare &thorn;air ioy es, and solace.</L>
<L>&THORN;ai avail til &thorn;am &thorn;at er in helle,</L>
<L>For &thorn;e foner shuld com &thorn;ider to duelle,</L>
<L N="3732">And &thorn;e foner &thorn;at &thorn;ider commes for syn,</L>
<L>&THORN;e les payn &thorn;ai have &thorn;at duelles &thorn;ar-in;</L>
<L>And ay &thorn;e ma saules &thorn;at &thorn;ider wendes,</L>
<L>&THORN;e mare &thorn;air payne es, &thorn;at never endes.</L>
<L N="3736">&THORN;us may help here and availe be skille</L>
<L>Til &thorn;e saules &thorn;at duelles ay in helle stille;</L>
<L>And til &thorn;e saules &thorn;at er in heven namly,</L>
<L>And til &thorn;am &thorn;at er in purgatory.</L>
<L N="3740">Bot help may na saules out of payn spede,</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;am &thorn;at has charit&eacute; and nede.</L>
<L>For in helle es na charit&eacute;,</L>
<L>And in heven na ned may be.</L>
<L N="3744">Bot bathe &thorn;a twa &thorn;e saules has</L>
<L>&THORN;at fra hethen til purgatory gas.</L>
<L>And als a man may here with his hande,</L>
<L>Make asethe for another lyfande,</L>
<L N="3748">&THORN;e whilk es noght of power &thorn;ar-to,</L>
<L>Right swa may a man for &thorn;e ded do.</L>
<L>&THORN;e saules &thorn;at til paradise er gane</L>
<L>Nede of help here haf &thorn;ai nane;</L>
<L N="3752">Bot if for &thorn;am war don any gude dede,</L>
<L>It may availe &thorn;am, &thorn;at of help has nede.</L>
<L>&THORN;e help &thorn;at es don here specialy</L>
<L>Availles til &thorn;e saules in purgatory,</L>
<L N="3756">Bot to som mare and til som les,</L>
<L>Aftir &thorn;ai er of worthynes;</L>
<L>And aftir &thorn;e charit&eacute; es clere</L>
<L>Of &thorn;am &thorn;at er lyffand here,</L>
<L N="3760">&THORN;at mast er bysy, and dus mare</L>
<L>For sum &thorn;an for other &thorn;at er &thorn;are.
<PB REF="00000147.tif" N="103"></L>
<L>Bot when a man fra &thorn;is world sal flitte</L>
<L>Na man for certayn here may wytte</L>
<L N="3764">Whether he sal &thorn;an til purgatory wende,</L>
<L>Or to blisse or to payn with-outen ende.</L>
<L>For som semes gude here and parfite,</L>
<L>&THORN;at, after &thorn;e dede, er dampned als-tite;</L>
<L N="3768">For parchaunce &thorn;ai er ille with-in,</L>
<L>And passes away in dedely syn.</L>
<L>Some semes synful, als &thorn;ai lyfed mys,</L>
<L>&THORN;at er save and er in &thorn;e way til blisse,</L>
<L N="3772">For parchaunce byfor &thorn;air endyng,</L>
<L>&THORN;ai er amended of &thorn;air myslyvyng.</L>
<L>Of &thorn;is may na man certayn be,</L>
<L>For it es Goddes pryvet&eacute;.</L>
<L N="3776">Bot we shuld trow, and suppose ay</L>
<L>&THORN;at alle er save and in gude way,</L>
<L>&THORN;at we se here gude werkes wirk,</L>
<L>And has &thorn;e sacramentes of halikyrk.</L>
<L N="3780">Bot whether it be or noght &thorn;us,</L>
<L>We suld do &thorn;at es in us;</L>
<L>We suld pray, bathe loud and stille,</L>
<L>For al cristen saules; &thorn;us charit&eacute; wille.</L>
<L N="3784">Now sum may aske why synges men mes</L>
<L>For a yhong child when it dede es,</L>
<L>&THORN;at of prayer, ne mes has na nede,</L>
<L>For it couth never do synful dede.</L>
<L N="3788">&THORN;is may be &thorn;e right skille why,</L>
<L>For &thorn;e lovyng of God principaly</L>
<L>And for usage of haly kyrk,</L>
<L>And for &thorn;e dedes use &thorn;at office to wirk.</L>
<L N="3792">And yhit may &thorn;e mes in sum case</L>
<L>Help &thorn;am in purgatory &thorn;at ned hase.</L>
<L>Here haf yhe herde, als &thorn;e buke bers witnes,</L>
<L>How almus, penance, praier and mes,</L>
<L N="3796">&THORN;at er done thurgh fre[n]des certayne,</L>
<L>May help &thorn;e saules &thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="foot">The MS. reads '&thorn;ar'.</NOTE> er in payne.</L>
<L>Now wille I shew yhow yhit mare &thorn;arto,</L>
<L>What pardon may to &thorn;e saules do,
<PB REF="00000148.tif" N="104"></L>
<L N="3800">&THORN;e whilk &thorn;ai purchaced, on right manere</L>
<L>In clene lif whilles &thorn;ai liffed here.</L>
<L>Pardon helpes &thorn;am, als clerkes says,</L>
<L>&THORN;at it has purchased in &thorn;air lif days;</L>
<L N="3804">For pardon of papes and bisschopes,</L>
<L>&THORN;at es granted here als men hopes,</L>
<L>May availe &thorn;air saules in purgatory,</L>
<L>&THORN;at has purchaced it here worthyly,</L>
<L N="3808">If &thorn;ai of &thorn;air syn had contricion</L>
<L>And war shrifen byfor &thorn;at pardon,</L>
<L>&THORN;an may pardon after &thorn;air dede</L>
<L>In purgatory &thorn;am stand in stede.</L>
<L N="3812">For pardon here, &thorn;at es certayn,</L>
<L>May &thorn;am relese of &thorn;e dede<NOTE PLACE="foot">dette (MS. Harl. 6923).</NOTE> of payn,</L>
<L>Als fer-forthe als pardon may reche,</L>
<L>&THORN;us haf I herd grete clerkes preche.</L>
<L N="3816">Pardon properly noght elles es</L>
<L>Bot of payne, &thorn;at es dette, forgyfnes.</L>
<L>Pardon may nane hafe bot he wil wirke,</L>
<L>For it es of &thorn;e tresur of haly kirke,</L>
<L N="3820">&THORN;at es gadirde for nede of pardon,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e vertu of Crestes passion,</L>
<L>And of &thorn;e worthines of &thorn;e dedys</L>
<L>Of his halowes and of &thorn;air medys;</L>
<L N="3824">And [it] es gaderd on many maners;</L>
<L>First als of marterdom of martires;</L>
<L>Of penance and travail of confessours,</L>
<L>And of &thorn;e thechyng of docturs;</L>
<L N="3828">And of chastit&eacute; of virgyns clene,</L>
<L>&THORN;at chast and haly ay has bene;</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e fruyt of haly kirk werkes,</L>
<L>And of &thorn;e prayers of gude prestes and clerkes;</L>
<L N="3832">Of alle &thorn;is, als I shewed byfor,</L>
<L>Es gadird haly kirkes tresor,</L>
<L>Of wilk &thorn;e pape &thorn;e kays bers,</L>
<L>Whar-with he bathe opens and spers.
<PB REF="00000149.tif" N="105"></L>
<L N="3836">&THORN;at falles hym of office to halde,</L>
<L>For he es in erthe, Godes vicar calde.</L>
<L>&THORN;a cays er noght elles to se</L>
<L>Bot playn power of his dignit&eacute;,</L>
<L N="3840">Thurgh whilk he may, be law and skille,</L>
<L>Louse and bynde at his wille.</L>
<L>For &thorn;e sam power hym falles to have,</L>
<L>&THORN;at Crist til Peter in erthe gave.</L>
<L N="3844">For Crist gave to Peter playn powere,</L>
<L>And says to hym on &thorn;is manere.</L>
<L><I>Quodcunque ligaveris super terram</I></L>
<L><I>erit ligatum et in celis, Et quodcunque</I></L>
<L N="3848"><I>solveris super terram, erit solutum</I></L>
<L><I>et in celis.</I></L>
<L>"Alle &thorn;at &thorn;ou byndes in erthe," says he,</L>
<L>"Sal in heven bunden be</L>
<L N="3852">And alle &thorn;at &thorn;ou lowses in erthe right</L>
<L>Sal be loused in heven bright."</L>
<L>&THORN;is power til alle papes gaf he,</L>
<L>&THORN;at aftir Petre in erthe shuld be,</L>
<L N="3856">Als shewes an exposicion</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e haly godspelle in a lesson.</L>
<L>&THORN;an semes it wele by &thorn;is skille here,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e pape has swa large powere</L>
<L N="3860">To assoyle a man, and hym forgyfe,</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;e dette of payn &thorn;at may greve,</L>
<L>Swa &thorn;at he, &thorn;at &thorn;e pape assoyles, fulfille</L>
<L>&THORN;at, &thorn;at &thorn;e laghe of &thorn;e gospelle wille,<NOTE PLACE="foot"><LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Yf he &thorn;at es assoilede fulfylle</L>
<L>Als &thorn;e lawe and &thorn;e godespelle wille. (Harl. 6923.)</L>
</LG></NOTE></L>
<L N="3864">And yheld agayn, if he be myghty,</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;at he tas wrangwysly;</L>
<L>For when &thorn;e pape, &thorn;at grace wil do,</L>
<L>He byndes hym and alle haly kirk &thorn;arto</L>
<L N="3868">For hym til wham &thorn;at grace avayles</L>
<L>To fulfille alle &thorn;at in hym failles,</L>
<L>Bot bischopes here of lagher state,</L>
<L>And has les power, als clerkes wate,
<PB REF="00000150.tif" N="106"></L>
<L N="3872">For-why &thorn;air dignit&eacute; here es les</L>
<L>And &thorn;arfor &thorn;air powere restreyned es;</L>
<L>Bot if it be noght swa suffishaunt</L>
<L>Als &thorn;e papes es, yhit may &thorn;ai graunt</L>
<L N="3876">Of &thorn;air power pardon aparty</L>
<L>Til &thorn;air hawen underloutes<NOTE PLACE="foot">underlynges (MS. Y).</NOTE> anly;</L>
<L>And yhit most &thorn;at, als I sayd befor,</L>
<L>Be gyfen of haly kirkes tresor.</L>
<L N="3880">Bot na man may here pardon wyn,</L>
<L>Bot he be out of dedly syn;</L>
<L>For he, &thorn;at kepyng of &thorn;at fair tresour has,</L>
<L>May noght it dele til haly kyrk fas;</L>
<L N="3884">And swilk er &thorn;ai and nan elles</L>
<L>&THORN;at here in dedly syn duelles;</L>
<L>For out of haly kirk er &thorn;ai,</L>
<L>&THORN;arfor na pardon whyn &thorn;ai may.</L>
<L N="3888">Bot &thorn;e frendes of haly kirk may wyn</L>
<L>Pardon, for &thorn;ai er with-in;</L>
<L>And swilk er &thorn;as &thorn;at here er fre</L>
<L>Of dedly syns and er in charit&eacute;;</L>
<L N="3892">Til wham pardon sal noght fail,</L>
<L>Bot in purgatory it sal &thorn;am avail,</L>
<L>To allege &thorn;air saules of payne,</L>
<L>Als fer als it reches of certayne,</L>
<L N="3896">&THORN;e whilk, als sum says, falles to be sett</L>
<L>For &thorn;e [r]emenand of payns, &thorn;at es, dett</L>
<L>&THORN;at parchaunce es lefte undon here;</L>
<L>And &thorn;at may falle on sere manere.</L>
<L N="3900">Aparty for penance &thorn;at es [en]ioynt,</L>
<L>&THORN;at es noght done at &thorn;e dedes poynt;</L>
<L>Aparty for veniel syns sere;</L>
<L>Aparty for syns &thorn;at er forgeten here;</L>
<L N="3904">Aparty for over litelle penance,</L>
<L>And for over littelle repentance;</L>
<L>Aparty, for penance enioint, and done</L>
<L>Parchaunce over reklesly and over sone;</L>
<L N="3908">Aparty, for penance &thorn;at enioynt es,</L>
<L>And es forgeten thurgh reklesnes.
<PB REF="00000151.tif" N="107"></L>
<L>Alle &thorn;is may be cald &thorn;e remenand,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e dette of payn, als I understand</L>
<L N="3912">&THORN;e whilk felle to be fulfylled haly,</L>
<L>Outher here or in purgatory,</L>
<L>Bot alle &thorn;is dett may &thorn;ar be qwytt</L>
<L>Thurgh large pardon, wha-swa has itt,</L>
<L N="3916">In forgyvenes of alle penance soght,</L>
<L>Whethir it be here enioynt or noght.</L>
<L>For swa mykel pardoun may a man</L>
<L>Purches here, &thorn;at he may &thorn;an</L>
<L N="3920">In purgatory qwyte alle &thorn;e dett,</L>
<L>&THORN;at hym fra blis may tary or lett;</L>
<L>For swa large es haly kirkes tresor,</L>
<L>&THORN;at it es ynogh to pay &thorn;arfor,</L>
<L N="3924">And for alle &thorn;e paynes &thorn;at dett may be</L>
<L>Of alle &thorn;e men of cristant&eacute;.</L>
<L>&THORN;us pardon in purgatory availles,</L>
<L>Als I tald; bot som clerkes counsailles</L>
<L N="3928">&THORN;at we it spare and reserve halely,</L>
<L>Until we com til purgatory,</L>
<L>And do here penance whilles we lyf may,</L>
<L>For a man sal thynk &thorn;are a day</L>
<L N="3932">Lenger &thorn;an hever thogh[t] him here,</L>
<L>&THORN;e space of alle ane hale yhere;</L>
<L>&THORN;an es a day of pardon to gesce</L>
<L>Mare worthy &thorn;an alle &thorn;is worldis riches,</L>
<L N="3936">For &thorn;e saule had lever, &thorn;at in payn dueles,</L>
<L>A day of pardon &thorn;an anythyng elles;</L>
<L>For alle &thorn;e werld, [if] it his ware,</L>
<L>He wald gyf for rest a day &thorn;are.</L>
<L N="3940">Of &thorn;is maters, &thorn;at &thorn;us mas mencion</L>
<L>Of help of frendes and of pardon</L>
<L>&THORN;at vailles &thorn;am &thorn;at er in purgatory,</L>
<L>Als I shewed byfor openly,</L>
<L N="3944">Spekes Innocent and Austyn</L>
<L>In bukes, whar &thorn;air<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;ir?</NOTE> maters er sen;</L>
<L>And Raymu[n]d spekes of &thorn;e same</L>
<L>In a boke, &thorn;at es called his name;
<PB REF="00000152.tif" N="108"></L>
<L N="3948">And Thomas Alqwyn spekes alswa</L>
<L>Of &thorn;is mater, and of other ma</L>
<L>In a boke, &thorn;e whilk made he,</L>
<L>&THORN;at<NOTE PLACE="foot">'And' (Harl. 6923).</NOTE> hat Veritas Theologie.</L>
<L N="3952">Here I have many maters redde,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e ferthe parte of &thorn;is boke spede,</L>
<L>In &thorn;e qwilk yhe hafe herd me specify</L>
<L>&THORN;e condicions of purgatory.</L>
<L N="3956">First what it es to fele and se,</L>
<L>And whar God has ordaynd it to be;</L>
<L>And what paynes falles &thorn;ar-to, les and mare,</L>
<L>And whilk saules byhoves be pyned &thorn;are;</L>
<L N="3960">And alswa for what manere of syn,</L>
<L>And what may &thorn;am help &thorn;at er &thorn;ar-in.</L>
<L>Of al &thorn;is haf I spoken til &thorn;e ende,</L>
<L>And now wille I til &thorn;e fifte part wende,</L>
<L N="3964">&THORN;at spekes of &thorn;e day of dome,</L>
<L>And of takens &thorn;at byfor sal come.</L>
</LG>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 N="5" TYPE="book">
<HEAD>Here bygyns &thorn;e fifte part &thorn;at es of &thorn;e day of dome and of takens &thorn;at sal cum byfor.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="3968">In &thorn;is part men may of ten &thorn;inges rede,</L>
<L>&THORN;at touches &thorn;e grete day of drede,</L>
<L>Of whilk sum byfor &thorn;at day sal be,</L>
<L>And at &thorn;e day, als men sal se.</L>
<L N="3972">&THORN;e first es of the wonderful takens sere,</L>
<L>&THORN;at byfor &thorn;at day sal be shewed here.</L>
<L>&THORN;e secunde es of &thorn;e fire &thorn;at sal bryn</L>
<L>&THORN;e world and al &thorn;at es &thorn;ar-in.</L>
<L N="3976">&THORN;e thred es of &thorn;e rysyng generale</L>
<L>Of alle men, bathe grete and smale.</L>
<L>&THORN;e ferthe es of crystes commyng don</L>
<L>Til &thorn;e dome, in proper parson.</L>
<L N="3980">&THORN;e fifthe es &thorn;e certayn stede</L>
<L>Whar Crist sal deme bathe qwik and dede.</L>
<L>&THORN;e sexte es of &thorn;e fourme of man,</L>
<L>In whilk Crist sal shew hym &thorn;an.
<PB REF="00000153.tif" N="109"></L>
<L N="3984">&THORN;e sevend, of &thorn;e accusers many,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e synful saul sal accuse &thorn;ar openly.</L>
<L>&THORN;e aghtynd, of &thorn;e acunt and &thorn;e rekennyng,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ai sal yheld of alle &thorn;air lyfyng.</L>
<L N="3988">&THORN;e neghend, of al men aftir &thorn;ai haf wroght,</L>
<L>Of wilk som sal be demed, and som noght,</L>
<L>&THORN;e tend es of &thorn;e grete dome final,</L>
<L>&THORN;at Crist sal gyf and mak ende of al.</L>
<L N="3992">Of &thorn;ir sal som falle, als yhe herd me say,</L>
<L>Byfor &thorn;at day and sum at &thorn;e day.</L>
<L>Byfor &thorn;e day sere takens sal com,</L>
<L>Of whilk men may here fynd wreten some,</L>
<L N="3996">Als of ancrist<NOTE PLACE="foot">'Antecrist' (Harl. 6923).</NOTE> commyng, and his poust&eacute;,</L>
<L>And of other ma &thorn;at byfor &thorn;at day sal be,</L>
<L>&THORN;e whilk takens men sal thynk ful harde,</L>
<L>Als yhe may se and here afterwarde.</L>
<L N="4000">And wha-swa wille avise hym wele,</L>
<L>He may ilk day here, se, and fele</L>
<L>Takens, war-thurgh he may understande,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e day of dome es fast comande.</L>
<L N="4004">For wonders &thorn;at shuld falle, als I trow,</L>
<L>Agayn &thorn;e worldes hende er sene now,</L>
<L>Thurgh whilk wondres grete clerkes knawes</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e worlde fast to &thorn;e endeward drawes.</L>
<L N="4008">Wharfor we shuld make us redy here,</L>
<L>Als &thorn;e day of dome war command nere.</L>
<L>Crist disciples, &thorn;at yherned haf knawyng,</L>
<L>Of sum takens agayns his last commyng,</L>
<L N="4012">Spak to Crist, als yhe may here,</L>
<L>In &thorn;e godspelle on &thorn;is manere:</L>
<L><I>Dic nobis signum adventus tui et</I></L>
<L><I>consummacionem seculi; Et respondens,</I></L>
<L N="4016"><I>Ihesus Christus dixit eis, Videte ne quis vos sedu|</I></L>
<L><I>cat; multi enim venient in nomine</I></L>
<L><I>meo dicentes, Ego sum Cristus, et multos</I></L>
<L><I>seducent &amp;c. Consurget enim gens</I>
<PB REF="00000154.tif" N="110"></L>
<L N="4020"><I>contra gentem et regnum in regnum,</I></L>
<L><I>et erunt pestulencie et fames, et terre</I></L>
<L><I>motus per loca. Hec autem omnia</I></L>
<L><I>inicia sunt dolorum, et habundabit</I></L>
<L N="4024"><I>iniquitas, et refrigescet caritas multorum.</I></L>
<L>'&middot;Says us", cryed &thorn;ai, "of &thorn;i commyng</L>
<L>Som taken and of &thorn;e world endyng.</L>
<L>Crist als tite answerd &thorn;am &thorn;an,</L>
<L N="4028">And sayd lukes &thorn;at yhow desayve na man,</L>
<L>For many sal com in my name,</L>
<L>&THORN;at sal say &thorn;us, 'Crist I am,'</L>
<L>And many a man &thorn;ai sal bygile</L>
<L N="4032">Bot &thorn;ai sal regne here bot a while;</L>
<L>Andrewme ogayne rewme, on &thorn;e same wyse</L>
<L>Men ogayne men, thurgh strength, sal ryse;</L>
<L>Pestilences and hungers sal be,</L>
<L N="4036">And erthedyns in many contr&eacute;.</L>
<L>And al &thorn;is sal be bygynnyng hard</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e sorows &thorn;at sal com aftirward;</L>
<L>Wykkednesse sal wax many falde,</L>
<L N="4040">And charit&eacute; of many sal wax calde."</L>
<L>&THORN;ir takens til his disciples tald he</L>
<L>&THORN;at ogayn &thorn;e worldes ende shuld be.</L>
<L>Bot sum of &thorn;ir takens has bene,</L>
<L N="4044">And sum of &thorn;am sal yhit be sene.</L>
<L>And of takens &thorn;at yhit sal com,</L>
<L>If yhe wille, I sal tel yhow som.</L>
<L>And first of ancrist wille I say</L>
<L N="4048">&THORN;at sal com befor domesday,</L>
<L>Aftir &thorn;e destruccion sal be</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e empyre of Rome, &thorn;at es yhit fre.</L>
<L>Som tyme al landes of &thorn;e world obout</L>
<L N="4052">Was sugette til Rome and underlout,</L>
<L>&THORN;at at certayn teremes<NOTE PLACE="foot">termes (Harl. 4196).</NOTE> gaf it trowage,</L>
<L>Als &thorn;e custom &thorn;an was and &thorn;e usage;</L>
<L>&THORN;at custom alle landes &thorn;an byhoved do,</L>
<L N="4056">Bot Saynt Paule says &thorn;us &thorn;arto:
<PB REF="00000155.tif" N="111"></L>
<L><I>Quoniam nisi venerit dissencio primum etc.,</I></L>
<L><I>id est, nisi prius dissenserint omnia regna</I></L>
<L><I>a Romano Imperio, que prius erant sub|</I></L>
<L N="4060"><I>dita, non antea veniet antichristus.</I></L>
<L>He says "bot if dissencion come,</L>
<L>&THORN;at es, bot-if alle landes hald agayn Rome,</L>
<L>Swa &thorn;at it be put til destruccion</L>
<L N="4064">Thurgh &thorn;am &thorn;at first was in subieccion,</L>
<L>Anticrist ar &thorn;at tyme sal noght com</L>
<L>&THORN;at sal com byfor &thorn;e day of dom.</L>
<L>&THORN;at destrucion, als says haly writt,</L>
<L N="4068">Sal be, bot &thorn;at tyme com noght yhitt.</L>
<L>Fra &thorn;at tyme sal na land ne contr&eacute;</L>
<L>In subieccion of Rome langer be;</L>
<L>Ne fra &thorn;an sal na man be bughsome,</L>
<L N="4072">Ne obedient to &thorn;e kirk of Rome.</L>
<L>Men sese &thorn;at &thorn;e empire, &thorn;at was swa myghty,</L>
<L>Es now destruyed a grete party;</L>
<L>Bot at &thorn;e last, als I sayd are,</L>
<L N="4076">It sal be destruyed wele mare,</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;e dignit&eacute; &thorn;at til it sal falle,</L>
<L>Sal noght in &thorn;at tyme perysshe alle.</L>
<L>It sal stand and duelle with-outen dout</L>
<L N="4080">In alle his regyons obout.</L>
<L>&THORN;os sal &thorn;e first taken bygyn at Rome;</L>
<L>For it es heved of al cristendome;</L>
<L>For when it es put til destrucion</L>
<L N="4084">Alle haly kyrk sal be put don.</L>
<L>Some clerkes says &thorn;at an sal come</L>
<L>&THORN;at sal hald &thorn;e empire of Rome</L>
<L>Alle halely and his croun bere</L>
<L N="4088">Wele, and in pees with-outen were.</L>
<L>He sal be last emparour &thorn;at &thorn;are sal be,</L>
<L>And mast of alle kynges of poust&eacute;;</L>
<L>&THORN;e whilk sal wele maynten his state</L>
<L N="4092">And &thorn;e empire, with-outen debate,</L>
<L>And it governe thurgh laghe and witte,</L>
<L>Als lang als he sal hald itte.
<PB REF="00000156.tif" N="112"></L>
<L>Bot afterwarde at &thorn;e last ende</L>
<L N="4096">Until Ierusalem he sal wende;</L>
<L>And on &thorn;e mount of Olyvette</L>
<L>He sal &thorn;e septre of Rome sette,</L>
<L>And his coron he sal lay don alswa,</L>
<L N="4100">And lef &thorn;am &thorn;ar and fra &thorn;am ga.</L>
<L>&THORN;us sal ende &thorn;e dignit&eacute; of Rome;</L>
<L>And als sone aftir sal anticrist come,</L>
<L>Als clerkes says, &thorn;at has understandyng</L>
<L N="4104">Of Daniel and of Saynt Paul saying;</L>
<L>&THORN;an sal anticrist &thorn;at tyme bygyn,</L>
<L>&THORN;at Saynt Paul calles &thorn;e man of syn.</L>
<L>For alle-if he be man, never-&thorn;e-les,</L>
<L N="4108">He sal be welle of alle wykkednes.</L>
<L>&THORN;e devels son he sal be cald;</L>
<L>Bot thurgh kynd men shuld him noght swa hald,</L>
<L>Bot thurgh his turnyng fra gode til ille;</L>
<L N="4112">For he sal &thorn;e devels wille fulfille.</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;e power of &thorn;e devel of helle</L>
<L>And alle his witte in hym sal duelle;</L>
<L>In wham al &thorn;e tresor of malice</L>
<L N="4116">Sal be hidde with alle maner of vice.</L>
<L>He sal til Criste contrarius be</L>
<L>And til alle his lyms &thorn;at he sal se;</L>
<L>And heghen hym thurgh pride, &thorn;at he sal halde,</L>
<L N="4120">Aboven al &thorn;at er paens goddes calde,</L>
<L>&THORN;at es to say, Iubiter and Mercury,</L>
<L>And Appolyn and Herculy;</L>
<L>And noght anly oboven &thorn;a goddes alle,</L>
<L N="4124">&THORN;at &thorn;e paens &thorn;air goddes sal calle,</L>
<L>Bot he sal heghe himself to be</L>
<L>Aboven &thorn;e haly trinit&eacute;;</L>
<L>And alle &thorn;e creatours, bath mare and les,</L>
<L N="4128">Shuld honoure over alle thyng &thorn;at es,</L>
<L>Ful synful sal be his bygynnyng,</L>
<L>And wonderful sal be his lyvyng.</L>
<L>And his endyng sal be sodayn;</L>
<L N="4132">For thurgh myght of God he[sal] be slayn,
<PB REF="00000157.tif" N="113"></L>
<L>In his tyme sal be swylk tribulacion</L>
<L>And swa mykel parsecucion,</L>
<L>&THORN;at unnethes any sal dur graunt</L>
<L N="4136">&THORN;at he es cristen, and God servant.</L>
<L>For mare parsecucion sal be &thorn;an,</L>
<L>&THORN;an ever was sythen &thorn;e world bygan.</L>
<L>Anticrist es, &thorn;os mykel at say,</L>
<L N="4140">Als he &thorn;at es ogayn Crist ay.</L>
<L>&THORN;an may ilk man be cald by skille</L>
<L>Anticrist &thorn;at dos ogayn Goddes wille.</L>
<L>&THORN;an may alle &thorn;as anticristes be calde,</L>
<L N="4144">&THORN;at ogaynes Goddes laghe will halde.</L>
<L>Bot ma[n]y swilk men may wele knawe</L>
<L>&THORN;at mykel dus ogayns Goddes lawe.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Be many skill we may some knawe</L>
<L>&THORN;at mekille dose agayne Goddes lawe. (MS. Harl. 6923.)</L>
</LG></NOTE></L>
<L>Bot anticrist, als says haly writ,</L>
<L N="4148">Sal com at &thorn;e last, &thorn;at com noght yhitt,</L>
<L>Als mast tyraunt with-outen pyt&eacute;,</L>
<L>&THORN;at ever was or ever sal be.</L>
<L>Wharfor I hald &thorn;ir gret mysdoers</L>
<L N="4152">Als anticrist lyms and his forgangers.</L>
<L>Now wha-swa wille a whyle duelle</L>
<L>Aparty here I wille hym telle</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e maner of anticrist bygynnyng,</L>
<L N="4156">And of his lif and of hys endyng.</L>
<L>He sal be geten, als clerkes shew can,</L>
<L>Bytwen a synful man and a woman,</L>
<L>And aftir &thorn;at he consayved sal be</L>
<L N="4160">&THORN;e fende sal entre, thurgh his poust&eacute;,</L>
<L>With-in his moder wambe sone;</L>
<L>&THORN;us, sais a grete clerke, sal be done</L>
<L>Thurgh was myght he sal be forth-broght;</L>
<L N="4164">And wonders thurgh hym sal be wroght.</L>
<L>He sal be cald &thorn;e child &thorn;at es lorn;</L>
<L>And in Corozaym he sal be born</L>
<L>Of a woman of &thorn;e kynred of San<NOTE PLACE="foot">Dane (MS. Harl. 6923) = of the tribe of Dan.</NOTE>;</L>
<L N="4168">Bot cristendome sal he have nan.
<PB REF="00000158.tif" N="114"></L>
<L>He sal be maliciouse and ful of envy,</L>
<L>Als of hym &thorn;us spekes &thorn;e prophecy:</L>
<L><I>Fiat Dan coluber in via, cerastes</I></L>
<L N="4172"><I>in semita, mordens ungulas equi,</I></L>
<L><I>ut cadat ascensor eius retro, Hoc est [Anticristus] sicut</I></L>
<L><I>serpens, in via sedebit, et in semita erit,</I></L>
<L><I>ut eos, qui per semitam iusticie ambu|</I></L>
<L N="4176"><I>lant, feriat et veneno sue malicie occidat.</I></L>
<L>"&THORN;e Dan" he says "sal &thorn;e nedder be</L>
<L>Sitand in &thorn;e way als men sal se;</L>
<L>And sal byte &thorn;e hors by &thorn;e hufe harde,</L>
<L N="4180">And mak &thorn;e upstegher fal bakwarde:</L>
<L>And &thorn;at es &thorn;us mykel at say,</L>
<L>Als<NOTE PLACE="foot">&THORN;at (Harl. 4196).</NOTE> anticrist, als nedder, sal sit in &thorn;e way,</L>
<L>And smyte &thorn;am alle, bathe mare and les,</L>
<L N="4184">&THORN;at walkes in &thorn;e way of rightwysnes,</L>
<L>And sla &thorn;am thurgh &thorn;e venym</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e malice &thorn;at sal cum of hym."</L>
<L>Yhit sal he be circumcid</L>
<L N="4188">And thurgh &thorn;at his malice a whyle sal hid.</L>
<L>Alswa til hym sal assygned be</L>
<L>A gude angelle, &thorn;at he sal noght se,</L>
<L>Aftir his birthe in his bygynnyng,</L>
<L N="4192">&THORN;at of him sal haf &thorn;e kepyng,</L>
<L>Bot for he agayn &thorn;e trouthe &thorn;at es,</L>
<L>Sal be hardend in wikkednes</L>
<L>His gude angelle sal fra hym wende,</L>
<L N="4196">And leve hym in &thorn;e kepyng of &thorn;e fende.</L>
<L>He sal be lered, als I understand,</L>
<L>And nurist and mast conversand</L>
<L>In &thorn;e cit&eacute; of Bethsayda;</L>
<L N="4200">In Capharnaum he sal regne alswa</L>
<L>&THORN;e whilk Bethsayda, and Capharnaum,</L>
<L>And Corozaym God weried whilom;</L>
<L>For God spak til &thorn;as thre cites &thorn;os,</L>
<L N="4204">Als &thorn;e godspelle here shewes us:
<PB REF="00000159.tif" N="115"></L>
<L><I>Ve tibi Corozayin! Ve tibi Bethsayda!</I></L>
<L><I>Ve tibi Capharnaum!</I></L>
<L>He says, "wa til &thorn;e Corozaym mot cum</L>
<L N="4208">And til &thorn;e Bethsayda and Capharnaum."</L>
<L>For &thorn;us in &thorn;e first he sal be born and bredde,</L>
<L>And in &thorn;e secunde be nuryst, and regne in &thorn;e thredde.</L>
<L>He sal gader fast til hym &thorn;an</L>
<L N="4212">Alle &thorn;at of &thorn;e devels crafte can,</L>
<L>Als negremanciens and tregettours,</L>
<L>Wiches and false enchauntours,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e devels crafte sal hym ken</L>
<L N="4216">Whar-thurgh he sal decayve &thorn;e men.</L>
<L>Afterwarde thurgh ledyng of &thorn;e fende</L>
<L>He sal even to Ierusalem wende;</L>
<L>And &thorn;ar sal he duelle in &thorn;at cit&eacute;</L>
<L N="4220">And in myddes &thorn;e temple make his se,</L>
<L>And say til alle &thorn;at &thorn;ar sal won,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he es Crist, Goddes son,</L>
<L>And mak &thorn;e folk hym to honour;</L>
<L N="4224">And sal say &thorn;at he es &thorn;air saveour.</L>
<L>He sal say &thorn;at na right cristen man</L>
<L>Was never byfor his tym bygan,</L>
<L>Bot fals anticristes he sal &thorn;am calle;</L>
<L N="4228">And say &thorn;ai lyved in fals trowthe alle</L>
<L>&THORN;at has bene fra &thorn;e worldes bygynnyng</L>
<L>Until &thorn;e tyme of his commyng.</L>
<L>He sal be lusty and lycherous,</L>
<L N="4232">And desayvabel and trecherous;</L>
<L>He sal hym feyn first als haly,</L>
<L>And shew &thorn;an appert ypocr[is]y,</L>
<L>To desayve cristen men and lele</L>
<L N="4236">Als says &thorn;e prophet Danielle:</L>
<L><I>In aperto tum per ypocrisym simulabit</I></L>
<L><I>sanctitatem, ut facilius decipere possit.</I></L>
<L>"First" he says "he sal apertely</L>
<L N="4240">Feyn halynes thurgh ypocrisy,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he mught lightlyer men bygile."</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;at time sal last bot a while,
<PB REF="00000160.tif" N="116"></L>
<L>He sal al kynges and princes til hym drawe</L>
<L N="4244">And turne &thorn;am alle til his lawe;</L>
<L>And thurgh &thorn;am &thorn;e poples sal turned be</L>
<L>Of ilka land and ilka cuntr&eacute;.</L>
<L>In alle stedes he sal walk and pas,</L>
<L N="4248">&THORN;ar Crist welk when he in erthe was.</L>
<L>In swylk a presumpcion he sal falle</L>
<L>&THORN;at he sal thynk hym loverd of alle.</L>
<L>Thurgh pride he sal ogayn God ryse</L>
<L N="4252">And hym sclaunder and his law dispise,</L>
<L>And afforce hym and be bysy,</L>
<L>His laghe to chaunge and fordo haly;</L>
<L>He sal turne al poples to his lawe,</L>
<L N="4256">And til him on four maners &thorn;am drawe.</L>
<L>A manere sal be, thurgh fals prechyng</L>
<L>Another thurgh fals miracles shewyng,</L>
<L>&THORN;e thred thurgh large gyftes to gyfe,</L>
<L N="4260">And &thorn;e ferthe thurgh drede of turmentis griefe.</L>
<L>Thurgh fals prechyng in ilk cuntr&eacute;</L>
<L>Many til hym sal turned be.</L>
<L>For he sal send thurgh alle &thorn;e world wyde</L>
<L N="4264">His prechours to preche on ilka side,</L>
<L>&THORN;e qwilk sal preche undir fals colour,</L>
<L>And say Cristes lawe es not bot errour;</L>
<L>And anticristes lawe &thorn;ai sal comend</L>
<L N="4268">And agayn suthfastnes it defend,</L>
<L>And forbede ilk man &thorn;at &thorn;ai noght halde</L>
<L>&THORN;e new lawe, &thorn;at es Cristes lawe calde,</L>
<L>And his ministres sal swa lette yhit</L>
<L N="4272">&THORN;at na man sal expound haly writ,</L>
<L>&THORN;at es to say, to right undirstandyng.</L>
<L>For &thorn;ai sal say it es bot lesyng,</L>
<L>And make &thorn;e pople to trow haly</L>
<L N="4276">&THORN;at &thorn;ai sal noght be saved &thorn;arby.</L>
<L>&THORN;us sal &thorn;ai bring &thorn;e folk in errour</L>
<L>Thurgh &thorn;air prechyng with false colour,</L>
<L>Swa his lawes sal pas and his powere</L>
<L N="4280">Fra &thorn;e est syde til &thorn;e west, thurgh &thorn;e world here;
<PB REF="00000161.tif" N="117"></L>
<L>And fra &thorn;e southe til &thorn;e north, alswa</L>
<L>His lawes and his power sal ga.</L>
<L>He sal turne men on another manere</L>
<L N="4284">Thurgh fals miracles and wonders sere;</L>
<L>For he sal &thorn;an shew wonders many</L>
<L>Thurgh enchauntementes and nygroma[n]cy.</L>
<L>Swa gretely, &thorn;at &thorn;e pople sal se,</L>
<L N="4288">And &thorn;at thurgh myght of &thorn;e devel sal be,</L>
<L>Of whilk wondirs I sal tel yhou sum,</L>
<L>He sal do fire fra &thorn;e heven don com,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at sal be noght bot an ille spirit,</L>
<L N="4292">&THORN;at out of &thorn;e ayre sal com doun tite,</L>
<L>And omang his disciples don light,</L>
<L>And with sere tunges til &thorn;am spek ryght,</L>
<L>Als dyd til &thorn;e apostels &thorn;e haly gast</L>
<L N="4296">And &thorn;at sal be in mens sight mast,</L>
<L>For &thorn;a &thorn;at his disciples sal be cald</L>
<L>Sal &thorn;am avant, and &thorn;am self hald</L>
<L>Better of lif and to God mare dere,</L>
<L N="4300">&THORN;an ever war Cristes appostels here.</L>
<L>Alswa thurgh &thorn;e devels crafte and myght,</L>
<L>He sal feyn him ded til mens syght,</L>
<L>And on &thorn;e thred day thurgh &thorn;e devels rede</L>
<L N="4304">He sal feyn hym to ryse fra dede,</L>
<L>And devels aftir sal bere hym up even</L>
<L>In-til &thorn;e ayre als he suld stey to heven;</L>
<L>And als he byfor sal be sene,</L>
<L N="4308">Als he fra dede rase, men sal wene</L>
<L>&THORN;at he es til heven ravyst,</L>
<L>And trow &thorn;an &thorn;at he es verray crist.</L>
<L>&THORN;us sal anticrist &thorn;an countrefette</L>
<L N="4312">&THORN;e wondirs of God in erthe swa grete;</L>
<L>Ma wondirs yhit wirk sal he</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e pople sal openly se.</L>
<L>He sal do trese growe and florisshe fayre</L>
<L N="4316">And chace &thorn;e wyndes about and &thorn;e ayre.</L>
<L>Fra heven he sal do falle rayne-shours</L>
<L>And mak waters to ryn ogayn &thorn;air cours.
<PB REF="00000162.tif" N="118"></L>
<L>He sal trobel &thorn;e se when he wille,</L>
<L N="4320">And pees it and make it be stille.</L>
<L>He sal chaung on wonder manere</L>
<L>Divers kyndes in figures sere.</L>
<L>He sal do dede ymages and dome</L>
<L N="4324">Speke of thynges &thorn;at er to come.</L>
<L>He sal alswa dede men uprays,</L>
<L>&THORN;at sal gang obout, als &thorn;e boke says,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at sal be thurgh &thorn;e devels quayntis,</L>
<L N="4328">For devels sal entre in-til &thorn;e dede bodys</L>
<L>And bere &thorn;a dede bodys obout,</L>
<L>Swa &thorn;at parfit men sal be in dout</L>
<L>Whether he es verray crist or noght,</L>
<L N="4332">And &thorn;us sal men be in errour broght.</L>
<L>On &thorn;e thred maner he sal bygille</L>
<L>Many thurgh gyftes within short whyle,</L>
<L>And turne &thorn;am til a fals belyefe</L>
<L N="4336">Thurgh large gyftes &thorn;at he &thorn;am sal gyfe.</L>
<L>For he sal fynde alle &thorn;e tresour</L>
<L>&THORN;at es, or was ever hidde byfor</L>
<L>Under erthe, or ourwar elles</L>
<L N="4340">&THORN;at may noght be gesced; for sum telles</L>
<L>&THORN;at mar tresor under erthe es hidde</L>
<L>&THORN;an oboven es knawen or kydde;</L>
<L>Of whilk he sal &thorn;am alle ryche make,</L>
<L N="4344">&THORN;at &thorn;e lawe of Criste here wille forsake.</L>
<L>&THORN;os sal he shew men welth worldly</L>
<L>For to desayve &thorn;am &thorn;an &thorn;arby.</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e ferthe maner aftir &thorn;an</L>
<L N="4348">He sal turne til hym many a man;</L>
<L>And do &thorn;am haly folowe his trace</L>
<L>Thu[r]gh grete tourmentes and manace,</L>
<L>And thurgh drede of dede &thorn;at mast may grefe,</L>
<L N="4352">For elles he sal noght thole &thorn;am lyefe.</L>
<L>Ful grete tribulacions he sal &thorn;am shewe,</L>
<L>Als Godin &thorn;e godspelle sayis thurgh Mathewe:</L>
<L><I>Tanta erit tribulacio, ut in errorem</I></L>
<L N="4356"><I>inducantur, si fieri potest, eciam electi.</I>
<PB REF="00000163.tif" N="119"></L>
<L>He says "mikel tribulacion</L>
<L>Sal be &thorn;an til ilka nacion,"</L>
<L>Thurgh out &thorn;e world, ferre and nere,</L>
<L N="4360">"&THORN;at &thorn;as &thorn;at God has chosen here</L>
<L>Suld be broght in error sone</L>
<L>If God wild suffre &thorn;at it warre done."</L>
<L>Bot in &thorn;e appocalipse apparty</L>
<L N="4364">Es sayd &thorn;us ful mistyly,</L>
<L><I>Pedes eius sunt simules auricalco,</I></L>
<L><I>sicut in camino ardente.</I></L>
<L>He says "his fete er like latoun bright</L>
<L N="4368">Als in a chymn&eacute; brynnand light."</L>
<L>And &thorn;is was &thorn;at Iohan saw in a vision</L>
<L>Of hym &thorn;at semed &thorn;e virgyn son.</L>
<L>By his fete &thorn;at als latoun was semand</L>
<L N="4372">Crist last lyms men may undirstand,</L>
<L>&THORN;e whilk sal be parfite men in charit&eacute;</L>
<L>&THORN;at agayne &thorn;e worldes ende martird sal be,</L>
<L>&THORN;at es to say, in tym of Anticrist,</L>
<L N="4376">Thurgh wham many saules sal be perist.</L>
<L>&THORN;e chimn&eacute;, brinand with &thorn;e het,</L>
<L>Bytakens &thorn;e tribulacion gret.</L>
<L>&THORN;at sal be when anticrist sal come,</L>
<L N="4380">Thurgh wham many sal thole grete marterdome.</L>
<L>Anticrist sal be &thorn;e mast tyraunt</L>
<L>&THORN;at ever was; for he sal haunt</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;e maners of turmentes kene</L>
<L N="4384">In whilk any martirs byfor has bene;</L>
<L>For on sere maners he sal &thorn;am turment</L>
<L>&THORN;at wille noght til his law assent;</L>
<L>And put alle &thorn;a to &thorn;e dede at &thorn;e last</L>
<L N="4388">&THORN;at ay duels in &thorn;e trouthe stedfast.</L>
<L>Bot alle cristen men in &thorn;at cuntr&eacute;</L>
<L>&THORN;ar Crist welk, mast tourmented sal be.</L>
<L>And Haymo says, &thorn;at a grete clerk was,</L>
<L N="4392">Hys tyrauntry thurgh &thorn;e world sal pas.</L>
<L>&THORN;e devels &thorn;at er now bunden swa,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ai may noght about flegh ne ga,
<PB REF="00000164.tif" N="120"></L>
<L>Ne nuye als mykel als &thorn;ai walde,</L>
<L N="4396">Sal &thorn;an be louse and nathyng &thorn;am halde.</L>
<L>&THORN;at tyme sal preche na cresten man,</L>
<L>For &thorn;ai sal be halden als cursed &thorn;an;</L>
<L>Ne nan sal bye with &thorn;am ne selle,</L>
<L N="4400">Ne felaghshepe hald with &thorn;am ne duelle,</L>
<L>Bot with &thorn;as &thorn;at had Criste forsaken</L>
<L>And &thorn;e merk of anticrist had taken,</L>
<L>&THORN;at men mught knawe and understand</L>
<L N="4404">&THORN;at &thorn;ai til anticrist war assentand.</L>
<L>For al &thorn;as men sal bere his merk,</L>
<L>&THORN;at sal forsake to wirk Cristes werk,</L>
<L>And sal folowe anticristes lawe,</L>
<L N="4408">By his merk men sal &thorn;am knawe,</L>
<L>&THORN;e whilk &thorn;ai sal ber, als I understande,</L>
<L>Outher in &thorn;e frount or in &thorn;e ryght hande.</L>
<L>Bot other &thorn;at wille noght do his rede</L>
<L N="4412">Sal be done to vilans dede.</L>
<L>On &thorn;is four maners, als I haf shewed,</L>
<L>He sal drawe til hym bathe lered and lewed,</L>
<L>And crysten law sal be doun layde,</L>
<L N="4416">&THORN;arfor &thorn;us in appocalips es sayde:</L>
<L><I>Cauda eius tertiam partem stellarum</I></L>
<L><I>celi trahebat, et misit eas in terra.</I></L>
<L>He says, "with his tayle he droghe don even</L>
<L N="4420">&THORN;e thred part of &thorn;e sternes of heven,</L>
<L>And into &thorn;e erthe sent &thorn;am ryght,"</L>
<L>&THORN;ar &thorn;ai mught noght shyne ne gyf lyght.</L>
<L>&THORN;is was &thorn;e taille of &thorn;e dragon</L>
<L N="4424">&THORN;at Saynt Johan saw in a vision.</L>
<L>&THORN;e dragon es understanden &thorn;e fende</L>
<L>And his taille anticrist &thorn;at folowed at &thorn;e ende</L>
<L>And &thorn;e thred part of &thorn;e sternes bright</L>
<L N="4428">Er cristen men undirstanden right,</L>
<L>&THORN;e whilk he sal fra right trowthe draw,</L>
<L>And do &thorn;am in erthe to hald his law.</L>
<L>&THORN;e men of &thorn;e worlde &thorn;at er covaytous</L>
<L N="4432">He sal turne thurgh gyftes precious,
<PB REF="00000165.tif" N="121"></L>
<L>For he sal gyf &thorn;am, &thorn;at turned wil be,</L>
<L>Of gold and silver grete plent&eacute;.</L>
<L>Alswa men of symple connyng</L>
<L N="4436">He sal turne thurgh miracles and prechyng.</L>
<L>Gude men, &thorn;at haldes Goddes commandmentes,</L>
<L>He sal turne thurgh manace and turmentes.</L>
<L>Many &thorn;at semes gude and rightwyse</L>
<L N="4440">Saltrow in hym, and Crystes trouth despyse.</L>
<L>First sal anticrist com in myldnes</L>
<L>And prech ogayn &thorn;e right trouth &thorn;at es,</L>
<L>And myracles sal thurgh hym be done;</L>
<L N="4444">&THORN;an sal &thorn;e Iewes resayve hym sone</L>
<L>And be turned til hym al haly.</L>
<L>And &thorn;at tyme sal com Ennoc and Ely</L>
<L>Ogayn anticrist to preche ful harde,</L>
<L N="4448">Als yhe may se and here afterwarde.</L>
<L>&THORN;an sal anticrist bygyn felly</L>
<L>To pursue men thurgh tyrauntry,</L>
<L>Gret parsecucion &thorn;an sal he wyrk</L>
<L N="4452">Agayn cristen men and haly kirk,</L>
<L>&THORN;an sal he destroye cristen lawe,</L>
<L>And Gog and Magog til hym drawe,</L>
<L>&THORN;e whilk er halden, als men telles,</L>
<L N="4456">&THORN;e werst folk &thorn;at in &thorn;e world duels.</L>
<L>Som says &thorn;at &thorn;ai er closed haly</L>
<L>By-yhonde &thorn;e mountes of Caspy;</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;ai er noght swa closed obout</L>
<L N="4460">&THORN;at &thorn;ai ne mught lightly com out,</L>
<L>Yif a qwene ne war, &thorn;at haldes &thorn;am in,</L>
<L>Thurgh stre[n]gthe, &thorn;at &thorn;ai may noght out wyn,</L>
<L>&THORN;at es cald &thorn;e qwene of Amazons,</L>
<L N="4464">Under whas powere &thorn;at folk wons,</L>
<L>Bot at &thorn;e last &thorn;ai sal breke out</L>
<L>And destroy many landes obout.</L>
<L>For &thorn;e Iewes has swylk a prophecy</L>
<L N="4468">And says &thorn;us omang &thorn;am commonly,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;is folk ogayne &thorn;e worldes ende</L>
<L>Sal com out, and til Ierusalem wende
<PB REF="00000166.tif" N="122"></L>
<L>With &thorn;air crist, &thorn;at wonders sal wirke,</L>
<L N="4472">And &thorn;an sal &thorn;ai distroie haly kyrke.</L>
<L>Some clerkes says, als &thorn;e glose telles,</L>
<L>&THORN;at Gog and Magog es noght elles</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;e host of onticrist [&thorn;at] sal come</L>
<L N="4476">Sodanly ogayn &thorn;e day of dome,</L>
<L>And ogayne haly kyrk werray</L>
<L>For to distroye it if &thorn;ai may.</L>
<L>&THORN;e glose of &thorn;e buke says alswa</L>
<L N="4480">&THORN;at by Gog er understanden alle &thorn;a</L>
<L>Thurgh whilk &thorn;e devel, our mast enemy,</L>
<L>Sal cristen men pursue prively.</L>
<L>By Magog may &thorn;as understanden be</L>
<L N="4484">Thurgh wham openly pursue sal he,</L>
<L>Or &thorn;as er understanden &thorn;ar-by,</L>
<L>&THORN;at in anticrist tyme first pryvely</L>
<L>And aftirward openly, sal wyrk</L>
<L N="4488">Wykkedness ogayne haly kyrk.</L>
<L>Gog es als mykel at say, als covert,</L>
<L>And Magog es noght elles bot als apert.</L>
<L>&THORN;ir twa prophetes, als says som,</L>
<L N="4492">Ennok and Hely byfor sal com,</L>
<L>Bytwene &thorn;e tyme of &thorn;e commyng priv&eacute;</L>
<L>Of anticrist, when he sal born be,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e tyme of his oppen commyng,</L>
<L N="4496">&THORN;at sal be thurgh open prechyng</L>
<L>And thurgh open parsecucion,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he sal do til diverse nacion.</L>
<L>Bytwen &thorn;a tymes &thorn;a prophetes twa</L>
<L N="4500">On sere partes sal preche swa,</L>
<L>&THORN;at thurgh &thorn;air prechyng &thorn;ai sal drawe</L>
<L>And convert &thorn;e Iewes til cristen lawe,</L>
<L>For &thorn;us spekes &thorn;e prophete Malachy,</L>
<L N="4504">In a boke of &thorn;e prophecy:</L>
<L><I>Convertent corda patrum</I></L>
<L><I>in filios.</I></L>
<L>He says "&thorn;ai sal turne thurgh Goddes myght</L>
<L N="4508">&THORN;e fadirs hertes intil &thorn;e sons right."
<PB REF="00000167.tif" N="123"></L>
<L>&THORN;at es, &thorn;ai sal turne &thorn;e Iewery</L>
<L>Until right cristendom halely.</L>
<L>&THORN;an sal Iewes &thorn;e sam lawe halde,</L>
<L N="4512">&THORN;at &thorn;ai haf, &thorn;at er cristen men calde</L>
<L>And als cristen men dus swa sal &thorn;ai do,</L>
<L>Als &thorn;e glose says &thorn;at acordes &thorn;ar-to:</L>
<L><I>Percipient fidem quam</I></L>
<L N="4516"><I>ipsi habuerunt.</I></L>
<L>"&THORN;e Iewes sal tak &thorn;an with hert glade</L>
<L>&THORN;e trouth &thorn;at cristen men byfor hadde."</L>
<L>Wharfor &thorn;e Iewes and cristen men,</L>
<L N="4520">Als &thorn;a twa prophetes sal &thorn;am ken,</L>
<L>Sal &thorn;an thurgh even entencion</L>
<L>Assent in Crist als a religion.</L>
<L>&THORN;ai sal preche als &thorn;e appocalips says,</L>
<L N="4524">A thousand and twa hundreth days</L>
<L>And sexti, als men sal se and here.</L>
<L>And als &thorn;e glose says; &thorn;at es, thre yhere,</L>
<L>Als Crist him-self did &thorn;at voched safe</L>
<L N="4528">To preche &thorn;e sam law &thorn;at we hafe.</L>
<L>&THORN;ai sal be als &thorn;e appocalips spekes,</L>
<L>In harde hayres clende<NOTE PLACE="foot">Cled (MS. Harl. 4196).</NOTE> and in sekkes;</L>
<L>&THORN;at es &thorn;ai sal &thorn;an penance preche</L>
<L N="4532">And thurgh ensaumple of penance teche,</L>
<L>Bot als tite als anticrist sal knawe</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ai turne Iewes til cristen lawe</L>
<L>Thurgh ensaumple &thorn;at &thorn;ai shew, and sarmon<NOTE PLACE="foot">Thurgh &thorn;air ensample and &thorn;air sermone (MS. Harl. 6923).</NOTE>,</L>
<L N="4536">&THORN;an sal he shew grete parsecucion</L>
<L>And grevusly &thorn;am tourment,</L>
<L>&THORN;at til his law wille noght assent,</L>
<L>And do &thorn;am to hard dede at &thorn;e last,</L>
<L N="4540">Yf &thorn;ai in &thorn;e trouthe be stedfast.</L>
<L>Anticrist sal be &thorn;an ful wrathe,</L>
<L>He sal do tak &thorn;a prophetes bathe</L>
<L>And in Ierusalem, thurgh &thorn;e devels rede,</L>
<L N="4544">Hastyly do &thorn;am bathe to dede.
<PB REF="00000168.tif" N="124"></L>
<L>&THORN;an sal &thorn;air bodys, als &thorn;e buke says,</L>
<L>In &thorn;e stretes ligg stille thre days</L>
<L>And an half, oboven erthe namly,</L>
<L N="4548">For na man sal &thorn;am dur biry,</L>
<L>For drede &thorn;at &thorn;ai sal haf &thorn;an</L>
<L>Of anticrist, &thorn;at wikked man.</L>
<L>&THORN;air enemys when &thorn;ai er slayn</L>
<L N="4552">Of &thorn;air dede &thorn;ai sal be fayn.</L>
<L>When &thorn;ai haf liggen dede on &thorn;is wyse</L>
<L>Thre days and an half, &thorn;ai sal ryse,</L>
<L>And &thorn;an &thorn;air enmys a voce sal here</L>
<L N="4556">Until &thorn;am spek, on &thorn;is manere:</L>
<L>'Ely and Ennok steyes up bathe,</L>
<L>For yhe er passed al maner of wathe.'</L>
<L>And als tyte, when &thorn;ai haf herd &thorn;is steven,</L>
<L N="4560">In a cloude &thorn;ai sal stey up til heven,</L>
<L>&THORN;at alle &thorn;e pople &thorn;an sal se.</L>
<L>A grete wondre tyl &thorn;am &thorn;at sal be.</L>
<L>Aftir &thorn;air dede, als &thorn;e buke says,</L>
<L N="4564">Anticrist sal regne, yhit fiften days,</L>
<L>&THORN;an sal he turne alle til hym haly</L>
<L>&THORN;at war turned til Ennok and Hely;</L>
<L>And alle, &thorn;at til hym wille noght trow &thorn;an,</L>
<L N="4568">Sal &thorn;an be don til &thorn;e dede, ilk man.</L>
<L>Anticrist, in his grete tyrantry,</L>
<L>Sal regne thre yhere and an half fully;</L>
<L>&THORN;an sal God abrege his days,</L>
<L N="4572">Als Mathew in &thorn;e Godspel says:</L>
<L><I>Nisi breviati finissent dies, non</I></L>
<L><I>erit salva omnis caro.</I></L>
<L>"Bot his days war abreged," says he,</L>
<L N="4576">"Fone men fra &thorn;an sal save be."</L>
<L>Bot his tyme God abrege sal &thorn;an.</L>
<L>Til &thorn;is, says Saynt Gregore &thorn;e haly man</L>
<L><I>Quia nos infirmos aspicit deus, dies</I></L>
<L N="4580"><I>malos quos singulariter intulit, misericorditer breviabit.</I></L>
<L>He says "for-&thorn;i, &thorn;at God sese right</L>
<L>&THORN;at we er freyle and feble of myght,
<PB REF="00000169.tif" N="125"></L>
<L>&THORN;e days &thorn;at er ille and hevy,</L>
<L N="4584">&THORN;at er putted til sere men singulerly,<NOTE PLACE="foot">singulary (MS. Harl. 4196).</NOTE></L>
<L>Yhit, at &thorn;e last, abrege sal he,</L>
<L>Thurgh his gudenes and his pyt&eacute;."</L>
<L>Anticrist sal be with-outen pere,</L>
<L N="4588">And he sal lyf twa and thretty yhere</L>
<L>And an half, als som clerkes says &thorn;ai se;</L>
<L>Of swa many yhere his eld sal be</L>
<L>Fra &thorn;e tyme of his first bygynnyng,</L>
<L N="4592">Until &thorn;e tyme of his last endyng.</L>
<L>For sum says he sal lyf als many yhere</L>
<L>Als Crist lifed, in manskynd here,</L>
<L>And when he has &thorn;us lang lyfed,</L>
<L N="4596">&THORN;an sal na ma thurgh him by<NOTE PLACE="foot">be?</NOTE> greved.</L>
<L>He sal &thorn;an son fele Goddes vengeance</L>
<L>And with-outen any repentance,</L>
<L>He sal be slayn, ful sodanly,</L>
<L N="4600">Thurgh &thorn;e myght of God almyghty,</L>
<L>Opon &thorn;e mounte of Olyvett,</L>
<L>In &thorn;e stede whar Crist his fete sett,</L>
<L>When he stey up til heven bright,</L>
<L N="4604">And swa sal he ende thurgh Goddes might.</L>
<L>Som clerkes yhit says alswa,</L>
<L>&THORN;at Saynt Michael sal hym sla,</L>
<L>Thurgh Goddes byddyng in &thorn;e same stede,</L>
<L N="4608">In &thorn;e whilk he sal be funden dede.</L>
<L>And &thorn;e boke says, alswa, &thorn;at he,</L>
<L>Thurgh &thorn;e gast of Goddes mouthe slayn sal be.</L>
<L>Bot how swa it be &thorn;is es certayn,</L>
<L N="4612">Thurgh Goddes myght &thorn;ar sal he be slayn.</L>
<L>Anticrist mynisters, when he es dede,</L>
<L>Sal mak ioy &thorn;an in ilka stede,</L>
<L>And haf &thorn;air delices nyght and day,</L>
<L N="4616">And wedden wyfes, and &thorn;us say:</L>
<L>'Alle-if our prince be dede &thorn;us</L>
<L>We haf pees and welthe plenteuus,'</L>
<L>And right als &thorn;ai sal say &thorn;us alle</L>
<L N="4620">Sodanly ded &thorn;ai sal doun falle,
<PB REF="00000170.tif" N="126"></L>
<L>Thurgh &thorn;e myght of God almyghty,</L>
<L>&THORN;us sal &thorn;ai enden sodanly.</L>
<L>Bot yhit when &thorn;ai alle er &thorn;us fordone,</L>
<L N="4624">&THORN;e grete dome sal noght be aftir alsone.</L>
<L>For &thorn;e glose of Danyel &thorn;us says:</L>
<L>"God sal graunt fyve and fourty days</L>
<L>Til alle &thorn;as &thorn;at desayved sal be,</L>
<L N="4628">Thurgh anticrist and his meyn&eacute;,"</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ai may amende &thorn;am of &thorn;air syn,</L>
<L>And do penance, ar &thorn;e dome bygyn."</L>
<L>&THORN;e Iewes sal &thorn;an al turned be</L>
<L N="4632">Til &thorn;at right trouthe, &thorn;e whilk haf we</L>
<L>&THORN;an sal God fulfille in &thorn;e last days,</L>
<L>&THORN;is worde &thorn;at he in &thorn;e godspel says,</L>
<L><I>Et fiet unum ovile</I></L>
<L N="4636"><I>et unus pastor.</I></L>
<L>He sais "alle folkes to fald sal falle,</L>
<L>And a hirde sal be to kepe &thorn;am alle."</L>
<L>&THORN;at folk Iewes and cristen men sal be talde</L>
<L N="4640">Under a trouthe in haly kirkes falde;</L>
<L>Fra &thorn;at tyme forthe sal hali kirke be</L>
<L>In pees and rest with-outen adversit&eacute;.</L>
<L>For &thorn;an sal faile alle power of &thorn;e fende,</L>
<L N="4644">Fra &thorn;at tyme unto &thorn;e worldes ende,</L>
<L>Swa &thorn;at he sal nother tempte ne gryefe</L>
<L>Haly kirk, ne man &thorn;at &thorn;an sal lyefe.</L>
<L>Bot how mikel space sal be fra &thorn;an</L>
<L N="4648">Til &thorn;e day of dome, wate na man;</L>
<L>For of al &thorn;e prophetes, &thorn;at men may neven,</L>
<L>And alle &thorn;e halghes, and angels in heven,</L>
<L>Mught never nane witt &thorn;at privit&eacute;,</L>
<L N="4652">What tyme &thorn;e day of dome sal be;</L>
<L>For God wille &thorn;at nane it byfor wytte,</L>
<L>Bot him-self &thorn;at has ordaynt itte;</L>
<L>&THORN;arfor Crist til his disciples sayde &thorn;us,</L>
<L N="4656">Als &thorn;e boke of apostels werkes shewes us:</L>
<L><I>Non est vestrum nosse tempora vel momenta</I></L>
<L><I>que pater possuit in sua potestate.</I>
<PB REF="00000171.tif" N="127"></L>
<L>"It falles noght yhow knaw &thorn;e time priv&eacute;</L>
<L N="4660">&THORN;at &thorn;e fadir has sette in his awen poust&eacute;,"</L>
<L>&THORN;arfor na man suld aske, ne say</L>
<L>How mykel we hafe til domes day;</L>
<L>Ne we suld noght yherne it to lere,</L>
<L N="4664">Ne witte wether it be ferre or nere.</L>
<L>Bot we suld mak us redy alle,</L>
<L>Als &thorn;e day of dome to morn suld falle,</L>
<L>And thynk ay on &thorn;at drede-ful dome,</L>
<L N="4668">Als &thorn;e haly man dyd, Saynt Ierome.</L>
<L>&THORN;at ay &thorn;ar-on thoght, bathe nyght and days,</L>
<L>And &thorn;arfor &thorn;us in a boke he says:</L>
<L><I>Sine comedam, sine bibam, sine aliquid</I></L>
<L N="4672"><I>aliud faciam, semper michi videtur illa</I></L>
<L><I>tuba resonare in auribus meis, 'sur|</I></L>
<L><I>gite mortui, venite ad iudicium.'</I></L>
<L>He says "whether I ette or I drynk,</L>
<L N="4676">Or oght elles do, ay me thynk</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e beme &thorn;at blaw sal on domsday,</L>
<L>Sounes in myn eres, &thorn;at &thorn;us says ay:</L>
<L>'Ryse yhe &thorn;at er dede, and come</L>
<L N="4680">Un-to &thorn;e grete dredful dome'."</L>
<L>Now haf yhe herd of &thorn;e bygynnyng</L>
<L>Of anticrist, and of his lif and his endyng,</L>
<L>&THORN;at men may a werray<NOTE PLACE="foot">verray.</NOTE> taken calle,</L>
<L N="4684">&THORN;at agayne &thorn;e day of dome sal falle.</L>
<L>Many ma takens yhit men sal se,</L>
<L>Byfor ar &thorn;at dreful day sal be,</L>
<L>Bathe in erthe and yhit in heven,</L>
<L N="4688">Als we here Crist in &thorn;e gospelle neven,</L>
<L>Whare he spekes of takens sere</L>
<L>&THORN;at sal falle, And says on &thorn;is manere:</L>
<L><I>Erunt signa in sole, et luna, et stellis;</I></L>
<L N="4692"><I>et in terris pressura gencium pre confusi|</I></L>
<L><I>ione sonitus maris et fluctuum, arescen|</I></L>
<L><I>tibus hominibus pre timore et expectacione, que</I></L>
<L><I>supervenient universo orbi. Nam virtutes</I>
<PB REF="00000172.tif" N="128"></L>
<L N="4696"><I>celorum movebuntur, Et tunc videbunt</I></L>
<L><I>filium hominis venientem in nubibus,</I></L>
<L><I>cum potestate magna et maiestate &amp;c.</I></L>
<L>&THORN;ir er &thorn;e wordes of &thorn;e gospelle,</L>
<L N="4700">&THORN;at Crist til his disciples gun telle.</L>
<L>He says &thorn;us als he ordaynd be done:</L>
<L>"Takens sal be in &thorn;e son and in &thorn;e mone,</L>
<L>And in &thorn;e sternes &thorn;at in heven men may ken,</L>
<L N="4704">And in erthe sal be grete thrang of men,</L>
<L>For &thorn;e mengyng of &thorn;e noys of &thorn;e se</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e flodes, &thorn;at &thorn;an sal be;</L>
<L>And men sal wax dry in &thorn;at dyn</L>
<L N="4708">For drede and for lang bydyng &thorn;ar-in,</L>
<L>&THORN;at til al &thorn;e world sal com" says he,</L>
<L>For &thorn;e myghtes of heven sal &thorn;an styrd be,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ai sal se &thorn;e son of man</L>
<L N="4712">Comand doun in cloudes &thorn;an,</L>
<L>With his grete myght and magest&eacute;,"</L>
<L>And &thorn;at tyme sal &thorn;e grete dome be.</L>
<L>&THORN;ir takens er tald aftir &thorn;e lettre here,</L>
<L N="4716">Bot &thorn;e exposicion may be on othir manere.</L>
<L>Alswa God, &thorn;at alle thynges knawes wele,</L>
<L>He says &thorn;us thurgh &thorn;e prophete Ioele:</L>
<L><I>Et dabo prodigia in celo sursum, et signa</I></L>
<L N="4720"><I>in terra deorsum, sanguinem et ignem et</I></L>
<L><I>vaporem fumi; sol convertetur in tenebras et lu|</I></L>
<L><I>na in sanguinem, antequam veniat dies domini</I></L>
<L><I>magnus et manifestus.</I></L>
<L N="4724">He says "I sal gyfe wonders sere</L>
<L>Up in heven, als men sal here;</L>
<L>And takens doun in erthe ere-on to luke,</L>
<L>&THORN;at es blode and fire and brethe of smoke;</L>
<L N="4728">&THORN;e son sal be turned in-til mirknes,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e mone in-til blode, and be lyghtles,</L>
<L>Byfor or &thorn;e day of our lord sal falle,</L>
<L>&THORN;at sal be grete and openly shewed til alle.</L>
<L N="4732">&THORN;at grete day is &thorn;e grete day of dome,</L>
<L>Agayn whilk alle &thorn;ir takens sal come;
<PB REF="00000173.tif" N="129"></L>
<L>&THORN;an may men by swilk takens wytte</L>
<L>&THORN;at it es &thorn;e mast day &thorn;at ever was yhitte,</L>
<L N="4736">And &thorn;e straytest and &thorn;e mast harde,</L>
<L>Als men may se and here aftirwarde.</L>
<L>Yhit spekes &thorn;e haly man Saynt Ierome</L>
<L>Of fiften takens &thorn;at sal come</L>
<L N="4740">Byfor Cristes commyng, als he says,</L>
<L>&THORN;e whilk sal falle in XV days;</L>
<L>Bot whether any other days sal falle</L>
<L>Bytwen &thorn;a days, or &thorn;ai sal alle</L>
<L N="4744">Continuely falle, day aftir day,</L>
<L>Saynt Ierom says, he can noght say;</L>
<L>And yhit for certayn approves noght he</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;a fiften days of takens sal be,</L>
<L N="4748">Bot he reherces &thorn;a takens fiftene</L>
<L>Als he &thorn;am fand, and writen had sene</L>
<L>In som bokes of &thorn;e Ebriens,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;a XV days contens.</L>
<L N="4752">Bot Saynt Ierome shewes noght ne telles,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he &thorn;am fand writen ourwhar elles,</L>
<L>Bot in &thorn;e Hebriens bokes he &thorn;am fande</L>
<L>And reherces &thorn;am, als he saw &thorn;am stande,</L>
<L N="4756">Ilka day aftir other even,</L>
<L>Als yhe may here me now neven.</L>
<L>&THORN;e first day of &thorn;as fiften days,</L>
<L>&THORN;e se sal ryse, als &thorn;e bukes says,</L>
<L N="4760">Abowen &thorn;e heght of ilka mountayne,</L>
<L>Fully fourty cubyttes certayne,</L>
<L>And in his stede even upstande,</L>
<L>Als an heghe hille dus on &thorn;e lande.</L>
<L N="4764">&THORN;e secunde day, &thorn;e se sal be swa law</L>
<L>&THORN;at unnethes men sal it knaw.</L>
<L>&THORN;e thred day, &thorn;e se sal seme playn</L>
<L>And stand even in his cours agay[n],</L>
<L N="4768">Als it stode first at &thorn;e bygynnyng,</L>
<L>With-outen mare rysyng or fallyng.</L>
<L>&THORN;e fierth day, sal swilk a wonder be,</L>
<L>&THORN;e mast wondreful fisshes of &thorn;e se
<PB REF="00000174.tif" N="130"></L>
<L N="4772">Sal com to-gyder and mak swilk romyng<NOTE PLACE="foot">roryng (MS Lands. 348).</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;at it sal be hydus til mans heryng.</L>
<L>Bot what &thorn;at romiyng<NOTE PLACE="foot">roryng (MS Lands. 348).</NOTE> sal signify,</L>
<L>Na man may whit, bot God almyghty.</L>
<L N="4776">&THORN;e fift day, &thorn;e se sal brynne</L>
<L>And alle watters als &thorn;ai sal rynne;</L>
<L>And &thorn;at sal last fra &thorn;e son rysyng</L>
<L>Til &thorn;e tyme of &thorn;e son doun gangyng.</L>
<L N="4780">&THORN;e sext day, sal spryng a blody dewe</L>
<L>On grisse and tres, als it sal shewe.</L>
<L>&THORN;e sevend day byggyns doun sal falle</L>
<L>And grete castels, and tours with-alle.</L>
<L N="4784">&THORN;e eght day, hard roches and stanes</L>
<L>Sal strik togyder, alle attanes.</L>
<L>An ilkan of &thorn;am sal other doun cast,</L>
<L>And ilkan agayn other hortel fast,</L>
<L N="4788">Swa &thorn;at ilka stan, on divers wyse,</L>
<L>Sal sonder other in thre partyse.</L>
<L>&THORN;e neghend day, gret erthedyn sal be,</L>
<L>Generaly in ilka contr&eacute;;</L>
<L N="4792">And swa gret erthdyn als sal be &thorn;an</L>
<L>Was never hard, sythen &thorn;e world bygan.</L>
<L>&THORN;e tend day &thorn;ar-aftir to neven,</L>
<L>&THORN;e erthe sal be made playn and even,</L>
<L N="4796">For hilles and valeis sal turned be</L>
<L>In-til playn, and made even to se.</L>
<L>&THORN;e ellevend day men sal com out</L>
<L>Of caves, and holes and wend about,</L>
<L N="4800">Als wode men, &thorn;at na witt can;</L>
<L>And nane sal spek til other &thorn;an.</L>
<L>&THORN;e twelfte day aftir, &thorn;e sternes alle</L>
<L>And &thorn;e signes fra &thorn;e heven sal falle.</L>
<L N="4804">&THORN;e thredend day sal dede men banes</L>
<L>Be sett to-gyder, and ryse al attanes,</L>
<L>And aboven on &thorn;air graves stand;</L>
<L>&THORN;is sal byfalle in ilka land.
<PB REF="00000175.tif" N="131"></L>
<L N="4808">&THORN;e fourtend day, al &thorn;at lyves &thorn;an</L>
<L>Sal dighe, childe, man and woman</L>
<L>For &thorn;ai shalle with &thorn;am rys ogayn</L>
<L>&THORN;at byfor war dede, outher til ioy or payn.</L>
<L N="4812">&THORN;e fiftend day, &thorn;os sal betyde,</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;e world sal bryn on ilk syde,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e erthe whar we now duelle,</L>
<L>Until &thorn;e utter end of alle helle.</L>
<L N="4816">&THORN;us tels Ierom &thorn;er takens fiftene,</L>
<L>Als he in &thorn;e bokes of Ebriens had sene.</L>
<L>Bot for alle &thorn;a takens &thorn;at men sal se,</L>
<L>Yhit sal na man certayn be</L>
<L N="4820">What tyme Crist sal come til &thorn;e dome,</L>
<L>Swa sodanly he sal doun come;</L>
<L>For als byfel in Noe and Loth days,</L>
<L>Swa sal he com, for Luke in &thorn;e godspel says:</L>
<L N="4824"><I>Et sicut factum est in diebus Noe, ita</I></L>
<L><I>erit adventus filii hominis: edebant</I></L>
<L><I>et bibebant, uxores ducebant et</I></L>
<L><I>dabantur ad nupcias, usque ad diem,</I></L>
<L N="4828"><I>qua intravit Noe in archam; et</I></L>
<L><I>venit diluvium et perdidit omnes: Si|</I></L>
<L><I>militer factum est in diebus Loth, ede|</I></L>
<L><I>bant et bibebant, emebant et vendebant,</I></L>
<L N="4832"><I>plantabant et edificabant,</I></L>
<L><I>qua die autem exiit Loth a Sodomis, et subilo</I></L>
<L><I>pluit ignem et sulphur de celo, et perdidit</I></L>
<L><I>omnes; secundum autem hoc erit</I></L>
<L N="4836"><I>qua die filius hominis revelabitur.</I></L>
<L>&THORN;ir er &thorn;e wordes of &thorn;e godspelle,</L>
<L>&THORN;at es on Inglissche &thorn;us to telle:</L>
<L>"Als was done in &thorn;e days of No&eacute;,</L>
<L N="4840">Right swa mans son sal com" says he,</L>
<L>"Men ete and drank &thorn;an and war glade,</L>
<L>And wedded wyfes, and bridalles made</L>
<L>Until &thorn;e day, namly, &thorn;at Noe</L>
<L N="4844">Went in-to &thorn;e shippe &thorn;at made he,
<PB REF="00000176.tif" N="132"></L>
<L>And sodanly come &thorn;e flode &thorn;at tyde</L>
<L>And fordid alle &thorn;e world swa wyde.</L>
<L>Alswa in &thorn;e days of Loth byfelle,</L>
<L N="4848">Men ete and drank, shortly to telle,</L>
<L>Ilkan with other, and salde and boght,</L>
<L>And planted, and bygged, and houses wroght,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at day, &thorn;at Loth yhed out of Sodome,</L>
<L N="4852">Sodanly Goddes vengeance come;</L>
<L>It rayned fire fra heven and brunstane,</L>
<L>And tynt al &thorn;at &thorn;are was, and spard nane,</L>
<L>Right &thorn;us sal falle, als men sal se,</L>
<L N="4856">&THORN;e day man son sal shewed be."</L>
<L>In &thorn;e ende of &thorn;e world, byfor &thorn;e dome,</L>
<L>An hydus fire sal sodanly come,</L>
<L>&THORN;at alle &thorn;e world sal haly bryn,</L>
<L N="4860">And nathyng spare &thorn;at es &thorn;ar-in,</L>
<L>For alle &thorn;e erthe sal bryn with-oute</L>
<L>And &thorn;e Elementes, and alle &thorn;e ayre oboute,</L>
<L>And alle &thorn;at God in &thorn;e world has wroght,</L>
<L N="4864">Sal &thorn;an be brynned and wasted to noght.</L>
<L>&THORN;is fire &thorn;at thurgh &thorn;e world sal ryse,</L>
<L>Sal com &thorn;an fra sere partyse;</L>
<L>For alle &thorn;e fire &thorn;at es in &thorn;e spere,</L>
<L N="4868">And under erthe, and aboven erthe here,</L>
<L>Sal mete togyder attans &thorn;an,</L>
<L>And bryn alle &thorn;at lyves, best and man,</L>
<L>And alle &thorn;at growes in erthe and ayre,</L>
<L N="4872">Tille alle be clensed, and made fayre</L>
<L>Of alle &thorn;e corrupcions &thorn;at men may se,</L>
<L>&THORN;e whilk in &thorn;e ayre or in &thorn;e erthe may be;</L>
<L>&THORN;is fire, als &thorn;e buk says als<NOTE PLACE="foot">And leres (Harl. 4196).</NOTE> lers,</L>
<L N="4876">Sal brin and wirk on four maneres.</L>
<L>It sal wirk als &thorn;e fir of helle</L>
<L>To punyssche &thorn;e synful &thorn;at &thorn;ar sal duelle</L>
<L>It sal wirk als fire of pnrgatory</L>
<L N="4880">To clense men of veniel syn fully.
<PB REF="00000177.tif" N="133"></L>
<L>It sal wirk als fire of herth here,</L>
<L>&THORN;at over alle sal bryn far and nere,</L>
<L>To wast alle &thorn;at on erthe springes</L>
<L N="4884">Als gresse, and tres, and alle other thynges,</L>
<L>And alswa &thorn;e bodys of ilk man</L>
<L>To brin haly in-to askes &thorn;an;</L>
<L>It sal wirk als &thorn;e fire of &thorn;e spere,</L>
<L N="4888">To make &thorn;e elementes clene and clere</L>
<L>And alle &thorn;e ayre bright of hew,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e hevens, for to serve als new.</L>
<L>Thurgh &thorn;is fire &thorn;at &thorn;us sal rayke obout,</L>
<L N="4892">&THORN;e face of &thorn;e erth sal brin with-out,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e shappe of &thorn;e world sal for-done be</L>
<L>Als it was first thurgh &thorn;e flode of Noe;</L>
<L>And als &thorn;at flode passed cubites fiften</L>
<L N="4896">Over &thorn;e heyghest mount, &thorn;at ever was sen,</L>
<L>Right swa &thorn;e fire als heyghe sal pas</L>
<L>To fordo &thorn;e world als it &thorn;an was;</L>
<L>And als God byfor his first commyng</L>
<L N="4900">Wald here fordo, with-outen lettyng,</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;e world thurgh water anly</L>
<L>Agayn &thorn;e fire of lychery,</L>
<L>Right swa, byfor his last commyng,</L>
<L N="4904">He sal of &thorn;e world mak endyng,</L>
<L>Thurgh fire &thorn;at sal swa brinnand be,</L>
<L>Agayn &thorn;e dasednes<NOTE PLACE="foot">coldnes (MS. Lands. 348).</NOTE> of charit&eacute;.</L>
<L>&THORN;e wirkyng of &thorn;e fire swa brinnand</L>
<L N="4908">Sal contend<NOTE PLACE="foot">contene?</NOTE> &thorn;ir thre short tymes passand,</L>
<L>&THORN;at es bygynnyng, mydward, and ende,</L>
<L>Als in &thorn;is bok es here contende.</L>
<L>First &thorn;e fire, at &thorn;e bygynnyng,</L>
<L N="4912">Sal cum byfor Cristes commyng,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e gude men sal &thorn;an clensen and fine,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e wikked men hard punnys and pyne,</L>
<L>&THORN;at here luffed syn and thoght it swete,</L>
<L N="4916">And &thorn;arfor says &thorn;us David &thorn;e prophete:</L>
<L><I>Ignis ante ipsum precedet, et inflammabit incircuitu inimicos eius.</I>
<PB REF="00000178.tif" N="134"></L>
<L>"&THORN;e fir byfor hym, on sere partys,</L>
<L N="4920">Sal ga and about brine his enemys;"</L>
<L>&THORN;at fire mens bodys to askes sal brin,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e world and alle &thorn;at es &thorn;ar-ine;</L>
<L>&THORN;us sal &thorn;e fire first byfor come,</L>
<L N="4924">Ar Crist com doun til &thorn;e dome.</L>
<L>And when &thorn;e fire has wasted, als I talde,</L>
<L>&THORN;an sal al men ryse, bathe yhong and alde,</L>
<L>Out of &thorn;air graves with saul and body,</L>
<L N="4928">And come til &thorn;e dome &thorn;an alle halely</L>
<L>And our Loverd Crist sal com doun &thorn;an,</L>
<L>And sit in dome, als domes man,</L>
<L>And deme &thorn;an, bathe gude and ille,</L>
<L N="4932">Als yhe may aftir-ward here, if yhe wille;</L>
<L>And yhit &thorn;e fire alle &thorn;at tyde</L>
<L>Sal brin obout hym, on ilka syde,</L>
<L>Als &thorn;e prophete David bers wytnes</L>
<L N="4936">In &thorn;e Psauter, &thorn;ar &thorn;us writen es:</L>
<L><I>"Ignis, in conspectu eius, exardescet,</I></L>
<L><I>et incircuitu eius tempestas valida."</I></L>
<L>"&THORN;e fyre sal brin in his sight," says he,</L>
<L N="4940">And obout hym grete tempest sal be."</L>
<L>And als lang als &thorn;at dome sal last</L>
<L>&THORN;e fire sal brin, on ilk syde fast;</L>
<L>And when &thorn;e dome es broght til ende,</L>
<L N="4944">&THORN;a &thorn;at sal be dampned sal wende,</L>
<L>With alle &thorn;e fire &thorn;at swa sal brin,</L>
<L>Til helle pytt, and duelle ay &thorn;ar-in.</L>
<L>&THORN;an sal alle &thorn;e fire be sweped doune</L>
<L N="4948">In-til helle, with alkyn corrupcioune,</L>
<L>And alle &thorn;e filth of &thorn;e world, neshe and hard,</L>
<L>Als in &thorn;is bok es writen aftirward.</L>
<L>&THORN;us thurgh alle &thorn;e world &thorn;e fire4sal brin,</L>
<L N="4952">And clense it of al manere of syn,</L>
<L>And of alle corrupcions, bath hegh and, law</L>
<L>&THORN;at men may now se, here, and knaw;</L>
<L>And when &thorn;e fire has wasted al erdly thyng,</L>
<L N="4956">&THORN;an sal &thorn;e hevens sees of movyng.
<PB REF="00000179.tif" N="135"></L>
<L>Our Lord yhit &thorn;an, or he com doun,</L>
<L>For to sytte in dome in proper parsoun,</L>
<L>Sal send byfor, als &thorn;e buke tels,</L>
<L N="4960">In four partys his angels,</L>
<L>With &thorn;air bemes &thorn;at &thorn;ai sal blaw,</L>
<L>&THORN;at alle &thorn;e world sal here and knaw;</L>
<L>Alle men &thorn;ai sal &thorn;an upcalle</L>
<L N="4964">And byd &thorn;am cum til &thorn;e dome alle.</L>
<L>Alle men sal ryse &thorn;an &thorn;at ever had life,</L>
<L>Man and woman, mayden and wyfe,</L>
<L>Gude and ille, with fleshe and felle,</L>
<L N="4968">In body and saul, als clerkes can telle;</L>
<L>And &thorn;at in als short whyle als hert may thynk,</L>
<L>Or mans eghe may open or wynk,</L>
<L>Fra &thorn;e tyme &thorn;at &thorn;ai &thorn;e son sal here,</L>
<L N="4972">For &thorn;e apostel says on &thorn;is manere:</L>
<L>"<I>Omnes resurgent in momento, in</I></L>
<L><I>ictu oculi, in novissima tuba."</I></L>
<L>He says "alle sal ryse in a tym movyng,</L>
<L N="4976">Als in &thorn;e space of an eghe twynklyng,</L>
<L>When &thorn;ai here &thorn;e dredeful blast</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e beme, &thorn;at &thorn;an sal blaw last."</L>
<L>Alle men sal &thorn;an tite up-ryse</L>
<L N="4980">In &thorn;e same stature and &thorn;e same bodyse,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ai had here in &thorn;air lifedays,</L>
<L>And in non other, als &thorn;e buk says.</L>
<L>&THORN;an sal alle ryse in &thorn;e same eld &thorn;an,</L>
<L N="4984">&THORN;at God had fully here als man,</L>
<L>Namly, when he uprayse thurgh myght</L>
<L>Fra dede, als says Saynt Austyn ryght;</L>
<L>&THORN;an was he of threty yhere elde and twa,</L>
<L N="4988">And of thre monethes &thorn;ar-with alswa;</L>
<L>In &thorn;at elde alle sal ryse at &thorn;e last,</L>
<L>When &thorn;ai here &thorn;e grete bemes blast,</L>
<L>With &thorn;air awen bodys alle hale</L>
<L N="4992">And with alle &thorn;air lymes, grete and smale.</L>
<L>For alle-if &thorn;e bodys of ilk man</L>
<L>Shulde alle be brynned til askes &thorn;an,
<PB REF="00000180.tif" N="136"></L>
<L>And yhit &thorn;ogh alle &thorn;e askes of &thorn;air bodys</L>
<L N="4996">War strew[d] and skaterd in sere partys,</L>
<L>Thurgh ilka land and ilka cuntr&eacute;,</L>
<L>&THORN;ai sal &thorn;an togyder alle gader[d] be.</L>
<L>And ilka body sal rise &thorn;an halely,</L>
<L N="5000">With alle &thorn;e lyms, &thorn;at falles til &thorn;e body,</L>
<L>And with alle &thorn;e hare of body and hede</L>
<L>Swa &thorn;at na hare sal want in na stede;</L>
<L>For &thorn;are sal na hare be peryste,</L>
<L N="5004">Als Saynt Luk says &thorn;e Evaungeli[s]tte:</L>
<L><I>Capillus de capite,</I></L>
<L><I>vestro non peribit.</I></L>
<L>"Na hare sal perishe, ne faile", says he,</L>
<L N="5008">"&THORN;at falles on &thorn;e heved for to be."</L>
<L>And if any lyms be here unsemely,</L>
<L>Thurgh outragioust&eacute; of kynd namely,</L>
<L>God sal abate &thorn;at outrage, thurgh myght,</L>
<L N="5012">And make &thorn;a lyms semely to sight;</L>
<L>And if any lym wanted, &thorn;at shuld falle</L>
<L>Til &thorn;e body, or any war over smalle,</L>
<L>Thurgh &thorn;e defaut here of kynd God &thorn;an wille</L>
<L N="5016">Alle &thorn;e defautes of &thorn;e lyms fulfille,</L>
<L>And &thorn;us sal he do namly, to al &thorn;a</L>
<L>&THORN;at sal be save and til blis ga.</L>
<L>For &thorn;air bodys sal be semely and bright</L>
<L N="5020">With avenand lymes til alle mens sight.</L>
<L>Bot God sal amend on nane wise</L>
<L>Defautes of &thorn;e lyms of synful bodys,</L>
<L>For &thorn;air bodys sal alle unsemely be,</L>
<L N="5024">And foul, and ugly<NOTE PLACE="foot">The MS. has 'ungly'.</NOTE>, opon to se.</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;at er gude &thorn;an and rightwyse,</L>
<L>&THORN;at sal be save, sal first upryse,</L>
<L>And up in-to &thorn;e ayre be ravyste,</L>
<L N="5028">Againe &thorn;e comyng of Ihesu Criste,</L>
<L>To kepe him when he doun sal come,</L>
<L>Als domesman for to sitte in dome.</L>
<L>&THORN;e mast parfite men sal Criste first kepe</L>
<L N="5032">And alle cum with hym in his felawshepe,
<PB REF="00000181.tif" N="137"></L>
<L>And with him ay be in body and saule,</L>
<L>Als &thorn;e apostel says, Saynt Paule:</L>
<L><I>Quoniam Christus Dominus in iussa et voce arcangeli,</I></L>
<L N="5036"><I>et in tuba dei, descendet de celo, et mortui</I></L>
<L><I>qui in Christo mortui sunt resurgent primi.</I></L>
<L><I>Deinde nos qui vivimus, qui relinquimur, simul</I></L>
<L><I>rapiemur cum illis in nubibus</I></L>
<L N="5040"><I>obviam Christo in aere, sic semper</I></L>
<L><I>cum Domino erimus.</I></L>
<L>He says "our Lord sal come doun fra heven,</L>
<L>In Goddis byddyng, and archaungel steven,</L>
<L N="5044">And in &thorn;e son of Goddes awen beme,</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;e world &thorn;an for to deme.</L>
<L>And &thorn;ai &thorn;at er dede in Crist &thorn;an,</L>
<L>Sal first uprise, ilka man;</L>
<L N="5048">And sythen we, on &thorn;e sam manere,</L>
<L>&THORN;at now lyves and er left here,</L>
<L>Sal &thorn;an with &thorn;am in cloudes be ravyste</L>
<L>Up in-to &thorn;e ayre for to mete Criste,</L>
<L N="5052">And swa with our Lorde ay sal be,</L>
<L>Fra &thorn;at tyme forward," &thorn;us says he.</L>
<L>Bot we synful &thorn;at sal rise &thorn;at tyde</L>
<L>Bynethe on &thorn;e erthe sal Crist abyde</L>
<L N="5056">In drede and sorow charged with synne,</L>
<L>For &thorn;ai may nour-whare away wynne.</L>
<L>&THORN;am war lever be depe in helle &thorn;an,</L>
<L>&THORN;an com byfor &thorn;at domesman.</L>
<L N="5060">&THORN;ai wald fayne fle, if &thorn;ai myght,</L>
<L>Or hide &thorn;am fra &thorn;at domesman sight</L>
<L>Under erthe, or ourwhar elles,</L>
<L>Als Saynt Johan, in &thorn;e apocalips, telles:</L>
<L N="5064"><I>Reges terre et principes, et tribuni, et</I></L>
<L><I>divites et fortes, et omnis</I></L>
<L><I>servus et liber, absconderunt se in</I></L>
<L><I>speluncis et in petris moncium, et</I></L>
<L N="5068"><I>dicent montibus et petris, 'Cadite</I></L>
<L><I>super nos', et collibus 'abscondite</I></L>
<L><I>nos, a facie sedentis super tronum</I></L>
<L><I>et ab ira agni.'</I>
<PB REF="00000182.tif" N="138"></L>
<L N="5072">He says "kynges of &thorn;e lande and princes sere,</L>
<L>And cheftayns &thorn;at er under &thorn;am here,</L>
<L>And riche men of divers cuntr&eacute;,</L>
<L>And strenthy men, and bond and fre,</L>
<L N="5076">In caves &thorn;ai wald &thorn;an hyde ilkan</L>
<L>And in cragges, and in roche of stan;</L>
<L>And sal say til montayns and roches &thorn;us,</L>
<L>'Fal opon us now and hyde us,</L>
<L N="5080">Fra &thorn;e face of hym &thorn;at syttes in throne</L>
<L>And fra &thorn;e wrethe of &thorn;e lamb', &thorn;us tels Saynt Iohan.</L>
<L>Many maner of men sal haf dred &thorn;an,</L>
<L>To com byfor &thorn;at dreful domesman,</L>
<L N="5084">Namely, synful men with-outen hope,</L>
<L>And yhit says &thorn;us &thorn;e haly man, Iope<NOTE PLACE="foot">Job (MS. Harl. 4196).</NOTE>:</L>
<L><I>Domine quando veneris iudicare terram,</I></L>
<L><I>ubi me abscondam a vultu ire tue, quia</I></L>
<L N="5088"><I>peccavi nimis [in vita mea]?</I></L>
<L>"Loverd", he says, "when &thorn;ou sal come</L>
<L>To deme &thorn;e erthe and sytte in dome,</L>
<L>Whar sal I fra &thorn;i wreth hyd me</L>
<L N="5092">For-why I haf synd ogaynes &thorn;e</L>
<L>Ful gretely in my life here?"</L>
<L>And yhit says Iob on &thorn;is manere:</L>
<L><I>Quis michi hoc tribuat</I></L>
<L N="5096"><I>ut in inferno protegas me,</I></L>
<L><I>et abscondas me donec</I></L>
<L><I>pertranseat furor tuus?</I></L>
<L>"Loverd, wha may gyf to me", says he,</L>
<L N="5100">"&THORN;at &thorn;ou in helle may hyd me</L>
<L>And cover me at &thorn;e dredful day,</L>
<L>Unto &thorn;i wrethe be passed oway,"</L>
<L>&THORN;an es it na wondre, als I sayde are,</L>
<L N="5104">If &thorn;e synful men haf drede and care,</L>
<L>&THORN;at sal dampned be and peryst</L>
<L>For to cum in &thorn;e syght of Ihesu Crist,</L>
<L>&THORN;at til &thorn;am swa wrethful sal seme &thorn;an,</L>
<L N="5108">When Job &thorn;us says &thorn;e halyman.
<PB REF="00000183.tif" N="139"></L>
<L>Our Lord Crist, thurgh his grete myght,</L>
<L>Sal &thorn;an com doun fra heven bright,</L>
<L N="5112">Als domesman to sit in dome,</L>
<L>And with him grete multitude sal come</L>
<L>Of angels, and of archangels,</L>
<L>And of al other halghes, als &thorn;e buk teles:</L>
<L N="5116"><I>Ecce Dominus veniet et</I></L>
<L><I>omnes sancti eius cum eo.</I></L>
<L>"Lo! our Lord sal com til &thorn;e dome</L>
<L>And alle his halghes sal with him come."</L>
<L N="5120">And sodanly he sal hym &thorn;an shewe,</L>
<L>Als says &thorn;e godspeller Saynt Mathewe:</L>
<L><I>"Sicut fulgur exiit ab oriente,</I></L>
<L><I>et paret in occidente, ita erit</I></L>
<L N="5124"><I>adventus filii hominis, subitus,</I></L>
<L><I>choruschans, et terribilis."</I></L>
<L>"Als &thorn;e levenyng out gas in short tyde</L>
<L>Fra &thorn;e est, and shewes it in &thorn;e west syde,</L>
<L N="5128">Right swa &thorn;e commyng of man son sal be,</L>
<L>Sodayne and bright and dreful to se.</L>
<L>He sal com doun, nathyng sal him lett,</L>
<L>Even onence<NOTE PLACE="foot">ageyns (MS. Y.).</NOTE> &thorn;e mount of Olyvet,</L>
<L N="5132">Whar he, in manhed, stey<NOTE PLACE="foot">stied (MS. Y.).</NOTE> up even</L>
<L>Fra his disciples, til &thorn;e fader in heven;</L>
<L>And in swilk fourme als he stey up &thorn;an,</L>
<L>He sal com doun to deme ilk man,</L>
<L N="5136">Gude and ille, bathe yong and alde,</L>
<L>Als &thorn;e angels til his disciples talde:</L>
<L><I>Hic Ihesus qui assumptus est a nobis</I></L>
<L><I>in celum, sic veniet et quemadmodum</I></L>
<L N="5140"><I>vidistis eum euntem in celum.</I></L>
<L>&THORN;ai sayd "Ihesu Crist &thorn;at here es uptane</L>
<L>Fra yhow, til heven, with flessch and bane,</L>
<L N="5144">Swa sal he com at &thorn;e world ende,</L>
<L>Als yhe saw hym up in-til heven wende;</L>
<L>In &thorn;at fourme of man he sal cum &thorn;an,</L>
<L>And sitte in dome als domesman.
<PB REF="00000184.tif" N="140"></L>
<L>When Criste es common doun to deme,</L>
<L N="5148">In fourme of man, als he sal seme,</L>
<L>In a place he sal his dome halde,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e vale of Iosaphat es calde,</L>
<L>Whare alle men sal to-gyder mete,</L>
<L N="5152">Als Crist says, thurgh Ioel &thorn;e prophete:</L>
<L><I>Congregabo omnes gentes, et</I></L>
<L><I>adducam eas in valle Iosaphat.</I></L>
<L>He says "alle men I sal to-gyder calle,</L>
<L N="5156">And in vale of Iosaphat lede &thorn;am alle,"</L>
<L>And yhit mare to &thorn;at he says &thorn;us,</L>
<L>Als he thurgh &thorn;e prophete shewes us:</L>
<L><I>Consurgent et ascendent</I></L>
<L N="5160"><I>omnes gentes in valle</I></L>
<L><I>Iosephat, quia ibi sedebo</I></L>
<L><I>ut iudicem omnes gentes.</I></L>
<L>He says "al men sal ryse to &thorn;e dome,</L>
<L N="5164">And in &thorn;e vale of Iosaphat come;"</L>
<L>"For &thorn;ar," he says, "I sal sitte namly,</L>
<L>To deme alle men als &thorn;ai er worthy."</L>
<L>&THORN;at vale, &thorn;e vale of &thorn;e erthe men calles,</L>
<L N="5168">For imyd &thorn;e erthe, with-outen, it falles;</L>
<L>Iosaphat es &thorn;us mykel at say,</L>
<L>Als stede of dome, at &thorn;e last day.</L>
<L>Crist sal noght fully &thorn;an doun come</L>
<L N="5172">On &thorn;e erthe for to sitte in dome,</L>
<L>Bot up in &thorn;e ayre he sal sitte,</L>
<L>On a whyte cloude, als says haly wrytte:</L>
<L><I>Ecce apparebit dominus super</I></L>
<L N="5176"><I>nubem candidam!</I></L>
<L>"Lo! our Lorde sal shew hym &thorn;an</L>
<L>On a whyte cloude, and sitte als domesman."</L>
<L>Even aboven &thorn;at vale namly,</L>
<L N="5180">Whare al men sal se his body.</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;e skilles why he sal &thorn;are sitte</L>
<L>Men may fynde here &thorn;at wille &thorn;am witte;</L>
<L>For &thorn;e vale of Iosaphat es sette</L>
<L N="5184">Bytwene &thorn;e mount of Olyvet
<PB REF="00000185.tif" N="141"></L>
<L>And Ierusalem, on &thorn;e other syde,</L>
<L>&THORN;at standes imyddes &thorn;e world so wyde;</L>
<L>And &thorn;ar es &thorn;e mount of calvery,</L>
<L N="5188">And &thorn;e sepulcre of Crist fast &thorn;arby.</L>
<L>And in &thorn;at cuntr&eacute; standes Bethleem,</L>
<L>Noght ful ferre fra Ierusalem;</L>
<L>&THORN;ar-for Crist sal sytte &thorn;ar &thorn;at day,</L>
<L N="5192">Onence &thorn;e myddes of erth &thorn;us for to say.</L>
<L>"Lo! here als yhe may alle now se</L>
<L>&THORN;e vale of Iosaphat under me</L>
<L>Whare byred was my moder Mary</L>
<L N="5196">Of wham flesshe and blode for yhow tok I."</L>
<L>He may say "lo! here, als yhe se now,</L>
<L>Bethleem whare I was born for yhow,</L>
<L>And in clotes lapped and layd was</L>
<L N="5200">In a cribbe, bytwen an ox and an asse."</L>
<L>He may say "lo here yhe may se stande</L>
<L>Ierusalem, &thorn;at es nere hande</L>
<L>Whare I had for yhow many buffet,</L>
<L N="5204">And with sharp skourges sare was bette,</L>
<L>And fra whethen &thorn;e crosse for yhow I bare,</L>
<L>&THORN;at on my shulder was layd &thorn;are."</L>
<L>He may say also "lo! here &thorn;arby,</L>
<L N="5208">Als yhe may se, &thorn;e mount of calvery</L>
<L>Whar I was hanged upon &thorn;e rode,</L>
<L>Bytwen twa thefes for yhour gode;</L>
<L>Whare my payn for yhow was mast</L>
<L N="5212">And whare I swelt and yhelded &thorn;e gast."</L>
<L>He may say yhit &thorn;us alswa;</L>
<L>"Lo! here &thorn;e sepulcre a lytil &thorn;ar-fra,</L>
<L>Whar I was layde for yhow als dede,</L>
<L N="5216">When I was beryd in &thorn;at stede."</L>
<L>He may say alswa, als here es sett,</L>
<L>"Lo! here &thorn;e mount of Olivett,</L>
<L>Whar aungels appered in mens lykenes,</L>
<L N="5220">When I stey til [h]even &thorn;ar blis ay es,</L>
<L>And tald yhow how my commyng shuld be</L>
<L>Tyl &thorn;e dome, als yhe may now se."
<PB REF="00000186.tif" N="142"></L>
<L>Now haf yhe herd &thorn;e skylles why,</L>
<L N="5224">He sal sit oboven &thorn;at vale namly,</L>
<L>&THORN;at men &thorn;e vale of Iosaphat calles</L>
<L>&THORN;e whilk imyndes<NOTE PLACE="foot">in myddes (MS. Harl. 4196).</NOTE> &thorn;e world falles.</L>
<L>Alswa another skille may &thorn;is be</L>
<L N="5228">Why he sal doun com in &thorn;at countr&eacute;</L>
<L>For &thorn;ar was his first commyng doun,</L>
<L>Anly for mans salvacioun,</L>
<L>When he first flessch and blod tok</L>
<L N="5232">Of &thorn;e mayden Mari, als says [&thorn;e] bok.</L>
<L>&THORN;us sal he com doun at sitte &thorn;are,</L>
<L>To deme al &thorn;e world, als I saide are,</L>
<L>Crist ful awsterne &thorn;an sal be</L>
<L N="5236">Agayn synful me[n] &thorn;at him sal se;</L>
<L>And dredful and hydus, als says &thorn;e boke,</L>
<L>He sal be to &thorn;am, when &thorn;ai on hym loke,</L>
<L>And ful delitable unto &thorn;e sight</L>
<L N="5240">Of ryghtwyse men &thorn;at lyffed here ryght.</L>
<L>Bot alle &thorn;e parsons of &thorn;e Trinit&eacute;</L>
<L>And &thorn;e godhed sal noght &thorn;an shewed be</L>
<L>To ille and gude, &thorn;at sal appere &thorn;an,</L>
<L N="5244">Bot Crist allane in fourme of man,</L>
<L>Goddes son &thorn;at &thorn;an sal deme us</L>
<L>And &thorn;arfor Saynt Johan says &thorn;us:</L>
<L><I>"Omne iudicium dedit filio, ut honorifi|</I></L>
<L N="5248"><I>cent filium, sicut honorificant patrem."</I></L>
<L>"God has gyfen til his son," says he,</L>
<L>"Alle &thorn;e dome &thorn;at gyven sal be,</L>
<L>&THORN;at men honour &thorn;e son ryght,</L>
<L N="5252">Als &thorn;ai honour &thorn;e fadir ful of myght."</L>
<L>&THORN;e gude men sal se hym in manhed &thorn;an,</L>
<L>With &thorn;e godhed, als God and man,</L>
<L>&THORN;e whilk he sal noght fra &thorn;am hyde;</L>
<L N="5256">For &thorn;ai sal se hym &thorn;an glorifide,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at sal be a blisful syght,</L>
<L>Swa fair he sal seme til &thorn;am, and bright.
<PB REF="00000187.tif" N="143"></L>
<L>&THORN;e ille men in manhed sal hym se.</L>
<L N="5260">Anly als he henged on &thorn;e rode tre,</L>
<L>Alle bla and blody als he &thorn;an was,</L>
<L>When he deyhed for mans trespas.</L>
<L>&THORN;at sight til &thorn;am sal be payne and drede,</L>
<L N="5264">For &thorn;ai sal noght se of his godhede;</L>
<L>And for &thorn;e godhede es ful of blisse,</L>
<L>&THORN;arfor &thorn;e sight of it &thorn;ai sal misse.</L>
<L>Bot in his manhed anly, als I say,</L>
<L N="5268">He sal shew hym til &thorn;am &thorn;at day,</L>
<L>For in fourme of man he sal &thorn;an seme</L>
<L>And in his manhede he sal &thorn;am deme.</L>
<L>He sal &thorn;an at his doun commyng,</L>
<L N="5272">&THORN;e taken of &thorn;e croys wyth hym bring,</L>
<L>On whilk he boght us fra elle pyn<NOTE PLACE="foot">Hell pyne (MS. Harl. 4196).</NOTE>;</L>
<L>For he wald noght man saul tyn;</L>
<L>&THORN;at taken of &thorn;e crose alle men sal se,</L>
<L N="5276">Bot ful dilitable it sal be</L>
<L>Til rightwys men, and seme fule bright;</L>
<L>And dredful til synful mans syght.</L>
<L>&THORN;is taken of &thorn;e cros sal be shewed &thorn;an,</L>
<L N="5280">Als &thorn;e buk says, and be hyd fra na man:</L>
<L><I>Hoc signum crucis erit in celo, cum</I></L>
<L><I>dominus ad iudicandum venerit.</I></L>
<L>"&THORN;is taken of &thorn;e cros in heven sal seme</L>
<L N="5284">When our loverd sal com to deme."</L>
<L>&THORN;at es at say aboven in &thorn;e ayre,</L>
<L>&THORN;at til gude men sal sem bright and fayre.</L>
<L>&THORN;is taken, als I trowe, sal noght be</L>
<L N="5288">&THORN;e sam cros, ne &thorn;e sam tre,</L>
<L>On whilk God was nayled fot and hande.</L>
<L>Bot a taken of &thorn;at cros semande.</L>
<L>Yhit som trowes, and swa may wel be,</L>
<L N="5292">&THORN;at &thorn;e taken of &thorn;e spere men sal &thorn;an se</L>
<L>&THORN;at staynged<NOTE PLACE="foot">stanged (MS. Harl. 4196).</NOTE> Crist until &thorn;e hert rote,</L>
<L>And of &thorn;e nayles &thorn;at hym thurgh hand and fote
<PB REF="00000188.tif" N="144"></L>
<L>Til &thorn;e hard rode tre fast fested;</L>
<L N="5296">And of &thorn;e croun of thornes &thorn;at was thrested</L>
<L>On his heved fast, &thorn;at &thorn;e blode out rane,</L>
<L>When &thorn;e thornes hym prikked til &thorn;e harnpane</L>
<L>And of &thorn;e scourges alswa &thorn;at brast his hyde<NOTE PLACE="foot">Also the skourges that his flesshe to-tere (MS. Addit 11305).</NOTE>,</L>
<L N="5300">&THORN;at &thorn;e blode ran doun, on ilk syde.</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;er takens sal &thorn;an be shewed</L>
<L>Byfor alle men, bathe lerd and lewed;</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;e synful, &thorn;at dampned sal be,</L>
<L N="5304">To &thorn;air shenshepe &thorn;an sal &thorn;am se.</L>
<L>Crist sal shew &thorn;an his woundes wyde,</L>
<L>In heved, and fote and in his syde,</L>
<L>&THORN;at fressche sal sem and alle bledand</L>
<L N="5308">Til &thorn;e synful, &thorn;at bifor hym sal stand.</L>
<L>He sal shew, to &thorn;air confusioun,</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;e signes of his passioun,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e enchesoun and &thorn;e manere</L>
<L N="5312">Of his ded &thorn;at he tholed here,</L>
<L>And alle &thorn;is sal he do &thorn;os openly,</L>
<L>To reprove &thorn;e synful men &thorn;ar-by</L>
<L>And &thorn;at sal be &thorn;air shenschip &thorn;an,</L>
<L N="5316">For Saynt Austyn says &thorn;us, &thorn;e halyman:</L>
<L><I>Fortasse, in corpore suo, dominus cicatrices serva|</I></L>
<L><I>vit ut in iudico hostibus exprobaret,</I></L>
<L><I>ut convincens eos dicat: Ecce homo</I></L>
<L N="5320"><I>quem crucifixistis; Ecce Deus et homo</I></L>
<L><I>quem credere noluistis: Videte vulnera</I></L>
<L><I>que infixistis; agnoscite latus</I></L>
<L><I>quod pupigistis propter vos</I></L>
<L N="5324"><I>apertum est et intrare noluistis.</I></L>
<L>He says, "our Lord Goddes son almyghty</L>
<L>Parantere has keped, in his body,</L>
<L>&THORN;e erres<NOTE PLACE="foot">&THORN;e <I>sore</I> of his woundes swi&thorn;e clere (MS. Y.).</NOTE> of his wondes sere,</L>
<L N="5328">&THORN;at he tholed for mans syn here,</L>
<L>For to shew &thorn;am til his enmys,</L>
<L>Whan he sal sytte in dome als iustys
<PB REF="00000189.tif" N="145"></L>
<L>To reprove &thorn;am at &thorn;e last day,</L>
<L N="5332">And to atteyn &thorn;am, and &thorn;os say;</L>
<L>"Lo! here, &thorn;e man in flesshe and blode</L>
<L>&THORN;e whilk yhe hynged on &thorn;e rode;</L>
<L>Lo! her God and man, &thorn;at man wroght,</L>
<L N="5336">In wham trow wald yhe noght;</L>
<L>Byhalde &thorn;e wondes &thorn;at yhe styked,</L>
<L>Sese here &thorn;e syd &thorn;at yhe priked,</L>
<L>&THORN;e whilk for yhow was open ay,</L>
<L N="5340">And yhe wald entre be<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>bi</I> (MS. Harl. 4196).</NOTE> ne way."</L>
<L>A how mikel shenshep sal be</L>
<L>To &thorn;e synful &thorn;at alle &thorn;is sal here and se!</L>
<L>&THORN;e whilk til hym dos here na gude agayne,</L>
<L N="5344">&THORN;at for &thorn;am tholed swa mykel payne;</L>
<L>And yhit noght &thorn;as &thorn;at dus na gud anly,</L>
<L>But other &thorn;at er swa ful of felony,</L>
<L>&THORN;at ay dos yvel ogayn gude,</L>
<L N="5348">And ofte dos Godes son on rode</L>
<L>In &thorn;at, &thorn;at in &thorn;am es thurgh syn,</L>
<L>Of whilk &thorn;ai wille never here blyn.</L>
<L>What may &thorn;ai answer &thorn;an and say,</L>
<L N="5352">How may &thorn;ai &thorn;am excuse &thorn;at day?</L>
<L>In nathyng may &thorn;ai be excused &thorn;an,</L>
<L>Swa rightwys sal be &thorn;e domesman;</L>
<L>For &thorn;at day, als &thorn;e buke wythenes,<NOTE PLACE="foot">witnes (MS. Harl. 4196).</NOTE></L>
<L N="5356">Sal noght be shewed but ryghtwysnes,</L>
<L>Wyth gret reddour til synful namly,</L>
<L>&THORN;at sal be demed, als &thorn;a her worthy.</L>
<L>&THORN;ai may defende &thorn;am be na ways</L>
<L N="5360">For Johan, wyth &thorn;e gilden mouth, &thorn;os says:</L>
<L><I>Non erit tunc locus defensionis,</I></L>
<L><I>ubi videbunt Christum exhibentem,</I></L>
<L><I>testimonia insigniaque sue passionis.</I></L>
<L N="5364">He sais "na sted of defens &thorn;ar sal be</L>
<L>War &thorn;ai sal Crist &thorn;an openly se</L>
<L>Gyfhand wytnes, and takens certayn,</L>
<L>Of his passioun and of his payn.
<PB REF="00000190.tif" N="146"></L>
<L N="5368">Alle sal haf gret drede &thorn;at day,</L>
<L>Bath gude and ille, als we here clerks say.</L>
<L>&THORN;ar sal be nouther aungel na<NOTE PLACE="foot">ne,</NOTE> man</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ai ne sal tremble for drede &thorn;an;</L>
<L N="5372">Alle-if &thorn;ai wat &thorn;at &thorn;ai sal be safe,</L>
<L>Yhit sal &thorn;ai &thorn;at day dre<NOTE PLACE="foot">dred,</NOTE> hafe</L>
<L>Noght for &thorn;am-self, for &thorn;ai er giltles,</L>
<L>Bot for &thorn;e gret reddure of ryghtwisnes,</L>
<L N="5376">And for &thorn;e gret austerit&eacute;,</L>
<L>&THORN;at Crist sal shew &thorn;at day to se,</L>
<L>Agayn &thorn;e synful men namly,</L>
<L>&THORN;at sal be dampned, wyth-outen mercy.</L>
<L N="5380">When rightwys men &thorn;at sal be saf,</L>
<L>And aungels swa mykel dred haf</L>
<L>What dred and dole aght synful haf &thorn;an?</L>
<L>&THORN;arfor &thorn;os says &thorn;e halyman:</L>
<L N="5384"><I>Si columpne celi contremiscent et</I></L>
<L><I>pavent adventum Christi,</I></L>
<L><I>et angeli pacis amare flebunt,</I></L>
<L><I>peccatores autem quid facient!</I></L>
<L N="5388">He says "if &thorn;e pylers of heven bright,</L>
<L>&THORN;at er haly men &thorn;at has liffed right,</L>
<L>Sal dred Cristes commyng and manhede,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e aungels alswa sal &thorn;an haf drede,</L>
<L N="5392">And yhit gret ful bitterly &thorn;ar-to,</L>
<L>What sal &thorn;e synful men &thorn;an do,</L>
<L>&THORN;at sal be dampned, als I sayd are?"</L>
<L>And says &thorn;e haly man &thorn;us mare:</L>
<L N="5396"><I>Si iustus vix salvabitur, impius</I></L>
<L><I>et peccator ubi parebunt?</I></L>
<L>"If &thorn;e rightwys man" yhit says he,</L>
<L>"Sal unnethes &thorn;an saved be,</L>
<L N="5400">&THORN;e synful and &thorn;e wykked man</L>
<L>Whyderward sal &thorn;ai wend &thorn;an?"</L>
<L>Ryghtwysmen, als &thorn;e buk telles,</L>
<L>Sal be saf &thorn;an and nan elles.</L>
<L N="5404">Our Loverd in manhed sal &thorn;an sitt</L>
<L>Oboune<NOTE PLACE="foot">Oboven (MS. Harl. 4196).</NOTE> &thorn;e synful, als says haly writ,
<PB REF="00000191.tif" N="147"></L>
<L>Austerne and wrahte<NOTE PLACE="foot">wrathe (MS. Harl. 4196).</NOTE> wyth a fel chere,</L>
<L>Wyth &thorn;am to threp &thorn;at has lyfed ille here.</L>
<L N="5408">Helle bynethen &thorn;at es wyde and depe,</L>
<L>Sal &thorn;an be open &thorn;am to kepe,</L>
<L>&THORN;e erthe &thorn;at &thorn;ai sal on stand sal scake,</L>
<L>Thurgh &thorn;air syn, and tremble and whake<NOTE PLACE="foot">qwake (MS. Harl. 4196).</NOTE>,</L>
<L N="5412">Swa &thorn;at unnethes it sal &thorn;am bere,</L>
<L>Swa mykel &thorn;air syn &thorn;e erth sal dere.</L>
<L>&THORN;e world obout &thorn;am sal be brinnande,</L>
<L>&THORN;e devels on ilk syde &thorn;am sal stande,</L>
<L N="5416">Gret sorow sal be omang &thorn;am &thorn;ar;</L>
<L>&THORN;e heven oboven sal strike &thorn;am sar,</L>
<L>With thundirs dyntes and levenyngs togyder;</L>
<L>&THORN;ai wald &thorn;an fle and wate never whider;</L>
<L N="5420">&THORN;ai sal be umset swa on ilka side,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ai may nouthir fle ne &thorn;am hide.</L>
<L>Many accusers &thorn;ar sal be &thorn;an,</L>
<L>To accuse &thorn;am byfor &thorn;at domesman;</L>
<L N="5424">For I fynd written, als yhe sal here,</L>
<L>Fiften maneres of accusours sere,</L>
<L>&THORN;at sal accuse in &thorn;at dredeful day</L>
<L>&THORN;e synful men, &thorn;at es to say,</L>
<L N="5428">Conscience &thorn;at es called Ynwitt,</L>
<L>And &thorn;air awen syns, and hali writt,</L>
<L>Gods creatures &thorn;at we ken,</L>
<L>Devels and aungels and haythen men,</L>
<L N="5432">And martirs &thorn;at has feled tourments sere,</L>
<L>And othir &thorn;at wranges has tholed here.</L>
<L>Mens sons and doghters unchastyede,</L>
<L>Pover men &thorn;at &thorn;air nede myght noght hyde,</L>
<L N="5436">Suggettes, and benefices receyved here.</L>
<L>&THORN;e tourmentes of Cristes passioun sere;</L>
<L>And God hym-self and alle &thorn;e trinit&eacute;,</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;ere ogayne &thorn;e synful sal be.</L>
<L N="5440">First sal &thorn;air awen conscience,</L>
<L>Accuse &thorn;am &thorn;an in Cristes presence,
<PB REF="00000192.tif" N="148"></L>
<L>Openly and noght in privet&eacute;;</L>
<L>For na thyng &thorn;an sal hidde be,</L>
<L N="5444">Alle thyng sal be shewed &thorn;ar oppenly;</L>
<L>For Danyel says &thorn;us in his prophecy:</L>
<L>"<I>Sedit iudicium et libri aperti sunt.</I>"</L>
<L>"&THORN;edome sattand &thorn;e bokes er oppen wyde";</L>
<L N="5448">And &thorn;us sal be sene &thorn;at tyde.</L>
<L>&THORN;e bokes er conscience and noght elles,</L>
<L>Als &thorn;e glose &thorn;ar-on &thorn;us telles:</L>
<L><I>Consciencie omnibus revelabuntur.</I></L>
<L N="5452">"Conscience", it says, "of ilka thyng</L>
<L>Sal be shewed til alle mens knawyng."</L>
<L>&THORN;air syns alswa, bathe mare and les,</L>
<L>Sal &thorn;am accuse, als &thorn;e boke bers wittnes.</L>
<L N="5456">For &thorn;air syns sal ay witth &thorn;am last,</L>
<L>Als &thorn;ai war bunden obout &thorn;air nekes fast,</L>
<L>&THORN;e whilk &thorn;am sal accuse &thorn;at day;</L>
<L>Agayn wham &thorn;ai sal noght kun say;</L>
<L N="5460">And als stolne thyng wreghes a thefe funden,</L>
<L>When it es obout his neke fast bounden,</L>
<L>Right swa &thorn;air syns sal wreghe &thorn;am &thorn;ar,</L>
<L>Als &thorn;ai bunden obout &thorn;air nekes war,</L>
<L N="5464">And &thorn;an sal &thorn;air syns say &thorn;us;</L>
<L>Til ilka synful man "&thorn;ou wroght us,</L>
<L>And we er &thorn;in with-outen dout,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ou has lang borne us obout."</L>
<L N="5468">Alswa accuse sal haly writt,</L>
<L>Namly &thorn;as men &thorn;at knawes it,</L>
<L>Or &thorn;e poyntes has herde &thorn;at falls &thorn;ar-to,</L>
<L>And wald noght aftir haly writt do.</L>
<L N="5472">Yhit sal Godes creatures sere,</L>
<L>Accuse &thorn;am on diverse manere,</L>
<L>Als &thorn;e son and &thorn;e mone and &thorn;e sterns,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e elementes &thorn;a[t] us governs;</L>
<L N="5476">And alle &thorn;e werld sal be &thorn;an redy,</L>
<L>To accuse &thorn;e synful men oppenly;</L>
<L>For alle creatoures hate &thorn;am sal,</L>
<L>When he es wrathe &thorn;at es maker of alle.
<PB REF="00000193.tif" N="149"></L>
<L N="5480">Alswa devels sal accuse &thorn;am &thorn;ar</L>
<L>Of alle &thorn;air syns, bathe les and mar.</L>
<L>And of &thorn;a syns &thorn;at &thorn;ai sal out-say,</L>
<L>Til whilk &thorn;ai egged &thorn;am, bathe nyght and day,</L>
<L N="5484">And of &thorn;as &thorn;ai sal &thorn;am &thorn;ar accuse,</L>
<L>Als a thefe his felaghe of theft duse,</L>
<L>&THORN;at hym accuses of &thorn;e same thyng</L>
<L>&THORN;at he with hym did thurgh his eggyng;</L>
<L N="5488">&THORN;e devels at &thorn;e dome sal be redy,</L>
<L>&THORN;at to tempte men here ay er bysy;</L>
<L>And &thorn;ai write alle syns, bathe les and mar,</L>
<L>Of whylk &thorn;ai may accuse &thorn;am &thorn;ar,</L>
<L N="5492">And alle syns &thorn;ai sal reherce &thorn;an,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ar-for &thorn;us says Iob, &thorn;e halyman:</L>
<L><I>Scribis Domine contra me amaritudines,</I></L>
<L><I>id est, permittis scribi contra me peccata amara.</I></L>
<L N="5496">"Loverd, &thorn;ou suffers here", says he,</L>
<L>"Be writen bitter syns ogaynes me."</L>
<L>Aungeles alswa, als we here clerkes say,</L>
<L>Sal accuse &thorn;e synful men at &thorn;at day,</L>
<L N="5500">For God &thorn;at til &thorn;am &thorn;air sauls touke,</L>
<L>For to kepe here als says &thorn;e buke,</L>
<L>Sal aske of &thorn;am, at his comyng,</L>
<L>Acount to yhelde of &thorn;air kepyng;</L>
<L N="5504">&THORN;an sal &thorn;e aungels answere &thorn;ar-to,</L>
<L>And say &thorn;us, "our rede &thorn;ai wald noght do</L>
<L>Bot agayne our wille foly &thorn;ai wald use",</L>
<L>&THORN;us sal aungels &thorn;e synful accuse.</L>
<L N="5508">Alswa haythen men, als says &thorn;e buke,</L>
<L>&THORN;at never baptem ne right trouthe tuke,</L>
<L>Als Iewes and Sarzyns and Paens,</L>
<L>&THORN;at wate noght what Criestes law bymens,</L>
<L N="5512">Sal &thorn;an accuse als men sal se,</L>
<L>&THORN;e fals cristen &thorn;at dampned sal be,</L>
<L>For &thorn;e haythen men at &thorn;at grete assys</L>
<L>Sal &thorn;an be halden als men rightwys,</L>
<L N="5516">To regard of &thorn;e fals cristen men</L>
<L>&THORN;at wald noght kepe &thorn;e comandmentes ten.
<PB REF="00000194.tif" N="150"></L>
<L>Bot spendes &thorn;air fyve wittes in vayne,</L>
<L>&THORN;arfor &thorn;ai sal have mykel mare payne,</L>
<L N="5520">In &thorn;e pitte of helle &thorn;at &thorn;am sal mar griefe</L>
<L>&THORN;an &thorn;e haithen men of mysbylyefe.</L>
<L>&THORN;e halghes alswa sal accuse alle &thorn;a,</L>
<L>&THORN;at sal be dampned and to helle ga;</L>
<L N="5524">And namly martirs, Godes awen knyghtes,</L>
<L>&THORN;ai sal accuse &thorn;e synful wyghtes,</L>
<L>Als &thorn;e tirauntes &thorn;at &thorn;am pyned and sloghe,</L>
<L>And othir &thorn;at &thorn;am til tourmentes droghe,</L>
<L N="5528">Of wham vengeance til God &thorn;ai cry,</L>
<L>Als &thorn;e appocalips &thorn;us shewes &thorn;ar-by:</L>
<L><I>Usquequo Domine sanctus et verus, non vindicas</I></L>
<L><I>sanguinem nostrum de hiis qui habitant in terra.</I></L>
<L N="5532">&THORN;at es "haly Loverd, sothefast and gude,</L>
<L>How lange sal be ar &thorn;ow venge our blude</L>
<L>Of our enemys &thorn;at in erthe duelles."</L>
<L>On &thorn;is manere &thorn;e appocalips telles;</L>
<L N="5536">Sen &thorn;ai to God ay vengance cry,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;am &thorn;at of &thorn;air blude er gilty,</L>
<L>Howe suld &thorn;ai &thorn;an in &thorn;e tyme of wreke</L>
<L>Be stille and noght ogayne &thorn;am speke?</L>
<L N="5540">Alswa alle &thorn;as &thorn;at has tholed here</L>
<L>Fals[h]edes and wrangs on sere manere,</L>
<L>Sal &thorn;at day accuse &thorn;am sone,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;am has here gret wranges done.</L>
<L N="5544">Yhit sons and doghters &thorn;at unchastyd war</L>
<L>Sal accuse &thorn;a[i]r fadirs and modirs &thorn;ar,</L>
<L>For-&thorn;i &thorn;at &thorn;ai war rekles and slawe</L>
<L>To chasty &thorn;am and hald &thorn;am in awe,</L>
<L N="5548">And to teche &thorn;am gude thewes,</L>
<L>And &thorn;arfor &thorn;e wys man &thorn;us in buke shewes</L>
<L><I>De patre impio conquerentur filii, quoniam</I></L>
<L><I>propter ipsum sunt in opprobrium.</I></L>
<L N="5552">"&THORN;e sons sal pleyne &thorn;am &thorn;an", says he,</L>
<L>"Of &thorn;e ille fader and agayn hym be,</L>
<L>For thurgh defaute of hym er &thorn;ai</L>
<L>In grete reprove", &thorn;at es to say,
<PB REF="00000195.tif" N="151"></L>
<L N="5556">In defaut of his disciplyne,</L>
<L>Parchaunce, be dampned til helle pyne,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e fader alswa be with &thorn;am spilte,</L>
<L>For he es &thorn;e cause of &thorn;air gilte.</L>
<L N="5560">Yhit &thorn;e pover sal &thorn;am ple[y]ne thurgh right,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e riche men in Godes syght,</L>
<L>And accuse &thorn;am &thorn;an ful grevosly,</L>
<L>For &thorn;ai had of &thorn;am na mercy,</L>
<L N="5564">For to helpe &thorn;am here in &thorn;air nede,</L>
<L>Nouthir to clathe &thorn;am ne to fede,</L>
<L>Bot lete silver and gold on &thorn;am rust,</L>
<L>&THORN;e whilk &thorn;ai had in hurde uptrust;</L>
<L N="5568">And &thorn;ar-of til pure wald noght gyve,</L>
<L>When &thorn;ai sawe &thorn;am at meschyve,</L>
<L>&THORN;ar-for &thorn;e ruste of &thorn;at moweld mon&eacute;</L>
<L>Agayne &thorn;am &thorn;an sal wittnes be.</L>
<L N="5572">And wormes and moghes on &thorn;e same manere,</L>
<L>&THORN;at in &thorn;air clathes has bred here,</L>
<L>&THORN;e whilk &thorn;ai had here over mesur,</L>
<L>And of &thorn;am wald noght parte til &thorn;e pur,</L>
<L N="5576">Sal &thorn;at day be in wittenes broght,</L>
<L>For &thorn;e pure &thorn;at &thorn;ai helped noght.</L>
<L>Alswa &thorn;a &thorn;at sugettes war til man,</L>
<L>Sal accuse &thorn;air soveraynes &thorn;an,</L>
<L N="5580">And<NOTE PLACE="foot">&THORN;at?</NOTE> &thorn;am has greved thurgh maystr&eacute; and myght</L>
<L>And of other wald do &thorn;am na right.</L>
<L>&THORN;e benefices &thorn;at God did &thorn;am here,</L>
<L>Sal &thorn;am accuse on sere manere,</L>
<L N="5584">For agayne &thorn;am sal Crist allege sone,</L>
<L>And shewe &thorn;am what he had &thorn;am done,</L>
<L>And reherce his benefices, mare and les,</L>
<L>To reprove &thorn;am of &thorn;air unkyndenes.</L>
<L N="5588">Yhit &thorn;e tourmentes of Cristes passioun,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he tholed for mans salvacioun,</L>
<L>Sal &thorn;am accuse at &thorn;at gret dome,</L>
<L>For-why &thorn;us says Saynt Ierome:</L>
<L N="5592"><I>Crux contra te perorabit, Christus</I></L>
<L><I>per vulnera sua, contra te allegabit,</I>
<PB REF="00000196.tif" N="152"></L>
<L><I>cicatrices contra te loquentur,</I></L>
<L><I>clavi de te conquerentur.</I></L>
<L N="5596">He says "&thorn;e croyce on whilk he dieghed for man</L>
<L>Sal stratly pray ogayne &thorn;e &thorn;an,</L>
<L>And Crist, thurgh his wondes wide,</L>
<L>Ogayne &thorn;e sal allege &thorn;at tyde;</L>
<L N="5600">&THORN;e erres of his wondes sal speke</L>
<L>Og[a]yne &thorn;e and of &thorn;e aske wreke;</L>
<L>&THORN;e nayles &thorn;at in his hend and fete stak,</L>
<L>On &thorn;e sal pleyne and gret playnt mak."</L>
<L N="5604">At &thorn;e last, God hym-self, mast of myght,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e trinit&eacute; sal accuse &thorn;am right,</L>
<L>For &thorn;ai wrethed God in &thorn;air legge poust&eacute;,</L>
<L>And alle &thorn;e parsons of &thorn;e trinit&eacute;,</L>
<L N="5608">Bathe &thorn;e fadir and &thorn;e son and &thorn;e haly gast.</L>
<L>&THORN;ar-for &thorn;at accusyng sal be mast,</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;e secunde parson &thorn;an alle sale deme,</L>
<L>&THORN;at es Crist Godes son, &thorn;at &thorn;an man sal seme.</L>
<L N="5612">Alle &thorn;at sal com byfor Crist &thorn;at day,</L>
<L>Sal strayt acounte yhelde, ar &thorn;ai passe away,</L>
<L>Of alle &thorn;air lif howe &thorn;ai here lyved,</L>
<L>&THORN;an sal be sene what &thorn;ai God gryeved</L>
<L N="5616">And byfor alle &thorn;e werld shewed sal be,</L>
<L>Oppenly and noght in privit&eacute;;</L>
<L>And byfor halghes and aungels bright,</L>
<L>And byfor devels horribel til mans sight,</L>
<L N="5620">And byfor alle wykked men alswa,</L>
<L>&THORN;at sal be dampned til endles wa.</L>
<L>For alle sal be &thorn;an &thorn;are, gude and ille,</L>
<L>To deme and be demed als rightwysnes wille;</L>
<L N="5624">For Crist, &thorn;at rightwyse domesman,</L>
<L>Sal calle alle men byfor hym &thorn;an,</L>
<L>Als &thorn;e prophet David bers witnes,</L>
<L>In psauter whare &thorn;us writen es:</L>
<L N="5628"><I>Advocavit celum desursum et terram,</I></L>
<L><I>discernere populum suum.</I></L>
<L>He says "he sal bifor hym calle</L>
<L>&THORN;e heven fra aboven and &thorn;e erthe alle,
<PB REF="00000197.tif" N="153"></L>
<L N="5632">For to deme right his folk &thorn;at day."</L>
<L>And &thorn;is vers es &thorn;us mykel at say,</L>
<L>He sal calle &thorn;an heven byfor hym tit,</L>
<L>&THORN;at es to say, haly men and parfit,</L>
<L N="5636">&THORN;at with hym in dome &thorn;an sal sitt,</L>
<L>And wyth hym deme, als says haly writt;</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;e erthe es noght elles to telle,</L>
<L>Bot wykked men and devels of helle,</L>
<L N="5640">&THORN;e whilk he sal calle at his wille,</L>
<L>For to chede<NOTE PLACE="foot">chese (MS. Harl. 4196).</NOTE> out &thorn;e gude fra &thorn;e ille.</L>
<L>&THORN;an sal ilka man &thorn;arof &thorn;air lyfyng</L>
<L>Be sette until and<NOTE PLACE="foot">ane (MS. Harl. 4196).</NOTE> hard rekkenyng,</L>
<L N="5644">For men sal &thorn;an strayte acount yhelde</L>
<L>Of alle &thorn;air tyme of yhouthe and elde;</L>
<L>Noght anly of ane or twa yhere,</L>
<L>Bot alle &thorn;e tyme &thorn;at &thorn;ai lyfed here,</L>
<L N="5648">And specyaly of ilka moment,</L>
<L>Of alle &thorn;e tyme &thorn;at God &thorn;am lent.</L>
<L>A moment of tyme es nan othir thyng,</L>
<L>Bot a short space als of a eghe twynklyng.</L>
<L N="5652">Na moment sal be unrekend &thorn;an,</L>
<L>Als Saynt Bernard says, &thorn;e halyman:</L>
<L><I>Sicut non peribit capillus de capite,</I></L>
<L><I>ita non erit momentum de toto</I></L>
<L N="5656"><I>tempore de quo sane</I></L>
<L><I>non conqueratur.</I></L>
<L>He says "als nan hare of alle &thorn;e hed</L>
<L>Sal perisse &thorn;at tyme in na sted,</L>
<L N="5660">Right swa sal be na moment,</L>
<L>Of alle &thorn;e tyme &thorn;at God had<NOTE PLACE="foot">has (MS. Harl. 4196).</NOTE> sent,</L>
<L>Of whilk sal be made na pleynyng."</L>
<L>In &thorn;e tyme of &thorn;at last rekkenyng,</L>
<L N="5664">Alswa &thorn;ai sal yhelde acount certayne,</L>
<L>Of ilk idel worde, spoken in vayne,</L>
<L>&THORN;at es to say, &thorn;at war fruytles,</L>
<L>Als haly writt bers wittnes:
<PB REF="00000198.tif" N="154"></L>
<L N="5668"><I>De omni verbo ociosi in die iudicii</I></L>
<L><I>reddenda est racio.</I></L>
<L>&THORN;e buke says shortly on &thorn;is manere:</L>
<L>"Of ilkan idel word and vayne here,</L>
<L N="5672">Reson sal be yholden right</L>
<L>At &thorn;e day of dome, in Goddes sight;"</L>
<L>And noght anely of idel wordes sayd,</L>
<L>Bot of ilk idel thoght &thorn;at God noght payd,</L>
<L N="5676">For excuse &thorn;am may &thorn;ai noght</L>
<L>Nouther of idel worde ne of thoght,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ai spak or thoght aftir &thorn;ai had witt,</L>
<L>Of whilk &thorn;ai war never here qwitt;</L>
<L N="5680">Wharfor our Loverd God alle-myghty,</L>
<L>Spekes &thorn;us thurgh &thorn;e prophet Ysay:</L>
<L><I>Ego cogitaciones eorum venio ut congregem</I></L>
<L><I>cum gentibus ad iudicandum sicut iudico gentes.</I></L>
<L N="5684">He says "I com to gadir with men</L>
<L>&THORN;e thoghtes of &thorn;am &thorn;at I ken,</L>
<L>For to deme &thorn;am alle, mar and les,</L>
<L>Als I sal men deme, thurgh rightwysnes."</L>
<L N="5688">Many aght be dredand &thorn;ar-for,</L>
<L>And yhit sais &thorn;us Saynt Gregor:</L>
<L><I>Ergo sic Deus vias cuiuscunque considerat</I></L>
<L><I>ut nec minutissime cogitaciones, que</I></L>
<L N="5692"><I>apud vos usu valuerunt, in iudicio</I></L>
<L><I>indiscusse remaneant.</I></L>
<L>He says "God", &thorn;at alle wysdom kan,</L>
<L>"Swa byhaldes &thorn;e wayes of ilk man</L>
<L N="5696">&THORN;at &thorn;e lest thoghtes &thorn;at thurgh use had yhe</L>
<L>In &thorn;e dome sal noght undiscussed be."</L>
<L>And noght anely of idel word and thoght,</L>
<L>Bot of alle idel werk &thorn;ai ever men wroght;</L>
<L N="5700">&THORN;ai sal alswa yhit acount yhelde</L>
<L>Noght anly of gret dedes of elde,</L>
<L>Bot of smale dedes of &thorn;air yhouthe,</L>
<L>Fra &thorn;e tyme &thorn;at &thorn;ai any witt couthe,</L>
<L N="5704">&THORN;at &thorn;ai had wroght, bathe nyghtes and days,</L>
<L>And &thorn;arfor Salamon &thorn;us says:
<PB REF="00000199.tif" N="155"></L>
<L><I>Letare iuvenis in adolescencia tua, et in</I></L>
<L><I>bono sit cor tuum in diebus iuventutis tue,</I></L>
<L N="5708"><I>et ambula in viis cordis tui et in tuitu</I></L>
<L><I>oculorum tuorum; Et scito quod pro</I></L>
<L><I>omnibus hiis te adducet</I></L>
<L><I>dominus in iudicium.</I></L>
<L N="5712">He says "&thorn;ou yhung man be glad and blithe,</L>
<L>In &thorn;i yhouthede &thorn;at passes swithe,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at &thorn;i hert in gude be stedfast,</L>
<L>Whilles &thorn;e days of &thorn;i youthe sal last</L>
<L N="5716">And in &thorn;e ways of &thorn;e herht ga</L>
<L>And in &thorn;e syght of &thorn;in eghen twa;</L>
<L>And wytt &thorn;ou for alle &thorn;is of yhouthede,</L>
<L>Our Loverd sal &thorn;e into &thorn;e dome lede;"</L>
<L N="5720">Whar resons sal be yholden sere;</L>
<L>And &thorn;arfor says Iob on &thorn;is manere:</L>
<L><I>Et consumere ne vis peccatis adolescencie mee.</I></L>
<L>"Loverd wil &thorn;ou waste me to noght</L>
<L N="5724">Thurgh &thorn;e syns &thorn;at I haf wroght,"</L>
<L>Alswa men sal &thorn;an yhelde acount sone,</L>
<L>Noght anly of &thorn;at &thorn;at &thorn;ai wrang had done</L>
<L>Witandly thurgh &thorn;air knawyng,</L>
<L N="5728">Bot alswa of &thorn;at &thorn;at &thorn;ai did thurgh erryng,</L>
<L>Of whilk &thorn;ai sal noght be excused &thorn;an,</L>
<L>Als in buk &thorn;us says &thorn;e wyse man:</L>
<L><I>Pro omni errato, sine bonum sine malum</I></L>
<L N="5732"><I>sit, adducetur homo in iudicio.</I></L>
<L>He says "for ilka thyng &thorn;at erred es</L>
<L>Be it gude or ille, mar or les,</L>
<L>Man, at &thorn;e last day, sal be ledde</L>
<L N="5736">To &thorn;e dome &thorn;at es mast dredde;"</L>
<L>And &thorn;arfor David, als &thorn;e psauter shewes us,</L>
<L>Was ful dredand, &thorn;at says &thorn;us:</L>
<L><I>Et ignorancias meas me memineris.</I></L>
<L N="5740">"Loverd" he says, "ne mene &thorn;ou noght</L>
<L>Of my freyle unknawynges of thoght."</L>
<L>Yhit sal &thorn;ai yhelde acunt withdrede,</L>
<L>Noght anly of ilk apert ille dede,
<PB REF="00000200.tif" N="156"></L>
<L N="5744">Bot alswa of ilkan ille dede priv&eacute;,</L>
<L>&THORN;at semed by syght &thorn;at gude suld be;</L>
<L>For some dede &thorn;at ille es, sems gud here,</L>
<L>For Saynt Gregor says on &thorn;is manere:</L>
<L N="5748"><I>Interdum sordet in oculis iudicis quod</I></L>
<L><I>fulget in oculis auditoris.</I></L>
<L>He says "some tyme es foule in &thorn;e domes man sight</L>
<L>&THORN;at in eghe of &thorn;e herer shynes bright."</L>
<L N="5752">Bot at &thorn;e dome sal &thorn;at discused be,</L>
<L>Als in &thorn;e psalme men may written se:</L>
<L><I>Cum accipero tempus.</I></L>
<L><I>Ego iusticias iudicabo.</I></L>
<L N="5756">God says &thorn;is wordes thurgh &thorn;e prophet David</L>
<L>And many othir &thorn;at accordes &thorn;ar-with,</L>
<L>He says "when I haf tyme receyved right</L>
<L>I sal deme rightwysnes, thurgh myght."</L>
<L N="5760">Alswa yhit men byhoves nedly &thorn;an,</L>
<L>Yhelde acount byfor &thorn;e domes man,</L>
<L>Noght anely of werkes &thorn;at &thorn;ai had wroght,</L>
<L>Bot alswa of dedes &thorn;at &thorn;ai did noght,</L>
<L N="5764">And of werkes of mercy and of almus</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ai noght did, for &thorn;e godspelle shewes &thorn;us:</L>
<L><I>Esurivi et non dedistis michi manducare,</I></L>
<L><I>sitivi et non dedidistis michi bibere.</I></L>
<L N="5768">&THORN;is es, als yhe sal aftirward here,</L>
<L>How God sal say on &thorn;is manere:</L>
<L>"I hungerd, and yhe me noght fedde,</L>
<L>I thrested, and yhe me na drynk bedde."</L>
<L N="5772">For &thorn;is &thorn;ai sal be aresoned straytly,</L>
<L>And for other werkes noght done of mercy.</L>
<L>And noght anely for &thorn;a werkes noght don,</L>
<L>Bot for &thorn;e gude &thorn;at &thorn;ar-of myght haf commen son.</L>
<L N="5776">Men byhoves alswa acount yhelde</L>
<L>Of &thorn;air saules, &thorn;at &thorn;am byhoved welde,</L>
<L>And haf in kepyng whille &thorn;ai myght lif,</L>
<L>Of whilk &thorn;ai sal &thorn;an answer gyf.</L>
<L N="5780">Now if a kyng of a riche kyngryke</L>
<L>&THORN;at had a doghter, &thorn;at war hym like
<PB REF="00000201.tif" N="157"></L>
<L>Of bewt&eacute; and of face and body,</L>
<L>&THORN;e whilk he luved specialy</L>
<L N="5784">And eghtild to mak hir qwene of worshepe,</L>
<L>And bytaght hir til his ryfe to kepe,</L>
<L>If he &thorn;ar aftir keped hir mys,</L>
<L>Me thynk it war na dout of &thorn;is</L>
<L N="5788">&THORN;at ne &thorn;e kyng wald haf rekkenyng,</L>
<L>And acount and answer of &thorn;at kepyng.</L>
<L>For it semes &thorn;at &thorn;e kyng had grete encheson</L>
<L>To sette hym for &thorn;at kepyng to reson,</L>
<L N="5792">And &thorn;e mare rekkesly<NOTE PLACE="foot">reklesly (MS. Harl. 4196).</NOTE> &thorn;at he hir yhemed</L>
<L>&THORN;e mare grevosly hym aght be demed.</L>
<L>What suld &thorn;e kyng of heven do &thorn;an,</L>
<L>Of a man or of a woman,</L>
<L N="5796">Til wham he has bytaght to kepe here,</L>
<L>His doghtir &thorn;at es hym leve and dere,</L>
<L>&THORN;at es man saul his awen liknes,</L>
<L>Whilles it fra dedly syn keped es,</L>
<L N="5800">&THORN;e whilk he eghteld to coroun qwene</L>
<L>In heven &thorn;ar ioy sal ay be sene?</L>
<L>Whaswa es rekles and kepes it ille,</L>
<L>He sal be aresoned, and &thorn;at es skille,</L>
<L N="5804">Of &thorn;e kepyng of it &thorn;at he tuke;</L>
<L>&THORN;arfor &thorn;e wyse man says &thorn;us in his buke:</L>
<L><I>Custodi solicite</I></L>
<L><I>animam tuam.</I></L>
<L N="5808">&THORN;at es on Ynglis in &thorn;is manere,</L>
<L>He says "kepe &thorn;i saul bysily here".</L>
<L>Bot he es sely &thorn;at may sikerly say</L>
<L>In &thorn;e tyme of &thorn;e dede at his last day</L>
<L N="5812">'I yhelde my saul in &thorn;is dede stour</L>
<L>Til &thorn;e Loverd &thorn;at es my saveour.'</L>
<L>Men sal yhit yhelde acount stray[t]ly</L>
<L>Noght of &thorn;air saules with-in anely</L>
<L N="5816">Bot alswa of &thorn;air bodys with-oute</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ai had to kepe, and bare aboute</L>
<L>Of whilk &thorn;ai sal yhelde rekkenyng,</L>
<L>Sen &thorn;ai had &thorn;ar-of &thorn;e kepyng.
<PB REF="00000202.tif" N="158"></L>
<L N="5820">Ilka mans body may be cald,</L>
<L>Als a castelle here for to hald,</L>
<L>&THORN;at til man es gyfen of God to kepe</L>
<L>For his profit and Goddes worshepe.</L>
<L N="5824">&THORN;e enemys ofte assales it hard</L>
<L>And &thorn;arfor says Saynt Bernard:</L>
<L><I>Bonum castrum custodit</I></L>
<L><I>qui corpus suum custodit.</I></L>
<L N="5828">"A gude castelle" he says, "kepes he</L>
<L>"&THORN;at his body kepes in honest&eacute;."</L>
<L>Man sal yhelde acount alswa,</L>
<L>At &thorn;e dome, ar &thorn;ai &thorn;e&thorn;en ga,</L>
<L N="5832">&THORN;at stratly of &thorn;am sal be tane;</L>
<L>Noght anely of &thorn;e saules by &thorn;am ane,</L>
<L>Ne anely of &thorn;air bodys &thorn;ar-by,</L>
<L>Bot of bathe togidir ioyntly,</L>
<L N="5836">&THORN;at es to say, ilkan sal &thorn;an</L>
<L>Yhelde acount of alle hale a man,</L>
<L>For a man properly may noght be cald,</L>
<L>Bot-if &thorn;e body and saul togidir hald</L>
<L N="5840">&THORN;e saule be itself man es nane,</L>
<L>Ne &thorn;e body with-out saule by it ane.</L>
<L>Bot man may be called on twyn manere,</L>
<L>Whilles &thorn;ai bathe er knyt togyder here.</L>
<L N="5844">For &thorn;es clerkes &thorn;at gret clergy can</L>
<L>Calles man bathe Inner man and utter man.</L>
<L>Inner man onence &thorn;e saule anely</L>
<L>And utter man onence &thorn;e body.</L>
<L N="5848">Bot &thorn;e body and saule bytwene &thorn;am twa,</L>
<L>Makes bot a man and na ma,</L>
<L>&THORN;arfor men sal yhelde acount ioyntly</L>
<L>Of bathe togyder, &thorn;e saule and &thorn;e body;</L>
<L N="5852">And for&thorn;i &thorn;at God, aftir his stature,</L>
<L>Made man mast digne and noble creature</L>
<L>&THORN;arfor if man be til God frawarde</L>
<L>And unkynde and of hym tak na rewarde,</L>
<L N="5856">&THORN;at ilk dignit&eacute; of man namely,</L>
<L>Sal, at &thorn;e dome, yhelde hym gylty.
<PB REF="00000203.tif" N="159"></L>
<L>Yhit sal men yhelde acount [noght] anely</L>
<L>Of &thorn;air self, bot of other many,</L>
<L N="5860">&THORN;at es to say, of ilka neghebur,</L>
<L>&THORN;at men fals to help and to socur.</L>
<L>For God til ilk man commandes right</L>
<L>To helpe his neghebur after his myght.</L>
<L N="5864">And &thorn;as, &thorn;at may helpe and wille noght,</L>
<L>Sal &thorn;an til ful strayt acount be broght.</L>
<L>Alswa fadirs and modirs, at &thorn;at day,</L>
<L>Sal yhelde acount, &thorn;at es to say,</L>
<L N="5868">Of sons and doghtirs &thorn;at &thorn;ai forthe broght,</L>
<L>&THORN;e whilk &thorn;ai here chastied noght.</L>
<L>And loverds alswa of &thorn;air meign&eacute;</L>
<L>&THORN;e whilk &thorn;ai lete uniustifyed be</L>
<L N="5872">And maysters of &thorn;air disciples alswa,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ai lete be unthewed, and untaght ga,</L>
<L>And chastid &thorn;am noght, ne &thorn;am wald lere,</L>
<L>For&thorn;i says Salamon on &thorn;is manere:</L>
<L N="5876"><I>Virga discipline fugabit stulticiam</I></L>
<L><I>in corde pueri colligatam.</I></L>
<L>"&THORN;e wande", he says, "of disciplyne smert,</L>
<L>Sal chace foly out of &thorn;e childes hert."</L>
<L N="5880">&THORN;arfor maysters som tyme uses &thorn;e wand</L>
<L>&THORN;at has childer to lere undir &thorn;air hand.</L>
<L>Prelats of ordir and of dignyt&eacute;</L>
<L>Sal acount yhelde in sere degr&eacute;</L>
<L N="5884">Of &thorn;air suggets undir &thorn;air powere,</L>
<L>How &thorn;ai &thorn;am reweld in &thorn;is lyf here,</L>
<L>And answer of &thorn;am &thorn;at lyfed noght wele,</L>
<L>For &thorn;us says &thorn;e prophet Ezechiele:</L>
<L N="5888"><I>Ecce! ego requiram gregem</I></L>
<L><I>meam de manu pastoris.</I></L>
<L>God says &thorn;us thurgh &thorn;e prophete:</L>
<L>"Lo! I sal aske my flok of shepe</L>
<L N="5892">Of &thorn;e hird &thorn;at had &thorn;am undir his hand;"</L>
<L>Of &thorn;is word aght prelates be dredand.</L>
<L>Men sal alswa yhelde rekkenynges sere</L>
<L>Of al gudes pat God has gefen &thorn;am here,
<PB REF="00000204.tif" N="160"></L>
<L N="5896">Als of gudes of kynde and gudes of graces,</L>
<L>And gudes of hap &thorn;at men purchases.</L>
<L>&THORN;e gudes of kynd er bodily strenthe,</L>
<L>And semely shappe of brede and lenthe</L>
<L N="5900">And delyvernes and bewt&eacute; of body;</L>
<L>Swilk gudes of kynd here has many.</L>
<L>Gudes of grace may &thorn;ir be,</L>
<L>Mynde, and witte, and sutilt&eacute;,</L>
<L N="5904">And fair shewyng of speche sutille,</L>
<L>And knawyng bathe of gude and ille,</L>
<L>Vertus of grete devocioun</L>
<L>And luf of lyf of contemplacioun.</L>
<L N="5908">Gudes of hap er &thorn;ir to gesce,</L>
<L>Als honours, power, and ryche[s].</L>
<L>Of alle &thorn;ir gudes men byhoves</L>
<L>Yhelde acounte, als &thorn;e buke pruves,</L>
<L N="5912">And answer straytly of &thorn;am alle.</L>
<L>I drede many in arrirage<NOTE PLACE="foot">rerage (MS. Harl. 4196).</NOTE> mon falle,</L>
<L>And til perpetuele prison gang,</L>
<L>For &thorn;ai despended &thorn;a gudes wrang,</L>
<L N="5916">For-whi God has gyfen here nathyng,</L>
<L>Of whilk he wille noght haf rekkennyng.</L>
<L>Som sal yhit, als I sayd ar,</L>
<L>Yhelde acount ful straytly &thorn;ar</L>
<L N="5920">Of &thorn;e gudes &thorn;at &thorn;ai wald noght bede</L>
<L>Til other &thorn;at of &thorn;am had nede,</L>
<L>For alle er we als a body here,</L>
<L>For &thorn;e apostel says on &thorn;is manere:</L>
<L N="5924"><I>Omnes enim unum</I></L>
<L><I>corpus sumus.</I></L>
<L>He says "we er alle als a body",</L>
<L>&THORN;at has diverse lyms many.</L>
<L N="5928">And als a lym of a body here</L>
<L>Es redy, aftir it has powere,</L>
<L>To serve alle &thorn;e other, mar and les,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;at office &thorn;at gyven it es,
<PB REF="00000205.tif" N="161"></L>
<L N="5932">Right swa ilk man &thorn;at here lyfes,</L>
<L>Of alle &thorn;at God thurgh grace him gyfes,</L>
<L>Suld other serve, &thorn;at &thorn;ar-of has nede,</L>
<L>Als he wille answere at &thorn;e day of drede.</L>
<L N="5936">Ful many men lyfes here of &thorn;a</L>
<L>&THORN;at er halden for to do swa,</L>
<L>Als he &thorn;at gret and myghty es,</L>
<L>Es halden to defende &thorn;am &thorn;at er les;</L>
<L N="5940">And &thorn;e ryche &thorn;at mykel rychesces has,</L>
<L>To gyf &thorn;am &thorn;at here in povert gas;</L>
<L>And men of laghe alswa to travayle</L>
<L>And to counsaile &thorn;am &thorn;at askes counsayle;</L>
<L N="5944">And leches alswa, if &thorn;ai wyse ware,</L>
<L>To hele &thorn;am &thorn;at er seke and sare;</L>
<L>And maysters of &thorn;air science to ken,</L>
<L>Namly, &thorn;am &thorn;at er unlered men;</L>
<L N="5948">And precheours Goddes worde to preche,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e way of lyf other to teche.</L>
<L>&THORN;us es ilk man halden with gude entent,</L>
<L>To help other of &thorn;at God has &thorn;am lent</L>
<L N="5952">Frely for Goddes luf, and for noght elles,</L>
<L>Wharfor Saynt Petre &thorn;e apostel &thorn;us telles:</L>
<L><I>Unusquisque, sicut accipit graciam, in alte|</I></L>
<L><I>rutrum illam administrare debet.</I></L>
<L N="5956">He says "ilk man &thorn;at grace has here</L>
<L>Als he resayves grace, on &thorn;e same manere</L>
<L>Suld he it ministre and frely bede</L>
<L>Til ilkan other &thorn;at &thorn;ai<NOTE PLACE="foot">&THORN;ar?</NOTE> of has nede"</L>
<L N="5960">And &thorn;us es ilk man halden to do,</L>
<L>For in &thorn;e godspelle yhitsays God mar &thorn;arto:</L>
<L><I>Quod gratis accepistis,</I></L>
<L><I>gratis date.</I></L>
<L N="5964">He says "&thorn;at &thorn;at yhe haf of grace fre</L>
<L>And frely resayved, frely gyf yhe."</L>
<L>&THORN;us sal men &thorn;an yhelde resons sere</L>
<L>Of alle &thorn;air lyf, als writen es here,</L>
<L N="5968">&THORN;at es of alle tymes spended in vayne,</L>
<L>And of ilka moment of tyme certayne;
<PB REF="00000206.tif" N="162"></L>
<L>And of ilkan Idel word and thoght,</L>
<L>And of ilkan ydel dede &thorn;at &thorn;ai wroght,</L>
<L N="5972">Outher in elde or in &thorn;air yhouthe,</L>
<L>Aftir &thorn;e tyme &thorn;at &thorn;ai witt first couthe,</L>
<L>And of dedes &thorn;at &thorn;ai thurgh erryng did;</L>
<L>And noght anely of open werkes bot of hid,</L>
<L N="5976">And noght anely of werkes wroght, bot unwroght</L>
<L>Als of werkes of mercy &thorn;at done war noght;</L>
<L>And of &thorn;air awen saules &thorn;ai sal reken &thorn;ar,</L>
<L>And of &thorn;air bodys &thorn;at &thorn;am obout bar;</L>
<L N="5980">And noght anly of ayther by &thorn;am-self &thorn;an,</L>
<L>Bot of bathe togyder als of a man;</L>
<L>And yhit noght anely of &thorn;am-self alle,</L>
<L>Bot of &thorn;air neghburs answer &thorn;ai salle;</L>
<L N="5984">And fadirs and modirs sal rekken &thorn;at tyde,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;air sons and &thorn;air doghtirs unchastide;</L>
<L>And loverdes alswa of &thorn;air men namly,</L>
<L>&THORN;e whilk &thorn;ai wald noght iustify;</L>
<L N="5988">And maysters of &thorn;air disciples alswa,</L>
<L>&THORN;e whilk &thorn;ai lete untaght in folis ga;</L>
<L>And prelates and prestes of ilka suggette,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ai wald noght in right rewel sette;</L>
<L N="5992">And alle other &thorn;at wrang and in ille entent</L>
<L>&THORN;e gudes spended &thorn;at God had &thorn;am lent,</L>
<L>And of alle wrang haldyngs of gudes sere,</L>
<L>Of whilk &thorn;ai parted noght til other here</L>
<L N="5996">&THORN;at of &thorn;am had nede, als &thorn;ai myght se;</L>
<L>Of alle &thorn;ir thynges men sal aresoned be.</L>
<L>At &thorn;e day of dome, als God has ordaynd,</L>
<L>Whar nathyng sal be hid ne laynd,</L>
<L N="6000">Of alle &thorn;ir, men sal yhelde acount strayt,</L>
<L>Sal nathyng &thorn;an be &thorn;ar to layt.</L>
<L>Ful sely es &thorn;at man or womman,</L>
<L>&THORN;at a gude rekkenyng may yhelde &thorn;an,</L>
<L N="6004">Swa &thorn;at he may pas qwyte and fre</L>
<L>Of alle thyng, &thorn;at may rekend be.</L>
<L>And swa sely may be alle &thorn;as,</L>
<L>&THORN;at fra hethen in charit&eacute; gas;
<PB REF="00000207.tif" N="163"></L>
<L N="6008">For he &thorn;at has here gude endyng,</L>
<L>Sal pas wele &thorn;ar, with light rekkenyng.</L>
<L>At &thorn;e day of dome, als byfor es talde,</L>
<L>Alle men sal be bathe yhung and alde,</L>
<L N="6012">And gude and ille, alle sal com &thorn;ider.</L>
<L>Swa mykel folk com never togyder,</L>
<L>Ne never was sene sythen &thorn;e werld bygan,</L>
<L>Als sal be sene byfor Crist &thorn;an,</L>
<L N="6016">&THORN;at sal be demed aftir &thorn;ai haf wroght.</L>
<L>Bot som sal deme and sum noght,</L>
<L>For som sal deme with &thorn;e domes-man,</L>
<L>&THORN;at thurgh dome sal noght be demed &thorn;an.</L>
<L N="6020">Som sal be demed &thorn;an ryghtwysly,</L>
<L>&THORN;at sal deme on na party;</L>
<L>Bot many other &thorn;ar sal seme,</L>
<L>&THORN;at sal nouther be demed ne deme.</L>
<L N="6024">&THORN;at &thorn;at sal deme and noght demed be,</L>
<L>Sal be parfit men with God priv&eacute;.</L>
<L>Of &thorn;a &thorn;at demed sal be and dem sal noght,</L>
<L>Sal some til blisse be demed and broght;</L>
<L N="6028">And sum sal be demed to helle to wende,</L>
<L>Whar pyn sal be with-outen ende.</L>
<L>Bot alle &thorn;at trowed noght als trow we,</L>
<L>Sal nouther deme ne demed be;</L>
<L N="6032">Bot for &thorn;ai wald noght til our trouthe come,</L>
<L>&THORN;a sal wende til helle with-outen dome.</L>
<L>First &thorn;as &thorn;at with Crist sal deme &thorn;at day</L>
<L>And noght be demed, er namly &thorn;ai</L>
<L N="6036">&THORN;at here forsuke &thorn;e werldes solace,</L>
<L>And folowed rightly Cristes trace,</L>
<L>Als his apostels and other ma,</L>
<L>&THORN;at for his luf tholed angre and wa;</L>
<L N="6040">&THORN;a sal deme with Crist and nan elles,</L>
<L>For-whi in &thorn;e godspelle &thorn;us he telles:</L>
<L><I>Vos, qui secuti estis me, sedebitis</I></L>
<L><I>super sedes duodecim, iudicantes duodecim</I></L>
<L N="6044"><I>tribus Israel.</I></L>
<L>He says "yhe &thorn;at folowes me here lyfand,
<PB REF="00000208.tif" N="164"></L>
<L>Sal sitt opon twelf setes demand</L>
<L>&THORN;e twelf nacions of Israel,"</L>
<L N="6048">&THORN;at es, &thorn;as &thorn;at God sese here als lele.</L>
<L>Som sal noght deme, bot demed be</L>
<L>Til blis, als men of grete charit&eacute;</L>
<L>&THORN;at blethely wirk wald &thorn;e werkes of mercy,</L>
<L N="6052">And keped &thorn;am here fra syn dedly.</L>
<L>Som sal noght deme, bot be demed</L>
<L>Til helle, and fra God be flemed,</L>
<L>Als &thorn;as &thorn;at er fals cristen men,</L>
<L N="6056">&THORN;at keped noght &thorn;e comandmentes ten,</L>
<L>And wald noght here forsake &thorn;air syn,</L>
<L>Bot whils &thorn;ai lyfyed ay dwelle &thorn;ar-in.</L>
<L>Som sal noght be demed &thorn;at day</L>
<L N="6064">&THORN;at sal wende to helle and dwelle &thorn;ar ay,</L>
<L>Als paens and sarazyns &thorn;at had na law,</L>
<L>And Iewes &thorn;at never wald Crist knaw,</L>
<L>&THORN;arfor &thorn;ai sal ga til payne endeles,</L>
<L N="6068">With-outen dome, for &thorn;us writen es:</L>
<L><I>Qui sine lege peccant,</I></L>
<L><I>absque lege peribunt.</I></L>
<L>"&THORN;as &thorn;at with-outen lawe uses syn</L>
<L N="6072">With-outen law sal perysshe &thorn;ar-in."</L>
<L>And &thorn;ar-for at &thorn;e day of dome namly,</L>
<L>Ilk man sal haf as he es worthy.</L>
<L>A ful hard day men sal &thorn;at day se,</L>
<L N="6076">When alle thyng sal &thorn;us discussed be.</L>
<L>&THORN;at day, sal na man be excused</L>
<L>Of nathyng &thorn;at he wrang here used,</L>
<L>&THORN;at sounes in ille on any manere,</L>
<L N="6080">Of whilk he was never delyverd here.<NOTE PLACE="foot">&THORN;e whiche sowne&thorn; to ille in eny manere dede. Of &thorn;e whiche he hade in thou&yogh;t no manere drede (MS. Y.).</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;e synful sal &thorn;are na mercy have,</L>
<L>For nathyng may &thorn;am &thorn;an save;</L>
<L>For-why &thorn;ai sal &thorn;an na help gett</L>
<L N="6084">Of sergeaunt, ne auturne, ne avoket,</L>
<L>Ne of nan other for &thorn;am to plede,</L>
<L>Ne &thorn;am to counsayle ne to rede,
<PB REF="00000209.tif" N="165"></L>
<L>Ne na halghe sal for &thorn;am pray.</L>
<L N="6088">&THORN;is may be cald a ful harde day,</L>
<L>Forwhi &thorn;an, als &thorn;e buke bers witnes,</L>
<L>Sal noght be shewed bot rightwysnes,</L>
<L>And grete reddure, with-outen mercy,</L>
<L N="6092">Until alle synful men namely.</L>
<L>&THORN;a &thorn;at of &thorn;air syn here wald noght stynt;</L>
<L>&THORN;ai sal &thorn;at day for ever be tynt</L>
<L>Fra God, with-outen any recoverere,</L>
<L N="6096">And delyverd be until &thorn;e devels powere.</L>
<L>Ful wa sal synful men be &thorn;at day,</L>
<L>And til helle pyne be put for ay,</L>
<L>And &thorn;arfor men may calle &thorn;at day,</L>
<L N="6100">&THORN;e grete day of delyveraunce,</L>
<L>&THORN;e day of wreke and of vengeaunce,</L>
<L>&THORN;e day of wrethe and of wrechednes,</L>
<L>&THORN;e day of bale and of bitternes,</L>
<L N="6104">&THORN;e day of pleynyng and accusyng,</L>
<L>&THORN;e day of answer and of strait rekkenyng,</L>
<L>&THORN;e day of iugements and of Iuwys,</L>
<L>&THORN;e day of angre and of angwys,</L>
<L N="6108">&THORN;e day of drede and of tremblyng,</L>
<L>&THORN;e day of gretyng and goulyng,</L>
<L>&THORN;e day of crying and of duleful dyn,</L>
<L>&THORN;e day of sorow &thorn;at never sal blyn,</L>
<L N="6112">&THORN;e day of flaying and of af[r]ay,</L>
<L>&THORN;e day of departyng fra God away,</L>
<L>&THORN;e day of merryng and of myrk[n]es,</L>
<L>&THORN;e day &thorn;at es last and &thorn;at mast es,</L>
<L N="6116">&THORN;e dai when Crist sal make ende of alle;</L>
<L>&THORN;us may man discryve &thorn;at day and calle.</L>
<L>Our loverd &thorn;at alle thyng can se and witt</L>
<L>At &thorn;e dredeful day of dome sal sitt,</L>
<L N="6120">Als kyng and rightwyse domesman,</L>
<L>In dome to deme alle &thorn;e werld &thorn;an,</L>
<L>Opon &thorn;e setil of his magest&eacute;.</L>
<L>&THORN;at day sal alle men byfor hym be,
<PB REF="00000210.tif" N="166"></L>
<L N="6124">Bathe gude and ille, mare and les;</L>
<L>&THORN;an sal noght be done bot rightwysnes.</L>
<L>He sal deme al men of ilka degr&eacute;,</L>
<L>Til ioy or payne &thorn;at demed sal be,</L>
<L N="6128">And<NOTE PLACE="foot">Als?</NOTE> rightwyse domes-man and suthefast</L>
<L>And gyf a fynal dome at &thorn;e last.</L>
<L>Bot how he sal deme I sal shewe,</L>
<L>Als telles &thorn;e godspelle of Mathewe;</L>
<L N="6132">Hys angels &thorn;an, aftir his wille,</L>
<L>Sal first departe &thorn;e gude fra &thorn;e ille,</L>
<L>Als &thorn;e hird &thorn;e shepe dus fra &thorn;e gayte,</L>
<L>&THORN;at falles to be putt til pastur strayt.</L>
<L N="6136">By &thorn;e shepe understand we may</L>
<L>&THORN;e gude men &thorn;at sal be saved &thorn;at day.</L>
<L>By &thorn;e gayte understand we may</L>
<L>&THORN;e ille men, &thorn;at &thorn;an dampned sal be.</L>
<L N="6140">&THORN;e gude sal be sette on his right hand,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e ille on his lefte syde sal stand;</L>
<L>&THORN;an sal our loverd say &thorn;us &thorn;at tyde</L>
<L>Til &thorn;am &thorn;at standes on his right syde:</L>
<L N="6144"><I>Venite, benedicti patris mei,</I></L>
<L><I>possidete paratum nobis regnum</I></L>
<L><I>a constitucione mundi.</I></L>
<L>He sal say &thorn;an, "commes now til me,</L>
<L N="6148">My fadir blissed childer fre,</L>
<L>And weldes &thorn;e kyngdom &thorn;at til yhow es dight</L>
<L>Fra first &thorn;at &thorn;e werld was ordaynd right."</L>
<L>For I hungerd and yhe me fedde,</L>
<L N="6152">I thrested and at drynk yhe me bedde;</L>
<L>Of herber grete nede I had,</L>
<L>Yhe herberd me with hert glad,</L>
<L>Naked I was, als yhe myght se,</L>
<L N="6156">Yhe gaf me clathes and clad me;</L>
<L>Seke I was and in ful wayke state,</L>
<L>Yhe wisit me, bathe arly and late;</L>
<L>In prisoun when I was halden stille,</L>
<L N="6160">Til me yhe come with ful gude wille.
<PB REF="00000211.tif" N="167"></L>
<L>&THORN;an sal &thorn;e rightwys men &thorn;at day,</L>
<L>Til our loverd answer &thorn;us and say;</L>
<L>'Loverd when saw we &thorn;e hungry,</L>
<L N="6164">And to gyf &thorn;e mete war we redy;</L>
<L>And when myght we &thorn;e thresty se,</L>
<L>And gaf &thorn;e drynk with hert fre;</L>
<L>When saw we &thorn;e nede of herber have,</L>
<L N="6168">And to herber &thorn;e vouched save;</L>
<L>When saw we &thorn;e naked and we &thorn;e cled,</L>
<L>And when saw we &thorn;e seke and in prison sted,</L>
<L>And visited &thorn;e with gude wille,</L>
<L N="6172">And comforted &thorn;e, als was skille?'</L>
<L>Our loverd sal &thorn;an &thorn;am answer &thorn;us,</L>
<L>And say, als &thorn;e godspelle shewes us:</L>
<L>'Suthly I say yhou, swa yhe wroght,</L>
<L N="6176">&THORN;at ilka tyme when yhe did oght</L>
<L>Until ane of &thorn;e lest &thorn;at yhe myght se</L>
<L>Of my brether, yhe did til me.'</L>
<L>&THORN;an sal our loverd til alle &thorn;as say,</L>
<L N="6180">&THORN;at &thorn;an on his lefte syde sal stand &thorn;at day,</L>
<L>And spek til &thorn;am with an austerne chere,</L>
<L>&THORN;ir wordes &thorn;at er hydus to here:</L>
<L><I>Discedite a me maledicti, in ignem</I></L>
<L N="6184"><I>eternum, qui preparatus est diabolo</I></L>
<L><I>et angelis eius.</I></L>
<L>"Yhe weryed wyghtes wende fra my sight,</L>
<L>Until &thorn;e endeles fire &thorn;at es dight</L>
<L N="6188">Til &thorn;e devel and til his aungels."</L>
<L>And &thorn;an sal he say &thorn;us, als &thorn;e buke tels,</L>
<L>'I hungred and had defaute of mete,</L>
<L>And yhe wald noght gyfe me at ete;</L>
<L N="6192">I thrested, and of drynk had nede,</L>
<L>And yhe wald na drynk me bede;</L>
<L>I wanted herber, &thorn;at I oft soght,</L>
<L>And alle &thorn;at tyme yhe herberd me noght;</L>
<L N="6196">Naked with-outen clathes I was,</L>
<L>And with-outen clathes yhe let me pas;
<PB REF="00000212.tif" N="168"></L>
<L>Seke I was, and bedred lay,</L>
<L>And yhe visite me nouther nyght ne day;</L>
<L N="6200">In prison I was, als wele wyst yhe,</L>
<L>And yhe wald na tyme com til me.'</L>
<L>&THORN;an sal &thorn;ai answere, als men sal here,</L>
<L>Til our loverd, and say on &thorn;is manere:</L>
<L N="6204">'Loverd when saw we &thorn;e haf hunger or thrist</L>
<L>Or of any herber haf grete brist;</L>
<L>Or naked, or seke, or in prison be,</L>
<L>And we na thyng did ne mynystred to &thorn;e?'</L>
<L N="6208">&THORN;an sal our loverd answer ogayne</L>
<L>And say til &thorn;am &thorn;ir wordes certayne:</L>
<L>'Suthly I say yhou, als falles &thorn;ar-to,</L>
<L>Alle tyme &thorn;at yhe wald noght do</L>
<L N="6212">Til ane of lest &thorn;at myne er kydde,</L>
<L>Als lang til me yhe noght didde.'</L>
<L>&THORN;us sal our loverd reherce openly</L>
<L>Til rightwys men, &thorn;e werkes of mercy,</L>
<L N="6216">For to make &thorn;am openly kyd,</L>
<L>Til grete worshepe of &thorn;am &thorn;at &thorn;am dyd;</L>
<L>And shew til &thorn;e synful, als falles &thorn;ar-to,</L>
<L>&THORN;air unkyndenes, &thorn;at wyld noght do</L>
<L N="6220">&THORN;e werkes of mercy for his luf,</L>
<L>Til &thorn;air grete shenshepe and repruve.</L>
<L>When he has &thorn;us sayde and made ende,</L>
<L>&THORN;e synful with &thorn;e devels sal wende</L>
<L N="6224">Until helle fire, &thorn;at never sal slake.</L>
<L>A ful hidus cry &thorn;an sal &thorn;ai make,</L>
<L>And say 'allas! &thorn;at we ever war wroght.</L>
<L>In manskynd; whyne war we noght!</L>
<L N="6228">Whyne had God made us swa,</L>
<L>&THORN;at us thurt never haf feled wele ne wa!</L>
<L>Now sal we bryn in &thorn;e fire of helle,</L>
<L>And with-outen ende &thorn;ar-in duelle.'</L>
<L N="6232">Helle &thorn;an &thorn;am sal swelghe als-tite</L>
<L>With-outen any lenger respyte;</L>
<L>And alle &thorn;e fire &thorn;at &thorn;an sal be sene,</L>
<L>And alle &thorn;e corrupcions &thorn;at ever has bene,
<PB REF="00000213.tif" N="169"></L>
<L N="6236">And &thorn;e filthe and alle &thorn;e stynk</L>
<L>Of alle &thorn;e werld &thorn;an sal synk</L>
<L>Doun with &thorn;am in-til &thorn;e pitte of helle,</L>
<L>To eke &thorn;air sorow &thorn;at &thorn;ar sal duelle.</L>
<L N="6240">Bot &thorn;e ryghtwys men, als pe buke bers wytnes</L>
<L>Sal wende til blisse, whar lyfe es endeles,</L>
<L>With our loverd and hys aungels ilkane</L>
<L>Shynand brighter &thorn;an ever son shane.</L>
<L N="6244">Now have yhe herd, als es contende</L>
<L>In &thorn;is fift part, how &thorn;e werld sal ende,</L>
<L>And how Crist, at his last commyng,</L>
<L>Sal in dome sitte and discusse alle thyng.</L>
<L N="6248">Here may a man read &thorn;at has tome,</L>
<L>A large proces of &thorn;e day of dome,</L>
<L>&THORN;at a lang tyme aftir I haf redde</L>
<L>Suld contene by skille, ar alle war spedde;</L>
<L N="6252">Bot ye sal understand and witte,</L>
<L>Als men may se in haly writte,</L>
<L>&THORN;at thurgh &thorn;e wysedom and &thorn;e vertu,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e myght of our Lord Ihesu,</L>
<L N="6256">Alle &thorn;e processe &thorn;at sal be &thorn;at day,</L>
<L>Of whilk any clerk can speke or say,</L>
<L>Sal &thorn;an swa shortely be sped and sone,</L>
<L>&THORN;at alle sal be in a moment done.</L>
<L N="6260">A moment es als of a tyme bygynnyng,</L>
<L>Als short als an eghe twynkelyng.</L>
<L>A grete wondir may &thorn;is be kyd,</L>
<L>Omang alle wondirs &thorn;at ever God dyd,</L>
<L N="6264">&THORN;at in swa short tyme at his commyng,</L>
<L>He mught deme and discusse al thyng;</L>
<L>Bot of &thorn;is suld nane muse, lered ne lewed,</L>
<L>For als grete wordirs<NOTE PLACE="foot">wondirs (MS. Harl. 1964).</NOTE> has God shewed;</L>
<L N="6268">Als grete a wonder es when he wroght,</L>
<L>With a short worde, alle &thorn;e world of noght,</L>
<L>And of &thorn;is &thorn;e prophete bers wittnes,</L>
<L>&THORN;at says &thorn;us, als it wryten es:
<PB REF="00000214.tif" N="170"></L>
<L N="6272"><I>Quia ipse dixit et facta sunt,</I></L>
<L><I>ipse mandavit et creata sunt.</I></L>
<L>"God sayde," says he, "and alle was done</L>
<L>He bad and alle was made sone."</L>
<L N="6276">&THORN;us in a short tyme alle thyng made he,</L>
<L>Mare wondir &thorn;an &thorn;is mught never be,</L>
<L>&THORN;an may he als shortly make endyng</L>
<L>Of alle thyng, als he made bygynnyng.</L>
<L N="6280">For swa witty and myghty es he</L>
<L>&THORN;at na-thyng til hym impossibel may be.</L>
<L>&THORN;e processe of &thorn;at day &thorn;at I haf talde,</L>
<L>Al &thorn;e men of &thorn;e world, bathe yhung and alde,</L>
<L N="6284">Sal se and undirstand it alle,</L>
<L>In als short tyme als it sal falle.</L>
<L>Now haf yhe herd me speke and rede</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e wondir &thorn;at &thorn;an sal be and drede.</L>
<L N="6288">Bot alle &thorn;ogh yhe haf herd me rede and say</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e reddure, &thorn;at sal be done &thorn;at day</L>
<L>Untille alle synful men namely,</L>
<L>&THORN;at sal be dampned with-outen mercy,</L>
<L N="6292">Als men may in &thorn;is part wryten se,</L>
<L>Na man &thorn;arfor suld in dispayre be;</L>
<L>For alle &thorn;at has mercy here sal be save,</L>
<L>And alle &thorn;at here askes mercy sal it have,</L>
<L N="6296">Yf &thorn;ai it sekes whilles &thorn;ai lyf bodily,</L>
<L>And trewely trayste in Goddys mercy,</L>
<L>And amende &thorn;am and &thorn;air syn forsake,</L>
<L>Byfor &thorn;e tyme ar &thorn;e dede &thorn;am take</L>
<L N="6300">And do mercy here and charit&eacute;,</L>
<L>&THORN;an gette &thorn;ai mercy and saved sal be.</L>
<L>Bot if &thorn;e dede byfor haf &thorn;am tane,</L>
<L>Ar &thorn;ai haf mercy, &thorn;an gette &thorn;ai nane,</L>
<L N="6304">Bot reddure of rightwysnes anely,</L>
<L>For &thorn;an sal be shewed na mercy.</L>
<L>Here may ilk man, if he wille,</L>
<L>Haf mercy &thorn;at dus &thorn;at falles &thorn;ar-tille;</L>
<L N="6308">&THORN;oghe he had done never swa mykel syn,</L>
<L>If he amended hym, he myght it wyn;
<PB REF="00000215.tif" N="171"></L>
<L>For &thorn;e mercy of God es swa mykel here,</L>
<L>And reches over alle, bathe fer and nere,</L>
<L N="6312">&THORN;at alle &thorn;e syn &thorn;at a man may do,</L>
<L>It myght sleken, and mare &thorn;ar-to,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ar-for says Saynt Austyn &thorn;us,</L>
<L>A gude worde &thorn;at may comfort us:</L>
<L N="6316"><I>Sicut scintilla ignis in medio maris,</I></L>
<L><I>ita omnis impietas viri ad miseriam dei.</I></L>
<L>"Als a litel spark of fire," says he,</L>
<L>"In mydward &thorn;e mykel se,</L>
<L N="6320">Right swa alle a mans wykkednes</L>
<L>Un-to &thorn;e mercy of God es."</L>
<L>Here may men se how mykel es mercy,</L>
<L>To fordo alle syn and foly.</L>
<L N="6324">For-why if a man had done here</L>
<L>Als mykel and als many syns sere,</L>
<L>Als al &thorn;e men of &thorn;e werld has done,</L>
<L>Alle myght his mercy fordo sone;</L>
<L N="6328">And if possibel whare, als es noght,</L>
<L>&THORN;at ilk man als mykel syn had wroght,</L>
<L>Als alle &thorn;e men &thorn;at in &thorn;e werld ever was,</L>
<L>Yhit mught his mercy alle &thorn;air syn pas.</L>
<L N="6332">&THORN;an semes it wele, als men may se,</L>
<L>&THORN;at of his mercy here [t]he[re]is grete plent&eacute;,</L>
<L>For his mercy spredes on ilka syde</L>
<L>Thurgh alle &thorn;e werld, &thorn;at es brade and wyde,</L>
<L N="6336">And sheues it be many ways,</L>
<L>And &thorn;arfor &thorn;e prophete David says:</L>
<L><I>Misericordia Domini plena</I></L>
<L><I>est terra.</I></L>
<L N="6340">"&THORN;e erthe", he says, "es ful of mercy."</L>
<L>&THORN;an may men it fynde here plenteuously;</L>
<L>And he &thorn;at has mercy, ar he hethen wende,</L>
<L>At &thorn;e grete dome sal fynde Criste his frende,</L>
<L N="6344">Whar rightwysnes anely sal be haunted,</L>
<L>And na mercy &thorn;an be graunted.</L>
<L>After &thorn;e grete dome alle &thorn;e werld brade</L>
<L>Sal seme &thorn;an als it war new made.
<PB REF="00000216.tif" N="172"></L>
<L N="6348">&THORN;e erthe sal be &thorn;an even and hale,</L>
<L>And smethe and clere als cristale;</L>
<L>&THORN;e ayre obout sal shyne ful bright,</L>
<L>&THORN;an sal ay be day and never nyght,</L>
<L N="6352">For &thorn;e elementes alle sal &thorn;an clene be</L>
<L>Of alle corrumpciouns &thorn;at we here se;</L>
<L>&THORN;an sal alle &thorn;e werld, in alle partys,</L>
<L>Seme als it war a paradys,</L>
<L N="6356">&THORN;e planetes and &thorn;e sternes ilkane,</L>
<L>Sal shyne brighter &thorn;an ever &thorn;ai shane.</L>
<L>&THORN;e son sal be, als som clerkes demes,</L>
<L>Seven sythe<NOTE PLACE="foot">sythes (MS. Harl. 4196).</NOTE> brighter &thorn;an it now semes;</L>
<L N="6360">For it sal be als bright als it first was,</L>
<L>Byfor ar Adam did trespas.</L>
<L>&THORN;e mone sal be als bright and clere,</L>
<L>Als &thorn;e son es now &thorn;at shynes here;</L>
<L N="6364">&THORN;e son sal &thorn;an in &thorn;e este stande,</L>
<L>With-outen removyng, ay shynande,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e mone ogayne it in &thorn;e weste,</L>
<L>And na mare sal travayle bot ay reste,</L>
<L N="6368">Als &thorn;ai war sette at &thorn;e bigynnyng,</L>
<L>When God made &thorn;am and alle thyng;</L>
<L>&THORN;ai war &thorn;an, als men may trow,</L>
<L>Mykel brighter &thorn;an &thorn;ai er now.</L>
<L N="6372">&THORN;e movand heve[n]s with-outen dout,</L>
<L>Sal &thorn;an ceese o turnyng obout,</L>
<L>And na mare obout in course wende,</L>
<L>For of alle thyng &thorn;an sal be made ende.</L>
<L N="6376">&THORN;e movand hevens now obout gas,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e son and &thorn;e mone &thorn;air course mas;</L>
<L>And &thorn;e othir planetes ilkane,</L>
<L>Moves als &thorn;ai &thorn;air course haf tane;</L>
<L N="6380">And alle &thorn;e elementes kyndely duse</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;at es nedeful til man use.</L>
<L>&THORN;us ordaynd God &thorn;am to serve man,</L>
<L>Bot of alle swylk servise &thorn;ai sal ceese &thorn;an.</L>
<L N="6384">For alle men aftir domesday</L>
<L>Sal be war &thorn;ai sal duelle for ay,
<PB REF="00000217.tif" N="173"></L>
<L>&THORN;e gude in blis, in rest and peese,</L>
<L>&THORN;e ille in payne &thorn;at never sal ceese.</L>
<L N="6388">What nede war &thorn;at &thorn;a creatures &thorn;an,</L>
<L>Shewed swilk servyse mare for man.</L>
<L>Na qwik creature sal &thorn;an be lyfand,</L>
<L>Thurgh out &thorn;e werld in na land,</L>
<L N="6392">Ne nathyng sal growe &thorn;an, gresse ne tre,</L>
<L>Ne cragges ne roches sal nan &thorn;an be,</L>
<L>Ne dale, ne hille, ne mountayne;</L>
<L>Bot alle erthe sal be &thorn;an even and playne,</L>
<L N="6396">And be made als clere and fayre and clene,</L>
<L>Als any cristal &thorn;at here es sene;</L>
<L>For it sal be purged and fyned with-oute,</L>
<L>Als alle other elementes sal be oboute,</L>
<L N="6400">And na mare be travayled o<NOTE PLACE="foot">on</NOTE> na side,</L>
<L>Ne with na charge mare occupide.</L>
<L>Now haf yhe herd me byfor rede</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e day of dome &thorn;at many may drede,</L>
<L N="6404">And of &thorn;e wondirful takens many,</L>
<L>&THORN;at salle falle byfor &thorn;at day namly,</L>
<L>And how &thorn;e werld &thorn;at we now se,</L>
<L>Aftir &thorn;e dome als new made sal be,</L>
<L N="6408">Als here es contened, wha-swa wille luke,</L>
<L>In &thorn;e fifte part of &thorn;is buke;</L>
<L>Here on now wille I na langer stande,</L>
<L>Bot ga til &thorn;e sext part neghest folowande,</L>
<L N="6412">&THORN;at specialy spekes, als writen es,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e paynes of helle &thorn;at er endeles,</L>
<L>&THORN;at<NOTE PLACE="foot">Bot (MS. Harl. 4196).</NOTE> alle men, &thorn;at here lyfe byhoves lede,</L>
<L>Aght specialy mast to drede;</L>
<L N="6416">For &thorn;a paynes er swa fel and hard,</L>
<L>Als yhe sal here be red aftirward,</L>
<L>&THORN;atilk man may ugge, bathe yhunge and alde,</L>
<L N="6420">&THORN;at heres &thorn;am be reherced and talde.</L>
</LG>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 N="6" TYPE="book">
<HEAD>Her begynnes &thorn;e sext party of &thorn;is boke &thorn;at spekes of &thorn;e paynes of Helle.<NOTE PLACE="foot">This heading is absent from MSS. Galba E IX, Harl. 4196).</NOTE></HEAD>

<PB REF="00000218.tif" N="174">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Many men here spekes of helle,</L>
<L N="6424">Bot of &thorn;e paynes &thorn;ar fune can telle,</L>
<L>Bot wha-swa here mught wit and k[n]aw wele</L>
<L>What paynes &thorn;e synful &thorn;ar sal fele,</L>
<L>&THORN;ai suld in grete ferdlayk be broght,</L>
<L N="6428">Ay when &thorn;ai on &thorn;a paynes thoght;</L>
<L>For &thorn;e mynde of &thorn;am myght men feer,</L>
<L>Swa bitter and swa horribel &thorn;ai er;</L>
<L>Bot for&thorn;i &thorn;at many knawes noght right,</L>
<L N="6432">Whatkyn paynes in helle er dight,</L>
<L>With-outen ende for synful men,</L>
<L>&THORN;arfor I sal shewe yhow, als I can,</L>
<L>Aparty of &thorn;a paynes sere,</L>
<L N="6436">Als yhe may sone aftirward here.</L>
<L>Bot first I wille shew whare es helle,</L>
<L>Als I haf herd som grete clerkes telle,</L>
<L>And sythen wille I shew yhow mare,</L>
<L N="6440">And speke of &thorn;e paynes &thorn;at er &thorn;are.</L>
<L>Som clerkes says, als &thorn;e buke bers witnes,</L>
<L>&THORN;at helle even in myddes &thorn;e erthe es;</L>
<L>For alle erthe by skille may likend be</L>
<L N="6444">Til a rounde appel of a tre,</L>
<L>&THORN;at even in myddes has a colke,</L>
<L>And swa it may be tille an egge yholke;</L>
<L>For als a dalk es even Imydward</L>
<L N="6448">&THORN;e yholke of &thorn;e egge, when it es hard,</L>
<L>Ryght swa es helle pitte, als clerkes telles,</L>
<L>Ymyddes &thorn;e erthe and nourwhar elles.</L>
<L>And als &thorn;e yholk ymyddes &thorn;e egge lys,</L>
<L N="6452">And &thorn;e white obout on &thorn;e same wys,</L>
<L>Right swa es &thorn;e erthe, with-outen dout.</L>
<L>Ymyddes &thorn;e hevens &thorn;at gas obout.</L>
<L>&THORN;us may men se by an egge hard dight,</L>
<L N="6456">How heven and erthe and helle standes right.</L>
<L>Ful hydus and myrke helle es kyd,</L>
<L>For-why it es with-in &thorn;e erthe hyd,</L>
<L>&THORN;ider &thorn;e synful sal be dryven,</L>
<L N="6460">Als tyte als &thorn;e last dome es gyven.
<PB REF="00000219.tif" N="175"></L>
<L>With alle &thorn;e devels ay &thorn;ar to duelle,</L>
<L>&THORN;at now er in &thorn;e ayre and in helle,</L>
<L>&THORN;ar sal &thorn;ai alle be stoped togider;</L>
<L N="6464">Wa sal &thorn;am be &thorn;at sal wende &thorn;ider,</L>
<L>For &thorn;ar es swa mykel sorow and bale,</L>
<L>And swa many paynes with-outen tale,</L>
<L>&THORN;at alle &thorn;e clerkes &thorn;at ever had wytt,</L>
<L N="6468">&THORN;at ever was, or &thorn;at lyfes yhitt,</L>
<L>Couth noght telle ne shew thurgh lare,</L>
<L>How mykel sorow and payne er &thorn;are.</L>
<L>And if it thurgh kynd myght be swa,</L>
<L N="6472">&THORN;at an hundreth thousand men or ma,</L>
<L>Had an hundreth thousand tunges of stele,</L>
<L>And ilk tung mught speke wysely and wele</L>
<L>And ilka tung of ilka man,</L>
<L N="6476">Had bygunnen when &thorn;e werld bygan,</L>
<L>To spek of helle, and swa suld speke ay</L>
<L>Whils &thorn;e werld suld last til domes day,</L>
<L>Yhit mught &thorn;ai noght &thorn;e sorow telle,</L>
<L N="6480">&THORN;at to synful es ordaynd in helle;</L>
<L>For-why na witt of man may ymagyn</L>
<L>What paynes &thorn;ar er ordaynd for syn.</L>
<L>Bot men may fynd, wha-swa wil loke,</L>
<L N="6484">Som maner of paynes wryten in boke,</L>
<L>Omang all other paynes &thorn;at er in helle,</L>
<L>Als men has herd wyse clerkes telle;</L>
<L>Bot what man es swa wyse and wytty</L>
<L N="6488">&THORN;at couthe telle &thorn;a paynes proprely,</L>
<L>Bot it war he &thorn;at had bene &thorn;are,</L>
<L>And sene &thorn;a paynes bath les and mare?</L>
<L>Bot he &thorn;at &thorn;ar commes for certayne,</L>
<L N="6492">May noght lightly turne agayne;</L>
<L>He most duelle &thorn;ar and never oway com,</L>
<L>For pe buke says &thorn;us of wysdom:</L>
<L><I>Non est agnitus, qui reversus</I></L>
<L N="6496"><I>est ab inferis.</I></L>
<L>&THORN;at es on Ynglisse "men knawes nane,</L>
<L>&THORN;at turned fra helle &thorn;at &thorn;ider was gane."
<PB REF="00000220.tif" N="176"></L>
<L>For alle &thorn;at er &thorn;ar most duelle for ay,</L>
<L N="6500">&THORN;ai may never be broght oway,</L>
<L>Bot-if war thurgh miracle anely,</L>
<L>And thurgh specyal grace of God almyghty,</L>
<L>Thurgh whilk som, &thorn;at in helle has bene,</L>
<L N="6504">And horrible paynes &thorn;ar has sene</L>
<L>Has bene broght oway fra alle &thorn;at stryf,</L>
<L>And bene turned ogayne fra ded til lyf;</L>
<L>Als Lazar was Mary brother Maudalayne,</L>
<L N="6508">&THORN;at saw and herd &thorn;are many a payne,</L>
<L>&THORN;at tyme namely when he was ded,</L>
<L>For his saul &thorn;an was at &thorn;at sted,</L>
<L>Four dayes, als God vouched save,</L>
<L N="6512">And swa lang his body lay here in grave;</L>
<L>And at &thorn;e last God raysed hym ryght</L>
<L>Fra ded til lyf thurgh his myght;</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;at &thorn;at he saw he noght forgatt,</L>
<L N="6516">And sone &thorn;are-after als he satt</L>
<L>With Crist at &thorn;e meete in Martha hows,</L>
<L>He talde a party of &thorn;a paynes hydus;</L>
<L>Bot yhit durst he noght al telle,</L>
<L N="6520">For drede of Crist, &thorn;at he saw in helle,</L>
<L>Yhit lyfed he after fyften yhere,</L>
<L>Bot he lughe<NOTE PLACE="foot">loghe (MS. Harl. 4196).</NOTE> never, ne made blythe chere,</L>
<L>For drede of dede &thorn;at he most efte dreghe,</L>
<L N="6524">And of &thorn;e paynes &thorn;at he saw with eghe.</L>
<L>For how bitter &thorn;e dede es nan may witt,</L>
<L>Bot he anely &thorn;at has feled itt,</L>
<L>And what paynes in helle er, nane wil wene</L>
<L N="6528">Bot he anely &thorn;at has &thorn;am sene.</L>
<L>Alswa twa of Symeon sons ryght,</L>
<L>&THORN;e whilk Caryn and Lentyn hight,</L>
<L>When &thorn;a first war dede and hethen went,</L>
<L N="6532">&THORN;ai saw in helle many a tourment,</L>
<L>And sithen when Crist dighed on &thorn;e rode,</L>
<L>&THORN;ai rase fra ded and obout yhode,</L>
<L>And tald how Crist, byfor &thorn;at he ras,</L>
<L N="6536">Til helle come and tuke out &thorn;at his was,
<PB REF="00000221.tif" N="177"></L>
<L>And mykel couthe &thorn;ai &thorn;an telle</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e paynes &thorn;at &thorn;ai saw in helle.</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;ai had no leve als I wene</L>
<L N="6540">To telle alle &thorn;at &thorn;ai &thorn;ar had sene;</L>
<L>Wharfor &thorn;ai lyfed here ay in penaunce,</L>
<L>And never aftir made blithe countinance,</L>
<L>Of wham es writen in a pistel &thorn;us,</L>
<L N="6544">&THORN;at Pilat sent til Tyberius,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;an emparour of Rome was,</L>
<L>For to certifie hym of &thorn;is cas.</L>
<L>And yhit many other &thorn;at war dede,</L>
<L N="6548">Has bene sumtyme at &thorn;at stede,</L>
<L>And sene &thorn;ar many hydus payne,</L>
<L>And thurgh miracle turned til lyf agayne;</L>
<L>Bot omang alle &thorn;at &thorn;ar has bene sene,</L>
<L N="6552">I fynde wryten paynes fourtene,</L>
<L>Thurgh whilk &thorn;e synful sal be pyned ay,</L>
<L>In body and saul aftir domesday;</L>
<L>&THORN;e whilk er als general paynes of helle,</L>
<L N="6556">And whilk &thorn;as er I sal yhow telle.</L>
<L>&THORN;e first es fire swa hate to reken,</L>
<L>&THORN;at na maner of thyng may it sleken.</L>
<L>&THORN;e secunde es calde als says som,</L>
<L N="6560">&THORN;at na hete of fire may overcom.</L>
<L>&THORN;e thred alswa es filthe and stynk</L>
<L>&THORN;at es stranger &thorn;an any hert may thynk.</L>
<L>&THORN;e ferthe es hunger sharpe and strang.</L>
<L N="6564">&THORN;e fift es brynnand threst omang.</L>
<L>&THORN;e sext es swa mykel myrknes,</L>
<L>&THORN;at it may be graped, swa thik it es.</L>
<L>&THORN;e seve[n]d es &thorn;e horribel sight</L>
<L N="6568">Of &thorn;e devels &thorn;at &thorn;ar er hydusly dight.</L>
<L>&THORN;e eghtend payne es vermyn grete,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e synful men sal gnaw and frete.</L>
<L>&THORN;e neghend es dyngyng of devels hand,</L>
<L N="6572">With melles of yren hate glowand.</L>
<L>&THORN;e tend payne es gnawyng with-in</L>
<L>Of conscience &thorn;at bites als vermyn.
<PB REF="00000222.tif" N="178"></L>
<L>&THORN;e ellevend es hate teres of gretyng,</L>
<L N="6576">&THORN;at &thorn;e synful sal scalden in &thorn;e dounfallyng.</L>
<L>&THORN;e twelfte es shame and shenshepe of syn</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ai sal haf &thorn;at never sal blyn.</L>
<L>&THORN;e threttend es bandes of fire brinnand,</L>
<L N="6580">&THORN;at &thorn;ai sal be bunden with fote and hand.</L>
<L>&THORN;e fourtend payne despayre es cald,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e synful sal ay in hert hald.</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;ir er generale paynes in helle;</L>
<L N="6584">Bot &thorn;ar er other ma &thorn;an tung may telle,</L>
<L>Or hert may thynk or eer may here,</L>
<L>Of special paynes &thorn;at er sere,</L>
<L>&THORN;e whilk many, aftir &thorn;ai er worthy,</L>
<L N="6588">Sal thole ever-mare in saule and body;</L>
<L>Bot of alle &thorn;a paynes can I noght say,</L>
<L>For na man &thorn;am reken ne specyfy may,</L>
<L>Bot yhit wille I speke som-what mare</L>
<L N="6592">Of &thorn;e general paynes &thorn;at I shewed are,</L>
<L>And with som autorities &thorn;am bynd,</L>
<L>Als men may in sere bukes writen fynd.</L>
<L>&THORN;e first als I tald es &thorn;e fire hate,</L>
<L N="6596">&THORN;at na thyng may sleken ne abate;</L>
<L>Whare &thorn;e synful men sal bryn thurgh hete</L>
<L>Of whilk God spekes &thorn;us thurgh &thorn;e prophete:</L>
<L><I>Ignis succensus est in furore</I></L>
<L N="6600"><I>meo, et ardebit usque ad in|</I></L>
<L><I>ferni novissima, id est, usque</I></L>
<L><I>in eternum.</I></L>
<L>"Fyre es kyndeld in my wreth", says he,</L>
<L N="6604">"And sal bryn until ende of helle sal be,</L>
<L>&THORN;at es ever-mare, als God vouches save,</L>
<L>For helle sal never-mare ende have."</L>
<L>&THORN;at fire es swa hate, and ay brynnes,</L>
<L N="6608">&THORN;at if alle &thorn;e waters &thorn;at standes or rynnes</L>
<L>On erthe, and alle &thorn;e sese with-oute,</L>
<L>&THORN;at encloses alle &thorn;e erthe oboute,</L>
<L>Suld ryn in-til &thorn;at fire swa hate,</L>
<L N="6612">Yhit myght it noght it sleken ne abate,
<PB REF="00000223.tif" N="179"></L>
<L>Na mare &thorn;an a drope of water shire</L>
<L>If alle Rome brend, mught sleken &thorn;at fire.</L>
<L>For &thorn;e fire of helle &thorn;at es endeles,</L>
<L N="6616">Es hatter &thorn;an fire here es,</L>
<L>Right als &thorn;e fire &thorn;at es brinnand here,</L>
<L>Es hatter and of mare powere,</L>
<L>&THORN;an a purtrayd fire on a waghe,</L>
<L N="6620">&THORN;at es paynted outher heghe or laghe,</L>
<L>With a rede coloure til mens sight,</L>
<L>&THORN;at nouther brynnes ne gyfes light,</L>
<L>Ne on othir manere avales ne ders.</L>
<L N="6624">Of &thorn;ir twa fires I fynde writen twa vers.</L>
<L><I>Quam focus est mundi picto fervencior igne,</I></L>
<L><I>Tam focus inferni superat fervenicia mundi.</I></L>
<L>"Als &thorn;e fire of &thorn;e werld hatter es</L>
<L N="6628">&THORN;an a fire paynted, be it mare or les,</L>
<L>Rightswa &thorn;e fire of helle passes thurgh hete,</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;e fires of &thorn;e werld, smale and grete,</L>
<L>And for-&thorn;i &thorn;at &thorn;e synful brynned ay here,</L>
<L N="6632">In &thorn;e fire of fole yhernyngs sere,</L>
<L>It es right &thorn;at &thorn;ai brynne &thorn;are</L>
<L>In &thorn;at hate fire for ever-mare.</L>
<L><I>"Est locus indignis ubi non extinguitur ignis,</I></L>
<L N="6636"><I>Non qui torquetur, nec qui torquet, morietur."</I></L>
<L>&THORN;e secunde payne es grete calde,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e synful sal fele, als I ar talde;</L>
<L>&THORN;at cald sal be swa strang and kene,</L>
<L N="6640">&THORN;at if &thorn;e mast roche &thorn;at man has sene,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e mast mountayne in any land,</L>
<L>War al attanes in fire brynnand,</L>
<L>And even Imyddes &thorn;at cald war,</L>
<L N="6644">It suld frese and turne al in-til yse &thorn;ar;</L>
<L>And for-&thorn;i &thorn;at &thorn;ai, omang other vice,</L>
<L>Brynned ay here in &thorn;e calde of malice,</L>
<L>And ay was dased in charit&eacute;,</L>
<L N="6648">&THORN;arfor it es right &thorn;at &thorn;ai be</L>
<L>In &thorn;at strang calde ever-mare lastand,</L>
<L>Whar &thorn;ai sal frese, bathe fote and hand.
<PB REF="00000224.tif" N="180"></L>
<L>&THORN;e devels sal tak &thorn;am fra &thorn;at fire,</L>
<L N="6652">And cast &thorn;am, with ful grete ire,</L>
<L>In-til &thorn;at cald to eke &thorn;air payne,</L>
<L>And efte &thorn;am cast in &thorn;e fire ogayne;</L>
<L>&THORN;us sal &thorn;ai cast &thorn;am to and fra,</L>
<L N="6656">And ever-mare &thorn;ai sal fare swa.</L>
<L>Of &thorn;is &thorn;e haly man bers wittenes</L>
<L>Iob &thorn;at says &thorn;us, als writen es:</L>
<L><I>Ab aquis nivium transibunt</I></L>
<L N="6660"><I>ad calorem nimium.</I></L>
<L>"Fra waters of snawes &thorn;e synful sal wende</L>
<L>Til &thorn;e over mykel hete &thorn;at has nan ende."</L>
<L>And Saynt Austyn says on &thorn;is manere,</L>
<L N="6664">In a buke, als es writen here.</L>
<L><I>Dicuntur namque, mali candere</I></L>
<L><I>exterius calore ut ferum in for|</I></L>
<L><I>nace, et interius frigore ut</I></L>
<L N="6668"><I>glacies in yeme.</I></L>
<L>"&THORN;e wikked sal outwith be glowand</L>
<L>Thurgh hete, als men in fire brynnand,</L>
<L>And with-in thurgh calde sharpe and kene,</L>
<L N="6672">Als yse &thorn;at es in wynter sene,"</L>
<L>&THORN;us sal &thorn;ai ay be in calde and hete;</L>
<L>&THORN;is tourment es ful strang and grete.</L>
<L>&THORN;e thred payne es, als men heres clerkes telle,</L>
<L N="6676">&THORN;e grete stynk and filthe &thorn;at es in helle;</L>
<L>Of &thorn;is Saynt Ierom, &thorn;e haly man,</L>
<L>Says &thorn;us, als I here shewe yhow can:</L>
<L><I>Ibi est ignis inextinguibilis,</I></L>
<L N="6680"><I>et fetor intollerabilis.</I></L>
<L>"&THORN;e fire es &thorn;ar of swa grete poust&eacute;,</L>
<L>&THORN;at it may never mar slekend be,</L>
<L>And swylk filthe and stynk es in &thorn;at ugly hole,</L>
<L N="6684">&THORN;at nan erthely man mught it thole;"</L>
<L>For na man in erthe may ymagyn</L>
<L>Swa mykel filthe, als sal be &thorn;ar-in,</L>
<L>Whar-for &thorn;ar sal be mare stynk</L>
<L N="6688">&THORN;an tung may telle or hert thynk.
<PB REF="00000225.tif" N="181"></L>
<L>&THORN;e whilk stynk, with filthe and fen,</L>
<L>Sal be strang payne til synful men,</L>
<L>And yhit &thorn;e fire &thorn;at bryn &thorn;am sal,</L>
<L N="6692">Sal gyfe a st[r]ang stynk with-alle,</L>
<L>For it sal be fulle of brunstane and pyk,</L>
<L>And of other thyng &thorn;at es wyk;</L>
<L>And for &thorn;e synful delyted &thorn;am here namly,</L>
<L N="6696">In &thorn;e filthe and stynk of lechery,</L>
<L>It es right &thorn;at &thorn;ai be ay omang</L>
<L>&THORN;e stynk and filthe in helle swa strang.</L>
<L>&THORN;e ferthe payne es, als I haf herd say,</L>
<L N="6700">&THORN;e strang hunger &thorn;at &thorn;ar sal last ay,</L>
<L>&THORN;e whi[l]k &thorn;e synful in helle sal fele,</L>
<L>Ever-mare als &thorn;ir clerkes knawes wele.</L>
<L>&THORN;e strenthe of hungre sal &thorn;am swa chace</L>
<L N="6704">&THORN;at &thorn;air awen flesshe &thorn;ai sal of-race;</L>
<L>And for hungre &thorn;ai sal yherne it ete,</L>
<L>For &thorn;ai sal gett nan other meete;</L>
<L>For hungre &thorn;ai sal be als brayne-wode,</L>
<L N="6708">Bot &thorn;e dede &thorn;ar sal be &thorn;air fode,</L>
<L>Als says &thorn;e prophet in a stede:</L>
<L>'&THORN;ai sal be fedde with &thorn;e dede:'</L>
<L><I>Mors depascet</I></L>
<L N="6712"><I>eos.</I></L>
<L>&THORN;is es on Inglys &thorn;us to rede:</L>
<L>"&THORN;e dede &thorn;am sal dolefuly fede."</L>
<L>For als he &thorn;at has here hungre grete,</L>
<L N="6716">Thurgh kynde langes mast aftir mete,</L>
<L>Right swa &thorn;e synful &thorn;at sal duelle &thorn;are,</L>
<L>Yhit sal lange aftir &thorn;e ded wel mare</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ai mast hated and drede here,</L>
<L N="6720">Bot dighe may &thorn;ai noght on na manere,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;is Saynt Ion bers wittnes,</L>
<L>Als in &thorn;e apocalipse writen es:</L>
<L><I>Disiderabunt mori, et mors</I></L>
<L N="6724"><I>fugiet ab eis.</I></L>
<L>"Yherne &thorn;ai sal to dighe fra &thorn;air wa,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e ded sal ay fle &thorn;am fra;"
<PB REF="00000226.tif" N="182"></L>
<L>And for&thorn;y &thorn;at &thorn;ai wald gyf na mete</L>
<L N="6728">Til &thorn;e poer, &thorn;at here hunger had grete,</L>
<L>Ne of &thorn;am had nouther reuthe ne mercy,</L>
<L>Bot used ay outrage and glotony,</L>
<L>It es right &thorn;at &thorn;ai haf &thorn;is payne</L>
<L N="6732">Grete hungre in helle ay &thorn;ar ogayne.</L>
<L>&THORN;e fifte payne es, als sal befalle,</L>
<L>Grete threst &thorn;at &thorn;ai sal haf with-alle,</L>
<L>Swa mykel in helle sal be &thorn;air threst,</L>
<L N="6736">&THORN;at &thorn;air hertes sal nere clewe<NOTE PLACE="foot">clefe (MS. Harl. 4196).</NOTE> and brest;</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;e flaume of fire &thorn;ai sal drynk,</L>
<L>Menged with brunstan &thorn;at foul sal stynk,</L>
<L>And with smoke of fyre and wyndes blast,</L>
<L N="6740">And with other stormes &thorn;at ay sal last,</L>
<L>&THORN;at alle togider &thorn;an sal mete;</L>
<L>And &thorn;arfor says David &thorn;e prophete:</L>
<L><I>Ignis et sulphur et spiritus</I></L>
<L N="6744"><I>Procellarum pars calicis eorum.</I></L>
<L>He says &thorn;us, als we writen fynde,</L>
<L>"Fire and brunstan and stormes with wynde,</L>
<L>A part sal be &thorn;ar of &thorn;air drynk,"</L>
<L N="6748">And &thorn;at sal be menged with smoke and stynk;</L>
<L>Yhit sal &thorn;ai drynk, ogayne &thorn;air wille,</L>
<L>Another manere of drynk &thorn;at es ille,</L>
<L>&THORN;at sal be bitter and venemus,</L>
<L N="6752">And be cald &thorn;air wyne, for &thorn;e prophet says &thorn;us:</L>
<L><I>Fel draconum vinum eorum, et venenum</I></L>
<L><I>aspidum insanabile.</I></L>
<L>"Galle of draguns &thorn;air wyne sal be,</L>
<L N="6756">And wenym of snakes &thorn;ar-with," says he,</L>
<L>"&THORN;at may noght be heled wele,"</L>
<L>Swa violent it es to fele.</L>
<L>&THORN;ir wordes, aftir &thorn;e lettre, er hard to here,</L>
<L N="6760">Bot men may &thorn;am take on othir manere.</L>
<L>&THORN;ai sal swa brynnand threst thole,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;air hertes sal bryn with-in als a cole,
<PB REF="00000227.tif" N="183"></L>
<L>For na licour sal &thorn;ai fynd to fele,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;air threst mught sleke and &thorn;air hertes kele;</L>
<L N="6764">&THORN;ai sal for threst &thorn;e hevedes souke</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e nedders &thorn;at on &thorn;am sal rouke,</L>
<L>Als a childe &thorn;at sittes in &thorn;e moder lappe,</L>
<L>And when it list, soukes hir pappe;</L>
<L N="6768">For I fynd &thorn;is word in haly writt,</L>
<L>Als Iob says &thorn;at witnesses it:</L>
<L><I>Caput aspidum</I></L>
<L><I>sugent.</I></L>
<L N="6772">"&THORN;e heved of nedders &thorn;at on &thorn;am sal fest"</L>
<L>He says, "&thorn;ai sal souke &thorn;an for threst."</L>
<L>Strang payne of threst &thorn;an haf &thorn;ai</L>
<L>When &thorn;ai sal souke for therst<NOTE PLACE="foot">threst (MS. Harl. 4196).</NOTE> swilk venym ay.</L>
<L N="6776">And for-&thorn;i &thorn;at &thorn;ai wald never blethely</L>
<L>Gyf til poer at drynk &thorn;at war thresty,</L>
<L>To sleken &thorn;air threst, ne on &thorn;am thynk,</L>
<L>Ne nouther gyf &thorn;am mete ne drynk,</L>
<L N="6780">And on &thorn;air-selven na drynk wald spare</L>
<L>Na day, til &thorn;ai drunken ware,</L>
<L>It es &thorn;an right &thorn;at &thorn;at &thorn;ai in helle fele</L>
<L>Brynnand threst &thorn;at never sal kele;</L>
<L N="6784">&THORN;at sal &thorn;ai haf when &thorn;ai com &thorn;ider,</L>
<L>And sharp hungre alswa bath to-gydre,</L>
<L>&THORN;at never sal cesse, als I sayde ar;</L>
<L>For &thorn;ir twa paynes with othir er endel[e]s &thorn;ar,</L>
<L N="6788">Of &thorn;is Saynt Ierom bers wittnes,</L>
<L>&THORN;at says &thorn;us, als writen es:</L>
<L><I>In inferno erit fames infinita,</I></L>
<L><I>et sitis infinita.</I></L>
<L N="6792">"In helle sal be whar never es rest</L>
<L>Endel[e]s hungre and endeles threst."</L>
<L><I>Inferni pene sunt hec, vermes, tenebreque</I></L>
<L><I>flamma, chorus demonum, fetor, frigusque fa|mes, sitis, horror.</I></L>
<L N="6796">&THORN;e sext payne es over mykel myrknes,</L>
<L>&THORN;at in helle sal be ay endeles;
<PB REF="00000228.tif" N="184"></L>
<L>&THORN;at swa thik es &thorn;at men mught it grape,</L>
<L N="6800">Fra whilk &thorn;e synful sal never eschape.</L>
<L>For na hert may thynk ne tung telle,</L>
<L>Swa mykel mirkenes als es in helle,</L>
<L>Of whilk Iob spekes, als &thorn;e buk shewes wele,</L>
<L N="6804">And says, &thorn;e synful sal grape and fele</L>
<L>Myrkenes, als mykel at mydday</L>
<L>Als at mydnyght, &thorn;at sal last ay:</L>
<L><I>Palpabunt tenebras in meridie,</I></L>
<L N="6808"><I>sicut in media nocte.</I></L>
<L>"In helle es never day bot ever nyght;</L>
<L>&THORN;ar brynnes ay fire, bot it gyf[es] na light."</L>
<L>Bot yhit &thorn;e synful sal ay se</L>
<L N="6812">Alle &thorn;e sorowe &thorn;at &thorn;ar sal be,</L>
<L>And ilka payne and ilka tourment,</L>
<L>Thurgh sparkes of fire &thorn;at obout sal sprent.</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;at sight sal be til &thorn;am &thorn;are,</L>
<L N="6816">Na confort, bot sorowe and kare.</L>
<L>&THORN;us to eke &thorn;air paynes, &thorn;ai sal haf sight,</L>
<L>With-outen any comfort &thorn;ar of light;</L>
<L>And for-&thorn;i &thorn;at helle es ay lightles,</L>
<L N="6820">It es cald &thorn;e land of myrkenes,</L>
<L>&THORN;at es depe and myrke and hydus,</L>
<L>&THORN;arfor says Iob, &thorn;e haly man, &thorn;us:</L>
<L><I>Ut non revertar ad terram</I></L>
<L N="6824"><I>tenebrosam.</I></L>
<L>He says; "Loverd &thorn;at I noght turne away</L>
<L>Til &thorn;e myrke land", whare sorow es ay,</L>
<L>Whare wonyng es ay hydus and ille,</L>
<L N="6828">Als Iob says &thorn;at &thorn;us spekes mar &thorn;ar-tille:</L>
<L><I>Ubi nullus ordo, sed sempiternus</I></L>
<L><I>horror inhabitans.</I></L>
<L>"&THORN;ar nan ordre wonand es," says he,</L>
<L N="6832">"Bot uglynes &thorn;at ever mare sal be."</L>
<L>And for&thorn;i &thorn;at &thorn;e synful in &thorn;air lyf here,</L>
<L>Lufed ay myrknes of syns sere,</L>
<L>And wald noght turne &thorn;am when &thorn;ai myght,</L>
<L N="6836">Fra &thorn;at myrknes til Goddes light,
<PB REF="00000229.tif" N="185"></L>
<L>It es right &thorn;at &thorn;ai duelle &thorn;are,</L>
<L>In &thorn;at hidus myrknes ever-mare,</L>
<L>And never-mare aftir light se;</L>
<L N="6840">A strang payne til &thorn;am &thorn;at sal be.</L>
<L>&THORN;e sevend payne es of &thorn;e fourtene</L>
<L>&THORN;e sight of devels &thorn;at sal be sene</L>
<L>Omang &thorn;e synful &thorn;at sal be in helle,</L>
<L N="6844">In whas company &thorn;ai sal ay duelle.</L>
<L>&THORN;at sight sal be swa hidus to se,</L>
<L>&THORN;at alle &thorn;e men of cristiant&eacute;</L>
<L>Couthe noght, thurgh witt, ymagyn right,</L>
<L N="6848">Ne descryve swa hydus a sight,</L>
<L>Als &thorn;ai &thorn;an sal se in helle ever-mare,</L>
<L>Of ugly devels &thorn;at sal be &thorn;are,</L>
<L>For &thorn;an sal be ma devels in helle,</L>
<L N="6852">&THORN;an any tung can reken or telle;</L>
<L>And ilkan sal mare grysely seme</L>
<L>&THORN;an any man can ymagyn and deme:</L>
<L>For swa hardy es na man, ne swa balde</L>
<L N="6856">In &thorn;is werld, nouther yhung ne alde,</L>
<L>If he myght right consayve in mynde,</L>
<L>How grysely a devel es in his kynde,</L>
<L>&THORN;at durst for alle gude of mydlerde</L>
<L N="6860">A devel se here, swa suld he be aferde;</L>
<L>For &thorn;e hardyest man in flesshe and bane</L>
<L>&THORN;at here lyfes, yf he sawe ane</L>
<L>Of &thorn;a devels in &thorn;air awen lyknes,</L>
<L N="6864">Suld wax wode for ferde and be wittles.</L>
<L>For-why na witt of man may endure</L>
<L>To se a devel in his propre figure.</L>
<L>How sal &thorn;ai fare &thorn;an &thorn;at ay sal &thorn;am se,</L>
<L N="6868">And ay in company with pam be?</L>
<L>&THORN;e synful sal ever-mare on &thorn;am luke</L>
<L>For &thorn;us we fynde wryten in boke:</L>
<L><I>In inferno videbunt eos, facie ad faciem,</I></L>
<L N="6872"><I>quorum opera in terris dilexerunt.</I></L>
<L>"In helle &thorn;ai sal &thorn;am se, face to face,</L>
<L>Whas werkes &thorn;ai lufed and folowed &thorn;e trace,
<PB REF="00000230.tif" N="186"></L>
<L>Whilles &thorn;ai war here in erthe lyfand;"</L>
<L N="6876">And with &thorn;at syght, als I understand,</L>
<L>&THORN;ai sal duleful crying and sorow here,</L>
<L>For Saynt Austyn says on &thorn;is manere:</L>
<L><I>Demones igne scintillante</I></L>
<L N="6880"><I>videbunt, et miserabilem</I></L>
<L><I>clamorem flencium et la|</I></L>
<L><I>mentancium audient.</I></L>
<L>"&THORN;ai sal se &thorn;ar devels with eghe,</L>
<L N="6884">Thurgh sparkes &thorn;at of &thorn;e fire sal fleghe,</L>
<L>And here &thorn;ar-with on ilka party,</L>
<L>&THORN;e wreched synful grete and cry."</L>
<L>And &thorn;e sorow and dule &thorn;at &thorn;ai sal make,</L>
<L N="6888">Sal never-mar &thorn;ar cees ne slake;</L>
<L>And for&thorn;i &thorn;at &thorn;at here hated to se,</L>
<L>And to here &thorn;at &thorn;at gude suld be,</L>
<L>And &thorn;arfor it es reson and ryght,</L>
<L N="6892">&THORN;at &thorn;ai ay se &thorn;at grysely syght,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at &thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;ai?</NOTE> heryng haf of duleful dyn,</L>
<L>To eke &thorn;air payn for &thorn;air sin.</L>
<L>&THORN;e aghtend payne, als &thorn;e buke says us,</L>
<L N="6896">Es &thorn;e horribel vermyn venemus.</L>
<L>&THORN;e whilk sal on &thorn;e synful rouke,</L>
<L>And ever-mare &thorn;am gnaw and souke,</L>
<L>Als ugly draguns, and nedders kene;</L>
<L N="6900">And tades swa hydus was never here sene</L>
<L>And othir vermyn ful of venym,</L>
<L>And wode bestes grysely and grym,</L>
<L>&THORN;at with tethe sal with &thorn;am ay gnaw and byte,</L>
<L N="6904">On alle &thorn;air lyms, whar &thorn;ai had delite</L>
<L>Synful werkes here for to wirk,</L>
<L>Agayne &thorn;e law of God and of haly kyrk.</L>
<L>&THORN;us for &thorn;ai did ay ogayns Goddes lawe,</L>
<L N="6908">Vermyn and wode bestes sal &thorn;am ay gnawe,</L>
<L>For &thorn;air syn &thorn;at &thorn;am thoght here swete,</L>
<L>&THORN;arfor God says &thorn;us thurgh &thorn;e prophete:</L>
<L><I>Dentes bestiarum immittam in eos, cum furo|</I></L>
<L N="6912"><I>re trahencium in terra atque serpencium.</I>
<PB REF="00000231.tif" N="187"></L>
<L>"I sal send in &thorn;e synful", says he,</L>
<L>"&THORN;e tethe of bestes &thorn;at felle sal be</L>
<L>With wodenes of &thorn;am in-til crthe drawand,</L>
<L N="6916">And of nedders &thorn;am fast gnawand."</L>
<L>&THORN;us sal wode bestes and vermyn gnaw &thorn;am ay</L>
<L>And never-mare pas fra &thorn;am oway;</L>
<L>And &thorn;at payne &thorn;e synful byhoves ay dreghe,</L>
<L N="6920">For-why &thorn;air vermyn sal never dieghe,</L>
<L>Bot ever-mare lyfand with &thorn;am duelle,</L>
<L>&THORN;arfor God says &thorn;us in &thorn;e godspelle:</L>
<L><I>Vermis eorum non morietur,</I></L>
<L N="6924"><I>et ignis eorum non extinguetur.</I></L>
<L>"&THORN;air vermyn salle never deghe," says he,</L>
<L>"Ne &thorn;air fyre salle never slekend be;"</L>
<L>And to &thorn;at says &thorn;us Saynt Austyne,</L>
<L N="6928">&THORN;at spekes here of &thorn;at vermyne:</L>
<L><I>Vermes infernales sunt immortales qui, ut pis|</I></L>
<L><I>ces in aqua, ita vivunt in flamma.</I></L>
<L>He says, "vermyn of helle salle ay lyfe,</L>
<L N="6932">And never deghe &thorn;e synfulle to gryefe,</L>
<L>The whilk salle lyfe in &thorn;e flawme of fyre,</L>
<L>Als fyssches lyfes in water schyre."</L>
<L>&THORN;at vermyn on &thorn;am salle ay crepe,</L>
<L N="6936">In &thorn;am fest &thorn;air clokes full depe;<NOTE PLACE="foot">And in &thorn;aim feste &thorn;air <I>clowes</I> ful depe (MS. Harl. 6923).</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;ai salle umlapp &thorn;am alle oboute,</L>
<L>And gnaw on ilka lym and souke;</L>
<L>With vermyn &thorn;ai salle alle coverd be,</L>
<L N="6940">Swa &thorn;at na lym of &thorn;am salle be fre,</L>
<L>And swa &thorn;ai salle be ay gnawand</L>
<L>On &thorn;air lyms, whether &thorn;ai lyg or stand;</L>
<L>Vermyn in helle salle be &thorn;air clethyng</L>
<L N="6944">And vermyn salle &thorn;are be &thorn;air beddyng.</L>
<L>Na clathes &thorn;ai salle have to gang in,</L>
<L>Ne na beddes to lyg in bot vermyn,</L>
<L>Wharfor I fynd wryten &thorn;are I have red,</L>
<L N="6948">How &thorn;e prophete discryved swilk a bed</L>
<L>To &thorn;e kyng Nabogodonosor,</L>
<L>And sayd &thorn;us to mak him ferd &thorn;arfor:
<PB REF="00000232.tif" N="188"></L>
<L><I>Subter te sternetur tinea, et</I></L>
<L N="6952"><I>operimentum tuum vermes.</I></L>
<L>He says "of wormes &thorn;i bed salle be</L>
<L>&THORN;at salle be strewed thyk under &thorn;e,</L>
<L>And &thorn;i covertoure on &thorn;e sene</L>
<L N="6956">Salle be vermyn fulle felle and kene."</L>
<L>Swilk beddes er ordaynd in helle</L>
<L>Ffor synfulle men &thorn;at &thorn;ar salle dwelle.</L>
<L>&THORN;us salle &thorn;ai be pyned for &thorn;air syn,</L>
<L N="6960">Ever-mare with fyre and vermyn,</L>
<L>And with many other payns ma;</L>
<L>Ffor God vouches safe &thorn;at it be swa,</L>
<L>Ffor &thorn;us fynd we wryten in haly wrytt,</L>
<L N="6964">In a boke of &thorn;e Bibelle &thorn;at hate Iudyth:</L>
<L><I>Dabit dominus ignem et vermes</I></L>
<L><I>in carnes eorum, ut urantur</I></L>
<L><I>et senciant, usque in sem|</I></L>
<L N="6968"><I>piternum.</I></L>
<L>It says "fyre and vermyn &thorn;at ay salle lyfe,</L>
<L>Our lord tylle &thorn;e flesch of synfulle salle gyfe,</L>
<L>Swa &thorn;at &thorn;ai salle bryn ever-mare,</L>
<L N="6972">And ay fele of vermyn bytyng sare."</L>
<L>&THORN;is payne es mare to fele and se,</L>
<L>&THORN;an alle &thorn;e paynes &thorn;at may be</L>
<L>In &thorn;is werld here, mare and les,</L>
<L N="6976">Als &thorn;e boke openly bers witnes,</L>
<L>&THORN;us salle vermyn in helle be gret payne,</L>
<L>Bot yhit may men say here ogayne,</L>
<L>Ffor men may in som boke wryten se</L>
<L N="6980">&THORN;at after &thorn;e gret dome &thorn;at last salle be,</L>
<L>Na quyk creature salle lyf &thorn;an,</L>
<L>Bot anely aungelle, develle and man,</L>
<L>'How suld in helle &thorn;an or ourwhare elles,</L>
<L N="6984">Any vermyn lyf als men telles,</L>
<L>Or any other best &thorn;at moght dere?'</L>
<L>To &thorn;is may men gyf answere</L>
<L>On &thorn;is manere, wha-swa kan;</L>
<L N="6988">&THORN;e vermyn &thorn;at salle be &thorn;an,
<PB REF="00000233.tif" N="189"></L>
<L>Als I understand, noght elles es</L>
<L>Bot devels in vermyn lyknes,</L>
<L>&THORN;at salle byte and gnaw &thorn;e synfulle &thorn;are,</L>
<L N="6992">To eke &thorn;air payne and mak it mare.</L>
<L>&THORN;us salle &thorn;e devels gnaw &thorn;am with-out,</L>
<L>In lyknes of vermyn alle obout.</L>
<L>And &thorn;air conscience als vermyn,</L>
<L N="6996">Salle gnaw &thorn;am over-alle with-in,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at gnawyng salle be fulle hard,</L>
<L>Of whilk I salle speke sone afterward.</L>
<L>&THORN;at vermyn in helle salle be mare grysely</L>
<L N="7000">&THORN;an vermyn here es, and mare myghty.</L>
<L>By vermyn here &thorn;an &thorn;at greves sare,</L>
<L>Men aght to drede &thorn;e vermyn &thorn;are;</L>
<L>And for&thorn;i &thorn;at &thorn;e synfulle was here namely,</L>
<L N="7004">Ay fulle of hateredyn and of envy,</L>
<L>And wald noght amend &thorn;am of &thorn;at syn,</L>
<L>Bot lete it gnaw &thorn;am ay with-in,</L>
<L>It es ryght and skylle thurgh Godes lawe,</L>
<L N="7008">&THORN;at &thorn;e vermyn in helle ay &thorn;am gnawe.</L>
<L>&THORN;e neghend payne es to understand,</L>
<L>Dyngyng of devels with hamers glowand;</L>
<L>Ffor &thorn;e devels &thorn;e synfulle salle ay bete</L>
<L N="7012">With glowand hamers huge and grete</L>
<L>And als smyths strykes on &thorn;e yren fast,</L>
<L>Swa &thorn;at it brekes and brestes at &thorn;e last,</L>
<L>Right swa &thorn;e devels salle ay dyng</L>
<L N="7016">On &thorn;e synfulle, with-outen styntyng;</L>
<L>And with hamers gyf swa gret dyntes,</L>
<L>&THORN;atalle to powdre moght stryke hard flyntes;</L>
<L>Ffor harder dyntes gaf never engyne,</L>
<L N="7020">&THORN;an &thorn;ai salle gyf, als says Saint Austyne:</L>
<L><I>Sicut machina bellita percutit</I></L>
<L><I>muros opidi, ita demones ym|</I></L>
<L><I>mo asperius et crudelius, corpora malorum</I></L>
<L N="7024"><I>et animas flagellabunt, post iudicium.</I></L>
<L>He says "als men may se ane engyne cast,</L>
<L>And at &thorn;e walles of a castelle stryke fast
<PB REF="00000234.tif" N="190"></L>
<L>With a stane &thorn;at es huge and hevy,</L>
<L N="7028">Swa salle devels stryke &thorn;ase<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;use?</NOTE> mare felly</L>
<L>&THORN;e ille bodyse and saules &thorn;at salle dwelle,</L>
<L>After &thorn;e last gret dome in helle."</L>
<L>&THORN;us salle &thorn;ai dyng on &thorn;am ever-mare,</L>
<L N="7032">With gret glowand hamers, and nane spare.</L>
<L>And &thorn;is payne tylle &thorn;am salle be endles,</L>
<L>Als &thorn;e bok here-of bers witnes;</L>
<L>Ffor &thorn;ai salle have power ay and leve,</L>
<L N="7036">&THORN;e synfull men to dyng and greve,</L>
<L>Als in a boke es schewed tylle us,</L>
<L>&THORN;at Saynt Austyne made, &thorn;are he says &thorn;us:</L>
<L><I>Parata iudicia blasphemtoribus, et percu|</I></L>
<L N="7040"><I>cientibus malleis stultorum corpora.</I></L>
<L>"&THORN;e domes salle &thorn;an be redy</L>
<L>Tille &thorn;e sklaunderers of God alle myghty,</L>
<L>And tylle &thorn;ase &thorn;at salle be ay smytand</L>
<L N="7044">&THORN;e bodyse of synfulle with melles in hand."</L>
<L>And for&thorn;i &thorn;at &thorn;ai wald noght take</L>
<L>Haly disciplyne here, for Godes sake,</L>
<L>&THORN;arfor &thorn;e devels salle stryk &thorn;am &thorn;are,</L>
<L N="7048">With hevy melles ay, and nane spare.</L>
<L>&THORN;e tend payne es &thorn;e gnawyng with-in</L>
<L>Of &thorn;air conscience &thorn;at never salle blyn;</L>
<L>Ffor with-in &thorn;am salle &thorn;e worme of conscience frete</L>
<L N="7052">Als with-outen salle do vermyn grete,</L>
<L>And swa salle &thorn;ai ever-mare, with-outen dout,</L>
<L>Be gnawen and byten with-in and with-out.</L>
<L>Ffulle mykelle sorow salle &thorn;an be in helle</L>
<L N="7056">Omang &thorn;e synfulle &thorn;at &thorn;are salle dwelle;</L>
<L>Ffor &thorn;ai salle ever &thorn;us cry and say,</L>
<L>'Allas! Allas! and walaway!</L>
<L>Whi ne wald we never are trow,</L>
<L N="7060">What payne and sorow here es now.'</L>
<L>&THORN;an salle &thorn;ai pleyne &thorn;am of &thorn;air wickednes,</L>
<L>And say &thorn;us, als in boke wryten es:</L>
<L><I>Quid nobis profuit superbia, quid divicia|</I></L>
<L N="7064"><I>rum iactancia, omnia transierunt velud um|</I>
<PB REF="00000235.tif" N="191"></L>
<L><I>bra, et tanquam nuncius percurrens, et tanquam</I></L>
<L><I>na vis procedens in fluctuantem aquam, et tan|</I></L>
<L><I>quam avis transvolans in aere, cuius itineris non</I></L>
<L N="7068"><I>est invenire vestigium.</I></L>
<L>"What avayld us pryde", &thorn;ai salle say,</L>
<L>"What rosyng of ryches or of ryche aray?</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;at pomp als we se now,</L>
<L N="7072">Es passed oway als a schadow,</L>
<L>And als messanger bifore rynand,</L>
<L>And als schypp &thorn;at gase in water flowand,</L>
<L>And als foghel fleghand in &thorn;e ayre als wynd,</L>
<L N="7076">Of whase gate men may na trace fynd."</L>
<L>&THORN;us salle alle &thorn;air pomp oway pas,</L>
<L>And be als thyng &thorn;at never was,</L>
<L>&THORN;an salle &thorn;am thynk when alle es oway,</L>
<L N="7080">Alle &thorn;air lyfe here bot als ane howr of a day,</L>
<L>&THORN;of &thorn;ai never so lang had lyfed here,</L>
<L>&THORN;ai may say on &thorn;is manere:</L>
<L>'Right now born we war in &thorn;e world to be,</L>
<L N="7084">Ryght now in alle our delytes lyfed we,</L>
<L>Ryght now we deghed and passed oway</L>
<L>Now er we in helle and swa salle be ay,'</L>
<L>&THORN;an salle &thorn;ai knaw how ille &thorn;ai haf lyfed,</L>
<L N="7088">When &thorn;e worme of conscience &thorn;am has greved,</L>
<L>&THORN;at with-in salle &thorn;am ay gnaw and byte</L>
<L>Ffor &thorn;ai in vanyt&eacute; had here delyte,</L>
<L>And for-&thorn;i &thorn;at conscience styrd &thorn;am noght,</L>
<L N="7092">To forsake &thorn;air folyes &thorn;at &thorn;ai wroght,</L>
<L>Bot folowed ay here &thorn;air flesschly wille;</L>
<L>&THORN;arfor it es gud, ryght, and skylle,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e worme of conscience with-in,</L>
<L N="7096">Ever-mare in helle &thorn;am gnaw for &thorn;air syn.</L>
<L>&THORN;e ellevend payne es teres of gretyng</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e synfulle &thorn;at, with-outen styntyng,</L>
<L>Sal grete ever-mare, als says &thorn;e boke;</L>
<L N="7100">Ffor-whi what for sorow, and what thurgh smoke</L>
<L>And what thurgh cald, and what thurgh hete</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ai salle thole, &thorn;ai salle ay grete,
<PB REF="00000236.tif" N="192"></L>
<L>And &thorn;us teres fra &thorn;air eghen salle ryn</L>
<L N="7104">Ever-mare and never salle blyn.</L>
<L>Swa mykelle water als salle falle &thorn;an,</L>
<L>Ffra a mans eghe may gesce na man;</L>
<L>Ffor-whi &thorn;ai salle ay be gretand,</L>
<L N="7108">And &thorn;air teres salle be ay flowand,</L>
<L>And fra &thorn;air eghen ryn swa fast,</L>
<L>And &thorn;air gretyng swa lang salle last,</L>
<L>&THORN;at in alle &thorn;e world here, als I wene,</L>
<L N="7112">Es noght swa mykelle water sene,</L>
<L>Als fra &thorn;air eghen salle falle &thorn;are;</L>
<L>Ffor &thorn;ai salle be gretand ever-mare.</L>
<L>Wharfor Saint Austyn says &thorn;us,</L>
<L N="7116">Whase wordes er auctentyke tylle us:</L>
<L><I>In inferno plures effundentur lacrime</I></L>
<L><I>quam sunt in mari gutte.</I></L>
<L>"In helle," he says, "out-yhetted salle be,</L>
<L N="7120">Ma teres &thorn;an dropes er in &thorn;e se,"</L>
<L>&THORN;e synfulle salle &thorn;are &thorn;us ever-mare grete,</L>
<L>And &thorn;air [teres] salle be of swa gret hete,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e water &thorn;at &thorn;an salle doun-ryn,</L>
<L N="7124">Ffra &thorn;air eghen, salle &thorn;am schald and bryn,</L>
<L>Ffor it salle be hatter &thorn;an ever was</L>
<L>Molten led or welland bras,</L>
<L>Als I have herd gret clerkes telle,</L>
<L N="7128">&THORN;at has descryved &thorn;e payns of helle;</L>
<L>And for-&thorn;i &thorn;at &thorn;ai had here ay lykyng</L>
<L>In &thorn;air syn and never forthynkyng,</L>
<L>Ne sorow &thorn;arfore, for &thorn;am thoght it swete,</L>
<L N="7132">&THORN;arfor &thorn;ai salle in helle ay grete,</L>
<L>And with &thorn;air teres be schalded sare,</L>
<L>To eke &thorn;air paynes, als I sayd are.</L>
<L>&THORN;e twelfte payne es schame and schenshepe,</L>
<L N="7136">&THORN;at &thorn;e synfulle salle have in helle swa depe,</L>
<L>Of ilka syn &thorn;at ever &thorn;ai dyd;</L>
<L>Ffor-whi &thorn;are salle be knawen and kyd</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;air syns of thoght, or word and werk,</L>
<L N="7140">Als says Saint Austyne &thorn;e gret clerk:
<PB REF="00000237.tif" N="193"></L>
<L><I>Omnia in omnibus patebunt, et se ab|</I></L>
<L><I>scondere non valebunt.</I></L>
<L>"Alle &thorn;air syns in &thorn;am salle shewed be</L>
<L N="7144">And &thorn;ai may nouther &thorn;an &thorn;am hyde ne fle."</L>
<L>&THORN;ai salle have mare schame of &thorn;air syn &thorn;are,</L>
<L>And &thorn;air schendschepe salle be mare,</L>
<L>&THORN;an ever had any man here in thoght</L>
<L N="7148">Ffor any velany &thorn;at ever he wroght,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at schame with &thorn;am salle last ay,</L>
<L>And never salle pas fra &thorn;am oway;</L>
<L>&THORN;ai may say &thorn;us &thorn;at &thorn;are &thorn;an dwelles,</L>
<L N="7152">Als &thorn;e prophete in &thorn;e psauter telles;</L>
<L><I>Tota die verecundia mea contra me est, et</I></L>
<L><I>confusio faciei mee cooperuit me.</I></L>
<L>&THORN;at es, "my schamefulnes," says he,</L>
<L N="7156">Alle day es ogayns me,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e schenschepe of my face</L>
<L>Salle cover me, in ilka place."</L>
<L>&THORN;ai salle swa schame ay of &thorn;air syn,</L>
<L N="7160">&THORN;at &thorn;am salle thynk als &thorn;ai suld bryn,</L>
<L>Ffor &thorn;e gret schame &thorn;at &thorn;ai salle have &thorn;are,</L>
<L>&THORN;at never salle cese, bot last ever-mare;</L>
<L>Wharfor if na payne war in helle,</L>
<L N="7164">Bot &thorn;at schame anely, &thorn;at I of telle,</L>
<L>It suld be tylle &thorn;am &thorn;are mare payne,</L>
<L>&THORN;an any man couth here ordayne;</L>
<L>And for&thorn;i &thorn;at &thorn;ai here in &thorn;air lyfe,</L>
<L N="7168">Durst never for schame of syn &thorn;am schryve,</L>
<L>Bot with-outen schame to syn was bald,</L>
<L>It es ryght &thorn;at &thorn;ai have, als I tald,</L>
<L>Schame in helle for &thorn;air syn,</L>
<L N="7172">Of whilk &thorn;ai wald here never blyn.</L>
<L>&THORN;e threttende payne es, als clerkes wate,</L>
<L>&THORN;e bandes of fyre brynand fulle hate,</L>
<L>With whilk &thorn;e synfulle salle be bonden,</L>
<L N="7176">Als in som boke wryten es fonden;</L>
<L>And &thorn;a bandes of fyre salle never slake.</L>
<L>Ffor &thorn;ai wald never &thorn;air syn forsake,
<PB REF="00000238.tif" N="194"></L>
<L>&THORN;ai salle be with &thorn;a bandes brynand,</L>
<L N="7180">In helle hard bonden, both fote and hand,</L>
<L>And straytely streyned ilka lym,</L>
<L>Thurgh &thorn;e devels &thorn;at er ugly and grym.</L>
<L>&THORN;air wonyng in helle salle be endeles,</L>
<L N="7184">Omang stynk and fylth in gret myrknes,</L>
<L>Whare ever es nyght and never day,</L>
<L>Als men may here gret clerkes say.</L>
<L>&THORN;an salle &thorn;ai fele, when &thorn;ai &thorn;are come,</L>
<L N="7188">Godes vengeance thurgh ryghtwise dome,</L>
<L>Ffor &thorn;air syn &thorn;at him here myspays,</L>
<L>Wharfor God &thorn;us in &thorn;e gosspelle says:</L>
<L><I>Ligatis manibus et pedibus, mittite</I></L>
<L N="7192"><I>in tenebras exteriores.</I></L>
<L>"Lat bynd &thorn;air hend and &thorn;air fete fast,</L>
<L>And in-to &thorn;e utter myrknes &thorn;am cast,"</L>
<L>&THORN;at es in &thorn;e deppest pytt of helle,</L>
<L N="7196">Whare mare sorow es &thorn;an tong may telle.</L>
<L>&THORN;are salle &thorn;air hevedes be turned dounward,</L>
<L>And &thorn;air fete upward bonden hard,</L>
<L>And &thorn;air bodyse be streyned bi fete and hed,</L>
<L N="7200">With brynand bandes glowand red;</L>
<L>&THORN;ai salle be pyned on &thorn;is manere,</L>
<L>With other paynes many and sere,</L>
<L>Als a gret clerk says openly,</L>
<L N="7204">In a boke &thorn;at he made thurgh study,</L>
<L>Of sere questyons of divinit&eacute;,</L>
<L>&THORN;at es cald 'Flos Sciencie'</L>
<L>&THORN;at es on Ynglys '&thorn;e flour of konyng'</L>
<L N="7208">Whare wryten es many priv&eacute; thyng;</L>
<L>In &thorn;at boke &thorn;us he telles,</L>
<L>How &thorn;ai salle hyng &thorn;at &thorn;ar &thorn;an dwelles:</L>
<L><I>Capita, inquit, eorum erunt ad-invicem deorsum versa,</I></L>
<L N="7212"><I>pedes sursum erecti, et undique penis distenti.</I></L>
<L>He says "in &thorn;e grond of helle dongeoune</L>
<L>"&THORN;e hevedes of synfulle salle be turned doune,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e fete upward fast knytted</L>
<L N="7216">And in strang payns be streyned and tytted."
<PB REF="00000239.tif" N="195"></L>
<L>And for-&thorn;i, &thorn;at &thorn;ai war here ay redy</L>
<L>To syn, with sere lyms of &thorn;air body,</L>
<L>&THORN;arfor &thorn;ai salle be bonden &thorn;are</L>
<L N="7220">Be divers lyms, als I sayd are,</L>
<L>With brynand bandes hate glowand,</L>
<L>&THORN;at ever mare salle be lastand;</L>
<L>And for-&thorn;i &thorn;at &thorn;ai wald noght God knaw,</L>
<L N="7224">Na kepe &thorn;e ordre here of his law,</L>
<L>Bot turned &thorn;am ay fro God-ward,</L>
<L>And on &thorn;e world &thorn;air hertes sett hard,</L>
<L>And swa mysturned here &thorn;air lyfyng</L>
<L N="7228">In-tylle vanyt&eacute; and flesschly lykyng,</L>
<L>&THORN;arfor it es ryght and resoune,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ai be turned up-swa-doune,</L>
<L>And streyned in helle and bonden fast,</L>
<L N="7232">With bandes of fire &thorn;at ay salle last.</L>
<L>&THORN;e fourtende payne es despayre to telle,</L>
<L>In whilk &thorn;e synfulle salle ay dwelle,</L>
<L>With-outen hope of mercy &thorn;an,</L>
<L N="7236">Ffor Salamon says &thorn;us, &thorn;e wise man:</L>
<L><I>Omnes qui ingrediuntur ad infernum non rever|</I></L>
<L><I>tentur, nec apprehendent semitas vite.</I></L>
<L>He says "alle &thorn;ase &thorn;at tylle helle wendes,</L>
<L N="7240">And in despayre salle be omang fendes,</L>
<L>Salle never after turne ogayne,</L>
<L>Ne tak &thorn;e ways of lyfe certayne."</L>
<L>For when &thorn;ai er dampned thurgh iugement,</L>
<L N="7244">And with body and saule tille helle er sent,</L>
<L>&THORN;ai salle never after, with-outen dout,</L>
<L>Have hope, ne thynk to com out,</L>
<L>Bot ever-mare dwelle with-outen hope,</L>
<L N="7248">Ffor &thorn;us says &thorn;e haly man Job:</L>
<L><I>Quia in inferno nulla est</I></L>
<L><I>redempcio.</I></L>
<L>"Ffor in hell", he says, "es na redempcyoune"</L>
<L N="7252">Thurgh na help of frende; for na devocyone</L>
<L>Of prayer, ne almusdede, ne messe,</L>
<L>May &thorn;am help, ne &thorn;air payn mak les.
<PB REF="00000240.tif" N="196"></L>
<L>A strang payn salle &thorn;is be in helle,</L>
<L N="7256">Ever-mare &thorn;us in despayre to dwelle,</L>
<L>With-outen hope of recouverere.</L>
<L>&THORN;is passes alle &thorn;e payns of &thorn;is lyfe here,</L>
<L>Ffor here has na man payn swa strang,</L>
<L N="7260">&THORN;at he ne has som tyme hope omang,</L>
<L>Outher of remedy &thorn;at men may kast,</L>
<L>Or &thorn;at it salle end and noght ay last;</L>
<L>Elles suld &thorn;e hert, thurgh sorow and care,</L>
<L N="7264">Over-tyte fayle, warn som hope ware;</L>
<L>Ffor in sorow here hope comfortes best.</L>
<L>And men says, warn hope ware it suld brest.</L>
<L>Bot in helle na hope may falle in thoght,</L>
<L N="7268">And &thorn;air hertes brest may noght;</L>
<L>Ffor &thorn;ai er ordaynd to lyf ay &thorn;are,</L>
<L>Swa &thorn;at &thorn;ai may be pyned ever-mare.</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;e lyfe of &thorn;am in &thorn;at stede</L>
<L N="7272">Es wers and bytterer &thorn;an &thorn;e dede.</L>
<L>Bot better it war to be fully slayne,</L>
<L>&THORN;an over-lang lyfe in strang payne;</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;e synfulle salle ay &thorn;are in payne be,</L>
<L N="7276">And na ded may &thorn;am sla bot ay &thorn;am fle,</L>
<L>Als &thorn;e boke openly schewes us,</L>
<L>Whare we may fynd wryten &thorn;us:</L>
<L><I>Mors fugiet ab eis.</I></L>
<L N="7280">"&THORN;e ded", &thorn;at here es strang and hard</L>
<L>"Salle ay &thorn;an fle fra &thorn;am-ward,"</L>
<L>&THORN;e payns of &thorn;e ded &thorn;ai salle ay dreghe,</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;ai salle never-mare fully deghe;</L>
<L N="7284">&THORN;ai salle ay lyf in sorow and stryfe,</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;air lyf salle seme mare ded &thorn;an lyfe;</L>
<L>&THORN;air lyfe in mydward &thorn;e ded salle stand,</L>
<L>Ffor &thorn;ai salle lyfe ever-mare deghand,</L>
<L N="7288">And deghe ever-mare lyfand with-alle,</L>
<L>Als men dose &thorn;at we se in swowne falle;</L>
<L>And for-&thorn;i, &thorn;at &thorn;ai here mykelle lufed syn,</L>
<L>And thurgh over-mykelle hope ay lyfed &thorn;ar-in,
<PB REF="00000241.tif" N="197"></L>
<L N="7292">And to leve &thorn;air syn had never wille,</L>
<L>&THORN;arfor it es gud, ryght and skylle,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ai be ay for &thorn;air foly,</L>
<L>In helle with-outen hope of mercy.</L>
<L N="7296">Now have I schewed yhow, als I couth telle,</L>
<L>&THORN;e fourtene generalle payns in helle;</L>
<L>Bot yhit es over &thorn;ase a payne generalle,</L>
<L>&THORN;at of alle other es mast principalle,</L>
<L N="7300">&THORN;at es tharnyng for ever of the syght namly,</L>
<L>Of our Lord God alle-myghty.</L>
<L>Ffor whilk syght &thorn;at &thorn;ai for ever have tynt,</L>
<L>&THORN;ai salle have sorow &thorn;at never salle stynt;</L>
<L N="7304">And &thorn;e sorow &thorn;at &thorn;arfor salle falle</L>
<L>Salle be mast payne to &thorn;am of alle,</L>
<L>For als &thorn;e syght of God in heven, es</L>
<L>Mast ioy of alle other, mare and les,</L>
<L N="7308">Right swa &thorn;e tharnyng for ever of &thorn;at syght,</L>
<L>Es &thorn;e mast payne in helle dyght;</L>
<L>Ffor alle &thorn;e payns &thorn;at in helle may be,</L>
<L>Suld noght &thorn;am dere if &thorn;ai moght him se.</L>
<L N="7312">Yhit salle &thorn;are be sere payns many ma</L>
<L>Als &thorn;e boke says, and mare sorow and wa</L>
<L>&THORN;an alle &thorn;e men of erth, ald and yhong,</L>
<L>Moght thynk with hert or telle with tong,</L>
<L N="7316">&THORN;at &thorn;e synful men &thorn;at salle wende</L>
<L>Tille helle salle have with-outen ende,</L>
<L>&THORN;e whilk payns and sorow salle never cees;</L>
<L>Ffor &thorn;are salle never be rest ne pees,</L>
<L N="7320">Bot travail and stryfe with sorow and care,</L>
<L>Fulle wa salle &thorn;am be &thorn;at salle dwelle &thorn;are;</L>
<L>&THORN;ai sall thynk on nathyng elles,</L>
<L>Bot on &thorn;air payns, als som clerkes telles,</L>
<L N="7324">And on &thorn;air syn &thorn;at &thorn;ai here wroght,</L>
<L>Swa salle payns and sorow troble &thorn;air thoght;</L>
<L>Ffor &thorn;are salle be &thorn;an herd and sene,</L>
<L>Alkyn sorow and trey and tene.</L>
<L N="7328">&THORN;are salle be wantyng of alkyn thyng,</L>
<L>In whilk moght be any lykyng,
<PB REF="00000242.tif" N="198"></L>
<L>And defaut of alle thyng &thorn;at gud moght be,</L>
<L>And of alle &thorn;at ille es gret plent&eacute;.</L>
<L N="7332">In helle salle be &thorn;an fulle dolefulle dyn,</L>
<L>Omang &thorn;e synfulle &thorn;at salle dwelle &thorn;ar-in,</L>
<L>&THORN;at ever-mare salle &thorn;us cry and say:</L>
<L>"Allas, allas and walaway!</L>
<L N="7336">&THORN;at ever we war of wemmen borne,</L>
<L>Ffor we er fra God for ever lorne?"</L>
<L>&THORN;an salle &thorn;ai grete and goule and with teth gnayste</L>
<L>Ffor of help ne mercy &thorn;ar &thorn;am noght trayste.<NOTE PLACE="foot">&THORN;ai salle gret and with teth gnayste, For mercy &thorn;ar &thorn;aim nane traiste (MS. Harl. 6923).</NOTE></L>
<L N="7340">&THORN;e devels obout &thorn;am &thorn;an in helle,</L>
<L>On &thorn;am salle ever-mare rare and yhelle;</L>
<L>Swa hydus noyse &thorn;ai salle &thorn;an make,</L>
<L>&THORN;at alle &thorn;e world it moght do qwake,</L>
<L N="7344">And alle &thorn;e men lyfand &thorn;at herd it,</L>
<L>To ga wode for ferd and tyne &thorn;air witt.</L>
<L>&THORN;e devils ay omang on &thorn;am salle stryke,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e synfulle &thorn;are-with ay cry and skryke;</L>
<L N="7348">&THORN;are salle be &thorn;an mare noyse and dyn,</L>
<L>&THORN;an alle &thorn;e men of erth couth ymagyn,</L>
<L>Ffor &thorn;are salle be swilk rareyng and ruschyng</L>
<L>And raumpyng of devels and dyngyng and dusching</L>
<L N="7352">And skrykyng of synfulle, als I said are,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e noyse salle be swa hydus &thorn;are,</L>
<L>Omang devels and &thorn;ase &thorn;at salle com &thorn;ider,</L>
<L>Ryght als heven and erth strake togyder.</L>
<L N="7356">Ane hydus thing es it to telle</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e noyse &thorn;at salle &thorn;an be in helle;</L>
<L>&THORN;e devels, &thorn;at ay salle be fulle of ire,</L>
<L>Salle stopp &thorn;e synfulle ay in &thorn;e fyre,</L>
<L N="7360">Swa &thorn;at &thorn;ai salle glowe ay als fyre brandes</L>
<L>And ay when &thorn;ai may weld &thorn;air hands,<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. Harl. 6923 reads <I>styr</I> for weld.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ffor sorow &thorn;ai salle &thorn;am hard wryng;</L>
<L>And walaway &thorn;ai salle ay syng.</L>
<L N="7364">In helle salle be &thorn;an swa gret thrang,</L>
<L>&THORN;at nane may remow for other ne gang.
<PB REF="00000243.tif" N="199"></L>
<L>On na syde, backward ne forward</L>
<L>Ffor &thorn;ai salle be pressed togyder swaharde,</L>
<L N="7368">Als &thorn;ai war stopped togyder in ane oven,</L>
<L>Ffulle of fyre bineth and oboven;</L>
<L>Bot never-&thorn;e-les helle yhit es swa depe,</L>
<L>And swa wyde and large, &thorn;at it moght kepe</L>
<L N="7372">Alle &thorn;e creatures, les and mare,</L>
<L>Of alle &thorn;e world if myster ware.</L>
<L>Ilka synfulle salle &thorn;are on other prese,</L>
<L>And nane of &thorn;am salle other eese,</L>
<L N="7376">Bot ever fyght togyder and stryfe,</L>
<L>Als &thorn;ai war wode men of &thorn;is lyfe,</L>
<L>And ilk ane scratte other in &thorn;e face,</L>
<L>And &thorn;air awen flessch of-ryve and race,</L>
<L N="7380">Swa &thorn;at ilk ane wald him self fayn sla,</L>
<L>If he moght, swa salle him be wa,</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;are-to salle &thorn;ai haf na myght,</L>
<L>Ffor &thorn;e ded salle never mar on &thorn;am lyght.</L>
<L N="7384">Ffulle fayn &thorn;ai wald &thorn;an ded be,</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;e ded salle ay fra &thorn;am fle;</L>
<L>After &thorn;e ded &thorn;ai salle yherne ilk ane,</L>
<L>Als in &thorn;e apocalypse schewes Saint Iohan:</L>
<L N="7388"><I>Desiderabunt mori, et</I></L>
<L><I>mors fugit ab eis.</I></L>
<L>"&THORN;ai sall yherne", he says, "to deghe ay,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e ded salle fle fra &thorn;am oway;"</L>
<L N="7392">Omang &thorn;am salle ay be debate,</L>
<L>Ilk ane of &thorn;am salle other hate.</L>
<L>&THORN;ai salle be fulle of hateredyn &thorn;an;</L>
<L>Ilk ane salle other wery and ban,</L>
<L N="7396">And say "cursed kaytif and wa worth &thorn;e,</L>
<L>And weryed mot &thorn;ou ever be,</L>
<L>And weryed mot &thorn;ai be ever-mare,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e gat and &thorn;at &thorn;e bare,</L>
<L N="7400">And &thorn;e tyme &thorn;at &thorn;ou was born alswa,</L>
<L>Ffor &thorn;i payne es tylle me sorow and wa;</L>
<L>It pynes me and greves me sare,</L>
<L>Als mykelle als myne awen payn or mare,
<PB REF="00000244.tif" N="200"></L>
<L N="7404">Ffor my payne it ekes, and mase mare grevus."</L>
<L>Ilk ane tylle other &thorn;an salle say &thorn;us.</L>
<L>&THORN;us ilk mans payne salle other dere,</L>
<L>And nane of &thorn;am salle other forbere;</L>
<L N="7408">Nouther son, ne doghter, ne syster, ne brother</L>
<L>Ffader ne moder, ne yhit nane other;</L>
<L>Ffor ilk ane salle other hate dedly,</L>
<L>And ilk ane gryn on other and cry.</L>
<L N="7412">Ilk ane salle gnaw &thorn;air awen tonges in sonder,</L>
<L>And ilk ane salle &thorn;are on other wonder.</L>
<L>&THORN;us in helle salle &thorn;ai far ay,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ar-with sklaundre God and say:</L>
<L N="7416">"Whar-to made God us tylle his lyknes,</L>
<L>And lates us now dwell &thorn;are sorow ay es;</L>
<L>Bot it semes &thorn;at God made us in vayne,</L>
<L>When we er &thorn;us putted tille endles payne,</L>
<L N="7420">Or he us made for noght els to dwelle</L>
<L>In erth, bot to be fyre brandes in helle."</L>
<L>&THORN;ai salle wery &thorn;e tyme &thorn;at &thorn;ai war wroght,</L>
<L>And say "allas whine war we noght."</L>
<L N="7424">&THORN;us salle &thorn;ai sklaundre God omang,</L>
<L>Swa hard &thorn;air payns salle be, and swa strang;</L>
<L>&THORN;ai salle ilk ane on other stare and gryn,</L>
<L>Als wode men dose here, and makes gret dyn;</L>
<L N="7428">An hydus thing to here it ware,</L>
<L>Wha-swa couth telle &thorn;e payns &thorn;are,</L>
<L>Als properly als &thorn;ai salle &thorn;are be.</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;at couth noght alle &thorn;e men of cristiant&eacute;.</L>
<L N="7432">Ne alle &thorn;e clerkes &thorn;at ever had witt,</L>
<L>Sen &thorn;e world bigan, ne &thorn;at lyfes yhit</L>
<L>Couth never telle, bi clergy, ne arte</L>
<L>Of &thorn;a payns of helle &thorn;e thowsand parte.</L>
<L N="7436">Ffor &thorn;e noumbre of payns &thorn;at &thorn;are griefes</L>
<L>Passes &thorn;e mens witt &thorn;at here liefes,</L>
<L>Or &thorn;at ever lyfed in any degr&eacute;,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at may men bi skylle &thorn;us se;</L>
<L N="7440">Ffor ilka syn &thorn;at &thorn;e synfulle has wroght,</L>
<L>Whar it never swa lytelle venyalle thoght,
<PB REF="00000245.tif" N="201"></L>
<L>&THORN;ai salle have certayne payne &thorn;are,</L>
<L>After &thorn;at &thorn;e syn es les or mare.</L>
<L N="7444">Wha couth &thorn;an telle, war he never swa wyse,</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;e syns and alle &thorn;e folyse,</L>
<L>Both dedly and alswa venyale,</L>
<L>And leve nane untald, gret ne smale,</L>
<L N="7448">&THORN;e whilk a man has here fallen in,</L>
<L>Ffra &thorn;e tyme &thorn;at he first bigan to syn,</L>
<L>Both in thoght, in word and dede?</L>
<L>Alswa say nane es &thorn;at tyme couth rede.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Als wha say na man couth thaim rede (MS. Harl. 6923).</NOTE></L>
<L N="7452">And for ilka thing done here in vayne,</L>
<L>In helle es ordaynd certayne payne</L>
<L>Tille synfulle men &thorn;at salle dwelle &thorn;are.</L>
<L>&THORN;an bihoves &thorn;am, als I sayd are,</L>
<L N="7456">Ffor ilka syn &thorn;at &thorn;ai dyd here,</L>
<L>Have certayne payne singulere;</L>
<L>And for ilka manere of syn and foly,</L>
<L>Be pyned in helle specyaly.</L>
<L N="7460">And als oft-sythe als &thorn;ai here newed &thorn;air syn</L>
<L>Als oft-syth &thorn;air payn salle new &thorn;are bigyn;</L>
<L>&THORN;arfor swamany payns tylle &thorn;am salle falle,</L>
<L>&THORN;at na witt may comprehende &thorn;am alle;</L>
<L N="7464">Ffor na syn &thorn;at &thorn;ai ever here dyd,</L>
<L>Dedly ne veniele, salle be hyd,</L>
<L>Bot alle openly sene and nan be laynd,</L>
<L>Ffor whilk salle be &thorn;are sere payns ordaynd;</L>
<L N="7468">Wha moght &thorn;an alle &thorn;e payns telle,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e synfulle men salle have in helle?</L>
<L>Ffor-whi if a man fra hethen pass oway</L>
<L>In a dedly syn, at his last day,</L>
<L N="7472">Ffor ilka venyel syn, &thorn;at ever dyd he,</L>
<L>He salle &thorn;an diversly pyned be;</L>
<L>And als oft renoueld<NOTE PLACE="foot">renewed?</NOTE> salle be ilk payne,</L>
<L>Als he turned new tylle ilk syn ogayne.</L>
<L N="7476">And &thorn;e lest payne &thorn;are es mare to se,</L>
<L>&THORN;an alle &thorn;e payns of &thorn;is world may be,
<PB REF="00000246.tif" N="202"></L>
<L>Ffor alle &thorn;e payns of &thorn;is world here,</L>
<L>&THORN;at ever was sene fer or nere,</L>
<L N="7480">Als to &thorn;e lest payne &thorn;are moght noght be tald,</L>
<L>Bot als a bathe of water, nouther hate ne cald<NOTE PLACE="foot">Als a leuke bath nouther hate ne calde (MS. Harl. 6923).</NOTE></L>
<L>Ffor alle &thorn;e sorow of &thorn;is world, ilka dele,</L>
<L>War noght bot als solace and ioy to fele,</L>
<L N="7484">Als to regard of &thorn;e lest payne,</L>
<L>&THORN;at es in helle; &thorn;is es certayne,</L>
<L>Ilk synfulle salle haf syght &thorn;are</L>
<L>Of alle &thorn;e payns, both les and mare,</L>
<L N="7488">&THORN;at alle &thorn;e synfulle men salle dreghe.</L>
<L>&THORN;an salle ilk ane se &thorn;are with eghe</L>
<L>Men and wymmen, many a thousand,</L>
<L>On ilk syde obout, in sere payns dwelland;</L>
<L N="7492">And &thorn;at syght, &thorn;at ilk ane salle &thorn;are se</L>
<L>Of ilka payne, tylle &thorn;am payne salle be;</L>
<L>Ffor alle &thorn;e payns &thorn;at salle falle tylle ilk man</L>
<L>Salle be sorow tylle alle &thorn;at sese &thorn;am &thorn;an.</L>
<L N="7496">&THORN;us salle ilk ane dreghe mare payn in helle,</L>
<L>&THORN;an hert moght ever think or tong telle;</L>
<L>What of payns &thorn;at to &thorn;am-self salle be dyght,</L>
<L>And what of payns &thorn;at &thorn;ai salle have of syght.</L>
<L N="7500">Ffor alle &thorn;e payns, &thorn;at &thorn;are salle be knawen,</L>
<L>Salle greve ilk man als mykelle als his awen;</L>
<L>Swilk payns to here, als men may here rede,</L>
<L>Aght to mak ilk man of helle have drede;</L>
<L N="7504">For I trow &thorn;at here es no man lyfand,</L>
<L>Swa hard-herted, &thorn;at wald understand</L>
<L>And trow what payns in helle er wroght,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he ne suld have gret dred in thoght,</L>
<L N="7508">&THORN;e whilk suld mak him hate alle foly,</L>
<L>Wharfor he war swylk payns worthy.</L>
<L>Bot alle &thorn;ase &thorn;at wille &thorn;air syn forsake,</L>
<L>Whils &thorn;ai lyfe here, ar &thorn;e ded &thorn;am take,</L>
<L N="7512">And of alle thing have forthynkyng</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ai have done ogayns Godes bydyng,
<PB REF="00000247.tif" N="203"></L>
<L>And turn &thorn;am tylle God fra &thorn;air syn,</L>
<L>And ask his mercy and trayst &thorn;ar-in,</L>
<L N="7516">And be lufand un-tylle him and bowsom,</L>
<L>In &thorn;a payns of helle salle never com,</L>
<L>Bot tylle &thorn;e blys of heven mon &thorn;ai wende,</L>
<L>And have &thorn;are &thorn;air lykyng with-outen ende.</L>
<L N="7520">Here have I spoken of &thorn;e payns of helle,</L>
<L>Als yhe have herd me openly telle,</L>
<L>And of &thorn;e sext part of &thorn;is boke made ende.</L>
<L>Now wille I tylle &thorn;e sevend part wende,</L>
<L N="7524">&THORN;at es &thorn;e last part of alle;</L>
<L>&THORN;e whilk spekes als I shew yhow salle,</L>
<L>Specialy of &thorn;e ioyes in heven,</L>
<L>&THORN;at er mare &thorn;an any tong may neven.</L>
<L N="7528">Bot fyrst I wille schew yhow whare heven es,</L>
<L>Als clerkes says and &thorn;e boke bers witnes;</L>
<L>And efter &thorn;at I salle schew yhow mare,</L>
<L>And telle yhow of sere ioyes &thorn;at er &thorn;are.</L>
</LG>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 N="7" TYPE="book">
<HEAD>Here bygyns &thorn;e sevend part of &thorn;is boke &THORN;at es of &thorn;e ioyes of heven.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Many &thorn;e blys of heven covaytes,</L>
<L>Bot fone &thorn;e ryght way &thorn;ider laytes;</L>
<L N="7536">And som thurgh syn er made so blynd,</L>
<L N="7536*">&THORN;at &thorn;e right way &thorn;ider &thorn;ai kan noght fynd,</L>
<L>Som wald be &thorn;are, with-outen dout,</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;ai wille noght travaille &thorn;are obout;</L>
<L>Bot whasa wille tak &thorn;e way &thorn;ider-ward,</L>
<L N="7540">Behoves in gud werkes travaille hard;</L>
<L>Ffor tylle &thorn;e kyngdom of heven may no man com</L>
<L>Bot he ga bi &thorn;e way of wisdom;</L>
<L>&THORN;e way of wysdom es mekenes</L>
<L N="7544">And other virtuse, mare and les.</L>
<L>And &thorn;at way es cald a gastly way,</L>
<L>Bi whilk men suld here travaille ay,</L>
<L>&THORN;at es &thorn;e way &thorn;at ledes men even</L>
<L N="7548">Untylle &thorn;e hegh kyngdom of heven.</L>
<L>Bi other way may nane, bot he fleghe,
<PB REF="00000248.tif" N="204"></L>
<L>Pass up tylle heven it es swa heghe;</L>
<L>Ffor it es &thorn;e heghest place &thorn;at God wroght,</L>
<L N="7552">And &thorn;e first, when he made alle thing of noght.</L>
<L>Na man may gesce swa lang space,</L>
<L>Als es fro hethen untylle &thorn;at hegh place;</L>
<L>Ffor bitwene us and &thorn;at heghe heven</L>
<L N="7556">Es alle &thorn;e firmament to neven,</L>
<L>&THORN;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">&THORN;at?</NOTE> clerkes bi skylle hevens calles,</L>
<L>&THORN;e whilk er ay moveand als falles.</L>
<L>&THORN;us er oboven us hevens sere,</L>
<L N="7560">Bot alle er &thorn;a noght olyke clere;</L>
<L>Ffor &thorn;e heghest heven es wele bryghter</L>
<L>&THORN;an &thorn;e other hevens &thorn;at er lagher;</L>
<L>Ffor &thorn;e heghest has swa mykelle bryghtnes,</L>
<L N="7564">And swa fayre and swa delytable es,</L>
<L>&THORN;at alle &thorn;e men of erth couth noght</L>
<L>Swa mykelle ymagyn, ne think in thoght.</L>
<L>Sere hevens God ordaynd for sere thyng,</L>
<L N="7568">Bot &thorn;e heghest God made for our wonyng.</L>
<L>&THORN;ese hevens er oboven us heghe,</L>
<L>Als clerkes says, &thorn;at er wise and sleghe;</L>
<L>Ane es, &thorn;at we &thorn;e sterned heven calle,</L>
<L N="7572">&THORN;are &thorn;e planetes and &thorn;e sternes er alle,</L>
<L>&THORN;at men may se here, on nyght, schyne;</L>
<L>Ane other es, &thorn;at clerkes calles cristallyne,</L>
<L>&THORN;at next oboven &thorn;e sterned heven es,</L>
<L N="7576">And es mare &thorn;an &thorn;at of wydenes;</L>
<L>Som clerkes it calles on &thorn;is manere;</L>
<L>&THORN;e water heven, &thorn;at es als clere</L>
<L>Als cristalle, &thorn;at hoves oboven &thorn;are,</L>
<L N="7580">Ryght als water &thorn;at frosen ware;</L>
<L>&THORN;us telles Berthelemewe in &thorn;e boke</L>
<L>Of propertes of sere thinges to loke:</L>
<L>&THORN;ir twa hevens ay obout-rynnes,</L>
<L N="7584">Both day and nyght, and never blynnes;</L>
<L>&THORN;e erth, &thorn;at &thorn;a hevens obout-gase,</L>
<L>Es bot als a poynt Imyddes a compase;
<PB REF="00000249.tif" N="205"></L>
<L>Swa lytelle it es semand with-out</L>
<L N="7588">To regard of &thorn;a hevens obout;</L>
<L>And Imyddes &thorn;e erth es ordaynd helle,</L>
<L>&THORN;are &thorn;e synfulle, &thorn;at salle be dampned salle dwelle</L>
<L>Als men may before rede and se,</L>
<L N="7592">And lawer &thorn;an helle may na place be;</L>
<L>&THORN;us both &thorn;e hevens obout-gase ay</L>
<L>And never salle ceese untylle domesday;</L>
<L>Ffor clerkes says &thorn;at knawes and sese,</L>
<L N="7596">Of &thorn;ir twa hevens &thorn;e propertese,</L>
<L>&THORN;at if &thorn;ai moved noght, alle suld peryssch,</L>
<L>Both man and beste, foghel and fyssch</L>
<L>And alle &thorn;at under &thorn;am may be,</L>
<L N="7600">&THORN;at lyves and growes, both gresse and tre,</L>
<L>All suld be smored<NOTE PLACE="foot">Al schulde be spilt wyth-outen doute (MS. 22283).</NOTE> with-outen dout,</L>
<L>Warne &thorn;a hevens ay moved obout;</L>
<L>Ffor if &thorn;ai stode never swa schort while stylle,</L>
<L N="7604">Alle &thorn;at on erth es suld perysch and spylle;</L>
<L>&THORN;us telles gret clerkes of clergy,</L>
<L>&THORN;at has bene lered in astronemy</L>
<L>And knawes &thorn;e constellacyouns</L>
<L N="7608">And &thorn;e heven &thorn;at &thorn;e erth envirouns.</L>
<L>Of &thorn;air moveyng &thorn;an have yhe no wonder,</L>
<L>Ffor it noryssch[es] alle &thorn;at es &thorn;are-under,</L>
<L>In wate and drye, in hate and cald,</L>
<L N="7612">Ay whils &thorn;ai move, als I bifore tald,</L>
<L>&THORN;ir hevens obout-gase alle erthly thynges</L>
<L>And &thorn;am norysches and forth-brynges,</L>
<L>Ffor als clerkes says &thorn;at to &thorn;am tentes</L>
<L N="7616">&THORN;ai tempre &thorn;e streng[t]he of alle &thorn;e elementes</L>
<L>Ay als &thorn;ai move whils &thorn;ai obout-ga.</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;e thred heven es oboven &thorn;a twa,</L>
<L>Swa wonderly heghe and swa ferre</L>
<L N="7620">&THORN;at nathyng may be heghere;</L>
<L>Yhit som clerkes ma hevens nevens,</L>
<L>And says &thorn;at &thorn;are er other seven hevens,
<PB REF="00000250.tif" N="206"></L>
<L>&THORN;at semes lawer, als men may se,</L>
<L N="7624">&THORN;an &thorn;e twa hevens falles to be,</L>
<L>Ffor-whi &thorn;e clerkes &thorn;e planetes alle</L>
<L>Bi certayne skylle hevens &thorn;ai calle.</L>
<L>And seven planetes er oboven us;</L>
<L N="7628">Ffyrst &thorn;e Mone and Mercury and Venus,</L>
<L>Sythen &thorn;e Son and &thorn;an Mars and Iubiter,</L>
<L>And Saturnus oboven &thorn;an &thorn;at es hegher.</L>
<L>Ilk ane &thorn;air course obout ay mase</L>
<L N="7632">In &thorn;air cercles, als God ordaynd hase;</L>
<L>&THORN;ai styk noght fast, als smale sternes dose,</L>
<L>Ilk ane his course mase thurgh use;</L>
<L>Ilka planete falles for to be</L>
<L N="7636">Hegher &thorn;an other in ordre and degr&eacute;;</L>
<L>&THORN;e Mone, &thorn;e fyrst and lawest, es sene,</L>
<L>And Saturnus &thorn;e heghest es, als I wene;</L>
<L>Oboven us er alle &thorn;e planetes seven,</L>
<L N="7640">And &thorn;e cercle of ilk ane es called ane heven</L>
<L>&THORN;at er wonderly bryght and fayre;</L>
<L>Yhit ane other heven es called &thorn;e ayre</L>
<L>&THORN;at es lagher, &thorn;ar &thorn;e foghles has flyght,</L>
<L N="7644">And &thorn;at heven es mast nere our syght</L>
<L>Bot it es noght swa clere ne clene</L>
<L>Als &thorn;e other hevens oboven er sene:</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;e cercles of &thorn;e planetes alle</L>
<L N="7648">&THORN;at we here clerkes &thorn;us hevens calle,</L>
<L>Er bryght and clere, als &thorn;e bokes schewes us</L>
<L>And ilk planete es ferrer &thorn;an other fra us;</L>
<L>Ffra &thorn;e erth untylle &thorn;e cercle of &thorn;e mone, es</L>
<L N="7652">&THORN;e way of fyve hundreth wynter, and na les,</L>
<L>&THORN;at es als mykelle space at say,</L>
<L>Als a man moght ga, in playne way,</L>
<L>In fyve hundreth yhere fully,</L>
<L N="7656">If he moght lyfe swa lang in body,</L>
<L>Als a gret philosiphir &thorn;at hyght</L>
<L>Rabby Moyses telles ryght</L>
<L>&THORN;at thurgh witt mykelle couth se;</L>
<L N="7660">And over &thorn;at alle, swa says he,
<PB REF="00000251.tif" N="207"></L>
<L>&THORN;at ilka cercle &thorn;at es sene</L>
<L>Of ilka planete, may contene,</L>
<L>Als men may fynd wryten here,</L>
<L N="7664">&THORN;e way of fyve hundreth yhere</L>
<L>Als es gesced in brede and thyknes,</L>
<L>Swa mykelle and thyk ilk ane es,</L>
<L>&THORN;at es at say, als mykelle space here</L>
<L N="7668">Als a man moght ga in fyve hundreth yhere.</L>
<L>&THORN;of &thorn;at travaille him suld noght gryfe</L>
<L>If he here swa lang moght lyfe;</L>
<L>And fra &thorn;e poynt of &thorn;e erthe tille Saturnus</L>
<L N="7672">&THORN;e heghest planete may be gesced &thorn;us,</L>
<L>&THORN;e way of seven thowsand yhere</L>
<L>And thre hundreth, als es wryten here,</L>
<L>&THORN;at es at say, als es here contende,</L>
<L N="7676">Als mykelle space als a man moght wende</L>
<L>In seven thowsand yhere, and<NOTE PLACE="foot">in?</NOTE> playn way gang</L>
<L>And th[r]e hundreth, if he suld lyf swalang;</L>
<L>Swa &thorn;at ilk yhere be acounted halely</L>
<L N="7680">Of thre hundreth days and fourty,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at &thorn;e way of ilka day</L>
<L>Be fully of fourty myle of way,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at ilka myle fully contene</L>
<L N="7684">A thowsand pases or cubites sene.</L>
<L>Raby Moyses says alle &thorn;is,</L>
<L>&THORN;at er noght alle my wordes bot his;</L>
<L>Bot whether alle &thorn;is be soth or noght,</L>
<L N="7688">God wate, &thorn;at alle thyng has wroght,</L>
<L>Ffor he made alle thyng thurgh myght and sleght</L>
<L>In certain noumbre and mesure and weght;</L>
<L>Bot swa sutelle and wise may na man be,</L>
<L N="7692">&THORN;at &thorn;at mesuryng knawes swa wele als he;</L>
<L>Ffor na thyng &thorn;at may be, mare or les,</L>
<L>Or &thorn;at ever was, tylle him unknawen es;</L>
<L>Himself fra erth, upward met &thorn;at way,</L>
<L N="7696">When he stey tylle heven on halghe Thursday,</L>
<L>&THORN;at wate he best thurgh wytt and sleght,</L>
<L>What space &thorn;at way contened of heght.
<PB REF="00000252.tif" N="208"></L>
<L>Bi alle &thorn;e hevens had he gane,</L>
<L N="7700">And passed alle &thorn;e sternes ilk ane,</L>
<L>And up tylle &thorn;e heghest heven he went,</L>
<L>And alle &thorn;is way he passed in a moment,</L>
<L>In &thorn;e heghest part of &thorn;e sterned heven.</L>
<L N="7704">Oboven alle &thorn;e planetes seven,</L>
<L>Standes swa many sternes smale,</L>
<L>&THORN;at na man may &thorn;am telle bi tale,</L>
<L>&THORN;at standes fast &thorn;are, als &thorn;e buke pruves,</L>
<L N="7708">And er led obout with &thorn;e heven &thorn;at moves,</L>
<L>Als nayles er in a whele with-out,</L>
<L>&THORN;at with &thorn;e whele er turned obout;</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;e planetes er noght led swa,</L>
<L N="7712">Ffor in &thorn;air cercles obout &thorn;ai ga.</L>
<L>&THORN;e sternes semes smale, als we deme,</L>
<L>Bot swa smale er &thorn;ai noght als &thorn;ai seme,</L>
<L>Ffor &thorn;ai er schewed fra us swa fer,</L>
<L N="7716">&THORN;at we may noght se how mykelle &thorn;ai er;</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;e lest sterne &thorn;are &thorn;at we on-luke.</L>
<L>Es mare &thorn;an erth, als says &thorn;e boke;</L>
<L>Ffor clerkes says, if alle erth in fyre ware,</L>
<L N="7720">And possibel war &thorn;at a man war &thorn;are,</L>
<L>Him suld thynk, &thorn;of it bryned bryght,</L>
<L>Les &thorn;an &thorn;e lest sterne &thorn;at schynes on nyght,</L>
<L>&THORN;an aght &thorn;at heven gret space contene,</L>
<L N="7724">&THORN;are swa many sternes may be sene.</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;ir hevens here sene may be,</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;e alther-heghest heven may na man se.</L>
<L>Tille &thorn;at heven couth na clerk thurgh arte,</L>
<L N="7728">&THORN;e space gesce bi ane hundreth thowsand part</L>
<L>Ffor it es swa heghe, als Sydrak says,</L>
<L>&THORN;at if a stane &thorn;at war of pays,</L>
<L>Of ane hundreth mens lyftyng,</L>
<L N="7732">Might falle fro &thorn;e&thorn;en, it suld be in fallyng</L>
<L>A thowsand yhere and na les,</L>
<L>Ar it come at &thorn;e erth, swa heghe it es;</L>
<L>Bot aungels &thorn;at fro heven er sent,</L>
<L N="7736">May com doune tylle erth in a moment,
<PB REF="00000253.tif" N="209"></L>
<L>And up ogayne tylle heven may flegh,</L>
<L>In &thorn;e space of a twynkellyng of ane eghe.</L>
<L>And swa may a saule &thorn;at es clene and lyght,</L>
<L N="7740">Com &thorn;ider fro hethen in als schort a flyght,</L>
<L>Thurgh &thorn;e myght of God and thurgh noght elles</L>
<L>And swa has done many &thorn;at &thorn;are dwelles;</L>
<L>&THORN;is may be halden a gret ferly,</L>
<L N="7744">Omang alle &thorn;e wonders of God alle-myghty,</L>
<L>&THORN;at ane aungelle may pass swa many myle,</L>
<L>Ffra heven tylle hyder, in swa schort awhyle.</L>
<L>And a saule thurgh Godes myght and grace,</L>
<L N="7748">May fro hethen com &thorn;ider in swa short space.</L>
<L>This heven es &thorn;e alther-heghest place of alle,</L>
<L>Hegher es na thyng &thorn;at may bifalle,</L>
<L>&THORN;e whilk alle thyng contenes of dignyt&eacute;,</L>
<L N="7752">And in nathyng contende may be,</L>
<L>It contenes over-alle, on ilk party,</L>
<L>Bath bodily thyng and gastly,</L>
<L>And als helle es lawest place &thorn;at may falle,</L>
<L N="7756">Swa es &thorn;is heven alther-heghest place of alle;</L>
<L>And als sorow es ay in &thorn;e lawest place,</L>
<L>Swa es ay in &thorn;e heghest, ioy and solace.</L>
<L>And als tylle &thorn;e lawest place, drawes us syn,</L>
<L N="7760">Swa tylle &thorn;e heghest may vertues us wyn.</L>
<L>&THORN;is heven es cald heven empiry</L>
<L>&THORN;at es at say heven &thorn;at es fyry,</L>
<L>Ffor it semes alle als fyre of gret myght,</L>
<L N="7764">&THORN;at brynnes noght bot schynes bryght.</L>
<L>&THORN;is heven falles noght obout to ga,</L>
<L>Ne moves noght als dose &thorn;e other twa,</L>
<L>Bot standes ay stylle, for it es &thorn;e best,</L>
<L N="7768">And &thorn;e most worthi place of pees and rest</L>
<L>&THORN;at God has ordaynd for &thorn;air wonyng,</L>
<L>&THORN;at gyfes &thorn;am here tylle ryghtwise lyfyng.</L>
<L>&THORN;is heven es cald Godes awen se,</L>
<L N="7772">Ffor &thorn;ar syttes &thorn;e haly trinit&eacute;,</L>
<L>And alle &thorn;e orders of aungels,</L>
<L>And alle &thorn;e blyssfulle spirites &thorn;at in heven dwels,
<PB REF="00000254.tif" N="210"></L>
<L>And &thorn;e saules of gud men and clene,</L>
<L N="7776">&THORN;at in &thorn;is world ryghtwyse has bene.</L>
<L>And at &thorn;e dredfulle day of dome,</L>
<L>When alle men salle bifor God come,</L>
<L>&THORN;an salle alle the ryghtwyse men wend &thorn;ider,</L>
<L N="7780">In body and saule both togyder,</L>
<L>&THORN;e whilk anely &thorn;an salle be save,</L>
<L>And fulle blys in body and saule have.</L>
<L>&THORN;an salle mare ioy be in heven,</L>
<L N="7784">&THORN;an hert may thynk or tong kan neven,</L>
<L>Or ere may here or any eghe se,</L>
<L>&THORN;e whilk &thorn;ai salle have, &thorn;at save salle be;</L>
<L>&THORN;an passes &thorn;at ioy alle mens witt,</L>
<L N="7788">Als es fonden wryten in haly wrytt.</L>
<L><I>Quod oculus non vidit, nec</I></L>
<L><I>auris audivit, nec in cor ho|</I></L>
<L><I>minis ascendit, quod preparavit</I></L>
<L N="7792"><I>Deus diligentibus se.</I></L>
<L>"Eghe moght never se, ne ere here,</L>
<L>Ne in-tylle mans hert com &thorn;e ioyes sere</L>
<L>&THORN;at God has ordaynd &thorn;are and dyght,</L>
<L N="7796">Tylle alle &thorn;at here lufes him ryght."</L>
<L>Ffor swa mykelle ioy &thorn;are salle be,</L>
<L>&THORN;at alle &thorn;e men of Cristiant&eacute;,</L>
<L>If ilk ane war parfyte in clergy</L>
<L N="7800">In divinit&eacute; and in astronomy,</L>
<L>In gemettry and gramer, and arte,</L>
<L>Couth noght gese bi &thorn;e thowsand parte,</L>
<L>Ne think in hert ne with tong neven,</L>
<L N="7804">&THORN;e ioyes &thorn;at &thorn;an salle be in heven.</L>
<L>Ffor swa wyse here was never man yhit,</L>
<L>Ne swa sleghe, ne swa sotelle of wytt,</L>
<L>Had he never swa mykelle understandyng,</L>
<L N="7808">Bot God anely &thorn;at knawes alle thyng,</L>
<L>&THORN;at couth telle a poynt or ymagyn</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e ioyes in heven &thorn;at never salle blyn,</L>
<L>Als proprely als &thorn;ai er &thorn;are to say,</L>
<L N="7812">Bot als &thorn;e boke &thorn;am schewes, swa we may.
<PB REF="00000255.tif" N="211"></L>
<L>Alle manere of ioyes er in &thorn;at stede.</L>
<L>&THORN;are es ay lyfe with-outen dede;</L>
<L>&THORN;are es yhowthe ay with-outen elde,</L>
<L N="7816">&THORN;are es alkyn welth ay to welde.</L>
<L>&THORN;are es rest ay, with-outen travayle;</L>
<L>&THORN;are es alle gudes &thorn;at never sal fayle;</L>
<L>&THORN;are es pese ay, with-outen stryfe;</L>
<L N="7820">&THORN;are es alle manere of lykyng of lyfe;</L>
<L>&THORN;are es, with-outen myrknes, lyght;</L>
<L>&THORN;are es ay day and never nyght;</L>
<L>&THORN;are es ay somer fulle bryght to se,</L>
<L N="7824">And never mare wynter in &thorn;at contr&eacute;:</L>
<L>&THORN;are es alkyn druryes and rychesce,</L>
<L>And mare nobillay &thorn;an any man may gesce;</L>
<L>&THORN;are es mare worsche[pe] and honoure,</L>
<L N="7828">&THORN;an ever had kyng here or emparoure;</L>
<L>&THORN;are es alkyn power and myght</L>
<L>And endeles wonyng sykerly dyght;</L>
<L>&THORN;are es alkyn delyces and cese,</L>
<L N="7832">And syker peysilbilnes<NOTE PLACE="foot">peysibilnes?</NOTE> and pese;</L>
<L>&THORN;are es peysebelle ioy ay lastand,</L>
<L>And ioyfulle selynes ay lykand;</L>
<L>&THORN;are es sely endeles beyng,</L>
<L N="7836">And endeles blysfulhede in alle thyng;</L>
<L>&THORN;are es ay blysfulle certaynt&eacute;,</L>
<L>And certayne dwellyng ay fre;</L>
<L>&THORN;are es laykyng and myrthes sere;</L>
<L N="7840">&THORN;are es laghyng and lufly chere;</L>
<L>&THORN;are es melody and aungels sang;</L>
<L>And lovyng and thankyng ay omang;</L>
<L>&THORN;are es alle frendschepe &thorn;at may be,</L>
<L N="7844">And parfyte luf and charyt&eacute;;</L>
<L>&THORN;are es acorde ay and anehede,</L>
<L>And yheldyng of mede for ilk gud dede;</L>
<L>&THORN;are es lowtyng and reverence,</L>
<L N="7848">And boghsomnes and obedience;</L>
<L>&THORN;are es alle vertuse with-outen vyce,
<PB REF="00000256.tif" N="212"></L>
<L>&THORN;are es plent&eacute; of dayntes and delice;</L>
<L>&THORN;are es alle &thorn;at lykes and may avayle,</L>
<L N="7852">And nathyng &thorn;at greves or may fayle;</L>
<L>&THORN;are es alle &thorn;at gud es at wille,</L>
<L>And na thyng &thorn;at may be ille.</L>
<L>&THORN;are es alle wisdom with-outen foly,</L>
<L N="7856">And honest&eacute; with-outen vilany;</L>
<L>&THORN;are es bryghtnes and bewt&eacute;</L>
<L>Of alle thing &thorn;at men salle &thorn;are se.</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;ir ioyes er &thorn;are generalle,</L>
<L N="7860">Bot &thorn;e mast soverayne ioy of alle</L>
<L>Es &thorn;e syght of Godes bryght face,</L>
<L>&THORN;at passes alle other ioyes and solace;</L>
<L>Ffor swa mykelle may na ioy be,</L>
<L N="7864">Als es &thorn;e syght of &thorn;e trinit&eacute;,</L>
<L>&THORN;at es &thorn;e Fader, and Son, and Haly gaste.</L>
<L>&THORN;e syght of whilk salle be ioy maste;</L>
<L>Ffor-whi swa mykelle ioy and blys</L>
<L N="7868">Na ioy may be als es &thorn;is.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Forwhi &thorn;ar may be ioy ne blis, Swa mekyl to fele als is &thorn;is. (MS. Harl. 2394.)</NOTE></L>
<L>Ffor alle &thorn;at &thorn;an salle se him ryght,</L>
<L>May knaw alle thing thurgh &thorn;at syght,</L>
<L>&THORN;at ever was, and es, and salle be,</L>
<L N="7872">Als men may afterward rede and se.</L>
<L>Here have I shewed on a general manere</L>
<L>&THORN;e ioyes of heven, many and sere.</L>
<L>Bot now will I specialy shew yhow mare</L>
<L N="7876">Of seven maners of blysses &thorn;are,</L>
<L>And of seven schenschepes in helle alle-swa,</L>
<L>&THORN;at er even contrary tylle &thorn;a,</L>
<L>And whilk blysses falles specyaly</L>
<L N="7880">Tylle &thorn;e saule, and whilk tylle &thorn;e body,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;as &thorn;at God in heven salle se;</L>
<L>And whilk schendschepes salle appropried be</L>
<L>Tylle &thorn;e bodyse of &thorn;ase, &thorn;at salle ga</L>
<L N="7884">Tylle helle, and whilk tille &thorn;e saules alle-swa.</L>
<L>I spak bifore of sere ioyes generaly,</L>
<L>Bot now will I here sere blysses specify,
<PB REF="00000257.tif" N="213"></L>
<L>And &thorn;air contraryes &thorn;at er hard,</L>
<L N="7888">Als yhe salle here be red afterward.</L>
<L>Saint Anselme says, &thorn;e haly man,</L>
<L>Als I here schew yhow kan,</L>
<L>&THORN;at omang alle &thorn;e ioyes of heven,</L>
<L N="7892">Salle be sene specialle blysses seven,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e bodyse salle have &thorn;at salle be save,</L>
<L>And other seven &thorn;at &thorn;e saules salle have</L>
<L>In &thorn;e kyngdome of heven alle to-gyder,</L>
<L N="7896">After &thorn;e dome, when &thorn;ai com &thorn;ider;</L>
<L>Bot tylle &thorn;e synfulle bodyse &thorn;are ogayne</L>
<L>&THORN;at salle be dampned tylle helle payne,</L>
<L>Seven specialle schendschepes salle falle</L>
<L N="7900">And other seven tylle &thorn;e saules with-alle</L>
<L>In helle to-gyder lastand ever-mare,</L>
<L>Wa es &thorn;am &thorn;at salle dwelle &thorn;are.</L>
<L>Heres now, ar I pass ferrer,</L>
<L N="7904">Whilk &thorn;a specyalle blysses er,</L>
<L>&THORN;at er appropried tylle &thorn;a bodyse</L>
<L>And tylle &thorn;e saules of men ryghtwyse,</L>
<L>And &thorn;air contraryes, &thorn;at I schendschepes calle</L>
<L N="7908">&THORN;at tylle &thorn;e synfulle bodyse and saules salle falle.</L>
<L>&THORN;e fyrst blys es bryghtnes cald</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e saved bodyse salle ay hald;</L>
<L>Ffor be &thorn;air bodyse never swa dym here,</L>
<L N="7912">In heven &thorn;ai salle be fayre and clere</L>
<L>And mare schyneand and mare bryght,</L>
<L>&THORN;an ever &thorn;e son was tylle mans syght;</L>
<L>Swa fayre a syght bifore was never sene,</L>
<L N="7916">Als salle be &thorn;an, ne swa clene,</L>
<L>When ilka body &thorn;at salle be save,</L>
<L>Swa mykelle bryghtnes &thorn;are salle have;</L>
<L>Ffor if a man had eghen swa bryght,</L>
<L N="7920">And if swa moght be, swa mykelle syght,</L>
<L>Als had alle &thorn;e creatures lyfand,</L>
<L>Yhit moght he noght, als I understand,</L>
<L>Ogayne swa mykelle bryghtnes loke,</L>
<L N="7924">Als a body salle have, &thorn;us says &thorn;e boke.
<PB REF="00000258.tif" N="214"></L>
<L>Bot &thorn;e dampned bodyse &thorn;are ogayne</L>
<L>Salle be foule and stynkand als carayne;</L>
<L>And fulle myrk and dym salle &thorn;ai be</L>
<L N="7928">And fulle hydus and wlatsom to se;</L>
<L>Ffor swa foul a syght saw never man</L>
<L>Als &thorn;e dampned bodyse salle be &thorn;an,</L>
<L>&THORN;at with &thorn;e saules salle dwelle in helledepe,</L>
<L N="7932">&THORN;is salle to &thorn;am be payne and schendschepe.</L>
<L>&THORN;e secunde blys after es swyftnes,</L>
<L>&THORN;at ilk body salle have &thorn;at ryghtwise es;</L>
<L>Ffor in les while &thorn;an a man may wynke,</L>
<L N="7936">&THORN;ai salle mow fleghe whider &thorn;ai wille thynke</L>
<L>With body and saule togyder thurgh flyght,</L>
<L>Ffra heven tylle erth and ogayne ryght,</L>
<L>And fra &thorn;e ta syde of &thorn;e world wyde,</L>
<L N="7940">If &thorn;ai wyld, tylle &thorn;e tother syde;</L>
<L>And whider-swa &thorn;ai &thorn;air thoght wille sett</L>
<L>Nathyng &thorn;am salle ogayne-stand ne lett.</L>
<L>&THORN;is may &thorn;ai do with-outen travayle,</L>
<L N="7944">And &thorn;is swyftnes salle never fayle;</L>
<L>Ffor als &thorn;e lyght of &thorn;e son, thurgh strenthe,</L>
<L>May fleghe fra &thorn;e est tylle &thorn;e west on lenthe,</L>
<L>Ryght swa &thorn;ai may whyder &thorn;ai wille, fleghe</L>
<L N="7948">In a schort twynkellyng of ane eghe.</L>
<L>Ffor &thorn;ai salle be als swift &thorn;an</L>
<L>Als any thoght es here of man.</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;e synfulle bodyse salle ever-mare</L>
<L N="7952">On a contrary manere fare;</L>
<L>&THORN;ai salle be swa hevy charged with syn,</L>
<L>Both with-outen and with-in,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ai salle have no myght to stand,</L>
<L N="7956">Ne unnethes to styr fote ne hand,</L>
<L>Ne yhit nane other lym of body,</L>
<L>&THORN;air syn salle weghe on &thorn;am swa hevy.</L>
<L>&THORN;e thred blys es strenthe and myght</L>
<L N="7960">&THORN;at &thorn;e ryghtwise bodyse salle have thurgh ryght,</L>
<L>Ffor thof &thorn;ai feble here and wayke ware,</L>
<L>Swa mykelle myght &thorn;ai salle have &thorn;are,
<PB REF="00000259.tif" N="215"></L>
<L>And swa mykelle strenthe ay lastand,</L>
<L N="7964">&THORN;at na thyng salle mow ogayne &thorn;am stand;</L>
<L>Swa &thorn;at &thorn;ai salle mow remowe at &thorn;air wille,</L>
<L>Ilka mountayne and ilka hille,</L>
<L>&THORN;at ever was in &thorn;e world sene;</L>
<L N="7968">And if &thorn;ai wild, alle &thorn;e erth bidene,</L>
<L>With-outen any ogayne-standyng,</L>
<L>Or any lettyng of any-thyng;</L>
<L>And in &thorn;at dede have no mare swynk,</L>
<L N="7972">&THORN;an a man has here to loke or wynk.</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;e synfulle bodyse, &thorn;at dampned salle be,</L>
<L>Salle be swa wayke and swa feble to se,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ai salle unnethes mow stand,</L>
<L N="7976">Ne myght have anes to lyft &thorn;air hand</L>
<L>To wype &thorn;e teres fra &thorn;air eghen oway,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at waykenes salle last with &thorn;am ay.</L>
<L>&THORN;e ferth blys alle-swa es fredome</L>
<L N="7980">&THORN;at &thorn;e saved bodyse salle have &thorn;at salle come</L>
<L>Tylle heven, whare alkyn ioyes er,</L>
<L>To do what &thorn;ai wille with-outen daunger;</L>
<L>Ffor-whi &thorn;ai salle never fele na thyng</L>
<L N="7984">Bot &thorn;at at salle be at &thorn;air lykyng;</L>
<L>And na thing salle &thorn;am warn ne lett,</L>
<L>To do &thorn;air wille whare-swa it es sett;</L>
<L>Ffor alle thing tylle &thorn;am salle be boghand,</L>
<L N="7988">And na thing salle ogayne &thorn;am stand,</L>
<L>Ne ogayns &thorn;am na thing be sett,</L>
<L>&THORN;air wille ne &thorn;air purpose to lett,</L>
<L>Nowther men, ne stele, ne stane, ne tre,</L>
<L N="7992">Ne noght elles, swa fre salle &thorn;ai be;</L>
<L>&THORN;ai salle mow passe ay whare &thorn;ai wille</L>
<L>And alle &thorn;air lykyng &thorn;an ful-fylle.</L>
<L>&THORN;is fredom and &thorn;is fraunches</L>
<L N="7996">Salle be appropried tylle &thorn;e saved bodyse</L>
<L>With &thorn;e saules of &thorn;am &thorn;at God salle chese,</L>
<L>And &thorn;is fredom &thorn;ai salle never lese.</L>
<L>Bot on contrary manere ogayne &thorn;at blys,</L>
<L N="8000">&THORN;e dampned bodyse salle fredom mys;
<PB REF="00000260.tif" N="216"></L>
<L>Ffor &thorn;ai salle be stresced in helle als thralle,</L>
<L>And alle &thorn;at may greve thole with-alle;</L>
<L>&THORN;ai salle be chaced ogayne &thorn;air wille</L>
<L N="8004">Tylle alle manere of thing &thorn;at es ille;</L>
<L>&THORN;us salle &thorn;ai in helle in thraldom be,</L>
<L>Ffra whilk &thorn;ai may never mare fle.</L>
<L>&THORN;e fyft blys, als clerkes wate wele,</L>
<L N="8008">Es hele &thorn;at &thorn;e saved bodyse salle fele,</L>
<L>With-outen seknes or grevaunce,</L>
<L>Or angre, or payne, or penaunce;</L>
<L>Ffor Ivel ne payne salle never &thorn;am greve,</L>
<L N="8012">Bot in hele and lykyng &thorn;ai salle ay leve,</L>
<L>In heven with ioy on ilka syde,</L>
<L>Ffor &thorn;are salle &thorn;ai be glorifyde.</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;e dampned bodyse, on other-wyse,</L>
<L N="8016">Salle have strang yvels and angwyse,</L>
<L>Als saules has &thorn;at in purgatory dwels</L>
<L>Ffor certayne tyme, als &thorn;e boke tels.</L>
<L>Bot swa lang lastes no sekenes &thorn;are.</L>
<L N="8020">Als in helle, for &thorn;at lastes ever-mare;</L>
<L>Ffor purgatory, als wryten es,</L>
<L>Has ende, and helle es endeles.</L>
<L>&THORN;e sext blys es &thorn;e gret delyte,</L>
<L N="8024">&THORN;at &thorn;e saved bodyse salle have swa parfyte</L>
<L>&THORN;at no man lyfand kan ne may,</L>
<L>Swa mykelle yhern here, nyght ne day;</L>
<L>Ffor here moght never man far swa wele,</L>
<L N="8028">With swa mykelle delyte als &thorn;ai salle fele</L>
<L>In alle &thorn;air wittes, ne swa mykelle ioy have,</L>
<L>Als God on &thorn;am salle &thorn;an vouche save.</L>
<L>&THORN;ai salle have swa mykelle ioy &thorn;are,</L>
<L N="8032">&THORN;at nane of &thorn;am salle desyre mare;</L>
<L>Ffor als &thorn;e iren &thorn;at es glowand,</L>
<L>Thurgh strenthe and hete brynand,</L>
<L>Semes better to be fyre-bryght,</L>
<L N="8036">&THORN;an iren, als tylle any mans syght,</L>
<L>Right swa &thorn;a &thorn;at in heven salle won</L>
<L>Salle seme bryghter &thorn;an fyre, and schyne als son
<PB REF="00000261.tif" N="217"></L>
<L>And be fulle-fyld ay in &thorn;at place</L>
<L N="8040">Of &thorn;e luf of God and of his grace,</L>
<L>And of alle delyces and ioy and blys,</L>
<L>&THORN;e whilk &thorn;ai salle never-mare mys;</L>
<L>And als men here oft has sene</L>
<L N="8044">&THORN;at a vesselle dypped alle bidene</L>
<L>In water, or in other lycour thyn,</L>
<L>Be &thorn;e vesselle never swa wyde wyth-in,</L>
<L>Has water bath with-in and with-out,</L>
<L N="8048">Binethen, oboven, and alle about,</L>
<L>And na mare water with-in may hald,</L>
<L>Ne nane other thing &thorn;at lycoure es cald,</L>
<L>Right swa &thorn;e ryghtwise salle have ioy, mare</L>
<L N="8052">&THORN;an &thorn;ai may think or yhern &thorn;are;</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;e dampned bodyse ogayn-ward</L>
<L>Salle in helle fele payns strang and hard;</L>
<L>Ffor &thorn;ai salle bryn in fyre, ilk ane,</L>
<L N="8056">&THORN;at salle be menged with bronstane</L>
<L>Ffulle hate brynand, and with pyk,</L>
<L>And with other thing &thorn;at es wyk,</L>
<L>Omang vermyn &thorn;at salle &thorn;am byte,</L>
<L N="8060">And devels &thorn;at ay salle &thorn;am smyte,</L>
<L>With other payns strang and felle,</L>
<L>Ma &thorn;an hert may thynk or tong telle.</L>
<L>&THORN;e sevend blys es endeles lyfe,</L>
<L N="8064">&THORN;at &thorn;e saved salle have, with-outen stryfe,</L>
<L>Ever-mare in heven swa heghe;</L>
<L>Ffor &thorn;ai salle ay lyf and never deghe,</L>
<L>And with God alle-myghty &thorn;are ay won,</L>
<L N="8068">&THORN;at es sothfast Fader, and sothfast Son,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e Haly Gast in Trinit&eacute;;</L>
<L>And in &thorn;at lyfe his face &thorn;ai salle ay se.</L>
<L>Now if a man moght lyf here,</L>
<L N="8072">In &thorn;is world a thowsand yhere,</L>
<L>Yhit suld his lyfe be broght tylle ende,</L>
<L>And fra &thorn;is world bihoved him wende.</L>
<L>Yhit suld him thynk, and he toke kepe,</L>
<L N="8076">His lyfe noght bot als a dreme in slepe,
<PB REF="00000262.tif" N="218"></L>
<L>&THORN;an suld &thorn;e lenthe of alle his lyfedays,</L>
<L>Seme bot als a day, als &thorn;e prophet says:</L>
<L><I>Quoniam mille anni ante oculos tuos, tanquum</I></L>
<L N="8080"><I>dies hesterna que preteriit.</I></L>
<L>He says &thorn;us: "Lord! a thowsand yhere</L>
<L>Bi-for &thorn;ine eghen, &thorn;at alle thyng sese here,</L>
<L>At &thorn;e last, es noght bot als yhister-day,</L>
<L N="8084">&THORN;at was awhile and es passed oway."</L>
<L>&THORN;us when &thorn;is lyfe tylle ende es broght,</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;e tyme of it semes als noght;</L>
<L>&THORN;an es a day mare in heven swa clere,</L>
<L N="8088">&THORN;an here er many thowsand yhere;</L>
<L>And many thowsand yheres here es les,</L>
<L>&THORN;an &thorn;are a day, als &thorn;e boke bers witnes.</L>
<L>&THORN;an salle &thorn;e lyf be als lang &thorn;are,</L>
<L N="8092">Als &thorn;at day lastes, and &thorn;at es ever-mare;</L>
<L>Ffor &thorn;are es ay day and never nyght,</L>
<L>&THORN;arfor &thorn;e prophet says &thorn;us ryght:</L>
<L><I>Melior est dies una in atriis</I></L>
<L N="8096"><I>tuis super milia.</I></L>
<L>He says: "Loverd! better es a day lastand</L>
<L>In &thorn;i halles &thorn;an a thowsand;"</L>
<L>&THORN;at es, better es in heven a day,</L>
<L N="8100">&THORN;an a thowsand here &thorn;at passes oway;</L>
<L>Ffor alle &thorn;e days &thorn;at here may falle,</L>
<L>Passes oway, and &thorn;is lyf with-alle,</L>
<L>And in a day in heven salle be contende</L>
<L N="8104">&THORN;e tyme &thorn;at never salle have ende;</L>
<L>&THORN;an salle &thorn;at day, als &thorn;e boke us leres,</L>
<L>Pass many hundreth thowsand yheres.</L>
<L>And als in helle salle be nyght,</L>
<L N="8108">Als day salle be in heven bryght;</L>
<L>Ffor als men in heven salle ay day se,</L>
<L>Ryght swa salle nyght ay in helle be.</L>
<L>&THORN;us salle day in heven be contende,</L>
<L N="8112">And nyght in helle, with-outen ende;</L>
<L>Bot se we noght how schort a day es here</L>
<L>To regard of a hundreth yhere?
<PB REF="00000263.tif" N="219"></L>
<L>Yhit es a hundreth yhere les</L>
<L N="8116">To regard of &thorn;e tyme &thorn;at es endeles;</L>
<L>Ffor Saint Austyn telles in a sarmon,</L>
<L>&THORN;at a day here may be a porcyon,</L>
<L>Of ane hundreth yhere, als men may se,</L>
<L N="8120">Alle-if &thorn;at porcyon fulle lytylle be,</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;e space of ane hundreth yhere es</L>
<L>Na porcyon of endelesnes;</L>
<L>Ffor if a thowsand yhere &thorn;at es mare</L>
<L N="8124">Of endlesnes a porcyon ware,</L>
<L>After a thowsand thowsand yheres to kast,</L>
<L>Endlesnes suld sese &thorn;an at &thorn;e last,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at wille noght &thorn;e reson of endelesnes</L>
<L N="8128">Suffer &thorn;at it be schorter &thorn;an it es;</L>
<L>Ffor if endlesnes any end moght hald,</L>
<L>&THORN;an war it endlesnes unproperly cald.</L>
<L>Bot in &thorn;at endlesnes es contende</L>
<L N="8132">Alle &thorn;e tyme &thorn;at may have nane ende;</L>
<L>And lyfe in heven salle als lang be</L>
<L>Als men salle tyme &thorn;are with-outen ende se,</L>
<L>&THORN;an semes it wele, als I sayd are,</L>
<L N="8136">&THORN;at lyfe salle be &thorn;are ever-mare</L>
<L>Wharfor ilk man with hert stedfast,</L>
<L>Suld seke &thorn;at lyfe &thorn;at ay salle last,</L>
<L>&THORN;e whilk ilk man may lyghtly wyn,</L>
<L N="8140">&THORN;at here lyfes wele and wille fle syn,</L>
<L>And leve noght &thorn;at lyf &thorn;at lastes ay</L>
<L>Ffor &thorn;is lyfe here &thorn;at passes oway;</L>
<L>Ffor &thorn;at lyfe es syker, and swa es noght &thorn;is.</L>
<L N="8144">&THORN;at lyfe es swa fulle of ioy and blys</L>
<L>&THORN;at a man salle thynk &thorn;are a hundreth yhere,</L>
<L>In &thorn;at lyfe, schorter &thorn;an a day here.</L>
<L>Tylle &thorn;at ioyfulle lyf may alle men com</L>
<L N="8148">&THORN;at meke of hert er here, and bowsom.</L>
<L>&THORN;us salle endles lyfe appropryed be,</L>
<L>Tylle &thorn;e saved bodyse &thorn;at ay God salle se.</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;e dampned &thorn;at tylle helle salle wende,</L>
<L N="8152">Salle have ded &thorn;are with-outen ende,
<PB REF="00000264.tif" N="220"></L>
<L>And &thorn;at ded salle ay new &thorn;am gryefe.</L>
<L>In &thorn;at ded &thorn;ai salle ay lyefe,</L>
<L>And swa be pyned, in &thorn;air wyttes fyve,</L>
<L N="8156">&THORN;at &thorn;air lyfe salle seme mare ded &thorn;an lyve.</L>
<L>&THORN;ai salle seme, whether &thorn;ai lyg or stand,</L>
<L>Als men in transyng, ay deghand;</L>
<L>&THORN;ai salle ay deghand lyf, and lyfand dyghe,</L>
<L N="8160">And ever-mare payns of ded &thorn;us dryghe,</L>
<L>And &thorn;are-with be tourmented, ay omang,</L>
<L>With other bytter payns and strang;</L>
<L>&THORN;ar-for &thorn;e lyfe in helle may be cald</L>
<L N="8164">&THORN;e secund ded, and swa may we it hald.</L>
<L>&THORN;an may &thorn;ai say, &thorn;at salle lyf &thorn;are,</L>
<L>Allas! &thorn;at ever moder &thorn;am bare.</L>
<L>Here have I tald, als yhe moght here,</L>
<L N="8168">Of seven manere of blysses sere,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e saved bodyse salle have thurgh ryght</L>
<L>With &thorn;e saules in heven bryght,</L>
<L>And of &thorn;e seven schendschepes alle-swa</L>
<L N="8172">&THORN;at es even contrary tylle &thorn;a,</L>
<L>&THORN;e whilk &thorn;e bodyse in helle salle have ay,</L>
<L>&THORN;at salle be dampned at domesday.</L>
<L>Bot I wille schew yhow yhit with-alle,</L>
<L N="8176">Seven manere of blysses, &thorn;at salle falle</L>
<L>Tylle &thorn;e saules namely with &thorn;e bodyse,</L>
<L>Of alle &thorn;e men &thorn;at er gude and ryghtwise,</L>
<L>&THORN;at salle be saved at &thorn;at tyde,</L>
<L N="8180">And in heven be gloryfyde;</L>
<L>And yhit seven schendschepes wille Ineven,</L>
<L>&THORN;at er even contrary tylle &thorn;a seven,</L>
<L>&THORN;e whilk salle falle, with-outen ende,</L>
<L N="8184">Tylle &thorn;a saules of &thorn;e synfulle &thorn;at salle wende,</L>
<L>With &thorn;e bodyse, untylle helle pytt,</L>
<L>Als es fonden in haly wrytt.</L>
<L>&THORN;e fyrst blys &thorn;at &thorn;e saules salle have</L>
<L N="8188">Of ryghtwise men, &thorn;at salle be save</L>
<L>Es wisdom; for &thorn;ai salle knaw and se</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;at was, and es, and yhit salle be.
<PB REF="00000265.tif" N="221"></L>
<L>&THORN;ai salle have knawyng of God fully,</L>
<L N="8192">And of &thorn;e myght of &thorn;e Fader alle-myghty,</L>
<L>&THORN;ai salle knaw &thorn;e wytt of &thorn;e son and taste,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e gudenes of &thorn;e Haly-gaste:</L>
<L>&THORN;us salle &thorn;air knawyng parfyte be,</L>
<L N="8196">In alle &thorn;e haly trinit&eacute;.</L>
<L>&THORN;ai salle knaw alle thing and wytt,</L>
<L>&THORN;at God has done and salle do yhit,</L>
<L>In heven, in helle and in erth aywhare,</L>
<L N="8200">&THORN;us wise &thorn;ai salle be ever-mare.</L>
<L>Ffor &thorn;ai salle have swa mykelle grace,</L>
<L>When &thorn;ai se God, face to face,</L>
<L>&THORN;at nathyng, &thorn;at God ever dyd,</L>
<L N="8204">Salle be layned fra &thorn;am ne hyd,</L>
<L>&THORN;at es to say, of &thorn;at God vouches save,</L>
<L>&THORN;at any creature knawyng may have;</L>
<L>Ffor Saint Austyn &thorn;at mykelle couth of clergy,</L>
<L N="8208">Says in a sarmon &thorn;at he made openly,</L>
<L>&THORN;at, in &thorn;e syght of God &thorn;at &thorn;ai salle se,</L>
<L>Thre manere of knawyng tylle &thorn;am salle be.</L>
<L>Ffor &thorn;ai salle se him &thorn;are both God and man,</L>
<L N="8212">And &thorn;am-self &thorn;ai salle se in him &thorn;an,</L>
<L>And alle men and alle thing, les and mare.</L>
<L>&THORN;ai salle se, and knaw in &thorn;at syght &thorn;are,</L>
<L>Als we may thre thynges se here</L>
<L N="8216">In a myroure of glas, &thorn;at es clere;</L>
<L>Ane es &thorn;e myrour &thorn;at byfor us es,</L>
<L>Ane other es our awene face and lyknes,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e thred we may &thorn;ar-in se yhit,</L>
<L N="8220">&THORN;at es alle thyng &thorn;at es onence it;</L>
<L>Right swa men salle se God als he es,</L>
<L>In &thorn;e myroure of his bryghtnes,</L>
<L>Als properly als possible may be,</L>
<L N="8224">Tylle any creature him to se.</L>
<L>&THORN;ai salle se &thorn;am-self in him so bryght,</L>
<L>And alle men to-gyder, at a syght,</L>
<L>And alle other thyng &thorn;ai salle knawe,</L>
<L N="8228">And se over-alle, both hegh and lawe.
<PB REF="00000266.tif" N="222"></L>
<L>Alle men &thorn;an salle se &thorn;at &thorn;are salle dwelle,</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;e creatures in heven and helle.</L>
<L>&THORN;are salle be schewed &thorn;an tylle &thorn;am, apertly,</L>
<L N="8228">Sere privetese of God alle-myghty,</L>
<L>&THORN;at na man here moght knaw ne wytt</L>
<L>Thurgh clergy, ne thurgh haly-wrytt;</L>
<L>&THORN;at es, how God invysible es,</L>
<L N="8232">And unchaungeable, and endles;</L>
<L>And how he was bifor alle thing,</L>
<L>And with-outen any bygynnyng;</L>
<L>And how, and whi, he salle be</L>
<L N="8240">With-outen ende, &thorn;ai salle &thorn;an se;</L>
<L>Alle thyng &thorn;at now es fra &thorn;am hyd,</L>
<L>Salle &thorn;an tylle &thorn;am be knawen and kyd.</L>
<L>&THORN;ai salle &thorn;an se &thorn;are, openly,</L>
<L N="8244">Of alle thynges &thorn;e skylle and &thorn;e cause whi;</L>
<L>Als whi ane es chosen here and taken,</L>
<L>And ane other left and forsaken;</L>
<L>Whi ane es uptane tylle a kyngdom,</L>
<L N="8248">And ane other es putted in-tylle thraldom;</L>
<L>And whi som childer er ded and lorn</L>
<L>In &thorn;air moder wambe, ar &thorn;ai be born;</L>
<L>&THORN;ai salle knaw, with-outen drede,</L>
<L N="8252">Skylle whi som deghes in &thorn;air barnhede,</L>
<L>And som after when &thorn;ai mast strenthe weld;</L>
<L>And whi som lyfes tylle &thorn;air mast eld;</L>
<L>&THORN;ai salle yhit sertaine skylle se &thorn;an</L>
<L N="8256">Whi som er born in fayre schap of man,</L>
<L>And som in uncomly stature,</L>
<L>And whi som er ryche here, and som pore,</L>
<L>And whi som childer geten in hordom,</L>
<L N="8260">Er baptized, and has cristendom,</L>
<L>And som &thorn;at er in lele wedlayk born,</L>
<L>Ar &thorn;ai be cristened, er ded and lorn;</L>
<L>And whi som bi[g]ynnes to be stedfast</L>
<L N="8264">To lyfe wele, and endes ille at &thorn;e last;</L>
<L>And whi som has here ille bigynnyng,</L>
<L>And, at &thorn;e last, mase a gud endyng.
<PB REF="00000267.tif" N="223"></L>
<L>Of &thorn;ir thynges, and of other many,</L>
<L N="8268">&THORN;e skylles salle be knawen &thorn;an openly,</L>
<L>In &thorn;e boke of lyfe &thorn;at open salle be,</L>
<L>&THORN;e whilk es &thorn;e syght of &thorn;e trinit&eacute;.</L>
<L>&THORN;us salle alle men, &thorn;at in heven &thorn;an dwelles,</L>
<L N="8272">Knaw and witt, als Saint Austyn telles,</L>
<L>And in &thorn;e bryghtnes of God openly se</L>
<L>Alle thing &thorn;at ever was, or yhit salle be,</L>
<L>And alle &thorn;e soth of ilk thyng, and skylle,</L>
<L N="8276">Als fer-forth als God vouches safe, and wille.</L>
<L>&THORN;are salle ilk man als wele knaw other,</L>
<L>Als a man here knawes hys syster or brother,</L>
<L>And wyt of what contr&eacute; &thorn;ai ware,</L>
<L N="8280">And wha &thorn;am gatt, and wha &thorn;am bare.</L>
<L>Ilk ane salle knaw &thorn;an other thoght</L>
<L>And alle &thorn;e dedes &thorn;at &thorn;ai ever wroght;</L>
<L>&THORN;us wyse salle &thorn;ai be &thorn;at salle come</L>
<L N="8284">Tylle &thorn;e kyngdom of heven, after &thorn;e dome.</L>
<L>&THORN;ai salle be Godes sons, and tille him lyke,</L>
<L>And be made his heyres of hevenryke,</L>
<L>And be alle als Godes of gret myght,</L>
<L N="8288">Als &thorn;e prophet, in &thorn;e psauter, says ryght:</L>
<L><I>Ego dixi: 'Dii estis et</I></L>
<L><I>filii excelsi omnes.'</I></L>
<L>He says: "I sayd, 'yhe er Godes alle</L>
<L N="8292">And Godes sons men salle yhow calle'."</L>
<L>Wharfor it semes, &thorn;at when &thorn;ai com</L>
<L>Tylle heven, &thorn;ai salle be fulle of wysdom</L>
<L>And fulle of myght, lastand ever-mare,</L>
<L N="8296">When &thorn;ai salle alle be als Godes &thorn;are.</L>
<L>Bot now may &thorn;ou ask me and lere</L>
<L>A questyon, and say on &thorn;is manere:</L>
<L>'Salle &thorn;ai oght think &thorn;at salle be safe,</L>
<L N="8300">On &thorn;e syns of whilk &thorn;ai &thorn;am schrafe</L>
<L>Here in &thorn;air lyfe, and made &thorn;am clene,</L>
<L>And of &thorn;am assoyled has bene?'</L>
<L>Saint Anselme answers to &thorn;is,</L>
<L N="8304">And says &thorn;at &thorn;ou &thorn;at salle have heven blys,
<PB REF="00000268.tif" N="224"></L>
<L>Salle love God and thank him &thorn;are</L>
<L>Of alle gudes, both les and mare,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he has done tylle &thorn;e here,</L>
<L N="8308">And tylle alle other, on &thorn;e same manere,</L>
<L>&THORN;e whilk, at &thorn;e day of dome, salle be safe,</L>
<L>And with &thorn;e endles blys salle have.</L>
<L>Gret gud he dose &thorn;e, whils &thorn;ou lyfes,</L>
<L N="8312">When he &thorn;i syns &thorn;e here forgyves;</L>
<L>How moght &thorn;ou &thorn;an, with hert fre,</L>
<L>Thank God of &thorn;at &thorn;at he has forgyven &thorn;e,</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;e syns &thorn;at &thorn;ou has wroght,</L>
<L N="8316">If &thorn;ou moght thynk on nane in thoght?</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;ou salle &thorn;is understand wele,</L>
<L>&THORN;at na mare grevance salle &thorn;ou fele,</L>
<L>Ne na mare payne have, ne myslykyng,</L>
<L N="8320">When &thorn;ou has of &thorn;i syns meneyng,</L>
<L>&THORN;an he has, &thorn;at som tyme had in stryfe</L>
<L>A sare wound, with swerd or knyfe,</L>
<L>&THORN;at parfytely es haled and wele,</L>
<L N="8324">Of whilk he may na mare sare<NOTE PLACE="foot">The MS. has 'sale'.</NOTE> fele;</L>
<L>And als &thorn;ou now has na schame of &thorn;e dede</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou dyd in &thorn;i barnhede,</L>
<L>Or &thorn;at &thorn;ou dyd in &thorn;i dronkennes,</L>
<L N="8328">Of whilk tylle &thorn;e now na schame es.</L>
<L>Na mare schame salle &thorn;ou &thorn;an have in thoght,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e syns &thorn;at &thorn;ou here has wroght,</L>
<L>Of whilk &thorn;ou ert here schryven parfytely,</L>
<L N="8332">And &thorn;at God has forgyfen here, thurgh mercy</L>
<L>And na mare &thorn;an Petre now has schame</L>
<L>Of &thorn;at, &thorn;at he forsoke our Lord bi name;</L>
<L>Or Mary Maudelayne now has of hir syn</L>
<L N="8336">&THORN;at scho som tyme delyted hir in.</L>
<L>Na mare schame salle men &thorn;an have</L>
<L>Of &thorn;air syn here done, &thorn;at salle be save.</L>
<L>Bot for-&thorn;i &thorn;at God &thorn;at boght us fre,</L>
<L N="8340">Wyld thurgh his mercy and his pet&eacute;,
<PB REF="00000269.tif" N="225"></L>
<L>And couth, thurgh his awen wytt clere,</L>
<L>And myght wele, thurgh his awen powere,</L>
<L>Swa gret syns &thorn;am frely forgyve</L>
<L N="8344">And &thorn;e woundes hale<NOTE PLACE="foot">The MS. has 'have'.</NOTE>, &thorn;at war gryfe,</L>
<L>Whare-thurgh &thorn;ai had deserved wele</L>
<L>&THORN;e pyne of helle ever-mare to fele,</L>
<L>&THORN;arfor &thorn;ai salle luf him &thorn;e mare,</L>
<L N="8348">And &thorn;e mare him love and thank &thorn;are,</L>
<L>And als wele for other mens trispas</L>
<L>And other mens syn &thorn;at he heled has,</L>
<L>Als for &thorn;air awen &thorn;at &thorn;ai wroght here,</L>
<L N="8352">&THORN;arfor says David, on &thorn;is manere:</L>
<L><I>Misericordias Domini</I></L>
<L><I>ineternum cantabo.</I></L>
<L>He says: "I salle &thorn;e mercyes syng</L>
<L N="8356">Of our Loverd, ay with-outen cesyng."</L>
<L>And swa salle alle syng, with-outen ende,</L>
<L>&THORN;at tylle &thorn;e blys of heven salle wende;</L>
<L>And swa moght &thorn;ai on nane wise syng,</L>
<L N="8360">Warn &thorn;ai had of &thorn;air syns meneyng,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ai had done here bodily</L>
<L>And God forgaf thurgh his mercy;</L>
<L>&THORN;us salle &thorn;e saule be fulle of wysdom &thorn;are,</L>
<L N="8364">And alle thing knaw and se, als I sayd are.</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;e saules &thorn;at with &thorn;e bodyse salle synk</L>
<L>In-tylle helle, salle on na gud thynk,</L>
<L>Ne have witt, ne knaw, ne fele</L>
<L N="8368">Na dede &thorn;at ever was done wele,</L>
<L>Bot on &thorn;air payns salle be alle &thorn;air thoght</L>
<L>And on &thorn;air syns &thorn;at &thorn;ai had wroght;</L>
<L>Ffor &thorn;ai salle on nathyng have meneyng,</L>
<L N="8372">Bot anely on &thorn;air awen wicked lyfyng,</L>
<L>And on &thorn;air sorow, with-outen ende,</L>
<L>And on &thorn;air wrechednes &thorn;at salle &thorn;am schende</L>
<L>&THORN;e whilk &thorn;ai salle, ay, bifor &thorn;am se,</L>
<L N="8376">And &thorn;at syght tylle &thorn;am schendschepe sallebe.
<PB REF="00000270.tif" N="226"></L>
<L>&THORN;e secund blys &thorn;at &thorn;e saule salle fele,</L>
<L>With &thorn;e bodyse, als &thorn;ir clerkes wate wele,</L>
<L>Salle be frendschepe and parfyte love,</L>
<L N="8380">&THORN;at es mare &thorn;an ever man moght here prove;</L>
<L>Ffor ilk ane salle mare luf other &thorn;an,</L>
<L>&THORN;an ever lufed here any man,</L>
<L>And als parfytely and als lang</L>
<L N="8384">Als he salle luf him-self omang.</L>
<L>And &thorn;at luf salle be fested swa fast,</L>
<L>&THORN;at it salle never fayle, bot ay last;</L>
<L>Ffor als ilka lym of a body</L>
<L N="8388">Lufes alle &thorn;e other lyms kyndely,</L>
<L>And yhernes, ay, gretly &thorn;air hele,</L>
<L>Swa parfyte &thorn;at luf salle be and lele;</L>
<L>Ffor &thorn;ai salle alle be of ane assent</L>
<L N="8392">And of a wille and of ane entent;</L>
<L>Ffor &thorn;ai salle be &thorn;an alle als a body</L>
<L>In sere lyms, and als a saule anely;</L>
<L>And God &thorn;air heved salle be &thorn;are,</L>
<L N="8396">&THORN;at salle &thorn;am luf als mykelle or mare,</L>
<L>Als dose &thorn;e heved of &thorn;e body &thorn;at loves</L>
<L>&THORN;e lyms kyndely &thorn;at on it moves.</L>
<L>&THORN;at clere luf and &thorn;at alliance</L>
<L N="8400">Salle never-mare fayle, thurgh na distance,</L>
<L>Ne thurgh stryfe, &thorn;at man may make;</L>
<L>&THORN;at band of luff salle never slake.</L>
<L>Bot even &thorn;e contrary salle men se,</L>
<L N="8404">Omang &thorn;e saules &thorn;at dampned salle be;</L>
<L>Ffor &thorn;ai salle be fulle of felony,</L>
<L>Of hatred, of wreth and of envy;</L>
<L>Swa &thorn;at ilk ane wald with other fyght,</L>
<L N="8408">And strangelle other, if &thorn;ai myght.</L>
<L>&THORN;us salle &thorn;ai hate and stryfe ilk ane,</L>
<L>Ffor peese salle be omang &thorn;am nane,</L>
<L>Ne rest, ne eese, ne worschepe,</L>
<L N="8412">Bot travayle, and pyne, and schendschepe.</L>
<L>Bot God alle-myghty, and alle-swa alle his</L>
<L>&THORN;at with him salle dwelle in heven blis,
<PB REF="00000271.tif" N="227"></L>
<L>Salle &thorn;am in sorow and pyne se</L>
<L N="8416">And of &thorn;am &thorn;ai salle have na pet&eacute;,</L>
<L>Bot hate &thorn;am als Godes enmyse.</L>
<L>And &thorn;at hatredyn salle &thorn;an be ryghtwyse;</L>
<L>Ffor &thorn;e fader, &thorn;at &thorn;an salle be save,</L>
<L N="8420">Na pet&eacute; of &thorn;e son &thorn;are salle have,</L>
<L>&THORN;at salle be dampned tylle helle payne;</L>
<L>Ne &thorn;e son, &thorn;at salle be saved &thorn;are ogayne,</L>
<L>Salle have na reuthe, ne na pyt&eacute;,</L>
<L N="8424">Of &thorn;e fader &thorn;at dampned salle be;</L>
<L>Ne &thorn;e moder, on &thorn;e same manere,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e doghter &thorn;at scho lufed here;</L>
<L>Ne &thorn;e doghter of &thorn;e moder na mare;</L>
<L N="8428">Ne &thorn;e brother of &thorn;e syster &thorn;are;</L>
<L>Ne &thorn;e syster of &thorn;e brother.</L>
<L>Nane of &thorn;am salle have reuthe of other;</L>
<L>Ne nane other, &thorn;at salle be saved &thorn;an,</L>
<L N="8432">Salle have reuthe ne pet&eacute; of dampned man.</L>
<L>Bot when &thorn;e ryghtwyse &thorn;e synfulle salle se</L>
<L>Pyned in helle, glad &thorn;ai salle be,</L>
<L>Ffor twa skyls, and ioyfulle and fayne;</L>
<L N="8436">Ane es, for-&thorn;i &thorn;at &thorn;ai er skaped &thorn;at payne,</L>
<L>Ane other es for-&thorn;i &thorn;at Godes vengeance</L>
<L>Es ryghtwise, and his ordinance.</L>
<L>&THORN;is proves &thorn;e prophete, als &thorn;e boke schewes us,</L>
<L N="8440">&THORN;are he says in &thorn;e psauter &thorn;us:</L>
<L><I>Letabitur iustus, cum</I></L>
<L><I>viderit vindictam.</I></L>
<L>He says &thorn;at "ilka ryghtwyse man</L>
<L N="8444">Fulle glad and blyth salle be &thorn;an,</L>
<L>When &thorn;ai Godes vengeance se</L>
<L>On &thorn;e synfulle, &thorn;at &thorn;an dampned salle be.</L>
<L>&THORN;e thred blys, als men may in boke rede,</L>
<L N="8448">Es veray acord and anehede,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e saules salle have in heven to-gyder,</L>
<L>With &thorn;e bodyse, when &thorn;ai com &thorn;ider;</L>
<L>Ffor ilk ane salle folow others wille,</L>
<L N="8452">And ilk ane othe[r]s lykyng fullfylle;
<PB REF="00000272.tif" N="228"></L>
<L>And als &thorn;ine ane eghe folows ryght.</L>
<L>&THORN;e tother, &thorn;are it settes &thorn;e syght,</L>
<L>And nouther may turne, hyder ne &thorn;ider,</L>
<L N="8456">Bot &thorn;ai both ay turne to-gyder,</L>
<L>Right swa salle God acord with alle his,</L>
<L>And ilk ane with other in that blys;</L>
<L>And to what thyng &thorn;e saule has talent,</L>
<L N="8460">To &thorn;at &thorn;e body salle, ay, assent;</L>
<L>And what-swa God &thorn;an wille be done</L>
<L>To &thorn;at &thorn;ai salle assent alle-sone;</L>
<L>And what thyng swa &thorn;ai &thorn;an wille,</L>
<L N="8464">&THORN;at salle God als-tyte fulle-fylle.</L>
<L>&THORN;is acorde and anehede sall never ceese,</L>
<L>Bot ever-mare last with rest and peese.</L>
<L>Alle salle &thorn;ai be alle ane in company,</L>
<L N="8468">And als a saule and a body.</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;e dampned &thorn;are ogayne salle stryve,</L>
<L>Ilkane with other, for &thorn;air wicked lyve;</L>
<L>Ffor ilk ane salle hate other &thorn;an,</L>
<L N="8472">And ilk ane salle wery other and ban;</L>
<L>Ilk ane salle yherne with other to fyght,</L>
<L>And ilk ane wald sla other if &thorn;ai myght;</L>
<L>&THORN;e body salle hate &thorn;e saule bi skylle,</L>
<L N="8476">Ffor &thorn;e saule here thoght ay &thorn;e ille;</L>
<L>&THORN;e saule salle ay hate &thorn;e body,</L>
<L>Ffor &thorn;e body wroght &thorn;e foly;</L>
<L>And for-&thorn;i &thorn;at &thorn;e saule fyrst syn thoght</L>
<L N="8480">And &thorn;e body it afterward wroght,</L>
<L>And wyld noght leve, ne stand &thorn;are ogayne,</L>
<L>Untylle &thorn;e ded &thorn;e body had slayne.</L>
<L>&THORN;ar-fore bath to-gyder salle dwelle,</L>
<L N="8484">With-outen ende, in &thorn;e pyne of helle.</L>
<L>&THORN;e ferth blys, omang &thorn;e tother alle,</L>
<L>&THORN;at to &thorn;e saules, with &thorn;e bodyse, salle falle,</L>
<L>&THORN;e whilk salle be saved, es powere;</L>
<L N="8488">Ffor &thorn;ai salle &thorn;are have both fer and nere,</L>
<L>Swa mykelle power and maistry</L>
<L>And lordschip, and be swa myghty
<PB REF="00000273.tif" N="229"></L>
<L>&THORN;at alle thyng &thorn;an salle be done</L>
<L N="8492">At &thorn;air wille, hastily and sone;</L>
<L>And what-swa &thorn;ai wille think in thoght,</L>
<L>Alle salle be at &thorn;air wille &thorn;are wroght;</L>
<L>Ffor alle thing salle be tylle [&thorn;am] boghand,</L>
<L N="8496">And nathyng salle ogayne &thorn;am stand;</L>
<L>Ffor God salle fulle-fylle alle &thorn;air lykyng,</L>
<L>And folow &thorn;air wille in alle thing.</L>
<L>&THORN;us salle &thorn;ai haf &thorn;are gret powere,</L>
<L N="8500">And heghnes, for &thorn;air awen gret lawnes here,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ai had in &thorn;air lyfe days,</L>
<L>And &thorn;arfor God, in &thorn;e gosspelle says:</L>
<L><I>Qui se humiliat</I></L>
<L N="8504"><I>exaltabitur.</I></L>
<L>He says: "Wha-swa here lawes him ryght</L>
<L>He salle be heghed, in heven bryght."</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;e dampned &thorn;are ogayne halely,</L>
<L N="8508">Salle want alkyn power and maistry,</L>
<L>And &thorn;are-with &thorn;ai salle tharne alle thing,</L>
<L>Of whilk men moght have lykyng.</L>
<L>&THORN;ai salle ay be in gret dred and awe,</L>
<L N="8512">And under fote ay be halden lawe.</L>
<L>&THORN;ai salle have nathyng at &thorn;air wille,</L>
<L>Bot alle thing &thorn;at salle lyke &thorn;am ille.</L>
<L>Mykelle sorow &thorn;am salle &thorn;an bityde,</L>
<L N="8516">Ffor &thorn;air heghenes here, and &thorn;air pryde,</L>
<L>Als &thorn;e bok says &thorn;at beres wytnes,</L>
<L>And als in &thorn;e same gosspelle wryten es:</L>
<L><I>Qui se exaltat hu|</I></L>
<L N="8520"><I>miliabitur.</I></L>
<L>&THORN;at es, "wha-swa heghe here wille him bere</L>
<L>He salle be lawed" and putted in daungere,</L>
<L>&THORN;at es in gret daunger of fendes,</L>
<L N="8524">In pyne of helle, &thorn;at never endes.</L>
<L>&THORN;e fyft blys &thorn;at salle falle alswa,</L>
<L>To &thorn;e saules, &thorn;at with &thorn;e bodyse salle ga</L>
<L>Tylleheven-ryke, es honoure and worschepe,</L>
<L N="8528">Of whilk God him-self salle tak kepe;
<PB REF="00000274.tif" N="230"></L>
<L>Ffor &thorn;ai salle have &thorn;are sere honours,</L>
<L>And be corouned, als kynges and emparours.</L>
<L>And sytt in setyls schynand bryght,</L>
<L N="8532">With alkyn nobelay, rychely dyght;</L>
<L>With bryghtnes of lyght &thorn;ai salle be cled,</L>
<L>And gret reverence &thorn;am salle be bed,</L>
<L>And be honourd als Godes frendes dere,</L>
<L N="8536">Ffor &thorn;e worschepe &thorn;at &thorn;ai dyd him here,</L>
<L>In gud werkes, &thorn;at tylle him war swete,</L>
<L>&THORN;arfor &thorn;us says David, &thorn;e prophete:</L>
<L><I>Omnis honorati sunt</I></L>
<L N="8540"><I>amici tui Deus.</I></L>
<L>"&THORN;i frendes, Loverd, &thorn;at honourd &thorn;e</L>
<L>Es mykelle honourd, and swa ay salle be."</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;e dampned, &thorn;at with syn er fyled,</L>
<L N="8544">&THORN;are ogayne salle be revyled,</L>
<L>And despysed, and ay schent with-alle,</L>
<L>And stresced ogayne &thorn;air wille als thralle,</L>
<L>And pyned with gretter paynes sere,</L>
<L N="8548">&THORN;an ever was sene in &thorn;is world here;</L>
<L>&THORN;ai salle[thole] alle thyng &thorn;at schendschepe es</L>
<L>With payn and sorow &thorn;at es endles,</L>
<L>Omang hete and cald, vermyn and stynk,</L>
<L N="8552">And alkyn fylth &thorn;at hert may think;</L>
<L>And alle &thorn;e sorow &thorn;ai &thorn;at salle fele,</L>
<L>Salle be endles, als &thorn;ai salle knaw wele.</L>
<L>&THORN;e sext blys &thorn;at to the saules of ryghtwise</L>
<L N="8556">Salle be appropryed &thorn;an with &thorn;e bodyse,</L>
<L>In &thorn;e kyngdom of heven, es sykernes,</L>
<L>To dwelle ay &thorn;are whare alkyn ioy es,</L>
<L>Ffor &thorn;ai salle be &thorn;are syker and certayne</L>
<L N="8560">To have endeles ioy, and never-mare payne,</L>
<L>And to won ay &thorn;are, with-outen dout,</L>
<L>And with-outen lettyng, and putting out,</L>
<L>And with-outen alle manere of drede;</L>
<L N="8564">Ffor of nathyng &thorn;are &thorn;ai salle have nede,</L>
<L>&THORN;ai salle noght far, als men fares here</L>
<L>&THORN;at lyfes ay in dred and were;
<PB REF="00000275.tif" N="231"></L>
<L>Ffor here, both kyng and emparoure</L>
<L N="8568">Has dred to tyne &thorn;air honoure;</L>
<L>And ilka ryche man has dred alle-swa</L>
<L>His gudes and ryches to for-ga;</L>
<L>And ilk man, &thorn;at here fares wele,</L>
<L N="8572">Has ay dred angers to fele.</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;ai &thorn;at salle com tylle heven blys,</L>
<L>Salle never have dred &thorn;at ioy to mys;</L>
<L>Ffor &thorn;ai salle be syker Inoghe &thorn;are,</L>
<L N="8576">&THORN;at &thorn;air ioy salle last ever-mare.</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;e dampned men &thorn;are ogayne,</L>
<L>Salle ay be dredand in &thorn;air payne,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;air payns suld eked be,</L>
<L N="8580">And be made mare grevous to se,</L>
<L>Ffor &thorn;e devels sal, ay, on &thorn;am gang</L>
<L>To and fra, over-thewrt and endlang;</L>
<L>And omang &thorn;am ay ymagyne,</L>
<L N="8584">How &thorn;ai may eke &thorn;air sorow and pyne;</L>
<L>And &thorn;e mare payne &thorn;at &thorn;ai tille synfulle salle seke</L>
<L>&THORN;e mare &thorn;ai &thorn;air awen payne salle eke.</L>
<L>And, if &thorn;ai do swa, it es na ferly,</L>
<L N="8588">Ffor &thorn;ai er ay fulle of Ire and envy.</L>
<L>&THORN;e devels salle ay opon &thorn;am gang,</L>
<L>And ay on &thorn;am stamp with &thorn;air feth omang</L>
<L>And threst &thorn;am doune, in fyre and smoke,</L>
<L N="8592">And &thorn;arfor says Iob &thorn;us in a boke:</L>
<L><I>Vadent et venient super</I></L>
<L><I>eos demones horribiles.</I></L>
<L>He says, "grysely devels salle gang and com</L>
<L N="8596">On &thorn;e synfulle &thorn;at tylle God war unbowsom."</L>
<L>&THORN;us dredand salle &thorn;ai ay be &thorn;are,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;air payne suld be ay mare and mare;</L>
<L>Ffor &thorn;ai salle be certayne &thorn;are &thorn;ai dwelle,</L>
<L N="8600">&THORN;at &thorn;ai salle never com out of helle.</L>
<L>&THORN;e sevend blys es ioy parfyte,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e saules salle have, with gret delyte,</L>
<L>With &thorn;e bodyse &thorn;at saved salle be,
<PB REF="00000276.tif" N="232"></L>
<L N="8604">And won in heven, whare &thorn;ai salle ay God se</L>
<L>Ffor-whi ilk ane &thorn;are salle &thorn;at tyde,</L>
<L>In body and saule be gloryfyde,</L>
<L>And fulle ioy and blys have with-alle,</L>
<L N="8608">With alle manere of delyces &thorn;at may falle.</L>
<L>Ilk ane with other salle be knawen,</L>
<L>And fele other mens ioy als &thorn;air awen;</L>
<L>And mare ioy and blys moght never be,</L>
<L N="8612">&THORN;an ilk ane salle &thorn;are-on other se.</L>
<L>&THORN;ai salle se, in heven-ryke swa wyde,</L>
<L>Many sere ioyes, on ilka syde;</L>
<L>Ffor &thorn;are salle be mare sere ioyes &thorn;an,</L>
<L N="8616">&THORN;an ever couth noumbre erthly man;</L>
<L>Of whilk syght &thorn;ai salle mare ioy have,</L>
<L>&THORN;an any man moght yhern or crave.</L>
<L>Ilk ane salle be payed swa wele</L>
<L N="8620">Of his part of ioy &thorn;at he salle fele,</L>
<L>&THORN;e whilk he salle parfytely have &thorn;are,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he salle willen yhern no mare;</L>
<L>&THORN;are salle ilk ane many thowsandes se</L>
<L N="8624">In sere ioyes, als him-self salle be.</L>
<L>And &thorn;e syght of ilka ioy &thorn;an,</L>
<L>Salle be swa delytable tille ilka man,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e ioy of a syght &thorn;are salle pas</L>
<L N="8628">Alle &thorn;e ioyes &thorn;at ever in erth was;</L>
<L>And alle &thorn;at tylle heven salle be tane</L>
<L>Salle &thorn;are &thorn;an se &thorn;a ioyes ilk ane.</L>
<L>And &thorn;e syght of ilka ioy &thorn;are, salle be</L>
<L N="8632">Ioy tylle ilka man &thorn;at it salle se,</L>
<L>&THORN;an salle ilk man have ma ioyes in heven,</L>
<L>&THORN;an hert may thynk, or tong kan neven;</L>
<L>&THORN;ai salle have ioy, with-in and with-out,</L>
<L N="8636">Oboven, benethe, and alle obout.</L>
<L>Oboven &thorn;am, &thorn;ai salle have ioyfully</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e syght of God alle-myghty,</L>
<L>Binethe &thorn;am, of &thorn;e sternes and planetes sere,</L>
<L N="8640">And &thorn;e world &thorn;at &thorn;an salle be bryght and clere;
<PB REF="00000277.tif" N="233"></L>
<L>Oboven &thorn;am, of heven &thorn;at &thorn;ai bryght salle se,</L>
<L>And of other creatures &thorn;at fair salle be,</L>
<L>With-in &thorn;am, of &thorn;e glorifying of man,</L>
<L N="8644">Of &thorn;e body and saule to-gyder &thorn;an;</L>
<L>With-outen &thorn;am, of &thorn;e blysfulle companyse</L>
<L>Of aungels, and of men ryghtwise.</L>
<L>&THORN;ai salle have ioy in alle &thorn;air wittes,</L>
<L N="8648">In heven with God &thorn;are he syttes;</L>
<L>Ffirst &thorn;ai salle se with &thorn;air eghen bryght</L>
<L>Many a fayre blyssfulle syght;</L>
<L>&THORN;ai salle &thorn;air God apertly se,</L>
<L N="8652">And alle &thorn;e thre parsons in trinit&eacute;,</L>
<L>&THORN;e Fader, and Son, and Haly-gaste,</L>
<L>&THORN;at sight salle be &thorn;air ioy maste.</L>
<L>Ffor als he es, &thorn;ai salle him se &thorn;an,</L>
<L N="8656">Sothfast God, and sothfast man;</L>
<L>Thurgh whilk syght &thorn;ai salle knaw,</L>
<L>And se alle thing both heghe and law</L>
<L>And se alle &thorn;e werkes &thorn;at ever God wroght;</L>
<L N="8660">And ilk mans dede, and ilk mans thoght,</L>
<L>And alle &thorn;at salle in helle be &thorn;an,</L>
<L>Ilka develle and ilka man,</L>
<L>And alle payns &thorn;at salle be &thorn;are,</L>
<L N="8664">&THORN;ai salle se, both les and mare;</L>
<L>And alle erth, and &thorn;e hevens obout,</L>
<L>And alle &thorn;at es, with-in and with-out;</L>
<L>Alle salle &thorn;ai se, thurgh myght and grace,</L>
<L N="8668">In &thorn;e bryghtnes of Godes face,</L>
<L>Of whilk &thorn;ai salle ever-mare have syght,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;e mast ioy es in heven bryght.</L>
<L>And for &thorn;ai salle ay &thorn;us God bihald,</L>
<L N="8672">&THORN;ai salle knaw alle thyng, &thorn;at &thorn;ai knaw wald.</L>
<L>In &thorn;is lyfe here men sese him noght,</L>
<L>Bot anely thurgh ryght trowth in thoght,</L>
<L>Als thurgh a myroure be lyknes,</L>
<L N="8676">Bot &thorn;are salle men se him als he es.</L>
<L>Here men him sese gastly, thurgh grace,</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;are salle men se him, face tylle face.
<PB REF="00000278.tif" N="234"></L>
<L>And &thorn;at syght &thorn;are salle alle men have,</L>
<L N="8680">With-outen ende, &thorn;at salle be save.</L>
<L>&THORN;ai salle alle-swa se &thorn;are, apertly,</L>
<L>His blysfulle Moder Saint Mary</L>
<L>&THORN;at next syttes God in heven bryght,</L>
<L N="8684">Oboven alle aungels, als es ryght;</L>
<L>Ffor he chese hir tylle his moder dere,</L>
<L>And of hir toke flessch and blode here,</L>
<L>And vouched safe to souke hir brest,</L>
<L N="8688">&THORN;arfor it es ryght scho sytt him nest.</L>
<L>Scho es swa fayre &thorn;are scho syttes,</L>
<L>&THORN;at hir fayrnes passes all mens wittes;</L>
<L>A gret ioy &thorn;at may be cald,</L>
<L N="8692">Hir fairnes anely to behald.</L>
<L>&THORN;ai salle se &thorn;are, als &thorn;e boke telles,</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;e neghen orders of aungels,</L>
<L>&THORN;at er swa fayre on to loke,</L>
<L N="8696">And swa bryght, als says &thorn;e boke,</L>
<L>&THORN;at alle fayrnes of &thorn;is lyfe here,</L>
<L>&THORN;at ever was sene, fer or nere,</L>
<L>&THORN;at any man myght ordayne defautles,</L>
<L N="8700">War noght a poynt to &thorn;at fairnes,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ai salle se &thorn;ar of &thorn;at syght</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e ordres of &thorn;e aungels bryght.</L>
<L>&THORN;ai salle se &thorn;am fulle pleysand &thorn;an,</L>
<L N="8704">And servisabylle tylle God and man;</L>
<L>And ilk ane ordre, in &thorn;air degr&eacute;</L>
<L>Salle do &thorn;at &thorn;at mast lykand salle be,</L>
<L>Bath tylle God and tylle man ryght;</L>
<L N="8708">A gret ioy salle be &thorn;are of &thorn;at syght,</L>
<L>Ffor ilk ane aungelle bi him-ane</L>
<L>Salle clerer schyne &thorn;an ever son schane;</L>
<L>&THORN;at syght men may a gret ioy calle,</L>
<L N="8712">To se &thorn;e aungels swa bryght alle,</L>
<L>&THORN;at in heven salle be sene to-gyder;</L>
<L>&THORN;at syght salle alle se &thorn;at salle com &thorn;ider.</L>
<L>Swa fayre a syght, als &thorn;at salle seme,</L>
<L N="8716">Couth never na wytt here ymagyn ne deme.
<PB REF="00000279.tif" N="235"></L>
<L>&THORN;ai salle se in heven alle-swa</L>
<L>Patriarches, and prophetes and other ma,</L>
<L>And apostels and evangelistes,</L>
<L N="8720">&THORN;at folowd nane other lyf bot cristes.</L>
<L>&THORN;ai salle se Innocentes many ane,</L>
<L>Of whilk som was, in Goddes name slane,</L>
<L>And other martyrs and confessours,</L>
<L N="8724">And haly heremytes and doctours,</L>
<L>&THORN;at haly wryt wald teche and ken;</L>
<L>And many other haly men,</L>
<L>Lered and lewed, &thorn;at lyfed wele here,</L>
<L N="8728">Both religiouse and seculere.</L>
<L>&THORN;ai salle se haly virgyns &thorn;are</L>
<L>&THORN;at here lufed God, ay mare and mare,</L>
<L>And keped &thorn;am chast, for Godes sake,</L>
<L N="8732">Of whilk som wald &thorn;e ded for his luf take.</L>
<L>&THORN;ai salle se &thorn;are in ioy and blys,</L>
<L>Other &thorn;at God salle chese for his,</L>
<L>Als wedded men &thorn;at lyfed wele here,</L>
<L N="8736">And other many of states sere.</L>
<L>A fayr syght salle be &thorn;an to se,</L>
<L>Of alle &thorn;e fayr folk &thorn;at &thorn;are salle be,</L>
<L>&THORN;at bryghter salle schyne &thorn;an ever schane son,</L>
<L N="8740">&THORN;is syght salle alle se &thorn;at &thorn;are salle won.</L>
<L>&THORN;ai salle alle-swa apertly se</L>
<L>Ilk ane be worscheped in his degr&eacute;,</L>
<L>With gret nobelay, and have sere honours,</L>
<L N="8744">And alle be als kynges and emparours,</L>
<L>Coround with ryche corouns of blys,</L>
<L>A fulle delytabelle syght salle be &thorn;is.</L>
<L>&THORN;ai salle se &thorn;are &thorn;e gret medes,</L>
<L N="8748">&THORN;at men salle have &thorn;are, for &thorn;air gud dedes,</L>
<L>After ilk ane of &thorn;am has lyfed here;</L>
<L>And &thorn;as er swamykelle, and many, and sere,</L>
<L>&THORN;at never ende salle &thorn;ai have bot last ay,</L>
<L N="8752">&THORN;at na man, thurgh wytt, mesure may,</L>
<L>Ne &thorn;am reken, ne telle &thorn;am kan,</L>
<L>Swa many medes &thorn;ai salle have &thorn;an.
<PB REF="00000280.tif" N="236"></L>
<L>&THORN;air medes salle be swa precyouse,</L>
<L N="8756">And swa delitable, and plenteuouse,</L>
<L>&THORN;at na man lyfand, als &thorn;e boke says,</L>
<L>Couth ne myght &thorn;am gesce ne prays.</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;a medes salle lyke &thorn;am als wele,</L>
<L N="8760">&THORN;at &thorn;am seese, als &thorn;am &thorn;at salle &thorn;am fele.</L>
<L>&THORN;ai salle se heven fulle large and wyde,</L>
<L>And round and even, on ilka syde,</L>
<L>And bryghter schynand &thorn;an ever schane son;</L>
<L N="8764">Wele salle &thorn;am be &thorn;at &thorn;are salle won.</L>
<L>A delitable syght &thorn;at salle be</L>
<L>Tylle &thorn;am &thorn;at salle dwelle in &thorn;at contr&eacute;.</L>
<L>&THORN;at contr&eacute; swa fayre es on to loke,</L>
<L N="8768">And swa bryght and brade, als says &thorn;e boke,</L>
<L>&THORN;at alle &thorn;is world, &thorn;are we won yhit</L>
<L>War noght bot als a myddyng-pytt</L>
<L>To regard of &thorn;at contr&eacute; swa brade,</L>
<L N="8772">&THORN;at God swa mykelle and fayr has made.</L>
<L>&THORN;at contr&eacute; es halden swa large a land,</L>
<L>&THORN;at with-in &thorn;e space of &thorn;at myght stand</L>
<L>Many a thowsand of werldes sere,</L>
<L N="8776">&THORN;of ilk world war als large als &thorn;is here;</L>
<L>And &thorn;at land es cald soveraynly</L>
<L>&THORN;e kyngdom of God alle-myghty,</L>
<L>&THORN;e whilk es made als a cet&eacute;,</L>
<L N="8780">Whare men salle many wonynge-stedes se,</L>
<L>&THORN;are alle &thorn;e haly men salle dwelle,</L>
<L>&THORN;arfor says Crist &thorn;us in &thorn;e gospelle:</L>
<L><I>Multi mansiones sunt,</I></L>
<L N="8784"><I>in domo patris mei.</I></L>
<L>He says "wonyng-stedes er many</L>
<L>In &thorn;e hows of my fader God alle-myghty."</L>
<L>Our Loverd, his fader hous calles</L>
<L N="8788">His kyngdom, &thorn;at tille alle his falles,</L>
<L>&THORN;e whilk es as a cit&eacute; bryght,</L>
<L>With alkyn ryches dubbed and dyght,</L>
<L>Als says Saint Iohan, Godes derlyng dere,</L>
<L N="8792">In &thorn;e apocalyps, on &thorn;is manere:
<PB REF="00000281.tif" N="237"></L>
<L><I>Vidi sanctam civitatem Ierusalem novam descendentem</I></L>
<L><I>de celo, paratam sicut sponsam viro suo ornatam.</I></L>
<L>"I saw," he says, "&thorn;e haly cet&eacute;</L>
<L N="8796">Of Ierusalem, alle new to se,</L>
<L>Comand doun fra heven bryght,</L>
<L>Of God alle-myghty rychely dyght,</L>
<L>Als bryde, made fayre tylle hir brydegome;"</L>
<L N="8800">&THORN;us says Saint Iohan he saw come.</L>
<L>&THORN;is cet&eacute; es for to understand,</L>
<L>Haly kyrk &thorn;at here es fyghtand</L>
<L>Ogayne &thorn;e develle and his myght,</L>
<L N="8804">&THORN;at it assayles, both day and nyght;</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;at fyght salle noght last ay,</L>
<L>It salle last no langer &thorn;an tylle domesday.</L>
<L>&THORN;an salle haly kyrk, of fyghtyng cees,</L>
<L N="8808">And be with God, in rest and pees;</L>
<L>Ffor it es bryde, and God es brydegome;</L>
<L>&THORN;an salle &thorn;ai both to-gyder come,</L>
<L>And in heven won ay to-gyder;</L>
<L N="8812">And alle &thorn;air childer salle &thorn;an com &thorn;ider.</L>
<L>&THORN;at to &thorn;am has bene bowsom and trewe;</L>
<L>And &thorn;at bi-takens &thorn;e cet&eacute; newe;</L>
<L>Ffor &thorn;an salle haly kyrk &thorn;at tyde,</L>
<L N="8816">In heven be new gloryfyde,</L>
<L>And won ay &thorn;are with God alle-myghty,</L>
<L>In ioy, and myrthe, and melody.</L>
<L>Bot yhit haly kyrk, &thorn;at es Godes bryde,</L>
<L N="8820">Bihoves be fyghtand, yhit here to abyde</L>
<L>&THORN;e comyng of Crist &thorn;at es hir brydegome,</L>
<L>&THORN;at ay es myghty for to over-come,</L>
<L>Ffor haly kyrk fyghtes for Godes ryght;</L>
<L N="8824">And God overcomes thurgh his myght.</L>
<L>On twa-wise may haly kyrk be tane,</L>
<L>And, at &thorn;e last, salle bath be in ane;</L>
<L>On a manere es cald haly kyrk fyghtand,</L>
<L N="8828">On ane other es haly kyrk over-comand.</L>
<L>&THORN;ir clerkes says als &thorn;e boke beres witnes,</L>
<L>&THORN;at haly kyrk, &thorn;at here fyghtand es,
<PB REF="00000282.tif" N="238"></L>
<L>Es noght els, bot a gaderyng</L>
<L N="8832">Of alle cristen men of lele lyfyng.</L>
<L>Haly kyrk over-comand es alle-swa</L>
<L>God with alle &thorn;e company of &thorn;a</L>
<L>&THORN;at dwelles with him, in his blys,</L>
<L N="8836">&THORN;e whilk he has hyght tylle alle his.</L>
<L>Under haly kyrk, &thorn;at here fyghtand es,</L>
<L>Er alle gud cristen men, mare and les.</L>
<L>Under haly kyrk &thorn;at es over-comand,</L>
<L N="8840">Er alle haly men in heven wonand.</L>
<L>Bot haly kyrk &thorn;at here fyghtes fast,</L>
<L>After &thorn;e day of dome at &thorn;e last,</L>
<L>In &thorn;e bryght cet&eacute; in heven salle won</L>
<L N="8844">Ever-mare, with hir spowse Godes Son;</L>
<L>Ffor &thorn;an salle &thorn;e noumbre fulle-fyld be</L>
<L>Of alle haly men in &thorn;at cet&eacute;,</L>
<L>Thurgh haly kyrk &thorn;at es Godes spowse;</L>
<L N="8848">And &thorn;at cet&eacute; Crist calles his Faders howse,</L>
<L>Ffor &thorn;are salle alle men &thorn;at er ryghtwise and haly,</L>
<L>Ever-mare dwelle in aungels company;</L>
<L>And ilk ane salle have a blysfulle wonyng,</L>
<L N="8852">And ioy parfyte, with-outen endyng.</L>
<L>&THORN;is cet&eacute; of heven &thorn;at es wyde and brade,</L>
<L>Na man wate properly how it es made,</L>
<L>Ne can, thurgh wrytt, ymagyn in thoght,</L>
<L N="8856">Of whatkyn matere it es wroght,</L>
<L>It es noght made of lyme ne stane,</L>
<L>Ne of tre; for of swilk matere has it nane,</L>
<L>Als &thorn;ir erthly cetese er made of here,</L>
<L N="8860">&THORN;at er made of corruptybelle matere;</L>
<L>Ffor na thyng falles to be in &thorn;at cet&eacute;,</L>
<L>&THORN;at corruptybelle or fayland may be.</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;e matere &thorn;are-of, als I trow,</L>
<L N="8864">Es of alle thing &thorn;at es of gret vertow.</L>
<L>&THORN;is cet&eacute; was never made with hand,</L>
<L>Bot thurgh &thorn;e myght and witt of God alle-weldand</L>
<L>&THORN;is cet&eacute; contenes alle heven-ryke</L>
<L N="8868">Bot nane wate properly to what it es lyke;
<PB REF="00000283.tif" N="239"></L>
<L>We fynd wryten, &thorn;at it es fayre and bryght,</L>
<L>Bot na man kan descryve it ryght;</L>
<L>Ffor swa wyse clerk was never of lyve,</L>
<L N="8872">&THORN;at &thorn;e fairnes of it couth properly descryve,</L>
<L>Bot alle-if I kan noght descryve &thorn;at stede,</L>
<L>Yhit wille I ymagyn, on myne awen hede,</L>
<L>Ffor to gyf it a descripcion;</L>
<L N="8876">Ffor I have &thorn;are-to, gret affeccyon;</L>
<L>And gret comforth and solace it es to me</L>
<L>To thynk and spek of &thorn;at fayr cet&eacute;;</L>
<L>&THORN;at travaille may greve me nathyng,</L>
<L N="8880">Ffor &thorn;are-in have I gret lykyng.</L>
<L>Ogayne ryght trowth nathing I do,</L>
<L>If I lyken &thorn;e cet&eacute; &thorn;at me langes to,</L>
<L>&THORN;e whilk men may lyken on som party,</L>
<L N="8884">Bath to bodily thing and gastly.</L>
<L>And for-&thorn;i &thorn;at alle thing &thorn;at es clere and bryght</L>
<L>Es mast lykand here tylle bodily syght,</L>
<L>&THORN;arfor I wille it lyken tille bodily thing.</L>
<L N="8888">&THORN;at es fayre to syght with gastly understandyng.</L>
<L>&THORN;e bryght cet&eacute; of heven es large and brade,</L>
<L>Of whilk may na comparyson be made</L>
<L>Tille na cet&eacute; &thorn;at on erth may stand,</L>
<L N="8892">Ffor it was never made with mans hand.</L>
<L>Bot yhit, als I ymagyn in my thoght,</L>
<L>I lyken it tylle a cet&eacute; &thorn;at war wroght</L>
<L>Of gold, of precyouse stanes sere,</L>
<L N="8896">Opon a mote<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. Lands. 348 reads 'mount'.</NOTE>, sett of berylle clere,</L>
<L>With walles, and wardes, and turrettes,</L>
<L>And entr&eacute;, and yhates, and garettes;</L>
<L>And alle &thorn;e walles war made, of &thorn;at cet&eacute;,</L>
<L N="8900">Of preceyouse stanes and ryche perr&eacute;;</L>
<L>And alle &thorn;e turrettes, of cristalle schene,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e wardes enamyld, and overgylt clene,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e yhates of charbucles suld falle,</L>
<L N="8904">And &thorn;e garettes aboven of rubys and curalle;
<PB REF="00000284.tif" N="240"></L>
<L>And at &thorn;at cet&eacute; had lanes and stretes wyde,</L>
<L>And fayr bygyngs on ilka syde,</L>
<L>Alle schynand als gold bryght burnyst</L>
<L N="8908">And with alkyn ryches replenyst;</L>
<L>And &thorn;at alle &thorn;e stretes of &thorn;e cet&eacute; and &thorn;e lanes</L>
<L>War even paved with precyouse stanes;</L>
<L>And &thorn;at &thorn;e brede and lenthe of &thorn;at cet&eacute;</L>
<L N="8912">War mare &thorn;an here es of any cuntr&eacute;;</L>
<L>And &thorn;at alle manere of melody</L>
<L>Of musyk and of mynstralsy,</L>
<L>&THORN;at moght be schewed with mowthe or hand,</L>
<L N="8916">War continuely &thorn;are-in sownand,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at ilk day, on sere manere suld falle,</L>
<L>Swa &thorn;at na man moght irk with-alle.</L>
<L>And &thorn;at ilka lane and ilka strete,</L>
<L N="8920">Of &thorn;is cet&eacute; war fulle of savours swete,</L>
<L>Of spycery and of alle other thyng,</L>
<L>Of whilk any swete savoure moght spryng;</L>
<L>And &thorn;at &thorn;ar war plent&eacute; of mete and drynk,</L>
<L N="8924">And of alle other delyces &thorn;at man may thynk;</L>
<L>And &thorn;at ilka citesayne &thorn;at wonned &thorn;are,</L>
<L>Had als mykelle bewt&eacute; or mare,</L>
<L>Als Absolon, &thorn;at swa fayre was,</L>
<L N="8928">Whase bewt&eacute; moght bi skylle pas</L>
<L>&THORN;e bewt&eacute; of alle manere of men erthly,</L>
<L>Swa clene he was in lym and body;</L>
<L>And &thorn;are-with als mykelle strenthe had omang</L>
<L N="8932">Als Sampson had, &thorn;at was so strang,</L>
<L>&THORN;at a thowsand men armed clene</L>
<L>He over-come and felled doune alle bi-dene;</L>
<L>And &thorn;at ilkane war als swyft to pas</L>
<L N="8936">And to ryn, als Assahelle of fote was,</L>
<L>And swa swyft was to ryn and ga,</L>
<L>&THORN;at thurgh rase wald turne bath buk and ra;</L>
<L>And &thorn;at ilkane had &thorn;are-with als mykelle lykyng</L>
<L N="8940">And als mykelle &thorn;air wille in alle thing,</L>
<L>Als Salamon had, &thorn;at als God vowched save</L>
<L>&THORN;at had alle thyng &thorn;at he wald have:
<PB REF="00000285.tif" N="241"></L>
<L>And &thorn;at ilkane &thorn;ar-with, had als mykelle fredome</L>
<L N="8944">Als August had &thorn;at was emparour of Rome,</L>
<L>Tylle whame alle landes of &thorn;e world obout</L>
<L>Served, and tille him war underlout;</L>
<L>And &thorn;at ilkane had with-alle als continuele hele</L>
<L N="8948">Als Moyses had &thorn;at was swa lele,</L>
<L>&THORN;at God wald never with yvelle dere him,</L>
<L>Bot anely &thorn;at he made his eghen dym;</L>
<L>And &thorn;at &thorn;are-with, if possible ware,</L>
<L N="8952">Ilkane moght als lang be lyfand &thorn;are,</L>
<L>Als Matussale namely dyd here,</L>
<L>&THORN;at lyfed nere a thowsand yhere;</L>
<L>And &thorn;at ilk ane moght als mykelle wisdom weld,</L>
<L N="8956">Als Salamon had, &thorn;at men swa wise held,</L>
<L>&THORN;at thurgh his wisdom had knawyng</L>
<L>Of alle thing and understanding;</L>
<L>And &thorn;at ilk ane &thorn;are-with lufed als wele or mare,</L>
<L N="8960">And als gud frende ay tylle other ware,</L>
<L>Als David tylle Ionathas was kyd,</L>
<L>Wham he lufed als he his awen saule dyd;</L>
<L>And &thorn;at ilk ane with &thorn;at honourd ware</L>
<L N="8964">Of alle &thorn;e other &thorn;at wond &thorn;are,</L>
<L>Als Ioseph was of &thorn;e Egypciens ryght,</L>
<L>Wham &thorn;ai lowted als loverd of gret myght;</L>
<L>And &thorn;are-with &thorn;at ilk ane war in alle thing</L>
<L N="8968">Als mykelle als was Alexander the gret kyng</L>
<L>&THORN;at conquerd Affryk, Europe and Asy,</L>
<L>&THORN;at contened alle &thorn;e world halely;</L>
<L>And &thorn;at ilkane acorded with other in anehede,</L>
<L N="8972">Als Lisyas with Sampson dyd in dede,</L>
<L>Of whilk nouther wald nathing do,</L>
<L>Bot als ayther of &thorn;am assented &thorn;are-to;</L>
<L>And with alle &thorn;is, &thorn;at ilkane als syker ware</L>
<L N="8976">Of &thorn;air dwellyng, to won lang &thorn;are,</L>
<L>Als Ennoc and Hely, on &thorn;e same wyse,</L>
<L>&THORN;at er syker of &thorn;air dwellyng in paradyse,</L>
<L>Ffra &thorn;e tyme &thorn;at &thorn;ai war &thorn;ider ravyst,</L>
<L N="8980">And salle be untylle &thorn;e comyng of Anticrist;
<PB REF="00000286.tif" N="242"></L>
<L>And over alle &thorn;is, &thorn;at ilkane als mykelle joy had</L>
<L>Als he suld have &thorn;at war lad</L>
<L>Tylle &thorn;e galows, and sodainly in &thorn;e gate</L>
<L N="8984">War tane and putted tille a kynges state;</L>
<L>And, &thorn;are-with, &thorn;an<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;at?</NOTE> tylle ilk ane suld falle</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;e ioyes &thorn;ai moght have alle.</L>
<L>He &thorn;at alle &thorn;es had, als bifore wryten es,</L>
<L N="8988">Suld pass alle &thorn;e world in worthines:</L>
<L>What man, thurgh witt, couth telle ioy mare</L>
<L>In &thorn;is world to weld, &thorn;an alle &thorn;is ware?</L>
<L>Ffor wha-swa had alle &thorn;ese, withouten dout,</L>
<L N="8992">Had here ioyinoghe, both with-in and without</L>
<L>With alkyn delyces &thorn;at he moght have here,</L>
<L>Specialy in alle his wittes sere,</L>
<L>&THORN;at es to say, in syght and hereyng,</L>
<L N="8996">And in smellyng, tastyng and feleyng;</L>
<L>Bot yhit alle &thorn;ir blysses &thorn;at yhe herd me neven</L>
<L>War als noght, als to regard to &thorn;e blys of heven;</L>
<L>Ffor als mykelle difference, or mare, suld be</L>
<L N="9000">Bitwene heven and swilk a cet&eacute;,</L>
<L>Als es bitwene a kynges palays</L>
<L>And a swynsty &thorn;at es lytelle to prays,</L>
<L>And na mare comparyson may be made</L>
<L N="9004">Bitwene &thorn;e cit&eacute; of heven, wyde and brade,</L>
<L>And swilk a cet&eacute; made of gold and perr&eacute;,</L>
<L>&THORN;an bitwene alle &thorn;e world and a faulde may be;</L>
<L>Alle-swa alle ryches &thorn;at may here be sene</L>
<L N="9008">War noght bot als muk &thorn;at es unclene,</L>
<L>To regard of &thorn;e precyouse rychesce</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e cet&eacute; of heven &thorn;at na man may gesce.</L>
<L>And alle &thorn;e melodyse of &thorn;e world sere,</L>
<L N="9012">War noght bot als sorow to here,</L>
<L>To regard of &thorn;e blyssfulle melody</L>
<L>&THORN;at in &thorn;e cet&eacute; of heven es ay redy.</L>
<L>And alle swete savours &thorn;at men may fele,</L>
<L N="9016">Of alkyn thing &thorn;at here savours wele,</L>
<L>War noght bot als stynk to regard of &thorn;at flayre</L>
<L>&THORN;at es in &thorn;e cet&eacute; of heven swa fayre;
<PB REF="00000287.tif" N="243"></L>
<L>And alle &thorn;e worschepe &thorn;at here may be,</L>
<L N="9020">War noght bot als schendschepe to se,</L>
<L>To regard of &thorn;e gret worschepe</L>
<L>Of whilk men salle in heven tak kepe.</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;e fairnes &thorn;at Absolon had in syght,</L>
<L N="9024">War noght bot laythede<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. Lansd. 348 reads 'fil&thorn;e'.</NOTE> in heven bryght.</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;e strenthe of Sampson &thorn;at was pereles,</L>
<L>War noght tald &thorn;are bot wayknes.</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;e delyces &thorn;at had Salomon &thorn;e kyng,</L>
<L N="9028">War noght in heven bot myslykyng.</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;e swyftnes of Assahel &thorn;at had he,</L>
<L>War noght &thorn;are bot slawnes to se.</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;e fredom &thorn;at August had whilom,</L>
<L N="9032">War noght tald &thorn;are bot thraldom.</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;e hele &thorn;at here had Moyses</L>
<L>War noght tald &thorn;are bot als seknes.</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;e eld &thorn;at Matussale had here,</L>
<L N="9036">War les &thorn;are &thorn;an &thorn;e lest day of &thorn;e yhere.</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;e wisdom &thorn;at Salomon had redy</L>
<L>War noght tald &thorn;are bot als foly.</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;e luf &thorn;at David Ionathas lufed,</L>
<L N="9040">War noght &thorn;are bot als hatereden proved.</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;e honoure &thorn;at &thorn;e Egypciens Ioseph dyd,</L>
<L>War noght in heven bot schendschip kyd.</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;e myght &thorn;at Alexander had aywhare,</L>
<L N="9044">War noght tald bot wayknes &thorn;are.</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;e acord &thorn;at Lisyas had in his lyfe</L>
<L>With Sampson, war &thorn;ar bot als strife.</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;e sykernes &thorn;at had Ennoc and Ely</L>
<L N="9048">Of &thorn;air dwellyng in paradyse, namly,</L>
<L>War noght bot als unsykernes</L>
<L>Of wonyng in heven &thorn;at es endles.</L>
<L>&THORN;us may I lyken, als I ymagyn,</L>
<L N="9052">&THORN;e cet&eacute; of heven and &thorn;e blys &thorn;are-in,</L>
<L>Tylle a cet&eacute; of gold and of precyouse stanes sere</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;e cet&eacute; of heven es mare bryght and clere,
<PB REF="00000288.tif" N="244"></L>
<L>And es sett on swa heghe a hylle,</L>
<L N="9056">&THORN;at na synfulle man may wyn &thorn;ar-tylle;</L>
<L>&THORN;e whilk hylle I lyken tylle berylle clene,</L>
<L>&THORN;at es clerer &thorn;an any &thorn;at here es sene;</L>
<L>&THORN;at hille es noght els bi understandyng,</L>
<L N="9060">Bot haly thoght and brynand yhernyng,</L>
<L>&THORN;at haly men had here to &thorn;at stede,</L>
<L>Whils &thorn;ai lyfed, bi-for &thorn;air dede;</L>
<L>Ffor God wille &thorn;at &thorn;ai als heghe up-pas,</L>
<L N="9064">Als &thorn;air thoght and yhernyng upward was.</L>
<L>Yhit I lyken, als I ymagyn in thoght,</L>
<L>&THORN;e walles of heven tylle walles &thorn;at war wroght</L>
<L>Of alle manere of precyouse stanes sere,</L>
<L N="9068">Cymented with gold fulle bryght and clere;</L>
<L>And swa bryght gold ne swa clene,</L>
<L>Was never nane in &thorn;is world sene,</L>
<L>Ne swa ryche stanes, ne swa precyouse,</L>
<L N="9072">Als obout heven er, ne swa vertuouse.</L>
<L>&THORN;e precyouse stanes, gastly may be</L>
<L>Gud werkes, and &thorn;e gold charyt&eacute;,</L>
<L>&THORN;at obout &thorn;ase in heven salle schine clere,</L>
<L N="9076">&THORN;at dose gud werkes in charyt&eacute; here.</L>
<L>&THORN;e turrettes of heven, gret and smalle,</L>
<L>I lyken tylle turrettes of clere crystalle;</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;e turrettes of heven er mare clere shynand</L>
<L N="9080">&THORN;an ever was cristalle in any land.</L>
<L>&THORN;a turrettes, gastly, sere honours may be,</L>
<L>&THORN;at gud men, in heven, salle fele and se.</L>
<L>&THORN;e wardes of &thorn;e cet&eacute; of heven bryght</L>
<L N="9084">I lyken tylle wardes &thorn;at war stal worthly dyght</L>
<L>And clenly wroght and craftily tayled</L>
<L>Of clene sylver and gold and enamayld.</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;a wardes of &thorn;e cet&eacute; of heven,</L>
<L N="9088">Er mare crafty and strang &thorn;am any kan neven,</L>
<L>Bot gastly to speke, &thorn;a wardes swa dyght,</L>
<L>May be tald strenthe, and power, and myght,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;as salle have &thorn;at in heven salle dwelle,</L>
<L N="9092">Als yhe moght here me bifore telle.
<PB REF="00000289.tif" N="245"></L>
<L>&THORN;e yhates I lyken of heven swa brade,</L>
<L>Tylle yhates &thorn;at war of charbukelle stanes made</L>
<L>Bot swa clere charbukelle was never sene,</L>
<L N="9096">Als &thorn;a yhates of heven er ne swa clene;</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;a yhates, gastly to speke, er mekenes</L>
<L>And fredom of ryght fayth and bowsomnes,</L>
<L>&THORN;at gyfes way and entr&eacute; tylle men boghsom,</L>
<L N="9100">Intylle &thorn;e cet&eacute; of heven for to com.</L>
<L>&THORN;e garettes oboven &thorn;e yhates bryght</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e cet&eacute; of heven, I lyken &thorn;us ryght,</L>
<L>Tylle &thorn;e garettes of a cet&eacute; of gold,</L>
<L N="9104">&THORN;at wroght war, als I before told,</L>
<L>Of fyne curalle and rych rubys,</L>
<L>And of other stanes of gret prys,</L>
<L>With fyne gold wyre alle obout frett,</L>
<L N="9108">And bryght besandes burnyst omang sett.</L>
<L>&THORN;e garettes of heven, gastly, may be</L>
<L>Heghe state, and lordschip, and dignit&eacute;;</L>
<L>Ffor alle &thorn;at salle won in &thorn;at cet&eacute; &thorn;are,</L>
<L N="9112">Salle bere heghe state &thorn;are-in ever-mare.</L>
<L>&THORN;e lanes alle-swa and &thorn;e stretes alle,</L>
<L>&THORN;at in &thorn;e cet&eacute; of heven may falle,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e wonyng-stedes &thorn;at er &thorn;ar-in,</L>
<L N="9116">I lyken here, after I ymagyn,</L>
<L>Tylle &thorn;e lanes and stretes, less and mare,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e cet&eacute; of gold &thorn;at I spak of are,</L>
<L>With &thorn;e bygynges on ilk syde standand,</L>
<L N="9120">&THORN;at of fyne gold war made, bryght schynand;</L>
<L>Bot in na cet&eacute; &thorn;at men may neven,</L>
<L>Er stedes and lanes swa bryght als in heven;</L>
<L>Ne swa bryght wonyng-stedes als er &thorn;ar-in,</L>
<L N="9124">Can na man, thurgh wytt, ymagyn,</L>
<L>&THORN;e whilk salle schyne, with-in and with-out,</L>
<L>And on ilka syde alle obout,</L>
<L>Whare alle ryghtwyse men salle won at ees,</L>
<L N="9128">In ioyfulle quyete, and rest, and pese;</L>
<L>And &thorn;arfor haly kyrk, &thorn;at oft prays</L>
<L>Ffor &thorn;e saules in purgatory, &thorn;us says:
<PB REF="00000290.tif" N="246"></L>
<L><I>Tuam Deus deposcimus pietatem, ut eis tribue|</I></L>
<L N="9132"><I>re digneris lucidas et quietas mansiones.</I></L>
<L>"Loverd God, we ask &thorn;i pet&eacute;,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou vouche safe, als we pray &thorn;e,</L>
<L>To gyf &thorn;am wonyng stedes bryght</L>
<L N="9136">And restfulle", &thorn;at nede has of rest and lyght.</L>
<L>Na bodily eghe moght never here se</L>
<L>A poynt of swilk bryghtnes, als in heven salle be.</L>
<L>Ilka lane in heven and ilka strete</L>
<L N="9140">Most schyne bryght, bi skylle, for &thorn;ar salle mete</L>
<L>Aungels and men bryghter schynand,</L>
<L>&THORN;an ever schane &thorn;e son in any land;</L>
<L>Ffor &thorn;e body ofilk man salle schyne so bryght</L>
<L N="9144">&THORN;at tylle alle a contr&eacute;, ane moghtgyf lyght;</L>
<L>And ilka hare &thorn;are, on &thorn;air hede,</L>
<L>And on &thorn;air body, on ilka stede,</L>
<L>Salle be als bryght als es &thorn;e son,</L>
<L N="9148">&THORN;at we may se here whare we won,</L>
<L>Fulle bryght schynand oboven us,</L>
<L>And &thorn;arfor says &thorn;e boke &thorn;us:</L>
<L><I>Fulgebunt iusti sicut sol.</I></L>
<L N="9152">"&THORN;e ryghtwis men salle schyne als &thorn;e son,"</L>
<L>In heven whare &thorn;ai salle ever-mare won.</L>
<L>Now sen a ryghtwis man salle schyne als bright</L>
<L>Als &thorn;e son dose, &thorn;an mon he gyf lyght</L>
<L N="9156">Als fer als &thorn;e son dose and ferrer,</L>
<L>Fforwhi he salle &thorn;an be wele bryghter.</L>
<L>And yhit salle alle &thorn;at gret bryghtnes,</L>
<L>&THORN;at ryghtwis men salle have &thorn;are be les</L>
<L N="9160">&THORN;an &thorn;e bryghtnes of God alle-myghty,</L>
<L>Als salle be knawen &thorn;are openly,</L>
<L>Ryght als &thorn;e sternes here, whare we won,</L>
<L>Semes als to &thorn;e bryghtnes of &thorn;e son;</L>
<L N="9164">Ffor we salle be &thorn;are als sternes in bryghtnes,</L>
<L>And God bryghtest als son of ryghtwisnes.</L>
<L>Ilka lane and strete &thorn;at in heven may be,</L>
<L>Es lenger &thorn;an here es any contr&eacute;,
<PB REF="00000291.tif" N="247"></L>
<L N="9168">Ffor &thorn;e roume and &thorn;e space &thorn;at es contende</L>
<L>In &thorn;e cet&eacute; of heven has nane ende.</L>
<L>&THORN;a stretes and lanes, gastly to telle,</L>
<L>Er alle haly men &thorn;at &thorn;are salle dwelle;</L>
<L N="9172">And &thorn;air wonyngstedes may be &thorn;e medes,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ai salle have for &thorn;air gud dedes.</L>
<L>In &thorn;at cet&eacute; salle be mare rychesce</L>
<L>&THORN;an alle &thorn;e men of &thorn;e world may gesce;</L>
<L N="9176">Bot &thorn;ase ryches gastly to understand,</L>
<L>Er sere blysses and delyces ay lastand,</L>
<L>&THORN;e whilk alle &thorn;as, &thorn;at tylle heven salle wende,</L>
<L>Salle fele and se &thorn;are with-outen ende.</L>
<L N="9180">&THORN;e pament of heven may lykened be,</L>
<L>Tille a pament of precyouse stanes and perr&eacute;;</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;e pament of heven salle schyne mar clere</L>
<L>&THORN;an ever schane gold or precyouse stanes here;</L>
<L N="9184">And &thorn;at pament es sett swa fast,</L>
<L>&THORN;at it salle never fayle bot ay last,</L>
<L>In whilk may na crevyce be sene,</L>
<L>It es swa hale, and even, and clene.</L>
<L N="9188">&THORN;is pament of heven als of perr&eacute;,</L>
<L>Gastly to understand may be</L>
<L>Parfyte luf and lyfe endeles,</L>
<L>With pese, and rest and sykernes,</L>
<L N="9192">&THORN;at alle salle have &thorn;at salle won &thorn;are,</L>
<L>And &thorn;is pament salle last ever-mare.</L>
<L>&THORN;us may a man &thorn;at kan and wille,</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;e cet&eacute; of heven lyken bi skylle,</L>
<L N="9196">Tylle bodily thing &thorn;at es fayre and bryght,</L>
<L>And mast delytabelle here to syght,</L>
<L>And to precyouse stanes of vertow,</L>
<L>And to sylver and gold and thing of valow,</L>
<L N="9200">&THORN;at men may here bodily se,</L>
<L>Bot swilk thinges may nane in heven be.</L>
<L>Of verray ryches, gret plent&eacute; es &thorn;are,</L>
<L>&THORN;at er a hundreth thowsand-fald mare</L>
<L N="9204">&THORN;an alle &thorn;e ryches of &thorn;e world here,</L>
<L>&THORN;at ever was sene, fer or nere,
<PB REF="00000292.tif" N="248"></L>
<L>&THORN;at fayles and passes oway;</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;e rychesce of heven salle last ay,</L>
<L N="9208">&THORN;at er alle thing, als God vouches save,</L>
<L>&THORN;at men in heven yhernes to have.</L>
<L>Oboven &thorn;e cet&eacute; of heven salle noght be sene,</L>
<L>Bot bright bemes anly, als I wene,</L>
<L N="9212">&THORN;at sal schyne fra Goddes awen face,</L>
<L>And sprede obout and over &thorn;at place.</L>
<L>His bright face sal alle &thorn;as se,</L>
<L>&THORN;at sal duelle in &thorn;at blisful cit&eacute;;</L>
<L N="9216">And &thorn;at syght es &thorn;e mast ioy of heven,</L>
<L>Als men mught here me byfor neven.</L>
<L>And alle-if &thorn;at cit&eacute; be large and wyde,</L>
<L>Men salle hym se, until &thorn;e ferrest syde,</L>
<L N="9220">And als wele &thorn;as &thorn;at sal be fra hym fer,</L>
<L>Als &thorn;as &thorn;at sal &thorn;ar til hym be nerrer;</L>
<L>For als men of fer landes may haf sight</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e son, &thorn;at we se here schyne bright,</L>
<L N="9224">And als &thorn;e same son &thorn;at shynes byyhond &thorn;e se</L>
<L>Shewes it here, and in ilka cuntr&eacute;</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;e day, aftir &thorn;e ryght course es,</L>
<L>Bot when cloudes fra us hydes hir<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. Harl. 4196 reads 'his'.</NOTE> brightnes;</L>
<L N="9228">Right swa &thorn;e face of God alle-myghty,</L>
<L>Sal be shewed in heven appertely,</L>
<L>Tille alle &thorn;e men &thorn;at &thorn;ider sal wende,</L>
<L>&THORN;ogh som suld duelle at &thorn;e ferrest ende.</L>
<L N="9232">Bot ilk man, als he lufes God here,</L>
<L>Sal won &thorn;ar, som fer and som nere,</L>
<L>For som lufes God here mar &thorn;an sum,</L>
<L>And som lufes hym les &thorn;at til heven sal com</L>
<L N="9236">Alle &thorn;as &thorn;at God here lufes best,</L>
<L>When &thorn;ai com &thorn;ar sal be hym nerrest,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e nerrer &thorn;at &thorn;ai sal hym be,</L>
<L>&THORN;e verreylyer &thorn;ai sal hym se;</L>
<L N="9240">And &thorn;e mare verraly &thorn;ai se his face,</L>
<L>&THORN;e mare sal be &thorn;air ioy and solace.
<PB REF="00000293.tif" N="249"></L>
<L>Bot &thorn;a &thorn;at here lufs hym les,</L>
<L>&THORN;ai sal won &thorn;ar, aftir &thorn;air luf es;</L>
<L N="9244">Bot ilk man sal se hym in his degr&eacute;,</L>
<L>In what syde of heven swa he sal be.</L>
<L>Here haf yhe herd of many fayre sight,</L>
<L>&THORN;at ay salle be sene in heven bright;</L>
<L N="9248">Ful glade and ioyful alle &thorn;as may be,</L>
<L>&THORN;at swilk fayre sightes, ay, &thorn;ar sal se,</L>
<L>And of mykel ioy may &thorn;ai ay telle</L>
<L>&THORN;at in &thorn;at cit&eacute; of heven sal ay duelle.</L>
<L N="9252">Alswa ilkan sal haf in &thorn;air heryng,</L>
<L>Grete ioy in heven and grete lykyng,</L>
<L>For &thorn;ai sal here &thorn;ar aungel sang,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e haly men sal ay syng omang,</L>
<L N="9256">With delitabel voyces and clere;</L>
<L>And, with &thorn;at, &thorn;ai sal ay here</L>
<L>Alle other manere of melody,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e delytable noys of mynstralsy,</L>
<L N="9260">And of alkyn swet tones of musyke,</L>
<L>&THORN;at til any mans hert mught like;</L>
<L>And of alkyn noyse &thorn;at swete mught be,</L>
<L>Ilkan sal here in &thorn;at cit&eacute;,</L>
<L N="9264">With-outen instrumentes ryngand,</L>
<L>And with-outen movyng of mouth or hand,</L>
<L>And with-outen any travayle,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at sal never mar cese ne fayle.</L>
<L N="9268">Swilk melody, als &thorn;ar sal be &thorn;an,</L>
<L>In &thorn;is werld herd never nan erthely man,</L>
<L>For swa swete sal be &thorn;at noyse and shille</L>
<L>And swa delitabel and swa sutille,</L>
<L N="9272">&THORN;at alle &thorn;e melody of &thorn;is werld here,</L>
<L>&THORN;at ever has bene herd, fer and nere,</L>
<L>War noght bot als sorowe and care</L>
<L>Als to &thorn;e lest poynt of melody &thorn;are.</L>
<L N="9276">Omang &thorn;am alswa sal be swete savour,</L>
<L>Swa swete com never of herbe ne flour,</L>
<L>When &thorn;ai war in seson mast,</L>
<L>Or war mast of vertu for to tast;
<PB REF="00000294.tif" N="250"></L>
<L N="9280">Ne of spicery mught never spryng,</L>
<L>Ne yhit of nan othir thyng,</L>
<L>&THORN;at thurgh vertu of kynde suld savour wele</L>
<L>Swa swete savour als &thorn;ai sal fele;</L>
<L N="9284">For na hert may thynk, ne tung telle,</L>
<L>How swete sal ilkan til other smelle;</L>
<L>&THORN;at savour sal be ful plenteuouse,</L>
<L>And swa swete and swa delicious,</L>
<L N="9288">&THORN;at alkyn spicery &thorn;at men may fele,</L>
<L>And of alle othir thyng &thorn;at here savours wele,</L>
<L>War noght bot als thyng &thorn;at stynked sour,</L>
<L>Als to regarde of &thorn;at delycious savour.</L>
<L N="9292">&THORN;an sal &thorn;at savour &thorn;at es swa swete,</L>
<L>Be ioy til &thorn;am, ay when &thorn;ai samen mete,</L>
<L>Alswa ilkan &thorn;at sal won &thorn;ar,</L>
<L>Sal syng with angels, als I sayd ar,</L>
<L N="9296">In swilk tones &thorn;at sal be swete to here,</L>
<L>With ful delitabel voyces and clere;</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;ai sal love God ay in &thorn;air sang,</L>
<L>And thank hym of his mercy ay omang;</L>
<L N="9300">And ilkan of &thorn;at blisful company</L>
<L>Sal speke with othir &thorn;ar ful swetely,</L>
<L>With laghyng and with lufly sembland,</L>
<L>And say "weles us &thorn;at here er wonnand",</L>
<L N="9304">And thank God omang &thorn;at &thorn;am gun wysse</L>
<L>Til mekenes, &thorn;at &thorn;am led til &thorn;at blysse</L>
<L>With anger &thorn;at &thorn;ai had in &thorn;air lyf days,</L>
<L>&THORN;an may &thorn;ai say &thorn;us als David says:</L>
<L N="9308"><I>Letati sumus pro diebus quibus</I></L>
<L><I>nos humiliasti, annis quibus</I></L>
<L><I>vidimus mala.</I></L>
<L>"Loverd ful glad for &thorn;e days er we,</L>
<L N="9312">In whilk &thorn;ou made us lawe to be,</L>
<L>In &thorn;e yheres in whilk we saw illes."</L>
<L>&THORN;us may &thorn;ai syng and say for sere skilles.</L>
<L>&THORN;an sal &thorn;air sang and &thorn;air spekyng,</L>
<L N="9316">Be til &thorn;am gret ioy and lykyng;
<PB REF="00000295.tif" N="251"></L>
<L>Alswa &thorn;ai sal fele worshepes grete,</L>
<L>For ilkan sal be sette in a ryche sete,</L>
<L>And, als kynges and qwenes corouned be</L>
<L N="9320">With corouns dight with ryche perr&eacute;,</L>
<L>And with stanes of vertu, precyouse to prays,</L>
<L>Als David til God thus spekes and says:</L>
<L><I>Posuisti Domine super caput eius</I></L>
<L N="9324"><I>coronam de lapide precioso.</I></L>
<L>"Loverd on hys heved &thorn;ou sette ryght,</L>
<L>A coroune of preciouse stanes dight;"</L>
<L>Bot swa fayre coroune was never sene</L>
<L N="9328">In &thorn;is world, on kynges heved ne qwene.</L>
<L>&THORN;is coroune es &thorn;e coroune of blys,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e stane es ioy &thorn;at &thorn;ai sal never mys.</L>
<L>&THORN;is worshepe &thorn;at &thorn;ai sal fele, sal pas</L>
<L N="9332">Alle &thorn;e worshepes &thorn;at ever here was,</L>
<L>Of whilk &thorn;ai sal &thorn;ar mar ioy have,</L>
<L>&THORN;an any man can yherne or crave.</L>
<L>&THORN;us sal &thorn;ai have in &thorn;air wittes fyfe</L>
<L N="9336">Parfite ioy with endeles lyfe,</L>
<L>In &thorn;e heghe blisful cit&eacute; of heven,</L>
<L>Whar sere ioyes er ma &thorn;an tung can neven;</L>
<L>For &thorn;ai sal many hundreth thowsand se</L>
<L N="9340">Of men and wemen in &thorn;at cit&eacute;,</L>
<L>&THORN;at many sere ioyes &thorn;ar sal haf,</L>
<L>Als &thorn;ai er worthy and God vouches saf.</L>
<L>And alle &thorn;e ioyes &thorn;at &thorn;ai alle sal se,</L>
<L N="9344">Sal be ioyes til ilka man &thorn;at &thorn;ar sal be,</L>
<L>With-outen his awen ioyes, les and mare,</L>
<L>&THORN;at til hym-self sal be appropried &thorn;are;</L>
<L>For &thorn;e sight of ilk ioy &thorn;at &thorn;ai sal se &thorn;an,</L>
<L N="9348">Sal be ioy &thorn;ar til ilka man;</L>
<L>For other mens ioyes tham sal like als wele,</L>
<L>Als &thorn;ai sal &thorn;air awen &thorn;at &thorn;ai sal fele;</L>
<L>&THORN;an sal a man haf ma ioyes in heven</L>
<L N="9352">&THORN;an any tung couthe telle or neven;</L>
<L>For ilk man sal haf special ioy and mede,</L>
<L>For ilk gude thoght and ilk gude dede,
<PB REF="00000296.tif" N="252"></L>
<L>&THORN;at he ever thoght or wroght open or priv&eacute;.</L>
<L N="9356">&THORN;an may never &thorn;air ioys noumbred be,</L>
<L>&THORN;at ilk man in heven when &thorn;ai com &thorn;ider</L>
<L>Sal in body and saule haf alle togider,</L>
<L>And never mare of na ioy fele irkyng,</L>
<L N="9360">For &thorn;ai sal ay be new als at &thorn;e bigynning,</L>
<L>Of whilk &thorn;e leste ioy &thorn;ar to fele and se,</L>
<L>Sal be mar &thorn;an alle &thorn;e ioyes of the werld may be</L>
<L>&THORN;ai sal be fed &thorn;ar and cled wele,</L>
<L N="9364">With ioy of sight &thorn;at &thorn;ai sal fele,</L>
<L>&THORN;ai sal wirk &thorn;ar nan othir thyng,</L>
<L>Bot love ay God with-outen irkyng,</L>
<L>Als a versifiour says in a verse &thorn;arby,</L>
<L N="9368">&THORN;e whilk es made in metre &thorn;us schortly:</L>
<L><I>Visio sit victus, opus est</I></L>
<L><I>laus, lumen amictus.</I></L>
<L>"With &thorn;e sight of God &thorn;ai sal be fed,</L>
<L N="9372">And with brightnes of light &thorn;ai sal be cled,</L>
<L>And &thorn;air werk sal be ay lovyng,"</L>
<L>In whilk &thorn;ai sal haf gret likyng.</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;air mast ioy in heven sal be</L>
<L N="9376">&THORN;e blisful sight of &thorn;e trinit&eacute;,</L>
<L>&THORN;e whilk &thorn;ai sal se ever-mar;</L>
<L>And &thorn;at ioy sal pas alle othir &thorn;ar,</L>
<L>For ay whilles &thorn;ai &thorn;at sight sal se,</L>
<L N="9380">Of alle ioyes &thorn;ai sal fulfilled be;</L>
<L>And if &thorn;ai suld &thorn;at syght mysse,</L>
<L>&THORN;ai myght noght &thorn;an haf parfite blis.</L>
<L>For if a man war pyned in helle,</L>
<L N="9384">With ma payns &thorn;an tung may telle,</L>
<L>And he of Goddes face mught se oght,</L>
<L>Alle his payns suld &thorn;an gryefe hym noght.</L>
<L>Now haf I redde here how men sal hafe</L>
<L N="9388">Parfite ioy in heven &thorn;at sal be safe;</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;e dampned men &thorn;ar ogayne</L>
<L>Sal haf ful sorowe and parfite payne,</L>
<L>With-outen ende for &thorn;air wikked lyfe,</L>
<L N="9392">For &thorn;ai sal in alle &thorn;air wittes fyve,
<PB REF="00000297.tif" N="253"></L>
<L>Be turmented on sere manere,</L>
<L>With grysely payns, many and sere,</L>
<L>&THORN;at es to say, in syght and heryng,</L>
<L N="9396">In smellyng, tastyng, and felyng.</L>
<L>First &thorn;ai sal in helle about &thorn;am se</L>
<L>Mare sorow &thorn;an ever in &thorn;is werld mught be,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e sorow &thorn;at &thorn;ai sal se &thorn;ar,</L>
<L N="9400">Sal be strang payne til &thorn;am ever-mare.</L>
<L>&THORN;air wonyng in helle, als says &thorn;e buke,</L>
<L>&THORN;ai sal se ful of fire and of smoke,</L>
<L>And ful grysely, and myrk, and dym,</L>
<L N="9404">And about &thorn;am devels ful grym,</L>
<L>&THORN;at with sere payns sal payne &thorn;am ay,</L>
<L>Als men mught here me byfor say:</L>
<L>And alle-&thorn;ogh &thorn;ai in helle want light,</L>
<L N="9408">Yhit sal pai of alle payns haf sight,</L>
<L>Thurgh &thorn;e sparkes of fyr &thorn;ar, als says Saynt Austyn</L>
<L>Noght til &thorn;air comfort bot til &thorn;air pyne;</L>
<L>Yhit mare sorow &thorn;am sal bytyde,</L>
<L N="9412">&THORN;ai sal here in helle, on ilka syde,</L>
<L>Ful hydus noyse and duleful dyn</L>
<L>Of devels and of synful men &thorn;ar-yn:</L>
<L>&THORN;ai sal here devels &thorn;ar, rare ful hydusly,</L>
<L N="9416">And &thorn;e synful men goule and cry;</L>
<L>&THORN;ai sal &thorn;ar, in smellyng, fele mare stynk,</L>
<L>&THORN;an hert may here ymagyn or thynk,</L>
<L>Of brynnand brunstan and of pyk,</L>
<L N="9420">And of alkyn othir thyng &thorn;at es wyk.</L>
<L>&THORN;at stynk, als yhe sal understand wele,</L>
<L>Sal be strang payne til &thorn;am to fele;</L>
<L>Al-swa &thorn;ai sal ilkan other wery,</L>
<L N="9424">And myssay and sclaundre God allemyghty,</L>
<L>&THORN;ai sal ay stryfe and be at debate,</L>
<L>And ilkan other sal despice and hate.</L>
<L>Omang &thorn;am sal never be pees,</L>
<L N="9428">Bot hatreden and stryfe &thorn;at never sal cees.</L>
<L>&THORN;air throtes sal ay be filled omang,</L>
<L>Of alle thyng &thorn;at es bitter and strang,
<PB REF="00000298.tif" N="254"></L>
<L>Of lowe and reke with stormes melled,</L>
<L N="9432">Of pyk and brunstane togyder welled,</L>
<L>Of molten bras and lede with-alle,</L>
<L>And of other welland metalle:</L>
<L>&THORN;is sal be strang payne til &thorn;am to last,</L>
<L N="9436">Omang alle othir paynes, lest and mast,</L>
<L>With stryf &thorn;at sal be omang &thorn;am &thorn;an,</L>
<L>When ilkan sal other wery and ban;</L>
<L>Al-swa &thorn;ai sal fele, als I byfor talde,</L>
<L N="9440">Outrageus hete and outrageouse calde,</L>
<L>For now &thorn;ai sal frese in yse, and now in fire bryn</L>
<L>And be gnawen with-outen and with-in;</L>
<L>Within, als yhe sal understand,</L>
<L N="9444">With wormes of conscience ay bytand;</L>
<L>With-outen, with dragons felle and kene,</L>
<L>Swa hidus was never here nane sene,</L>
<L>With neddirs and tades and othir vermyn,</L>
<L N="9448">And with many hydus bestes of ravyn,</L>
<L>Als wode wolfes, lyons and beres felle,</L>
<L>&THORN;at sal noght be elles, bot devels of helle,</L>
<L>In liknes of hydus bestes and vermyne,</L>
<L N="9452">&THORN;at sal &thorn;am gnaw without, to eke &thorn;air pyne,</L>
<L>Als in &thorn;e sext part of &thorn;is boke es wryten.</L>
<L>&THORN;us sal &thorn;e synful be gnawen and byten</L>
<L>With outen, thurgh hydus bestes and vermyn,</L>
<L N="9456">And thurgh &thorn;e worme of conscience with-in.</L>
<L>&THORN;e devels alswa sal stryke &thorn;am felly,</L>
<L>With glowand hamers, ful huge and hevy,</L>
<L>&THORN;at sal seme of iren and stele;</L>
<L N="9460">&THORN;ir payns &thorn;ai sal with alle other fele.</L>
<L>&THORN;us sal &thorn;ai ever-mare be pyned &thorn;ar,</L>
<L>In alle &thorn;air fife wittes, als I said ar,</L>
<L>With sere payns als es gode skille,</L>
<L N="9464">For &thorn;ai here used &thorn;air wittes ille.</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;ir payns &thorn;at yhe herd me telle,</L>
<L>And many ma &thorn;at salle be in helle,</L>
<L>&THORN;ai sal thole ay &thorn;ar &thorn;at sal wende &thorn;ider,</L>
<L N="9468">In body and saule alle to-gider.
<PB REF="00000299.tif" N="255"></L>
<L>&THORN;us sal &thorn;ai ever mar contynuely</L>
<L>Haf parfite payne &thorn;ar, with-outen mercy,</L>
<L>Fra whilk payne and sorow God us shilde,</L>
<L N="9472">Thurgh prayer of hys moder mylde,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e right way of lyf us wysse,</L>
<L>Whar-thurgh we may com til heven blysse. Amen.</L>
<L>Now es &thorn;e last part of &thorn;is buke sped,</L>
<L N="9476">And alle &thorn;e maters &thorn;ar-in haf I red,</L>
<L>&THORN;at contenes, als yhe mught here,</L>
<L>Bathe general and special ioyes sere,</L>
<L>&THORN;at alle &thorn;as &thorn;at til heven sal come,</L>
<L N="9480">Sal haf aftir &thorn;e day of dome;</L>
<L>And sere schendshepes of helle alswa,</L>
<L>&THORN;at er even contrary til &thorn;a,</L>
<L>&THORN;e whilk, &thorn;as &thorn;at sal til helle wende,</L>
<L N="9484">Sal haf &thorn;ar, with-outen ende.</L>
<L>Whar-for wha-swa of &thorn;is wil take hede,</L>
<L>May be stird til luf and drede;</L>
<L>Til drede, thurgh mynde of &thorn;e hydusnes</L>
<L N="9488">Of payne and sorow &thorn;at in helle es;</L>
<L>Til luf, thurgh mynd of ioyes and blisse sere</L>
<L>&THORN;at God hetes til alle &thorn;at lufes hym here.</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;e drede es noght medeful to prufe,</L>
<L N="9492">&THORN;at accordes noght halely with &thorn;at lufe;</L>
<L>For if drede stand by itself anely,</L>
<L>Na mede of God it es worthy,</L>
<L>&THORN;arfor drede suld be lufes brother,</L>
<L N="9496">And ayther of &thorn;am stand with other,</L>
<L>For wha-swa lufes God on ryght manere</L>
<L>He has grete drede to wrethe hym here;</L>
<L>&THORN;an lufes he his bydynges to fulfille,</L>
<L N="9500">And dredes to do oght ogayne his wille,</L>
<L>Delites to be with God ay,</L>
<L>And dredes to be put fra hym oway.</L>
<L>For men suld noght drede God anly for payne</L>
<L N="9504">Bot men suld drede to tyn &thorn;e ioy soverayne,</L>
<L>&THORN;at es, &thorn;e syght of God of heven,</L>
<L>&THORN;e whilk yhe herd me byfor neven;
<PB REF="00000300.tif" N="256"></L>
<L>&THORN;at<NOTE PLACE="foot">&THORN;an (MS. Harl. 4196.)</NOTE> es pat luf ay with &thorn;at drede,</L>
<L N="9508">And &thorn;at dred of God es worthy mede,</L>
<L>For &thorn;ogh we suld never helle se,</L>
<L>Ne [for] syn suld never punyst be,</L>
<L>In purgatory ne in helle,</L>
<L N="9512">Ne in &thorn;is werld whar we duelle,</L>
<L>Yhit suld we luf God for hym-self ryght,</L>
<L>And drede to tyne hys luf and of him &thorn;e syght,</L>
<L>For, sikerly I dar wele say &thorn;is,</L>
<L N="9516">&THORN;at wha-swa wyst what ioy and blys</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e syght of God in heven war,</L>
<L>And als proprely had sene it als es &thorn;ar,</L>
<L>He had lever thole here &thorn;is payne,</L>
<L N="9520">Ilk day anes, alle qwik<NOTE PLACE="foot">The MS. reads 'qwilk'.</NOTE> to be flayne,</L>
<L>Ar he &thorn;e syght of his face suld tyne,</L>
<L>&THORN;at in heven so bright sal shyne.</L>
<L>Many sere ioys ma &thorn;ar sal falle,</L>
<L N="9524">Bot &thorn;at sight es mast principalle ioy of alle;</L>
<L>For &thorn;at ioyful sight sal contene</L>
<L>Alle other ioyes &thorn;at sal &thorn;ar be sene,</L>
<L>Of whilk ioys, &thorn;e lest sal pas</L>
<L N="9528">Alle &thorn;e ioy &thorn;at ever here was.</L>
<L>For ioy here es noght bot passand vanit&eacute;,</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;e ioyes &thorn;at er &thorn;ar ever-mar sal be,</L>
<L>Til whilk ioyes &thorn;at has nan ende,</L>
<L N="9532">God us bring when we hethen wende. Amen.</L>
</LG>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="epilogue">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Now haf I here als I first undir-toke,</L>
<L>Fulfilled &thorn;e seven partes of &thorn;is boke,</L>
<L>&THORN;at er titeld byfor to have in mynde.</L>
<L N="9536">&THORN;e first es of &thorn;e wrechednes of mans kynde;</L>
<L>&THORN;e secunde es of &thorn;e werldes condicions sere,</L>
<L>And of &thorn;e unstabelnes of &thorn;e werld here;</L>
<L>&THORN;e thred es of &thorn;e ded &thorn;at es bodily;</L>
<L N="9540">&THORN;e ferthe alswa es of purgatory;</L>
<L>&THORN;e fift es of domesday, &thorn;e last day of alle,</L>
<L>And of &thorn;e takens &thorn;at byfor sal falle;
<PB REF="00000301.tif" N="257"></L>
<L>&THORN;e sext es of &thorn;e paynes of helle to neven;</L>
<L N="9544">And &thorn;e sevend part es of &thorn;e ioyes of heven.</L>
<L>In &thorn;ir seven er sere materes drawen</L>
<L>Of sere bukes, of whilk som er unknawen,</L>
<L>Namly til lewed men of England,</L>
<L N="9548">&THORN;at can noght bot Inglise undirstand;</L>
<L>&THORN;arfor &thorn;is tretice drawe I wald</L>
<L>In Inglise tung &thorn;at may be cald</L>
<L>Prik of Conscience als men may fele,</L>
<L N="9552">For if a man it rede and understande wele,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e materes &thorn;ar-in til hert wil take,</L>
<L>It may his conscience tendre make,</L>
<L>And til right way of rewel bryng it bilyfe,</L>
<L N="9556">And his hert til drede and mekenes dryfe,</L>
<L>And til luf and yhernyng of heven blis,</L>
<L>And to amende alle &thorn;at he has done mys.</L>
<L>For &thorn;e undirstandyng of &thorn;ir maters seven,</L>
<L N="9560">&THORN;at men may in &thorn;is buke se and neven,</L>
<L>May make a man knawe and halde in mynde,</L>
<L>What he es here of his awen kynde,</L>
<L>And what he sal be, if he avyse hym wele,</L>
<L N="9564">And whar he es, for to knaw and fele.</L>
<L>Yhit may he se when he it redes</L>
<L>What he es worthy for his dedes,</L>
<L>Whether he es worthy ioy or payne</L>
<L N="9568">&THORN;is tretice may make hym be certayne,</L>
<L>For &thorn;ar-in may he many thynges se,</L>
<L>&THORN;at has bene, and es, and &thorn;at sal be;</L>
<L>&THORN;us may &thorn;is tretice, with &thorn;e sentence,</L>
<L N="9572">Pryk and stirre a mans conscience,</L>
<L>And til mekenes and luf and drede it dryfe,</L>
<L>For to bring hym til ryght way of lyfe.</L>
<L>Of alle &thorn;eis I haf sere maters soght,</L>
<L N="9576">And in seven partes I haf &thorn;am broght,</L>
<L>Als es contende in &thorn;is tretice here,</L>
<L>&THORN;at I haf drawen out of bukes sere,</L>
<L>Aftir I had in &thorn;am understandyng,</L>
<L N="9580">Alle-if I be of symple kunnyng.
<PB REF="00000302.tif" N="258"></L>
<L>Bot I pray yhou alle, par charit&eacute;,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;is tretice wil here or se</L>
<L>Yhe haf me excused at &thorn;is tyme,</L>
<L N="9584">If yhe fynde defaut in &thorn;e ryme,</L>
<L>For I rek noght, &thorn;ogh &thorn;e ryme be rude,</L>
<L>If &thorn;e maters &thorn;ar-of be gude.</L>
<L>And if any man &thorn;at es clerk,</L>
<L N="9588">Can fynde any errour in &thorn;is werk,</L>
<L>I pray hym he do me &thorn;at favour,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he wille amende &thorn;at errour;</L>
<L>For if men may here any errour se,</L>
<L N="9592">Or if any defaut in &thorn;is tretice be,</L>
<L>I make here a protestacion,</L>
<L>&THORN;at I wil stand til &thorn;e correccion</L>
<L>Of ilka rightwyse lered man,</L>
<L N="9596">&THORN;at my defaut here correcte can.</L>
<L>&THORN;is tretice specialy drawen es</L>
<L>For to stirre lewed men til mekenes,</L>
<L>And to make &thorn;am luf God and drede;</L>
<L N="9600">Ffor wha-swa wil it here or rede,</L>
<L>I hope he sal be stirred &thorn;ar-by.</L>
<L>Yf he trow &thorn;at God es alle-myghty,</L>
<L>And he sal it here or se,</L>
<L N="9604">And may noght &thorn;ar-by stirred be,</L>
<L>It semes &thorn;at he es wittles,</L>
<L>Or over mykel hardend in wikkednes.</L>
<L>Bot alle &thorn;as &thorn;at redes it, loud or stille,</L>
<L N="9608">Or heres it be red with gode wille,</L>
<L>God graunt &thorn;am grace &thorn;at &thorn;ai may</L>
<L>Be stird &thorn;ar-by til ryghtwyse way,</L>
<L>&THORN;at es, tille &thorn;e way of gude lyfyng,</L>
<L N="9612">And at &thorn;e last be broght til gude endyng.</L>
<L>And yhe &thorn;at has herd &thorn;is tretice red</L>
<L>&THORN;at now es broght til ende and sped,</L>
<L>For &thorn;e luf of our Loverd Ihesu,</L>
<L N="9616">Pray for hym specialy &thorn;at it dru,</L>
<L>&THORN;at if he lyf, God safe hym harmles,</L>
<L>And mayntene hys lyf in alle gudenes,
<PB REF="00000303.tif" N="259"></L>
<L>And if he be ded, als falles kyndely,</L>
<L N="9620">God of his saule haf mercy,</L>
<L>And bryng it til &thorn;at blisful place</L>
<L>Whar endeles ioy es and solace,</L>
<L>Til whilk place he us alle bryng,</L>
<L N="9624">&THORN;at for us vouched safe on rode to hyng. Amen.</L>
<TRAILER><I>Explicit tractus qui dicitur, Stimulus Consciencie</I>. Here endes &thorn;e tretice &thorn;at es called Pryk of Conscience.</TRAILER>
</LG>
</DIV1>
